<html><head><title>My Wal-Mart 'tis of thee</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>My Wal-Mart 'tis of thee</h1>

<font size=1>CULPEPER, VIRGINIA</font><p>
THIS is not the standard Wal-Mart story. The standard story is about the noisy protests when the world's biggest retailer moves into a small American community. In January 1995, for example, Wal-Mart opened one of its giant new Supercenters on the outskirts of Culpeper, a quaint town in a lovely part of north-western Virginia. Culpeper is a friendly place, where visitors are greeted warmly and waitresses call customers "honey" and "sweetie". It also prides itself on its heritage, from its historic town centre to its role in both the American revolution and the civil war. In Culpeper, as elsewhere, many locals saw Wal-Mart as a threat to the very fabric of American life.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But to get a sense of American life, there is now no better place than a Supercenter. While Bill Clinton's famous bridge to the 21st century is still in the planning stages, the arguably more significant monument of another (adopted) Arkansan, Wal-Mart's late founder, Sam Walton, is already in place. To walk into the Culpeper Wal-Mart, past the red lawnmowers and log-splitting machines lined up outside, is to enter a living museum of modern America--open 24 hours a day, seven days a week.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The first impressions are obvious but overwhelming. The place, like the country, is big. The Supercenter spreads over 201,000 square feet, the size of four American football fields. Man (or, in this instance, a young woman) resorts to technology to conquer distance: she is employed to whizz around on roller-skates, fetching and returning goods. To judge from the variety of customers--of all colours--the space is a giant melting-pot. This is a place where people from trailer parks mingle with people from designer homes, just as a couple of cappuccino-makers are on sale alongside the ordinary coffee machines. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The sense of abundance (some 100,000 different product lines) evokes Bill Clinton's phrase, "the age of possibility". Attached to the handle of each shopping trolley is an electronic calculator, together with a little advertisement for some product or other. Some slogans posted around the store stress value for money ("We sell for less", or "Wal-Mart. Always the low price"); others speak to a lofty idealism. Here, a basic right is not merely the pursuit of happiness, but its attainment ("You Must Be Satisfied. Our Policy Guarantees It!"). Patriotism is prized ("We Buy American Whenever We Can. So You Can, Too. Together We Can Do It."). So is local boosterism ("Virginia Proud. Wal-Mart Salutes Our Neighbours Who Make the Products You Buy."). There is also a preachy environmentalism ("Reduce, Reuse and Recycle. Together We Can Make a Difference."). A note on the signs points out that they are made out of 89.3% reprocessed plastic.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Wal-Mart, as in America, the tension between competing values can be fascinating. Patriotism, for example, is not always compatible with the commitment to low prices. By the stacks of fishing rods--at least 80 different types--a salesman explains to a customer that, although Wal-Mart really tries to buy American, "when it comes to quality and price, they're going to buy whatever's better." <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Just as striking is the clash between the cultures of fitness and of gluttony. The sports section is one of the biggest. There are exercise machines, vast numbers of bicycles and equipment for just about every sport. Tellingly, the space devoted to soccer balls is now about as big as that for American footballs, although basketballs are way ahead of both. Yet over at the food market customers are lured towards an offer of 24 glazed doughnuts for $3. Doughnuts and other indulgences help to explain why the busiest section for women's clothes is the one selling so-called Plus sizes. "There are a lot of big women in Culpeper," says the saleswoman there. Plenty of them can be seen with trolleys at Wal-Mart. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most intriguing of all is the juxtaposition of extreme freedom and Orwellian controls. On the freedom side, take the ease of buying guns. Wal-Mart's gun counter is below a display--duly credited to Lacy's Taxidermy of Culpeper--of two stuffed deer heads, a bear's head, a bass, an otter and a duck. Two dozen rifles and shotguns are on display in a glass case, the cheapest model priced at $74.67. The counter is constantly busy with customers, all men, occasionally in camouflage jackets.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Buying a gun is little harder than signing up at the local Blockbuster video store. All you need is a photo <font size=-1>ID</font> with a Virginia address, plus a second document (a utilities bill, say, or a cheque book) with the same address. The store charges $2 for a call to the state police for a background check, which may take 45 minutes or less ("I got one this morning that took all of five seconds," says a salesman, who also volunteers that handguns, although not on sale over the counter, can be ordered within a week). Customers are reminded that they need pay only 10% straight away, with the balance due within 60 days. So it is possible to walk away with a lethal weapon within minutes for about what it costs to buy a compact disc.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the compact disc section, meanwhile, words and images are considered too dangerous to be sold without prior vetting and, where necessary, censorship. A young customer, complaining that megastores "suck" but that there is nowhere else nearby to buy music, points out that the artwork of Nirvana's "In Utero" has been adjusted so as to obscure the fetuses on the original version, and the title of one of the songs has been changed from "Rape Me" to "Waif Me". Other discs are marked "Sanitised for your protection". A recent <i>New York Times</i> article reported that the mere prospect of being kept out of Wal-Mart, America's biggest retailer of pop music, is sometimes enough to make artists tone down their output. An outraged media critic, Jon Katz of HotWired, has called on freedom-lovers to boycott Wal-Mart stores. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Protectiveness towards children and the elderly, prominent themes in the 1996 election campaign, are Wal-Mart themes too. A notice board for The Missing Children's Network has details of lost or abducted children from Honolulu to Florida ("We never stop trying to bring them home," the store boasts). At the pharmacy, a notice apologises to retired federal employees for a new 20% charge by the insurers on their prescriptions, and tells them to protest against the charge: the Medicare controversy in microcosm.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Other social issues are alluded to in the application forms for people wanting to work at Wal-Mart, which employs more than 600,000 Americans. Applicants are informed that they must undergo a drug test, unless this is prohibited by state law. They must also be able to prove their legal right to work in America.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The 450 or so employees in the Culpeper store are disproportionately female, as is increasingly the case in the new American economy. They are also unfailingly friendly and helpful. Wal-Mart staff, known as "associates", are encouraged to practise the "ten-foot attitude" preached by Sam Walton: anybody coming within ten feet of a customer should look him in the eye, greet him and ask if they can help him. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Forms and a ballot box at the service desk enable customers to choose the "most helpful associate". So Wal-Mart customers can not only shop but vote, as well as go to the bank, the hairdresser, the optician, the McDonald's franchise. One of the few things they cannot find there is a church. When it comes to religion, the competition is simply too great, with more than 100 Baptist and Southern Baptist churches alone listed in Culpeper County.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the store does sell bibles--Catholic ones, Protestant ones, bibles with big type for senior citizens and "special interest" bibles for "children of colour". And for many, Wal-Mart has become an integral part of the Sunday ritual. The place is quiet before noon on Sundays, says a chatty check-out lady; but "right after church, we really get busy."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Like America itself, Sam Walton's monument excites strong reactions. People are wary of this superpower. They mistrust its motives, fear its cultural clout, deride its brashness and scoff at its contradictions. Yet they also marvel at its convenience and admire its success. And, as with America, the people keep coming.<br>

<p align=center>
