<html><head><title>Thinking lessons</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Education</b></p>
<h1>Thinking lessons</h1>

IT WAS bad-mark week for British education. An international study found that British teenagers are low down the league table of ability in maths (see <a href="br3.gif">chart</a>). Results of this year's national tests on 11-year-olds, while better than last year's, show that only 54% passed in maths and 58% in English. The tests were set at a level that 75% of 11-year-olds should be capable of reaching.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What is to be done? The teachers say the government must spend more money. The government says the teachers must return to old-fashioned methods. That is how the argument always goes. But there are other, less-discussed possibilities. Educational researchers are coming up with better methods for helping children learn:<font size=-1><li></font> Children can be taught how to think, concludes a new study by King's College, London. The five-year study looked at schools which gave pupils special lessons in which they had to work out for themselves the basic thought processes behind science and maths. A typical lesson started with the question "Does a cup of tea taste different if you put the milk in first or last?". In the course of their inquiry, pupils learnt about the principles behind statistics.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Pupils being taught how to think did significantly better in their <font size=-1>GCSE</font>s than conventionally-taught pupils. They even got better grades in English--although the special "thinking" lessons were designed only to help in maths and science.<font size=-1><li></font> Computers can be used to speed up pupils' progress in reading and writing. There is nothing new about using technology in education--Edison predicted in the 1920s that instruction by radio and films could eventually replace teachers--and plenty of recent studies have shown that interactive computer "games" can help with maths.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now, a study in 15 east London primary schools suggests that computers can also help children learn to read and write faster. In one of these schools, before the project began, seven-year-olds were progressing at less than half of the normal speed for their age. With the help of their computer-based lessons, they made 19 months' progress in one year.<font size=-1><li></font> After years of trying, the idea of "family literacy" is showing some promise. This aims to help under-achieving children by giving lessons to their parents, who often did badly at school themselves, and so cannot help their children to read and write. Earlier this year, the National Foundation for Educational Research evaluated four pilot schemes in Cardiff, Liverpool, Norfolk and Tyneside, and found that the children were still making progress six months after their parents' courses ended.<font size=-1><li></font> A simple idea whose effectiveness is supported by several American studies is to get bright sixth-formers to teach struggling 11-year-olds to read during lunch breaks. David Reynolds, professor of education at Newcastle University, says some British schools are now trying this out.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trick is to enthuse the older pupils. Teachers do this by playing on their social consciences ("you are on your way to a bright future at university, these poor kids are heading for the dole or worse") and limiting the coaching sessions to, say, six weeks at a time so they do not become a bore.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?848710800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
