<html><head><title>Dealing with Dennis the Menace</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<h1>Dealing with Dennis the Menace</h1>

IF THE recent bunfights over disruptive pupils achieved anything, it was to ensure a wide and receptive audience for a clutch of new reports showing how incompetently the problem of badly behaved children is being dealt with. Children expelled from school tend to be those most in need of education, but they often end up with next to none.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;While some schools go to great lengths not to expel disruptive children, sacrificing the education of other pupils and making teachers' lives a misery, others exclude children at the slightest excuse. This is one of the damning conclusions of a new report from Ofsted, the schools inspectorate for England.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Everybody reckons that exclusions are rising, but nobody has been keeping track of the problem until recently. New research by Christ Church College, Canterbury, shows that 13,400 children were expelled from schools in England last year, up 8% on the previous year. Some get a place in another school (often after weeks or even months of negotiations) but then get chucked out again. About 40% of expelled pupils get a place in a council-run "pupil-referral unit" (<font size=-1>PRU</font>). These usually provide only a part-time education, and a pretty poor one. An earlier Ofsted report said the standards in <font size=-1>PRU</font>s were "alarming". <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Around 27% get home tuition, but often for as little as two hours a week. All in all, says a study to be published next week by the Commission for Racial Equality (<font size=-1>CRE</font>), those expelled from school get, on average, one tenth of a full-time education in the year of expulsion.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That leaves plenty of time for mischief. Youth crime costs &#163;1 billion a year, and a new Audit Commission report points out that 42% of those sentenced in youth courts have been expelled from school. The <font size=-1>CRE</font>'s report reckons that each excluded pupil who turns to crime costs the police &#163;2,000 to deal with.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So even though a full-time place in a <font size=-1>PRU</font> can cost up to six times the &#163;2,300 annual cost of a typical secondary-school place, there is a growing realisation that more such places must be provided and their standards must be improved. It is also becoming clear that it is time to rethink the consensus which has prevailed for the past 20 years, which says that almost all children, whatever their behavioural problems, should go to mainstream schools.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?848710800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
