<html><head><title>No Mickey Mouse business</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>No Mickey Mouse business</h1>

THE media business is full of glamorous companies, but there is only one real star: Walt Disney. Last year, Disney made a profit of $1.4 billion on revenues of $12 billion, far outshining other entertainment firms. One of its biggest fans is none other than Bill Gates, the boss of Microsoft, the world's biggest independent computer-software firm.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So it is ironic that Microsoft may soon come head-to-head with Disney on what Microsoft might consider its own turf: cyberspace. On November 19th Disney launched a Web-based shop selling hundreds of bits of Disney paraphernalia from Winnie-the-Pooh pyjamas to 101-Dalmatians watches. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The shop is not Disney's first foray on to the World Wide Web: the company has launched several Web sites tacked on to its various businesses, such as one for "Toy Story", an animated film, and another for Disneyland, an amusement park. Last autumn, it set up a new division to develop products for the Internet. And in two weeks' time, it launches family.com, an advertiser-supported Web site aimed at families. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the biggest clash may be yet to come. According to <font size=-1>C/NET</font>, a trade magazine, Disney will launch its own on-line service early next year, to offer access to the Internet as well as to feature its own content and characters. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That should frighten America Online, CompuServe and <font size=-1>MSN</font>, Microsoft's newly relaunched network. These online services make much of their suitability for children (<font size=-1>MSN</font> even has an area dedicated to the youngest surfers). Disney, with its strength in home entertainment and warm, furry family values, looks an ideal partner to help children (and their parents) through the hazards of the Internet.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many of Disney's other electronic ventures have succeeded. A couple of years ago it started selling educational software. In the first half of this year, four of the top six <font size=-1>PC</font> educational programs were produced by Disney, according to <font size=-1>PC</font> Data, a research firm in Virginia. Disney now holds more than 10% of a fragmented market. If Disney can do as well on-line (and it probably will), Mr Gates may wish that Donald, Mickey and their friends were not quite the impressive characters he so admires.<br>

<p align=center>
