<html><head><title>On-line capitalism</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/fn.gif" width="360" height="26" alt="Finance and Economics" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Internet offerings</b></p>
<h1>On-line capitalism</h1>

<font size=1>NEW YORK</font><p>
<p><b>For small companies, selling stock has been a hugely expensive undertaking. The Web may change that</b></p><br>
EARLY next year, Ray Dallavecchia, the boss of a small toy and foam-products firm, plans to do something uncharacteristically daring. He will attempt to raise around $5m of equity capital. But he will not take the traditional route to market offered by venture capitalists or investment bankers. Rather, he intends to launch a do-it-yourself share offering on the Internet.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He will join a growing band of bosses from small firms who think that they have found in the World Wide Web a perfect way to sidestep the perils of Wall Street. Around 30 companies are in various stages of following the lead set by Spring Street Brewing, a New York beer maker, which pioneered Internet share offerings when it raised $1.6m last February. By appealing directly to investors via the Net, firms can raise money without spending a fortune on expensive underwriters. They can even sign up with a growing number of fledgling electronic stockmarkets, so that their shares can be traded. Already some 15 online investment banks are vying to help firms use the new technology. This trend could one day prove a potent threat to every sort of financial activity, from banking and accountancy to legal services, venture capital and share-dealing.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To understand why, consider the intriguingly named Poof Products, which Mr Dallavecchia has owned since 1991. The firm employs 45 people at a plant in Plymouth, Michigan, and sells more than $10m-worth of foam sports balls, puzzles and toys each year. But its industry is consolidating as retailers demand more products and broader marketing efforts than small firms can provide. Poof needs extra capital if it is to be an acquirer rather than someone else's acquisition.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hot-shot investment bankers are hardly knocking on Mr Dallavecchia's door. "Our funding needs are just too small to be of interest to most underwriters," he says. The few underwriters or venture capitalists who raise money for small firms such as Poof are astonishingly rapacious. A $5m offering might see as much as $700,000 eaten up in costs. The Internet offers an alternative. For $1,200 Mr Dallavecchia has bought a computer program called CapScape, which automates the tedious process of compiling an offer document. By using the program and then offering shares directly to investors over the Internet, Poof Products expects to raise its money at a cost of less than $100,000.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The savings offered by CapScape are formidable. The American government reckons that, on average, a share prospectus takes 900 hours to complete. CapScape's interactive worksheets shrink that to just 11 hours or so. The completed form must then be shown to a lawyer for review. But the professional fees involved in such an offering are relatively tiny: a few thousand dollars against perhaps $200,000 for a conventional prospectus for an initial public offering. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Like the lawyers and accountants, the financiers too have plenty to fear from the new technology. Those who now specialise in raising money for small companies, particularly banks and venture capitalists, will face unaccustomed competition. Ben Ezra Weinstein, the investment-advisory firm from Albuquerque, New Mexico that developed CapScape, intends precisely that. Hence its choice of a toll-free phone number: 1-888-<font size=-1>VC-GOAWAY</font>.<br>
</p><p><b><b>Bypass operation</b></b><br>
Should Wall Street tremble? Not just yet, reckons Andrew Klein, a savvy lawyer who is the boss of Spring Street Brewing. "The biggest beneficiaries of this will be small and fast-growing companies," he says. "Potential Internet issuers are not likely to be complaining about the quality of the coffee at Goldman Sachs or other big investment banks. They will be firms that want to by-pass venture funds."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Alongside his brewing interests, Mr Klein has started Wit Capital, an investment bank that also aspires to become an electronic stockmarket on which the shares of Internet offerings will be traded. By combining discount stockbroking with the underwriting of share issues, Mr Klein thinks he can widen the pool of investors who have access to newly-issued equity. In time, that could change how the stocks perform. New issues have a deserved reputation for volatility. On average they jump in price by nearly a fifth in the first hour of trading. That is because underwriters carefully control the pricing and direct the flow of shares to favoured customers, who then have the privilege of selling for an immediate premium. Investors who buy during that post-issue frenzy often end up with losses when prices tumble. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Imagine instead that shares in a new offering are allocated on a first-come, first-served basis, as Wit Capital intends. Small investors would have the same chance as big institutions of getting in on the ground floor. The offering price would reflect true market demand, letting the issuer collect every penny of the shares' value rather than giving windfalls to a few lucky investors. Michael Weinstein, joint boss of Ben Ezra Weinstein, thinks that many of the small investors who would be drawn to a fairer market would want to hold onto their shares rather than sell them for a quick profit--an additional benefit to the issuer.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Not that cyberspace share-dealers will have an easy ride. Existing fund-raisers are quick to point out that any smart crook can make an Internet offering. How might investors tell the real from the fake? A few Internet sites, such as the one run by Mr Klein and another by Clay Womack, a Californian entrepreneur, address this issue by promising to do thorough checks on companies that list shares for trading. Mr Womack has formed the Small Business Capital Acquisition Association, an independent body that will offer to guarantee the integrity of companies that list their stock on the Web. But, as in the physical world, money will attract crooks and the lure of fat returns will trap the gullible.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This will not deter Mr Dallavecchia, however. The commercial logic of Internet share offerings is so compelling that he is committed to the idea. Might his company's shares thereby be condemned to trade only on some obscure electronic bulletin board? Maybe. But Mr Dallavecchia is unconcerned. If nothing else, he should have investors who want to hold his shares as a long-term investment. No captain of industry could ask for more.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?848710800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="sf0791.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>
1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
