</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Clinton II: The Strategy</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Clinton II: The Strategy</h1>

<font size=1>WASHINGTON, DC</font><p>
TWO days after the election, Bill Clinton slept the relaxed sleep of the victor, waking up past noon. He had proclaimed a mandate for the "vital centre" of American politics; his Republican opponents, newly reconfirmed in their control of Congress, had said they would be delighted to serve the centre too. On all sides, there was talk of bipartisan co-operation. Then, on the third day, the president rose up and gave a press conference. The Republicans pounced.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The press conference, and the reaction to it, suggest how different this transition is from the one that followed Mr Clinton's election four years ago. Then, Mr Clinton had issued a list of large campaign promises--a tax cut, a stimulus package, more jobs, more health insurance, welfare reform--with little thought given to how these could be implemented: Mr Clinton was agonising over his priorities right up until inauguration day. This time, however, Mr Clinton has won election on a more modest programme, and has few doubts about his priorities. But, in contrast to four years ago, he faces a Congress controlled by the opposing camp.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Both at the press conference, and again in a television interview two days later, Mr Clinton declared that balancing the budget is at the top of his agenda; spreading tertiary education, making a success of welfare reform, extending health insurance in small increments and cleansing campaign finance follow. Already, reducing the deficit from $290 billion to $107 billion stands out as the big achievement of his first term in office. Other presidents have ended slavery or vanquished foreign dictators. Mr Clinton wants to be the first president since 1969 to balance the government's books.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is more than a little irony in this. Until just over a year ago, Mr Clinton disdained Republican calls to eliminate the deficit. He then changed course, seeing political advantage in fiscal virtue; but he nonetheless spent much of the election campaign denouncing Republican budget cuts as too harsh. Now, smiling genially, he marvels at how little difference there is between Republican proposals and his own. He declares that a budget-balancing deal could be done in "next to no time"--indeed, that it is "easily achievable" next year.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Republicans will come to relish these comments if Mr Clinton fails. And the obstacles are daunting. For one thing, the impressive progress on the budget in Mr Clinton's first term is due mainly to the tax increases of 1990 and 1993 and to the strong economy. Mr Clinton is not going to raise taxes again, and the economy is unlikely to remain robust for ever. In the absence of bold spending cuts, the deficit will grow rather than disappear.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And politics will make cutting tricky. Mr Clinton wants to laugh off his campaign assault on the cuts proposed last year by the Republicans, but the Republicans are not amused. On November 12th Mr Clinton invited the leaders of Congress to the White House, hoping to mark out common ground on the budget. But the Republicans conceded nothing. Having borne the brunt of Mr Clinton's attacks, they are determined that he should take the responsibility for suggesting cuts this time--cuts that Republicans can denounce at the next election. "We're in this boat together and we have to paddle it together," the president had pleaded earlier in the day. You steer, was the Republican reply. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This exchange may set the pattern of the next few months: the president longing for congressional Republicans to join him in policy-making, the Republicans politely coy. The Republicans hope that, if Mr Clinton is forced to take the lead, he will damage his reputation as much as he did during his first years in power, when his crusade for a tax increase and for health reform cost his party control of Congress in the 1994 election. Yet the Republicans' waiting game may not work much better than the president's genial smiles. For there are big differences between now and 1993-94.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unlike four years ago, there are few signs that Mr Clinton will veer to the unpopular left after his election. Rather than mulling a tax increase, he is committed to tax cuts. Rather than seeking a dramatic increase in the federal government's role in health care, he is set on modest advances. A month ago, it seemed possible that the trade unions' contribution to the Democrats' congressional campaign might force the new administration leftwards. But the unions' ads proved less effective than many had expected, freeing Mr Clinton to ignore their ideas.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is reflected in Mr Clinton's choice of second-term officials. Several of his more leftish advisers are on their way out: Robert Reich, the labour secretary; George Stephanopoulos and Harold Ickes, two White House officials; and possibly Henry Cisneros, the housing secretary. Meanwhile Mr Clinton's treasury secretary, Robert Rubin, and his new chief of staff, Erskine Bowles (see <a href="am3127.html">page</a>), are both conservative investment bankers. To cap it all, the president has let it be known that he hopes to appoint Republicans to his cabinet. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If Mr Clinton stays on the centre ground, the Republicans' refusal to support his policies may look petty. On campaign finance, for example, Mr Clinton has declared his support for a bill that would offer candidates free television ads in exchange for voluntary spending limits, and would control the flood of cash to national parties. The Republican leadership, by contrast, scoffs at this bill, preferring to attack Democrats' fund-raising from foreigners. But the bill is sponsored, among others, by Senator John McCain, a respected Republican. On this issue, voters may give Mr Clinton credit for reaching across party lines while Republicans played politics.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The other issues on Mr Clinton's agenda may draw similar verdicts. It will be hard for the Republicans to block the president's education plans without looking mean. Nor can they object to incremental health reform; one law of this sort, to which many sound objections could have been raised, passed the Senate unanimously this summer. Even welfare, once a good issue for Republicans, may yet embarrass them. In the past, Republicans could attack Mr Clinton for blocking schemes that would make the supposedly indolent poor earn their own keep. Now that the new welfare law requires poor mothers to get work, Mr Clinton is demanding only that jobs should be found for them. Republicans can hardly object to that. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the end, all the squabbles over these parts of Mr Clinton's second-term agenda will matter less than the big one on the budget. Yet here, too, the Republicans may be on weaker ground than they suppose. If they wait for Mr Clinton to propose his own budget cuts, they will undoubtedly get ones that promise progress on the deficit, but which nonetheless preserve the president's claim that he is less harsh than his adversaries. The Republicans will then be faced with a tough choice. If they pass the budget, they will allow the president to claim victory for his plan; if they block it, they allow him to accuse them of reckless obstruction. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Because of this, the Republicans may not stick to their waiting game for long. They will strive, instead, to come up with their own agenda for a second term, and to push it in parallel to the president's. This may bring them some success. On November 11th the Republicans let it be known that, by their count, the election had given them the votes to pass a constitutional amendment to balance the budget. This had an immediate effect: the next day Mr Clinton softened his old opposition to the measure. Their appetites whetted by this easy victory, Republicans may soon be pushing other schemes. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All of which suggests a paradox. A week ago, when the election results came in, Americans seemed to have voted for gridlock. They had not liked either party's schemes, and so they had sought to block both sides by dividing power between them. And yet, if the Republican waiting game does backfire, the opposite of gridlock may transpire. Mr Clinton may find that his policies sail through Congress; the Republicans may find that many of their ideas win Mr Clinton's support. Instead of one activist government, America might just get two of them.<br>

<p align=center>
