<html><head><title>Thrills, no; discipline, yes</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>Thrills, no; discipline, yes</h1>

<font size=1>WASHINGTON, DC</font><p>
ALL presidents tend to develop a growing sense of the importance of good management. As an aide to President Kennedy once said, "Everybody believes in democracy until he gets to the White House, and then you begin to believe in dictatorship, because it's so hard to get things done." Jimmy Carter at first thought he could get by without a chief of staff, but discovered the hard way that he was wrong. From the contrast between Mr Clinton's first chief of staff (his old Arkansas friend Mack McLarty, a nice man but a Washington novice) and his second (Washington-wise Leon Panetta, a huge success), Mr Clinton has had a clear lesson in what a vital post it is.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So vital that the president chose as his first post-election task the replacement of Mr Panetta, who wants to return to California. With some effort, Mr Clinton persuaded Erskine Bowles, a banker who learnt his trade with Morgan Stanley, to drop his new banking venture in North Carolina and return to Washington. The choice drew a warm reaction even from two usually hostile Republicans, Senators Jesse Helms and Lauch Faircloth of North Carolina. They respect Mr Bowles not only for his business acumen, but also for his pedigree: his wife, Crandall, is from a prominent local textile family and his father grew up with Mr Helms in Monroe, North Carolina.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton met Mr Bowles only four years ago, when Mr Bowles was raising money for the 1992 campaign. They quickly bonded, not least on the golf course. Appointed to head the Small Business Administration, Mr Bowles set about reducing the voluminous paperwork for <font size=-1>SBA</font> loans to a single sheet. Then, as deputy chief of staff, he reorganised the president's schedule to allow more time for thinking. Even after he left the White House last January, Mr Clinton still turned to Mr Bowles for delicate tasks such as handling the resignation of Dick Morris, the president's political consultant, in the midst of a sex scandal.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Businesslike" and "focused" are the words used to describe Mr Bowles by people who have worked with him. You will not hear from him any dreamy talk of bridges to the new millennium. Instead, in a deliberate southern drawl, you hear the sort of phrases found in business textbooks: "I believe in having an administration that has clearly defined goals, objectives and time lines such that it and its people can be held accountable." The Bowles regime promises few thrills and much discipline.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Which is how it should be. Without the prospect of an election to concentrate the presidential mind, the need for discipline in the White House is all the greater. Bowlesian management should help with agenda-setting, too. For the past two years, Mr Clinton has proved himself to be brilliant on the counter-attack against a Republican Congress. But now the policy initiative is back with him. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unlike Mr Panetta, Mr Bowles does not have years of experience on Capitol Hill to help him in the delicate task of dealing with Congress. But he does have a keen sense of time-management, at a stage when time is precious. To put it in the language of the new administration, Mr Clinton's stock is now up, but typically the bull market for second-term presidents does not last long. <br>
<br>
</td></tr></table>


<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
