<html><head><title>Hello, world</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>Hello, world</h1>

WHAT a rude interruption. Bill Clinton had hardly had time to celebrate his election victory. He was in the process of trying to put together a new foreign-policy team, one that could help him earn a distinguished place in the history books. He was about to set off to the Pacific for a bit of rest and a bit of diplomacy. And what should intrude? A foreign-policy crisis.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With memories still fresh of America's humiliation in Somalia early in Mr Clinton's first term, hurried decisions over sending troops to another African disaster area were not what the president would have wished for as an immediate post-election challenge. The situation in Zaire has all the potential for the sort of trouble that Americans are so wary of: complicated lines of command, the possibility of mission creep, fuzziness of objectives and of exit strategy. Awkwardly, the costs will complicate the administration's budget-balancing efforts. And embarrassingly, just as Mr Clinton was hoping for a second term marked by "indispensible" American world leadership, here was America struggling to keep up with an initiative promoted and headed by Canadians. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In truth, America was caught napping. First there was the distraction of the election, not a time when a president wants to talk about putting American soldiers in harm's way. Then there was the distraction of personnel changes. The president's top foreign-policy priority was reshuffling his team. The secretary of state, Warren Christopher, his sights on his own exit, set off on a final diplomatic journey. The Pentagon, whose boss, William Perry, is also on the way out, had the added diversion of a growing sexual-harassment scandal at army training camps.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the world does not wait obligingly for Americans to get their administrative house in order before posing its problems. Zaire is not the only matter calling for urgent attention. In Bosnia, which this week has seen the worst outbreak of fighting since the Dayton peace agreement nearly a year ago, decisions loom on the commitment of American troops for the longer term. Other issues--from <font size=-1>NATO</font> enlargement to the appointment of the United Nations secretary general, from the currently scratchy relations with France to the perpetually fraught policy towards Cuba--are crowding in.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this is complicated by the outcome of last week's election. Many of the senators who knew and cared most about the world have now left Congress. But one cantankerous presence remains as chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee: Jesse Helms, the senior senator from North Carolina. Mr Helms is not only stingy to a fault on the budget for foreign policy, meddling in his attempts to reorganise agencies and determined to intensify the cold war against Cuba. He is also deeply hostile towards the <font size=-1>UN</font>. In a recent article in <i>Foreign Affairs</i>, he argued that that this "power-hungry and dysfunctional organisation" was a threat to American national interests and that its bureaucracy needed to be cut at least by half; if it failed to reform, according to Mr Helms, America should withdraw from it.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet in another sense the conditions for grappling with foreign-policy decisions are more benign than they have ever been under the Clinton presidency. When Mr Clinton first came to the White House, he tended to see such issues as an unwelcome distraction from his busy domestic agenda. Over the past four years, through many a stumble, he has gained experience and credibility. And now, with a relatively slim agenda at home, foreign policy offers a bigger field for Mr Clinton's energies, a worthy challenge for a maturing second-term president.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He should therefore welcome the intrusion of the outside world, with all its complications. A new foreign-policy team--in particular, a more dynamic secretary of state--can signal a new sense of activism. But an effective team needs strong leadership from its captain, the president himself.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In part, the president's task is one of salesmanship. He has to sell the idea of foreign troop deployments, for example, to an inward-looking nation and a sceptical Congress. Further trade liberalisation, of the sort he will be discussing with America's Asia-Pacific partners, is also a hard sell, which is why so little was said about it during the election campaign; but it would be a worthy second-term crusade, which could begin with an effort to persuade Congress to expand the North American Free-Trade Agreement to allow the entry of Chile. The president will have to convince Congress to approve the extension of <font size=-1>NATO</font>'s security guarantees to new members in Central Europe. He will need to make allies see the seriousness of America's security concerns (in their dealings with Iran, say) and make sure that enemies (such as Iraq) appreciate the serious consequences of any misbehaviour. Not least, there is the job of persuading Congress to provide adequate money for the conduct of foreign policy. Leadership does not come cheap.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Effective salesmanship is difficult if it comes in the context of a foreign policy conducted on a case-by-case basis. That has been the approach taken by Mr Christopher, on the assumption that the post-cold-war world remains too confusing, and its security challenges too diffuse, for any overarching vision or doctrine to have much practical value. It is high time to question that assumption and to work out a clear ordering of American interests, along with a clearer rationale for the resources needed to pursue them. That would facilitate the task of salesmanship-- and it would make America's foreign policy less reactive and more creative.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No one would pretend that such clarity of purpose can come easily. It requires a formidable investment of time and effort. That is why Mr Clinton's designated time-manager--the next chief of staff, Erskine Bowles--should make sure that plenty of presidential "thinking time" is set aside for foreign policy. Too bad that it takes an African tragedy and Canadian prodding for America to wake up. But with the election out of the way, at least Mr Clinton is beginning to give foreign policy the attention it deserves.<br>
<br>
</td></tr></table>


<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
