<html><head><title>The world makes up its mind(s) about Zaire</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" width="224" height="26" alt="International" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>The world makes up its mind(s) about Zaire</h1>

<font size=1>KIGALI</font><p>
SHAMED by Canada, the United States at last this week declared its willingness to send troops to Zaire--albeit, it said initially, only "in principle" and "in a limited fashion". Its commitment will help clear the way for a United Nations mandate under Chapter 7 which will allow the force to deal firmly with anyone who obstructs it. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Memories of American deaths in Somalia, the presidential election, the end of a reign at the State Department and anxiety about the cost of an open-ended military commitment in a political quagmire, all contributed to American hesitation. But in the end the humanitarian imperative once again is dragging in the armies of the rich, even before their screens have been filled with images of disease and death among the 1m-plus refugees in eastern Zaire. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Zaire is no Somalia, but the core of the mission, protecting humanitarian aid in a war zone, is similar. The rest of the world may want to see starving children saved, but this is not necessarily a priority for the region's governments, rebels and warlords. So what are the local agendas that an intervening force will bump up against? <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In Zaire itself, for example, the government spokesman has called it treason for any aid agency to negotiate with the rebels in eastern Zaire, demanding that all aid go through Kinshasa. Top of any normal Zairean politician's agenda is his own rake-off; second, his future when President Mobutu Sese Seko has gone. Zaireans are also watching anxiously for other uprisings in parts of Zaire with a history of secession, though so far even the traditionally rebellious provinces of Shaba and Kasai are quiet. The eruption in Kivu seems to have united Zaireans in nationalist fervour against a "Rwandan invasion" which, they say, is aimed at establishing a Tutsi empire. Too bad that years of neglect of the region that is now so dear meant that no roads were built to it, so that Zaire's defeated troops in Kivu cannot be reinforced. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The rebels too have strong views on food aid. Laurent Kabila, their leader, wants it for local Zaireans, so long as he can be identified with the distribution. But he does not want food to reach the Hutu refugee camps north and west of Goma that his troops are now attacking. On his mind is the prospect, or fantasy, of sweeping across Zaire and overthrowing the government in Kinshasa. His immediate task--vigorously under way on Thursday--is to defeat the remains of the old Rwandan army and the Hutu militiamen in the camps. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What do these Hutus think about food aid or multinational force? They are hard pressed by the rebels and must be desperate for food. Their fears that an intervention force may try to disarm or even arrest them are likely to prove false. But they have few friends. The Zairean government, which once supported them, is now out of reach and their former French allies will not help them unilaterally this time. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rwanda, the Americans' local ally, is the real winner in eastern Zaire. Despite appeals for the refugees to return, the Kigali government may not care whether they live or die, so long as they stop coming back across the border as guerrillas. It knows many took part in the 1994 genocide, and it might be happier if all disappeared in the jungles of Zaire. Its worry is that an intervention force will let the Hutu militiamen escape or regroup in new refugee camps. At the moment, with a buffer zone created by its allies, the Zairean rebels, Rwanda feels secure. Burundi too. Its military regime, pressed by international sanctions and Hutu guerrilla infiltrations from Zaire, has been given breathing space. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So much for regional politics. The outsiders are not neutral either. The French, once the only major foreign power in the region, are still hurt at criticism of their intervention in 1994, which saved lives but also--unavoidably, but not by mere coincidence--helped the perpetrators of genocide to escape to Zaire. They are bitter about the anglophone takeover of Rwanda, and further complain that the United States is giving unqualified support to a regime in Rwanda which is dominated by a minority, took power by force and shows no sign of allowing much democracy. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When the crisis broke more than two weeks ago, the United States, like the Rwandan government, opposed sending even food aid, hoping that the trouble would drive the refugees back into Rwanda. Only last weekend the American ambassador to Rwanda asserted that military intervention was unnecessary. "The Americans are playing a power game," said a European diplomat in Kigali this week. "It matters much more to them to keep this Rwandan regime in power than to help the refugees." <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rwanda is the latest in a chain of African countries stretching south from Eritrea that have become close allies of the Americans. It has had vital military aid from them. Last week it emerged that three others, Eritrea, Ethiopia and Uganda, were to be given $20m worth of military equipment to fight Islamist Sudan. America may be reluctant to put its troops on the ground, but it has its ideas for the region.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?848106000,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
