<html><head><title>McFootsie</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>McFootsie</h1>

<font size=1>EDINBURGH</font><p>
UNIONISTS like to warn nationalist-minded Scots of the awful things that would happen to their vulnerable economy, should they be silly enough to vote for devolution or independence. But a stockmarket index of Scottish companies' performance which became available on November 11th shows that Scotland's indigenous companies have performed better, over the past decade, than those of Britain as a whole.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The index has been compiled by the <i>Scotsman </i>newspaper, Reuters, a news and financial data agency, and <font size=-1>HSBC</font> James Capel, a stockbroking firm. They have tracked the share performance of the biggest 50 Scottish companies (those which have Scottish head offices or do most of their business from Scotland) quoted on the Stock Exchange from 1985 (see <a href="br1.gif">chart)</a>.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Scottish firms are pretty small-- the index has a market capitalisation of &#163;32 billion, compared with the <font size=-1>FTSE</font> 100's &#163;670 billion. Banks and insurance firms (35% of the index) are over-represented; pharmaceutical firms and telecommunications companies are not represented at all. Yet despite these weaknesses, while the Scottish index closely followed the ups and downs of the <font size=-1>FTSE</font> index, the value of the Scottish companies has steadily grown at a faster pace: &#163;300 invested in Scottish firms in 1985 would now be worth &#163;1,000, whereas a similar sum invested in the <font size=-1>FTSE</font> 100 companies would have risen to &#163;800.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite Tory claims that Scottish nationalism frightens the markets, politics does not seem to have much effect on the index. Between August 1991 and March 1992, when opinion polls claimed to show that Labour was likely to win the 1992 election and when devolution and even independence were high on the Scots' agenda, the Reuters/Scotsman 50 index fell by 10%. But the <font size=-1>FTSE</font> 100 index also dropped by 8% over the same period.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Takeovers make more difference. In 1987, when <font size=-1>BP</font> bid for Britoil, a Glasgow-based oil firm, the Scottish index leapt up by 38%, three times more than the <font size=-1>FTSE</font> 100 index rose. This particular takeover, while it cheered investors, dismayed many Scots who feared that control of too many Scottish firms might be draining away to distant boardrooms, leaving a vulnerable branch economy north of the border.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But privatisation (also much deplored by Scots) has helped to reverse the takeover trend. Six of the companies in the index are former state-owned businesses which have all expanded by buying up rivals. Two, Scottish Power, an electricity generator, and Stagecoach, a bus operator, have snapped up enough firms in England to make them feared predators rather than juicy targets.<br>
<br>
</td></tr></table>


