<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<b>Lost war</b> &nbsp; Labour failed by just one vote to defeat the government over its handling of the "beef war" with the <font size=-1>EU</font>.
<p><b>Blank papers</b> &nbsp; The government published white papers on the health service and trade policy which contained no proposals for new laws. Labour said that preparing them had been a misuse of civil servants' time.<br>
<p><b>Shot down</b> &nbsp; Terry Dicks, a Tory <font size=-1>MP</font>, was sacked as an aide to John Watts, a transport minister, after calling for a free vote in the Commons on whether all handguns should be banned. Mr Dicks thinks they should be.<br>
<p><b>Whacko!</b> &nbsp; The government agreed to a free vote on bringing back the cane in schools. John Major, the prime minister, opposes this, but Gillian Shephard, the education secretary, and Michael Howard, the home secretary, favour it, as do many Tory backbenchers.<br>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Court out</b> &nbsp; The Appeal Court ruled that the government had treated the Egyptian-born Al Fayed brothers, owners of Harrods, unfairly when it refused them citizenship without giving its reasons.<br>
<p><b>Big deal</b> &nbsp; British Aerospace won a &#163;1 billion contract to provide Hawk trainer jets to Australia. But only the first 12 planes out of a total order of 40 will be built in Britain.<br>
<p><b>Buying power</b> &nbsp; Directors of East Midlands Electricity, a privatised electricity distributor, accepted a &#163;1.3 billion takeover bid from Dominion Resources, an American firm.<br>
<p><b>All out, all in</b> &nbsp; University and college staff voted for a one-day strike over pay on November 19th. But the Post Office dispute appears to be over; managers and union leaders agreed on a 3% pay rise and further talks on working practices.<br>
<p><b>Ho, ho, ho</b> &nbsp; The Plain English Campaign criticised Northampton council for describing a Christmas tree as a "horticultural festive element". The council said it was only joking.<br>

</td></tr></table></center>

