<html><head><title>Cable television's long march</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Cable television's long march</h1>

<font size=1>DENVER AND NEW YORK</font><p>
<p><b>The advent of the railway turned Britain's Victorian canal builders from technological leaders into industrial curiosities. Will satellite television have the same effect on John Malone and the rest of America's cable-TV barons?</b></p><br>
OPEN a copy of <i>USA Today</i> and your eye is likely to be caught by vast advertisements for satellite television. "Up to 60 pay-per-view movies every night", they promise, along with oodles of sport, a crystalline picture, and several hundred television and radio channels. All this for a mere $199 purchase of a pizza-sized satellite dish and a subscription not far out of line with the price of basic cable television.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such blandishments have had a disastrous effect on the shares of the cable-television industry--including those of Tele-Communications Inc (<font size=-1>TCI</font>), the firm with the largest cable systems (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>). Only three years ago, Bell Atlantic, a regional Bell telephone company, offered to pay $35 a share for <font size=-1>TCI</font>, and John Malone, <font size=-1>TCI</font>'s boss, was being touted as the most powerful man in American media. Now the shares trade at just $13.50--"dirt cheap" according to Mr Malone, who points out that this valuation is more than covered by <font size=-1>TCI</font>'s non-cable assets: "Our cable company is selling at negative equity."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many critics say such a stockmarket valuation is fair. History is littered with examples of expensive capital assets that quickly became obsolete, just as Britain's canal network did within 30 years or so of being built; or that were worth owning only once the cost of constructing them had been largely written off, as is likely to be the case with Eurotunnel, which runs the Channel tunnel. In a world of fast-changing technology, the fixed networks of the cable systems look vulnerable. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Worse, unlike America's telephone companies, which also have extensive fixed networks, cable firms have huge debts. For each of its 14.5m subscribers, <font size=-1>TCI</font> has accumulated $1,000 of debt: a total of $14.5 billion. Time Warner, the second-biggest cable firm--and one in which <font size=-1>TCI</font> has an indirect 9% stake--has debts of more than $17 billion (see <a href="wb8445.html">page</a>). As Richard Parsons, its president and a down-to-earth former banker, points out, debt is a liability. "We have low inflation, moderate interest rates and a healthy economy. But what if that changes? All of a sudden, that debt's going to eat you up."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the past, the most worrying thing about the cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> industry for most bankers was that it was too successful (Congress periodically demanded that it cut rates). Now the success of satellite-<font size=-1>TV</font>, which since its launch in 1994 has won nearly 4m customers (maybe half of them from the cable industry), looks a more realistic threat. Put simply, satellite television is cheaper to deliver than cable-<font size=-1>TV</font>, and because--unlike cable--it is digital, it provides more choice.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The start-up costs for a satellite company are relatively low, notably because viewers themselves buy and erect the receiving equipment. For their investment, customers get up to 200 channels (whereas a cable system typically offers around 50-60); significantly better picture and sound quality; and, in the case of Direc<font size=-1>TV</font>, the market leader, an exclusive package of football games across the country. Satellite-<font size=-1>TV</font> thus appeals to sport and film fans, who are big spenders. No wonder Mr Malone grumbles that "satellite is a cherry-picking, cream-skimming technology."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That said, it is hard to think of how the cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> barons could have played their hand worse. For years, they have blathered on about offering 500 channels of television, various interactive services, high-speed Internet access and so on. None of these has yet come to pass. They can hardly blame viewers for choosing a future that they themselves have advertised. All the same, the outlook for their industry is not quite as bleak as the stockmarket thinks.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From the cable firms' point of view, the forthcoming war can be divided into two battlefields: defending their franchise in multichannel television and trying to win one for various interactive services. A glance at the numbers suggests that some of the gloom in the television market is overdone. Arthur Gruen of Wilkofsky Gruen, a New York firm of media analysts, notes that in 1995 cable added 2.2m subscribers, compared with 1.5m for satellite and 200,000 for wireless television--another rival, promoted by the telephone companies.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is partly because satellite-<font size=-1>TV</font> has its own drawbacks. For a start, each television set in a home needs its own expensive receiving equipment (an important flaw, according to Tom Wolzein of Sanford Bernstein, a Wall Street stockbroker, seeing that 55% of cable homes have more than one set). Cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> also offers local programming; satellite, at least for now, offers only a national package. The cable companies are also beginning to close the gap between the number of channels that they and their airborne rivals can offer. The big barrier is that much of their network can currently carry only analogue television; converting that to higher-capacity digital fibre would cost a fortune (roughly $250 per home).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now <font size=-1>TCI</font>, Time Warner and <font size=-1>US</font>West (which is buying Continental Cablevision, America's third-largest operator) are developing ways to push more channels through their existing systems. This month, for example, <font size=-1>TCI</font> launches a digital-television service that uses a proprietary compression technology called Imedia to double the current 55 or so channels that the company carries. Digital channels, delivered this way, will be available to most <font size=-1>TCI</font> customers by the end of 1998. Unlike satellite customers, boast <font size=-1>TCI</font> bosses, their cable customers will not have to pay extra to buy or lease receiving equipment.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The aim is not only to halt the drift to satellite, but also to persuade existing subscribers to spend more, especially on pay-per-view services. So far, says Emily Green of Forrester Research, a consultancy in Boston, most of the rise in cable revenues has come from extending systems rather than from squeezing higher revenues from existing customers. (By contrast, satellite services, which offer a simple point-and-click way to order a film, have boosted pay-per-view revenues considerably). Mr Malone hopes that there will be a "huge surge of pay-per-view activity." <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The signs are that cable customers buy more if they are offered more. In Atlanta, where <font size=-1>US</font>West Media has recently begun offering 100 channels, including 20 pay-per-view options, Doug Holmes, the company's chief financial officer, says that pay-per-view revenues have risen by more than 10%, and the proportion of homes that sign up for cable television is up from 60% to 65%.<br>
</p><p><b><b>A new vision</b></b><br>
Fighting a rearguard action (even a successful one) against satellite-<font size=-1>TV</font> is not quite the glamorous multimedia future that Mr Malone envisaged a few years ago. The only way that cable firms will begin to seem exciting again is if they can show that their networks can be used for interactive services. After all, why squabble over coaxing people into spending another $5 a month for films if they can be persuaded to pay $35 a month for high-speed Internet access, or even more for telephone calls?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Once a cable system has been upgraded it should be able to offer all types of interactive services. But upgrading networks is costly, particularly if you are already knee-deep in debt. The cable firms are showing unfamiliar caution. <font size=-1>TCI</font> will eventually offer its new digital-<font size=-1>TV</font> customers an Internet service, for a few dollars a month, based on the World Wide Web. They will be able to order video shots of local news and weather, and take advantage of local advertising promotions. A smaller number of customers, whose networks will be expensively upgraded to offer high-speed Internet access first, will be carefully chosen-- from, for instance, university towns, full of wealthy computer addicts.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Local telephony, which the cable firms are now free to enter, offers a bigger target, but also requires even more investment. The idea of house-to-house combat with a cash-rich Baby Bell is far from enticing for most cable operators. However, this procrastination cannot last for long. Local cable firms are now ideal takeover targets (or "partners", as they prefer to put it) for long-distance telephone companies and Baby Bells from other areas who want to force their way into local telephony. <font size=-1>US</font>West, for instance, views its acquisition of Continental and its stake in Time Warner's well-clustered cable systems partly as a cheap way to break into other local markets.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the end, the problem for the cable barons is financial, not commercial. At the operating level their cash flow is strong; but they have too much debt to be able to make the most of their position. (Pointedly, <font size=-1>US</font>West boasts of being the only cable company with an investment-grade credit rating.) Many smaller cable firms will vanish into the maw of the telephone companies. As for Mr Malone, he mutters about buying back the cable side of <font size=-1>TCI</font> himself. Given current valuations, that may be a bargain.<br>

<p align=center>
