<html><head><title>Now tell the truth</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>

<h1 align=center>Now tell the truth</h1>


O ZYMANDIAS built his colossus in the desert; Mitterrand filled Paris with fantasies in glass; Franklin Roosevelt erected a welfare state. The chance of political longevity turns the mind to grandiose things. Before his re-election, Bill Clinton promised to build a bridge to the 21st century. Will this be another of his glittering rhetorical constructions, with spans of hot air and no visible means of support? Or could it be, against expectation, a solid and useful monument? <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Much will depend on Mr Clinton's estimate of how much America loves him. His 49% of the popular vote was an improvement on 1992; but it was neither hearty, nor a mandate. The fact that the Senate and the House remain Republican shows the limits of public trust in Mr Clinton and his party. Surprisingly, the divided government of the past two years proved rather productive; more important, it brought out a vein of responsibility in the president. Americans seem to want to make sure that a second-term Clinton preserves that virtue, and eschews both hubris and leftish Grand Designs. Yes, they like Mr Clinton; but not that much.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The president, who could never be accused of insensitivity to the public mood, comes into his new term knowing that flexibility has brought his presidency back from the dead. He knows, too, how to make people love him more. His last campaigning year has brought a succession of small presents to the virtuous middle class from a benevolent government: parental leave, college tuition credits, <font size=-1>V</font>-chips to protect children from video nastiness. A hundred such tiny bricks might build a Clinton monument. But it might not be enough for him; and it would certainly not be enough for America.<b><br>
</p><p><b>Unpalatable subjects</b></b><br>
All through the dreary campaign of 1996, certain issues went virtually unmentioned. They are the ones America's people and politicians find hardest to face. They are not amenable to minimalist measures, and offer no immediate return of popular gratitude. Mr Clinton hates that. But the beginning of a second and last term is the best chance--indeed, the only chance--for this shifting and ingratiating character to try to bring America face to face with the facts. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Top of the list come the inner cities, where a bundle of different social pathologies are combining to produce a deeply demoralised, unemployable and even criminal population. A Democrat of the Johnson school might suppose that only massive federal investment could save these places. Mr Clinton knows he does not have that option. But the country is full of local experiments in ghetto housing, welfare, transport and day care which, with visible presidential encouragement and a little well-directed federal money, could be applied more generally. Mr Clinton will have no giant government programmes to announce; but he could make sure that America does more than turn its back. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Part of this policy might involve reforming America's public schools: an issue Mr Clinton has recognised, but without much courage. Despite the tiny federal share of the education budget, the president is not powerless as an advocate. He could lend his support (underlined by careful disposition of existing federal funds) to charter schools that are properly independent, not suborned by his friends in the teachers' unions; to experimental voucher plans; and, most of all, to a standardised system of national examinations. And he should do so with one end in view: to persuade Americans that they are behind in the race to produce competent workers, and that this is a danger to the country's economic health.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor need straight talk end there. During the campaign, the economic and fiscal cycles greatly helped Mr Clinton. But the recovery is already showing signs of slowing down, while the deficit is set to rise again. This means that Mr Clinton can no longer dissemble over where his spending cuts must fall if he wants, as he claims, to leave the legacy of a balanced budget. He should name departments, agencies and programmes; and, most of all, he must tackle middle-class entitlements. This year, he screwed up his courage to end the biggest entitlement for the poor; but the poor are easily dealt with. Mr Clinton's name would ring more loudly down the years if he could revamp Social Security and cut the soaring cost of Medicare, two jealously protected programmes that are on the brink of failing to provide for their dependants. <b><br>
</p><p><b>The necessary focus</b></b><br>
The list could go on. It could include trade (show that America has laid the ghost of protectionism by abandoning talk of "fair trade" and pushing for <font size=-1>NAFTA</font> expansion); racial quotas (admit that current programmes have caused as much resentment as progress, and that they should be either ended or recast to help the poor); and foreign policy (persuade Americans that their involvement in Bosnia, or in other unstable but deserving places, must last if necessary beyond the election cycle and their own comfort level). It is a long agenda. But it is not entirely new. Mr Clinton had already started on some of it, before getting fidgety or hamstrung by his need for the love and gratitude of the voters. Now that that love has been more or less returned, what is needed is a focus on hard facts.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tricky words indeed for the glowing re-elected president: "focus" and "hard facts". Neither has ever been his strong point; and even as he celebrates, he knows that Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater special prosecutor, also has those two themes in mind. Grand strategies and bridges may soon tumble down in partisan strife, or may never be erected. Yet forthrightness about his private dealings, if it comes to that, might not doom him, as some suppose; and forthrightness about the country's failings would be a positive service. Bill Clinton's skill so far--his consummate skill--has been to persuade Americans that by nimble repositioning and soothing rhetoric they are being well-governed. This is not wholly implausible: <i>faute de mieux</i>, it got him re-elected. Now, however, he has a chance to do something really great: to tell the truth.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
