<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/issue/09-11-96/bw0759.html 199.173.162.110 19970113141947 text/html 7257
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 14:15:59 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 07-Nov-96 18:05:25 GMT
Content-length: 7072
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Engaged</h2>
<p>In the biggest-ever foreign takeover of an American company, <b>BT</b>, a British telecoms firm, agreed to pay around $21 billion for the 80% of America's <b>MCI Communications</b> that it does not already own to create a transatlantic giant called Concert. With annual revenues of almost $38 billion, Concert will be the world's fourth-largest telecoms company.</p>
<p>(See <a href="bw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>International <b>mergers and acquisitions</b> rose to $181.7 billion in the first nine months, and were on target for a record year even before <font size=-1>BT</font>'s monumental move. More money was spent on fewer targets and the greatest activity was across the Atlantic; America invested $11.7 billion in Britain, which reciprocated with $11.4 billion--a figure dwarfed by <font size=-1>BT</font>'s acquisition.</p>
<p>Invesco, a British fund manager, also did its bit by paying $1.6 billion for <b>AIMManagement Group</b>, the biggest foreign purchase yet of an American mutual-fund firm. The combined group, Amvesco, will combine Invesco's strength in retail funds with <font size=-1>AIM</font>'s big stockbroker network in America.</p>
<h2>Stormy Sky</h2>
<p><font size=-1>BS</font>ky<font size=-1>B</font> delayed the launch of a Time Warner channel in Britain as the spat between <b>Rupert Murdoch</b>, whose News Corp owns 40% of the <font size=-1>BS</font>ky<font size=-1>B</font> network, and <b>Ted Turner</b>, whose cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> outfit is now owned by Time Warner, worsened. Time Warner has refused to allow a 24-hour news channel from News Corp's Fox on to its New York city cable system. </p>
<p>Italy's Carlo De Benedetti sold his 27.4% stake in <b>Valeo</b>, a car-parts maker, for FFr6.5 billion ($1.3 billion). Because Valeo is that rarest of beasts-- a successful French company in a competitive industry-- many in France wanted it to remain in safe French hands. Their wish was granted: <font size=-1>CGIP</font>, a local holding company, bought 20.3% of the shares, with the rest going to a French financial firm and to J.P. Morgan, <font size=-1>CGIP</font>'s adviser.</p>
<p>In an effort to boost shareholder value, <b>Hoechst</b>, a giant German chemicals company, said it will seek a listing in New York next year. It will also divide itself into six subsidiaries, one of which may be separately quoted.</p>
<p>America's fourth-largest retailer, <b>J.C. Penney</b>, jumped into the fast-consolidating drugstore business by agreeing to buy <b>Eckerd </b>for $2.5 billion and assuming $760m of its debt. The deal will make J.C. Penney the second-largest drug retailer in America.</p>
<p>In Europe, the battle for control of <b>Lloyds Chemists</b>, a British drug retailer, intensified. Gehe of Germany reckons that it has pipped Britain's UniChem with a cash offer of &#163;650.6m ($1.1 billion) for Lloyds. But the contest could well continue.</p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>

<h2>Mopping up</h2>
<p>Determined to cleanse its Augean stables, Japan's new bad-loans agency began bankruptcy proceedings against <b>Sueno Kosan</b>, a property firm that borrowed heavily from the sick mortgage companies at the core of Japan's banking crisis. With over &#165;600 billion ($5.3 billion) in debt, it will be Japan's biggest-ever bankruptcy. More will follow.</p>
<p>The dollar fell sharply against <b>the yen</b> after Eisuke Sakakibara, a senior official at Japan's finance ministry, said in a newspaper interview that he thought the dollar's recovery from its sharp slide last year was about to finish. Japanese bond prices also fell after he described the market's view of the economy as too pessimistic.</p>
<p>The Hungarian government gave <b>ABN Amro</b>, a Dutch bank, the go-ahead to buy an 89% stake in <b>Magyar Hitel Bank</b>, the country's fifth biggest bank by assets. <font size=-1>ABN</font> Amro's bid was chosen ahead of another from Austria's Creditanstalt.</p>
<p>A grand jury in New York is examining whether criminal charges can be laid against some executives<b> </b>of <b>Texaco</b>, an American oil company. The move came after tape transcripts submitted in a discrimination suit brought by some black employees revealed executives using racist terms and discussing whether to destroy papers requested by the employees' lawyer.</p>
<p>Russia's "emergency commission" for <b>tax collection </b>is investigating state-owned Almazy Rossii-Sakha (<font size=-1>ARS</font>), which has a near-monopoly of Russian diamond production. The commission wants details of <font size=-1>ARS</font>'s dealings with De Beers of South Africa, which operates an international diamond cartel, and an explanation of the firm's $570m in debts and its failure to pay dividends even though it had $1.4 billion of sales last year.</p>
<h2>Flying high</h2>
<p>In what could be the biggest-ever order for Europe's <b>Airbus</b> consortium if all the options go through, <b>USAir</b> ordered 120 single-aisle aircraft valued at $5 billion, with options on a further 280. Airbus also announced a price of $198m for its proposed 550-seater plane-- matching Boeing's planned price for a similar aircraft.</p>
<p><font size=-1>(See <a href="bw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>IATA</font> members--250 <b>international airlines</b>--are still on route to make record profits of $5.5 billion this year, but earlier forecasts have been trimmed because of a jump in fuel costs. Morevover those profits are equivalent to a mere 4% return on revenues of $129 billion; combine that with higher costs from increasing regulation and many international airlines still look vulnerable.</p>
<p><b>British Airways</b> won permission from a French court to take over Air Libert&eacute; in partnership with Banque Rivaud. It will invest a FFr440m ($86m) in the defunct regional airline and merge it with <font size=-1>TAT</font>, another regional French carrier that it already owns. <font size=-1>BA</font> also reported a 9.3% rise in first-half profits, to &#163;470m ($718m).</p>
<p></p>

</td></tr></table></center>
