<html><head><title>Not booted</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>The House</b></p>
<h1>Not booted</h1>

<font size=1>WASHINGTON, DC, AND DECATUR, GEORGIA</font><p>
IN THE last weeks of the campaign, as his re-election appeared certain, Bill Clinton basked in predictions that he would be the first Democrat since Franklin Roosevelt to win a second term as president. But Mr Clinton has also made history in a different way, at once more impressive and less pleasing. Not since Woodrow Wilson was elected president in 1916 has a victorious Democrat failed to lead his party to victory in the House. But Mr Clinton has done just that. By Wednesday, with only a few of 435 House races still in doubt, it seemed Mr Clinton's coat-tails would boost Democratic representation in the House by nine seats. The Democrats had needed a 19-seat gain in order to control the chamber.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For Republicans, this represents a heartening change. Their House victory in 1994 had ended 40 years of continuous Democratic control, triggering a furious debate as to whether their ascendancy was a temporary fluke or a lasting realignment. Since the second world war, Republicans had captured the House twice before, in 1946 and 1952; but both triumphs had been erased two years later. Now, with a Republican House re-elected for the first time since 1928, Republicans have laid the fluke theory to rest. And, if history is any guide, they will increase their majority in 1998. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Republicans' biggest achievement was to hold on to all but a few of the 73 seats won for the first time in 1994. Freshmen are always vulnerable, and this year they seemed especially so. As a group, they had acquired a reputation for radical government-cutting. Their enthusiasm for scrapping environmental laws, and for curbing the cost of pensioners' health care, was thought to be especially unpopular. Moreover, the trade unions had spent $35m to try to unseat 32 of the most wobbly freshmen, an unprecedented effort. And yet only 14 freshmen were defeated.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This reflects three factors. Some voters, assuming Mr Clinton would win the presidency, may have shrunk from giving Democrats a "blank cheque". Others may have retained unhappy memories of the last time Democrats ran the House, when official cheques bounced with scandalous abandon. Still others may have been turned against the Democrats by the trade-union campaign. The union ads, accusing freshmen of wanting to "cut" education and health care, were pretty crude; and Republicans were able to hit back with ads saying that the unions, which are not popular in most parts of the land, were plotting to steal the election.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All in all, 77 Republican candidates were defending seats in districts that Mr Clinton carried for the Democrats in 1992. Yet all but 18 (11 freshmen plus seven others) triumphed. The Republicans offset this loss by toppling three Democrats. They also picked up ten formerly Democratic open seats. The large number of Democratic retirements this year (30 in all) worked against the party's hope of gaining the majority. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As in the presidential race, men, especially white men, voted Republican; and rich voters leaned to the Republicans also. As in the presidential race, more money was spent on campaigning than in the past. Yet, as of October 26th, the total raised by all House candidates came to $374m, representing less than $500,000 per candidate. The presidential and Senate campaigns have grown slick to the point of discarding volunteers, whose old tasks of envelope-stuffing and phone-banking have been usurped by computerised professionals. The House races still have home-made charm; they are still chaotic and surprising.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This contributed to one of the more cheering results of this election. Back in the summer, there were fears that black representation in the House would tumble. Judges had ruled unconstitutional nine districts that had been drawn so as to ensure black representation. Despite this, 37 blacks were elected to the House this time. That is one fewer than after the 1994 election, but still an improvement on the 25 returned in 1990.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Best of all, this election showed that blacks can win white votes, even in the South and even without having to compensate for race by espousing conservative opinions. Until now, the only blacks elected from majority-white districts were two Republicans (and one of these, Gary Franks, lost his seat this week). This time round, however, four black Democrats won in majority-white seats. Among them, Cynthia McKinney won with 58% of the vote in a two-thirds white district. And her victory took place a mere half-hour's drive from the district of Newt Gingrich, the conservative House speaker.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The McKinney triumph was unprofessional, unslick, and so all the more endearing. Ms McKinney declared, four days before the vote, that her main ally was "street heat". She had walked across more than a third of her district over the past month, delivering thousands of newsletters by hand. She had stood each morning at highway intersections for two hours, waving placards at commuters. And, with the help of a multiracial band of volunteers, she was set to win. Only one of her wishes failed to come true. Her baseball cap said "Boot Newt" on it.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?847501200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="am3119.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>
1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>

</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT21-B38-41</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA025-000273-B044-44</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/issue/09-11-96/am3119.html 199.173.162.110 19970113142207 text/html 6018
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 14:18:20 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 07-Nov-96 17:45:17 GMT
Content-length: 5833
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Progressives all</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Voter initiatives</b></p>
<h1>Progressives all</h1>

<font size=1>WASHINGTON, DC</font><p>
FOR candidates, election day settles the argument. They win or lose. In the case of propositions--of which there were 93 on the ballot this year, in 20 of the 24 states that allow them--election day is often merely the prelude to years of contention in court. Popular approval of measures does not mean they are constitutional. Nor does it mean that their opponents will gracefully concede defeat.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In California, where 12 propositions were on the ballot this year, the two most controversial passed handsomely: and immediately ran into legal challenges, which may have to go as far as the Supreme Court. The most important of these, Proposition 209, seeks to end all race-or gender-based preferences in state and local-government hiring, contracts and education. Just over 54% of the voters approved this measure; 46% opposed it, including top officials of all the state's colleges and universities. On Wednesday, civil-rights groups filed suit to block the measure, claiming not only that it was unconstitutional but that it conflicted with existing federal law.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Also passed, but delayed by legal challenges, was Proposition 215, which would legalise the use of marijuana in California (under doctor's orders) as a palliative in severe illness. Although cannabis relieves a host of ailments--from seizures to glaucoma to the nausea induced by chemotherapy--the federal government restricts it more tightly than even cocaine or morphine, forbidding doctors' prescriptions and blocking most research.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Arizona voters went further, approving not only the medical use of marijuana but also the parole of drug criminals not deemed to pose a risk to public safety. The money saved from incarceration is to be ploughed back into education and treatment, to which first-and second-time offenders will be sentenced instead of jail. Bill Clinton's drug tsar, Barry McCaffrey, called the proposition "a cruel hoax wrapped up in some attractive ideas", but voters apparently disagreed. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Election day also saw continued machinations by lovers of term limits. Facing a Supreme Court decision that ruled such limits on Congress unconstitutional, a group in Arlington, Virginia, placed similarly-worded initiatives on 14 different state ballots. Nine passed. In those states, legislators are now required to press for a constitutional amendment imposing term limits and, if they do not, to face re-election with ballots saying that they disregarded voters' instructions. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The technique is creative, to say the least. A similar plan worked early this century, when senators were first made subject to a popular vote. It is hard to get excited about term limits, which force voters into a choice they are free to make anyway by booting incumbents out. On the other hand, this is a good place to use referendums to make the public's wishes clear to their representatives. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Campaign-finance reform offers a similar challenge, but voters were encouraged by a heated national debate in the closing weeks of the campaign. Broad reforms passed this year in California, Colorado, Arkansas, Nevada and Maine. And the morally-concerned majority also had its say in Alaska, Colorado, and Washington, rural states where gun groups and hunters wield power disproportionate to their numbers. Propositions were passed there to restrain the use of bait, traps and hunting from aircraft, although anti-hunting measures failed in Michigan and Idaho.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Like the affirmative action fight in California, a number of state initiatives mirror national debates. Proposals to raise the minimum wage beyond the new federal level of $5.15 an hour were rejected in Denver, Missouri and Montana, but passed in California and Oregon. The larger significance of the huge number of initiatives-- more than double the number posted ten years ago--is a return to the enthusiasm for direct democracy that marked the first decades of the century, when many of the laws allowing initiatives were passed in the first place. It is also fitting for the time, now that a Republican Congress and a Democratic president both purport to embrace the states as laboratories of democracy. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;California saw the largest sum ever spent to defeat a proposition: $37m, poured out by corporations to deter Proposition 211, which would have made it exceptionally easy for shareholders to sue them for fraud. The measure was defeated by 74% to 26%. Money's usefulness apart, the moral of 1996 is clear: if you are a white male who wants to work for the minimum wage, bilk small investors and smoke joints when you're ill, California is the place to be.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
