<html><head><title>Loose change</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Campaign money</b></p>
<h1>Loose change</h1>

<font size=1>WASHINGTON, DC</font><p>
THE limp campaign of 1996 has one resonant claim to fame. It was the most expensive ever. Between them, the parties had raised more than $207m by October 16th, compared with $75m in the previous presidential-election year. When donations from individuals and political-action committees (<font size=-1>PAC</font>s), public financing and "independent" expenditures are included, Common Cause, an organisation that worries about such things, reckons the campaign cost a total of $2 billion. Most of it was spent on television advertising.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Last June, the Supreme Court handed down a broad interpretation of "independent" expenditures which emboldened parties to throw even more soft money into important races. Fifteen House candidates had spent more than $1m each by September 30th, with the speaker, Newt Gingrich, on top with $4.1m. According to Common Cause, 68 Senate candidates had by then spent $155m between them: Jesse Helms of North Carolina accounted for $12.2m, John Kerry of Massachusetts for $9.3m and Phil Gramm of Texas for $7.9m. Mr Gramm's opponent, Victor Morales, spent only $323,279. Texas is a particularly lopsided example of a general trend. In 20 races where an incumbent was running, only one challenger had spent more than the incumbent by September 30th.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From his perch in Little Rock on Tuesday night, President Clinton said "we must act and act now" on campaign-finance reform. With enough pressure from Ross Perot, it might happen. Mr Perot's 8% of the vote on Tuesday was a shadow of his 1992 performance, but his voice is still heard. As usual, he offers few specific solutions; he just demands that the problem be "fixed". But how? The Supreme Court has called restrictions on campaign spending a violation of free speech. Short of amending the constitution, then, legislators can assemble only a patchwork of voluntary limits, restriction on donations and free access to the media. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The voters of Maine opted on election day for a more radical approach, in a referendum calling for strict limits on spending and on private donations but offering public money to help candidates with their campaigns. A group of businessmen has derided this as "welfare for politicians". But David Donnelly, a backer of the idea, argues that his state will "truly sever the link" between private money and public officials. The law was designed to meet the Supreme Court's conditions, so it does not stop millionaires spending their own fortunes on their campaigns. But the millionaires' opponents can exceed the ordinary limits, and get extra public money to do so.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some say the current state of affairs is a small price to pay for the quadrennial choice of the country's leader. After all, Americans spent an estimated $2.5 billion on Halloween this year. But most Americans regularly put on their Halloween masks. Only one in 400 gives more than $100 to a political campaign. Behind the mask of politics, cash gets turned into unfair influence. Americans who deplore this phenomenon will be watching Maine with interest.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
