<DOCNO>WT21-B38-47</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA025-000273-B044-202</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/issue/09-11-96/br7575.html 199.173.162.110 19970113142338 text/html 3776
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 14:19:55 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 07-Nov-96 17:45:18 GMT
Content-length: 3591
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Oil bonus</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>Oil bonus</h1>

ONE bit of inflation has been good news for Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor of the exchequer: the rising oil price (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). Since August, the price of Brent North Sea, the marker crude, has risen from less than $20 to more than $25 a barrel. In the last few days, it has fallen back a bit but it is still nearly 25% higher than three months ago. Since the $14 low-point in the first quarter of 1994, oil prices have risen by 75%.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the last Treasury pronouncement on the effect of the oil price on government revenues, six years ago, officials estimated that a $10 rise in the price of a barrel of crude, if sustained for a year, would result in an increase in revenues of about &#163;2 billion. Since 1990, taxes on North Sea oil have been lowered, so, according to analysts, the benefit of a $10 increase is now reckoned to be about &#163;1.5 billion. Still, this windfall, equivalent to a reduction of more than 1p in the standard rate of income tax, is not to be sneezed at--especially by a hard-pressed Chancellor facing a pre-election budget in a month's time.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the longer term, however, the effects of higher oil prices are less beneficial. According to Opal, an oil-price research company, the price of unleaded petrol at the pumps has risen by an average of about 5p per litre since the low point of 54p per litre in July. Goldman Sachs, an investment bank, predicts that inflation in the world's five richest countries is likely to increase by 0.2-0.3% by the end of the year as a direct result of the movement in crude. British exporters are also anxiously monitoring the exchange rate. Over the past two months, the pound has risen strongly against both the dollar and the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark, to $1.64 and DM2.49 respectively.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Will the price stay high? Goldman Sachs predicts that the price of crude will average $25 a barrel in the last quarter of this year and in the first quarter of 1997. Other oil analysts disagree: there is still plenty of spare capacity, and production may start increasing. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The oil companies, meanwhile, are not complaining. <font size=-1>BP</font> announced on November 5th that its third-quarter profits had risen 33% to &#163;761m. Sir David Simon, its chairman, said the chancellor should not even think of a windfall tax. Now there's a thought.<br>
<br>
</td></tr></table>


<p align=center>
