<html><head><title>A lot at stake</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>The Co-operative movement</b></p>
<h1>A lot at stake</h1>

<font size=1>MANCHESTER</font><p>
GRAHAM MELMOTH hopes to be the Tony Blair of retailing. On November 4th Mr Melmoth became chief executive of the largest part of Britain's Co-op movement: the Co-operative Wholesale Society (<font size=-1>CWS</font>), a mutually owned conglomerate with annual sales of &#163;3 billion ranging from fish fingers to funerals, pensions to package holidays. Like Labour before Mr Blair became its leader, the Co-ops have been losing business to their capitalist rivals, and finding it hard to recruit young people. Not only does Mr Melmoth want a New Labour-style revival, he sees a modernised Co-op as the very heart of the "stakeholder society" that Mr Blair dreams of.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour and the Co-ops share common roots. Poor conditions in Britain's industrial towns in the 19th century led to the Labour movement's rise and were the reason why the Rochdale Pioneers set up the first Co-op in 1844, so that the poor could club together to buy decent, affordable food. The idea spread across Britain and at one point there were 1,400 local Co-op societies. But in modern times, fierce competition from privately owned supermarkets has led to a string of mergers and closures. There are now just 52 Co-op societies, of which by far the largest are <font size=-1>CWS</font> (which started out as the movement's wholesaler) and Co-operative Retail Services (<font size=-1>CRS</font>).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In spite of repeated attempts at modernisation, the Co-ops have continued to lose customers in recent years (see <a href="br2.gif">chart</a>). Their main problem is that whatever they do, capitalist firms do it better. Their original job of feeding the poor is now done by deep-discount supermarket chains like Aldi and Netto, whose prices are lower. Most Co-ops these days are aimed at the mass market. But, says Richard Hyman of Verdict, a retail consultancy, the stores and their product lines are often years behind their capitalist competitors.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Co-ops' mutual-ownership status means they cannot easily raise capital on the stockmarket, limiting their ability to invest in updating their stores. But, unlike those building societies which are heading for the stockmarket, Mr Melmoth does not accept that mutuality is past its sell-by date. Anyway, <font size=-1>CWS</font>'s complex ownership (it is owned both by individual shoppers and by other Co-op societies) would make a flotation highly impractical. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Melmoth says the Co-ops still have a strong position in catering to small towns and in running "convenience" stores. But even such unfashionable redoubts are now under attack. Giants like Tesco are building smaller shops in such secondary locations because new planning rules are limiting the number of sites for giant stores. Convenience stores are also being added at many petrol stations, and the deep-discounters are still expanding, grabbing more of the Co-op's cash-strapped shoppers.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How can the Co-ops fight this fresh onslaught? Recently, they have decided that if they cannot compete on price or product range, then they will compete on morals. Updating the principles of the Rochdale Pioneers, <font size=-1>CWS</font> is promoting itself as the "Responsible Retailer", championing "fair trade" with poor countries and selling environmentally friendly products. Its Co-op Bank subsidiary has won new customers by promising not to lend to dictators or firms that test their products on animals. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This has two big flaws. First, such lofty principles appeal most to the young and affluent, not the old and poor, who shop at the Co-op (and which it would not want to desert). Second, if ethics sell groceries, you can bet that capitalist supermarkets will turn moral. As if to prove this, on October 28th Tesco began selling organically grown fruit and vegetables at the same price as their intensively farmed equivalents.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As well as joining Tony Blair on the moral bandwagon, Mr Melmoth hopes to emulate his successful recruitment drive, by turning more Co-op shoppers into "stakeholders", ie, members of a Co-op society. Members used to be rewarded through the "divi", a loyalty-card scheme which most Co-ops abandoned years ago because it was too costly. Ironically, just as Co-ops are talking of bringing the divi back, their rivals, led by Tesco, have got in first with loyalty cards of their own. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One way of making the 52 Co-op societies more competitive would be to merge them, thereby cutting costs and rationalising the muddle of different names and formats that they trade under. But repeated attempts to merge <font size=-1>CWS</font> and <font size=-1>CRS</font> have failed; last month, plans to merge their non-food stores collapsed. Mr Melmoth plans to have another go, but even if he succeeds, a united Co-op would still be too small. So his short-term job (again, like Tony Blair's) is to continue his predecessors' work of modernising <font size=-1>CWS</font>, replacing a bureaucratic regional structure with a strong, centralised management and a clear marketing strategy.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;New Labour might not like to be associated with the Co-op's dowdy image but it should take an interest nonetheless. The Co-op movement is the nearest Britain gets to Mr Blair's "stakeholder" vision. If its approach cannot survive in competition with shareholder capitalism, the movement will prove that Mrs Thatcher was right when she said "there is no alternative". And one day soon, there may be no such thing as the Co-operative Wholesale Society.<br>

<p align=center>
