<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><p align=center>
<table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</p></center>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width="231" height="24" alt="Britain in Brief" border=0></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p><b>High interest</b> &nbsp; The Bank of England said the government was now unlikely to meet its target of bringing inflation down to 2.5%, and would probably have to raise interest rates further. It implied that a tough budget would limit the need for higher rates.<br>
<p><b>US advice</b> &nbsp; George Stephanopoulos, an adviser to Bill Clinton, has offered his services to the Labour Party's election campaign.<br>
<p><b>No ceasefire</b> &nbsp; Ronnie Flanagan, the new chief constable of the Royal Ulster Constabulary, said he believed the <font size=-1>IRA</font> leadership had held a "very significant" meeting on future tactics, but he did not expect an imminent ceasefire.<br>
<p><b>Last chance</b> &nbsp; Gillian Shephard, the education secretary, gave The Ridings school in Calderdale until the end of the month to produce a plan to overcome the school's serious disciplinary problems, or a government "hit squad" would be sent in to run the school.<br>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Blair backed</b> &nbsp; Labour Party members voted by a 19-1 margin to support the draft manifesto proposed by Tony Blair, the party's leader.<br>
<p><b>Howard attacked</b> &nbsp; Michael Howard, the home secretary, was criticised by Kenneth Baker and Douglas Hurd, two of his predecessors, over his plans to introduce mandatory sentences for repeat offenders.<br>
<p><b>Cutting edge</b> &nbsp; Police are to get new powers to stop and search people for knives or drugs. There will also be new laws to control the sale of combat knives.<br>
<p><b>Bank job</b> &nbsp; Seven men admitted a plot to steal huge sums of money by intercepting the electronic links between networks of cash dispensers, which the prosecution said would have put the entire banking system at risk.<br>
<p> <p><b>Thin yellow line</b> &nbsp; Traffic wardens in Durham are to be issued with body armour to protect them against gun and knife attacks.<br><br>

</td></tr></table></center>

