</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Clinton's slippery coat-tails</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>

</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>Clinton's slippery coat-tails</h1>

AS THE barber-shop quartet at the American embassy's election-night bash swung into "Georgia on my Mind", Bagehot spotted two modernising members of Britain's rival political parties in animated conversation. Were they debating what President Clinton's victory meant for America's budget deficit? Whether he would remain involved in Bosnia? Where next for the Helms-Burton act and Europe's trade with Cuba? Bagehot sidled nearer.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"It's just as we've been telling you," he heard the one in the Armani suit with the blue carnation in the buttonhole say. "It's the economy, stupid. Wait until next May when voters here start focusing on the bottom line, and they'll be flocking back to John Major just like they've flocked back to Bill Clinton on the other side of the pond. I don't care whether it's Bill or John, whatever you throw at an incumbent, you're not going to persuade voters that everything is bad when they are feeling good."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Trust you to be superficial," replied the one in the Armani suit with the red rose in the buttonhole. "Yes, of course the economy is important in any election, but that plays for us, not you. American voters admire the way Bill Clinton has cut the deficit, just as British voters admire the way Tony Blair got Labour away from tax-and-spend. When Bill talks education and training, voters think he talks sense--just as they do when Tony does it for us. As for your government, the voters fingered you as a load of bunglers from the day Britain left the European exchange-rate mechanism in 1992."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Though he was drinking only Perrier with his pecan pie, Mr Blair's colleague was becoming animated. "Here's the real message of tonight. Two years ago America fell into the hands of the crew who dominate your party here. There was Newt Gingrich and his 'Contract with America' and the religious right. Sure, it had its appeal; I don't deny that. But the American people tried it, and they didn't like it.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"It's the same with your lot here. Voters have had it up to their necks with right-wing policies. They've had it with right-wing rhetoric. And don't forget they've had 17 years of it where America has only had two.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Of course, they don't want the left either, which is why we've modernised. We've done just what Bill Clinton did to the Democrats, moving away from big government. Tony is Bill without the sex and the sleaze, which is why in May your lot will be history."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Sleaze, you're on to that old story again are you?" his Tory friend interposed. "Like your blessed Tony with that holier-than-thou crap of his? Look what has happened in America. There's Bob Dole, the war hero; there's Bill Clinton, sleaze incarnate--and who wins? Mr Sleaze. John Major is 'Honest John'. Do you really think sleaze could actually destroy him, when it hasn't stopped Clinton being re-elected?"<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Alright, sleaze may not have worked in America but neither have tax cuts," said his Labour friend. "You keep on telling me that Kenneth Clarke has only to cut taxes now, and promise more to come, and our poll ratings will plummet.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Well that didn't work in America, did it? Bob Dole promised tax cuts yet the voters were not interested. Some of them remembered that he used to be against bribery. It's the same with you. If you start cutting taxes now, British voters will remember the 22 times you've put them up since 1992."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"That proves nothing," said the Tory. "Bob Dole's problem was not that he promised tax cuts. Bob Dole's problem was that he was a lousy candidate.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"He never had a strategy. First he said that Clinton was a liberal, then he said he was stealing the Republicans' clothes. First he refused to play the sleaze card, then he was attacking Hillary. Bob Dole must be the worst candidate for high office since you ran Michael Foot in 1983. And despite all that, he started the campaign 20 points behind the president and finished up only eight points down.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"We Tories are going to stick to our lines. At least, we're going to stick to them unless the goons from Central Office persuade the prime minister to get side-tracked on to <font size=-1>EMU</font>. 'The Enterprise Centre of Europe.' 'New Labour, New Danger.' 'Opportunity for all.' And even you have to admit that John Major is a great campaigner. Remember the soap box? Remember his passion over the constitution in 1992? Well, you ain't seen nothing yet." <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The two paused to wave away a waiter bearing a tray of margaritas. Bagehot could bear to remain silent no longer. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Gentlemen, gentlemen. I have listened to you burbling on for the last half-hour and it has rarely been my misfortune to endure such a farrago of stuff and nonsense. The truth is that the American election and the British election are different sorts of events in different political systems played to different rules with different campaigning instruments. It is therefore not surprising that, as a cursory glance at the record will show, there is no correlation of any kind to be found between the results of 13 post-war presidential elections and those of Britain's 14 general elections. Incumbents win, incumbents lose; left and right advance and retreat; good candidates do well and bad candidates do badly on both sides of the Atlantic, in a way that is entirely <i>sui generis</i> to each particular election in each country in the circumstances of each election year; and therefore, despite your half-plausible theorising and your special pleading and your ingenious attempts to link what is not linked, nothing you have said has the least bearing on the question of which of your parties will win Britain's general election next year. Gentlemen, I bid you both good night."<br>
</td></tr></table>


<p align=center>
