<html><head><title>The silicon tigers' electric shocker</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Asian electronics</b></p>
<h1>The silicon tigers' electric shocker</h1>

<font size=1>SINGAPORE</font><p>
<p><b>The economic fortunes of Asian economies are bound up with the electronics industry. A self-inflicted glut is causing a scare</b></p><br>
WHETHER it is making cellular telephones, computers, televisions, pocket calculators or the chips that make them all work, nearly every country in Asia is involved in some aspect of the electronics industry. That is only natural. The electronics business can be entered in all sorts of ways, by making anything from simple components to elaborate consumer products. But too many tigers chasing even as buoyant a market as electronics is a recipe for glut. If the market turns down, Asian economies' fortunes will be dragged down with it.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Asian countries' dominance of some consumer-electronics markets is phenomenal. Taiwanese companies, for instance, make eight out of ten circuit boards found in the world's personal computers and half of the keyboards plugged into them. Singapore makes some 40% of the world's disk drives, and a third of <font size=-1>PC</font> microprocessors are packaged and tested in Malaysia. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the market into which Asian companies have leapt furthest is the one for memory chips. When shortages drove up chip prices four years running in the early 1990s, even Taiwanese food companies and plastic makers began building $1 billion-a-pop chip-making plants. Such diversification no doubt seemed irresistible at a time when margins were sometimes above 80%. But the resulting glut caused prices to collapse earlier this year--by as much as 70% for memory chips, which are used in products ranging from <font size=-1>PC</font>s to photocopiers.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now there appear to be signs of a return to what the semiconductor industry apparently considers "normal": output is set to rise and prices to resume their long-term decline at 30% a year. America's Semiconductor Industry Association forecasts that the value of chip sales will grow worldwide by 3.5% in the fourth quarter; but that is still modest compared with last year's 42% increase. For the time being, some of the new plants are likely to be mothballed.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The markets for the things that chips go into are still growing briskly (see <a href="wb2.gif">chart</a>). The number of personal computers worldwide is still forecast to rise by 16% between this year and 1997, according to International Data Corp, an American research firm. But prices are unlikely to stop falling--especially now that Hitachi and Sony, two of Japan's biggest consumer-electronics giants, are muscling into the computer business.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The danger in this is that the fortunes of Asia's economies are closely linked to those of the electronics industry, and especially to memory chips. The repercussions of plunging chip prices have been felt throughout the region. In the first half of this year, export growth throughout East Asia collapsed to just 7%, compared with 28% in the same period a year earlier, according to the Asian Development Bank (<font size=-1>ADB</font>). The bank suggests several reasons: the weaker yen has made Japan more competitive, and some countries in the region, such as China and Indonesia, are trying to cool their economies. But the <font size=-1>ADB</font>'s economists also lay a large part of the blame on a downturn in the electronics business.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Depressed demand for electronic products partly explains slower growth in Singapore. Its manufactured exports (two-thirds of which are electronics goods) shrank by 6% in September, while <font size=-1>GDP</font> growth in the third quarter had slowed to just 3.2% from a year earlier, when it was racing along at 8%. South Korea and Taiwan, two other countries that rely heavily on electronics, are also turning in lower growth figures.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To make matters worse for Asia's tigers, the region's poorer nations are also trying to muscle into the electronics business. The ensuing battle could keep capacity running well ahead of demand. The Philippines is one of the latest to push into electronics in a big way. From a low base, the value of its electronics exports surged by 45% in the first seven months of this year. With a relatively cheap, well-educated, workforce that speaks good English--the language of the computer industry--the country is pitching hard for more business. "I think we can assume overcapacity will be here for some time," says Liow Voon Kheong, director of the electronics division of Singapore's Economic Development Board. To help its electronics companies cope, Singapore recently launched a crash training programme to give more people the sort of skills the firms might want.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Faced with stiffer competition, firms will search out the fastest-growing niches. Many Taiwanese firms think that they have found a promising one: making lap-top computers, mostly for western firms such as Compaq, <font size=-1>IBM</font>, Hewlett-Packard, Apple and Dell. Lap-top computers tend to have higher profit margins than desktop <font size=-1>PC</font>s because they are more complex to make, and unit sales have been growing by 30% a year. This year Taiwan aims to make nearly 4m of them, overtaking Japan as the world's leading producer.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If other Asian firms follow suit, the Taiwanese could respond by shifting production to cheaper areas. Taiwan's Acer, which is the world's fourth-largest computer firm, has already opened a factory in the Philippines. Yet chasing cheap labour around the Pacific rim is no longer as helpful as it used to be. These days, wages account for less than 5% of the cost of producing many electronic goods. Far more value may therefore be added by nimble staff who can quickly redesign a product, rather than by opening an assembly plant in a country paying lower wages. The sooner Asia's tigers learn that lesson, the better.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?847501200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
