<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Currency capers</h2>
<p>(See <a href="bw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>The <b>dollar </b>reached a 3.5-year high against a flagging yen. But the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark rose strongly against the greenback after the country's leading economic institutes predicted that Germany might not fulfil the criteria for joining European economic and monetary union, and that German interest rates could soon rise. Meanwhile, an unexpected quarter-point rise in British interest rates caused an already strong pound to jump to a 20-month high of $1.63.</p>
<p>In South Africa, the <b>rand </b>fell to a record low of 4.74 to the dollar. Worries about the country's minuscule foreign reserves were among the things that were blamed for the currency's decline.</p>
<p>The <font size=-1>IMF</font> said payments of its $10 billion loan to Russia could resume soon. But first it wants to be sure that the government is tackling the country's <b>massive tax arrears</b>. Russian officials have launched bankruptcy proceedings against four big companies and threatened several others with similar action.</p>
<h2>Called to account</h2>
<p>Independent auditors, under the aegis of a committee led by a former chairman of America's Fed, Paul Volcker, are to be granted unprecedented access to <b>Swiss bank accounts</b> as part of an investigation into whether Swiss banks have disguised the assets of Nazi victims from their rightful owners.</p>
<p>Two of the biggest <b>German regional banks</b>,<b> </b>state-owned Norddeutsche Landesbank and Bankgesellschaft Berlin, in which the state of Berlin has a 56% stake, said that they were discussing a closer alliance. A full merger between the two would create Germany's second-biggest bank, with DM500 billion ($330 billion) of assets.</p>
<p><b>Deutsche Bank</b>, Germany's biggest, said that Rolf Breuer, a management-board member, will succeed Hilmar Kopper as its chief executive next May. Mr Breuer has helped to mastermind the bank's aggressive push into investment banking.</p>
<p>Several current and former senior executives of <b>ITC</b>, an Indian tobacco company in which Britain's <font size=-1>B.A.T</font> Industries has a stake, were arrested in connection with alleged violations of the country's foreign-exchange rules. </p>
<h2>Border controls</h2>
<p>France's prime minister, Alain Jupp&eacute;, promised to hold a parliamentary debate on the transfer of <b>Thomson Multimedia</b> to Daewoo, a South Korean company, as part of the government's plan to sell Thomson <font size=-1>SA</font>, a state conglomerate, to the Lagard&egrave;re group. Opposition to a sale of the consumer-electronics arm to the Korean firm is growing.</p>
<p>After winning over a recalcitrant Denmark, European Union foreign ministers formed a united front against America's <b>anti-Cuba legislation</b>. European legislation will make it illegal for <font size=-1>EU</font> firms to comply with American court rulings on the issue.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>(See <a href="bw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Italy's privatisation plans were boosted when its heavily oversubscribed sale of 14% of <b>ENI</b>, an energy giant, raised 7.7 trillion lire ($5 billion). The sell-off, which was the country's largest ever, cuts the state's stake in <font size=-1>ENI</font> to 71%. But plans to privatise <font size=-1>STET</font>, a telecoms group, are likely to be delayed until late 1997 because of political wrangling.</p>
<p>Britain's privatised utilities attracted attention yet again. <b>CalEnergy </b>of Nebraska launched a &#163;766m ($1.25 billion) hostile bid for <b>Northern Electric</b> and grabbed 13% of its shares in a dawn raid. </p>
<p>Battling on-line rivals and the Internet, <b>America Online</b> is separating into three operating divisions and revamping its pricing structure. Robert Pittman, former head of <font size=-1>MTV</font> Networks, will head the firm's core on-line division. The firm is also taking a $460m charge for its restructuring.<b> Microsoft</b> also created a new division, which will separate its Network on-line service and cable-<font size=-1>TV</font> channel from its software operations.</p>
<p>A French luxury-goods firm, <font size=-1>LVMH</font> Mo&euml;t Hennessy Louis Vuitton, is paying FFr12.6 billion ($2.5 billion) for a majority stake in San Francisco's <font size=-1>DFS</font>, the world's largest distributor of <b>luxury goods</b>,<b> </b> which has extensive dealings in East Asia. The deal is being challenged by some of <font size=-1>DFS</font>'s minority shareholders in America.</p>
<p>Dieter Bock resigned as chief executive of <b>Lonrho</b>, a British conglomerate, to become its non-executive deputy chairman, and sold his 18.3% stake to South Africa's Anglo American for &#163;258m ($422m). He will re-invest the cash in Lonrho's trading operations when the group completes its three-way split into hotels, trading and mining businesses. Stakis, a British hotel and casino group, offered to buy Lonrho's five luxury Metropole Hotels for &#163;327m.</p>
<h2>Lotus-eating</h2>
<p><b>Proton</b>, a Malaysian car maker, is paying &#163;51m ($83m) for a 64% stake in <b>Lotus</b>, a British car maker best known for its luxurious sports cars.</p>
<p><b>Volkswagen</b> said that it would appeal against a decision by a German court to dismiss its lawsuit accusing Opel, a subsidiary of General Motors, of defamation. The charge relates to a press conference in March, when Opel and <font size=-1>GM</font> announced that they had filed a lawsuit against <font size=-1>VW</font> alleging industrial espionage.</p>
<p><b>McDonnell Douglas </b> dropped a $3 billion plan to build what would have been its biggest-ever aircraft, the long-range <font size=-1>MD</font>-<font size=-1>XX</font>. The plane was to have put the company back in the big jet market.</p>

</td></tr></table></center>
