<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/issue/02-11-96/sf0783.html 199.173.162.110 19970113142903 text/html 20269
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 14:25:01 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 31-Oct-96 19:22:32 GMT
Content-length: 20083
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Where's the outrage?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif" width="407" height="26" alt="Special feature">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Where's the outrage?</h1>

<p><b>In January, America's voters were thought to be furious. Now, on the eve of the election, they seem remarkably content. What happened?</b></p><br>
THIS was meant to be an election fuelled by anger. Back in February, when Pat Buchanan won the New Hampshire primary, pundits noted that Americans were miserable, furious, insecure in their jobs, frightened of technology and still incensed with politicians. Of the candidates available then, only Mr Buchanan, with his eloquent invocations of class warfare and immigrant hordes, seemed to tap that feeling. "The peasants are coming with pitchforks!" he cried, summoning up a vision of his supporters besieging Evil Baron Bill in White Castle. Naturally, he could not win. But it was no surprise to see first Bob Dole, the Republican, and then Bill Clinton himself, setting off in hot pursuit of the discontented voters Mr Buchanan had spoken for. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a time, "insecurity" was the issue of the day. The candidates remembered, all too acutely, the fate of George Bush in 1992. Mr Bush had been taken by surprise in New Hampshire, again by Mr Buchanan, because he had failed to note that three-quarters of the voters there were worried about the economy<i>.</i> In 1992, the worries had been genuine. The economy had been slow to recover from recession; and, although the underlying indicators were healthy, the electorate was not then feeling the benefit. Bill Clinton's campaign mantra, "The rich got richer, and the middle class got the shaft", hit home; in their droves, the blue-collar Democrats who had switched to Ronald Reagan in the 1980s turned back to the Democratic Party. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This year, to all appearances, the state of the middle class (which in America encompasses almost everyone between janitors and millionaires), seemed equally unhappy. Since 1993, the North American Free-Trade Agreement had potentially enabled more jobs to be lost to low-wage Mexico (the "giant sucking sound"). Immigration, both legal and illegal, was at record levels. Companies were plunging headlong into the new vogue of "downsizing", boosting share prices while eliminating jobs in their thousands--and these were in secure industries, such as aerospace or telecoms, on which the post-war American dream had been founded. Worst of all, stagnant wages, which had been a feature of the 1980s, began to affect larger numbers of people higher up the income scale. Two jobs, rather than one, were needed to keep a middle-class family in the style to which it had become accustomed; and with working women had come a host of new social strains and difficulties.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The candidates in 1996 played with these issues for weeks. Yet, try as they might, they could not suggest what to do about them. In 1992, the solution had been relatively easy: a middle-class tax cut. Both Mr Clinton and Mr Bush offered one, and it was eagerly received: so eagerly, that it took Ross Perot to remind both candidates of the virtues of a balanced budget. This year, however, taxes have seemed to have little to do with the underlying malaise.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The presence in the Republican primaries of Steve Forbes, a billionaire publisher with a one-plank platform of a flat tax, encouraged most of the Republican candidates to flirt with their versions of a flat tax in the early months of the year. Mr Forbes disappeared early and the flat tax went with him, at least as an election issue. Only a shade of it--Mr Dole's vague promise of a "fairer and flatter" system--survived in the Republicans' economic plan. To the degree they grasped the flat-tax argument, voters seemed genuinely worried that it would not be revenue-neutral, but would be an unacceptable crimp on government. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Once the flat tax was set aside, both Mr Dole and Mr Clinton began to emphasise their original offer of tax cuts for the middle classes. But here was another surprise: the voters seemed wary, and not even particularly interested. Mr Dole's offer of a cut of 15%, the central theme of his campaign, never caught fire. Voters simply did not believe his arithmetic. Mr Clinton's smaller tax cut, not much more than a token nod to middle-class worries, was preferred because it was safer. Indeed, polls showed that most Americans, offered a choice between the Republican tax cut and a balanced budget, much preferred the latter.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps, then, the issue of job insecurity could be addressed directly. But this proved hard. Suggestions by Robert Reich, the labour secretary, that the government should try to oblige corporations to behave "more responsibly" towards their workers, got precisely nowhere. Mr Dole's brief attack on Wall Street greed was so ridiculous that it was abandoned the next day. Mr Clinton, who was not then actively campaigning, wisely kept his head down. Candidates were quickly reminded that it is unthinkable for an American government-- even one controlled by Democrats--to tell firms how to behave. The flurry died down.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But if corporations could not be blamed for middle-class anxiety, other things could. On the right, the Republicans had already taken up cudgels against both affirmative action and immigration, on no firm evidence that either was a stealer of middle-class jobs. The Clinton administration, too, had promised to review policies in both fields. Bills to overturn affirmative action and to crack down on immigration were already going through Congress. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a time, it seemed that these might be the hot issues of 1996. They were not. Outside California--where both issues have been the subject of contentious local propositions--voters failed to seize on either racial quotas or immigration as a focus for their anger. And once Mr Buchanan had retired from the scene, no candidate tried to encourage them. The votes of blacks and Latinos were not so lightly to be tossed away. Besides, as far as jobs and wages were concerned, most Americans were not at all as angry as they seemed. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This fact became increasingly clear as the campaign proceeded. In retrospect, the fury of January and February looks like the last gasp of wilful economic ignorance, before the figures became so relentlessly encouraging that Americans could no longer ignore them. Even at the end of last year, employment in the old manufacturing industries of the mid-west was rising so fast that workers had to be recruited from other states. <font size=-1>NAFTA</font> was found not to have exported jobs to Mexico; on the contrary, a new taste for American goods there added to job-creation north of the border. Downsizing had been balanced either by the creation of new jobs in the same companies, or by the opening of new opportunities elsewhere.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Increasingly, voters reported that they felt happier both about Mr Clinton's management of the economy, and about their own prospects. The president's bold claims to have created 10.5m new jobs, to have lowered unemployment to 5.1% and to have encouraged a long and solid expansion, were allowed to pass without much remark even by Republicans.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dole's assertion that the economy was "in bad shape" found no hearers; the claims of Jack Kemp, his running mate, that the economy could grow at twice the rate of the Clinton years were received with the ridicule they deserved. The typical swing voter was no longer the anguished man with a pink slip; it was the "soccer mom" whose four-wheel-drive car, demanding job and attendance at well-groomed football pitches suggested a prosperity hampered only by a chronic lack of time. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Undoubtedly, not everyone was lifted by the economic boom. But those who were left behind were increasingly the young, black, ill-educated or unskilled, whose votes were insignificant because they often did not bother to vote. Once most Americans reported that they felt more cheerful about their prospects, the issue of insecurity vanished: at least for the moment, and at least as fuel for anyone's campaign. <br>
</p><p><b>The moral high ground</b><br>What then of the other angry issues? At one time, there were plenty of them. Abortion, for example, had not died down since 1973, when a decision of the Supreme Court made it legal. The Christian right (disappointed in its efforts to get anti-abortion measures included in the Republicans' "Contract with America" of 1994) had vowed to fill the Republican convention with delegates pledged to oppose abortion.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Its efforts were largely successful. Yet the issue, while still mentioned locally, never surfaced for long in the national debate. This was largely because Mr Dole let it be known that the Republican Party could comfortably accommodate both supporters and opponents of abortion. Such an assurance stretched credulity, but it worked. For in truth, again, most of America is not angry about abortion; it dislikes the practice, believes it should be legal but rare, and is sick of the politicisation of the subject. Even Mr Clinton's veto of a bill banning partial-birth abortions, which provoked angry protests from America's Catholic bishops, caused barely a flicker in the mood of the electorate. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There might have been more mileage in that other pre-eminent issue of the right, moral decline. The topic was passionately debated in 1992, after Dan Quayle, Mr Bush's running mate, regretted the portrayal of single motherhood as an acceptable "lifestyle choice" in a television soap opera. At the Republican convention in Houston that year, Mr Buchanan's tirade about the liberal onslaught on Judeo-Christian values was rapturously received.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;From a conservative moralist's point of view, nothing in American media or public life has improved since that speech was made. Indeed, the presidency itself is now occupied by a man of questionable moral character. But the fate of the issue lay with the personality of the conservative candidate. Mr Dole was intent on avoiding moral righteousness to preserve the unity of his party, and the embarrassed cough of a decent man was no substitute. He struck a chord for a time with a bold attack on Hollywood for filling America's screens with violence and promiscuity; but, after Hollywood huffed, he more or less dropped the subject. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the closing weeks of the campaign, and especially in the second presidential debate, Mr Dole homed in on the ethically-challenged White House itself; but the connection between impenetrable Arkansas scandals, Asian fund-raisers and any wider sense of moral drift proved difficult to make. "Where's the outrage?" asked Mr Dole, plaintively, in Dallas on October 25th. Good question. But time and again, polls showed that voters were not much bothered by Mr Clinton's personal shortcomings. If he was a good <font size=-1>CEO</font>, they were happy to overlook the rest. And by September, the president did indeed seem to be the successful manager of contented folk: which raises the question: if he had not been, would he have weathered so buoyantly the justified attacks on his character? <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is not quite the whole story. To some extent, Mr Clinton's embrace of welfare reform in mid-campaign also deflated the issue of moral decline. In 1992, it could be argued (and was by both sides) that the system of welfare payments was a prime cause of demoralisation, dependency and inner-city failure. By 1996, the key word "responsibility" was being proclaimed at full blast by both parties. The easy dichotomy of 1992 (or, even more, of 1994) between morally stern Republicans and sloppily compassionate Democrats had disappeared in at least one vital area of government policy; it therefore became harder to argue that it was true in general. <br></p><p><b>A pox on both parties<br></b>Americans, however, were meant to be angry with politicians as a species this year, regardless of label. Observers of politics just before the Republican cataclysm of 1994 had described an electorate seething with a fury that could scarcely be explained. Incumbents were self-satisfied; the power of special interests was unbudgeable; too much time was spent in Washington; there was no accountability or control. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since most of the 1994 incumbents were Democrats, this discontent seemed easily remedied by a switch of parties in Congress--especially when Republicans were promising an upheaval. But voters remained angry even after they had kicked the Democratic bums out. The Republican honeymoon (and, in particular, the honeymoon of Newt Gingrich, the abrasive speaker of the House and self-appointed revolutionary leader) ended within a year, even though the freshmen in Congress delivered, or tried to deliver, almost everything they had promised. Rumour had it that the American voter was unappeasable; he hated both Republicans and Democrats. And his anger this time might really induce him to go for a third party.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It did not happen. It hardly ever happens, of course; but Ross Perot's 19% in 1992 had been impressive, and voters did not seem so angry then. Why did Mr Perot's campaign fail so signally in 1996? Partly because he was neither as fresh nor as visible as before; partly because his suppression of dissent in his Reform Party left a sour taste. But Americans were also not half as angry with the status quo as they were said to be. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For all the tirades against Republicans and Democrats, the truth is that the two big parties still deliver the goods both nationally and, more to the point, locally. At election time, the big-party machinery (with its plentiful lubricant of special-interest money) swings impressively into gear, and voters are swept along by it. Americans this year might have had some cause to be angry about a rotten choice of candidates; instead, they were resigned and passionless.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Besides, a third party succeeds only when it can harness an issue that is stirring the country to some extraordinary degree, but which the big parties are ignoring. Mr Perot's anti-deficit jeremiads almost provided such an issue in 1992; but both Republicans and Democrats have now seized that theme for their own, and no other similarly galvanising issue can be found these days. Americans in early 1996, asked which issues worried them, gave about 11% equally to crime, schools, the economy and a number of other things (see <a href="sf1.gif">chart</a>). This was the clearest sign--and it should not, perhaps, have come as a surprise--that there was no single furious torrent in January, more a confluence of streams which have since trickled out along numerous different channels and are now on the point of sinking into the ground. <br></p><p><b>The good old status quo</b><br>In fact, the overwhelming impression of the 1996 campaign is that voters, far from being furious with government, want things to remain pretty much as they are. They want none of the big entitlement programmes--Medicare, Social Security and the rest--to be touched. They like Mr Clinton's little bits of government-intervention-at-the-margin, on such matters as school uniforms and parental leave. They succeeded two years ago in kicking out an entrenched form of government, which has refreshed the debate; but they have also had their brush with revolution, and a little went a long way.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Republicans after the 1994 election misread voters' anger as badly as the Democrats did before it. They thought they had been given a mandate to deregulate, shrink government, cut spending and cut taxes. In fact, the negative grumpiness of voters did not translate into a positive passion for something different. Americans did not really know what they wanted. As it happens, parts of the revolution they got--from the banning of unfunded federal mandates to the turning over of welfare payments to the states--have made voters feel they are slightly more in control of the machinery of government. And there is nothing like the delegation of a portion of responsibility to make people feel that they are happy for the government to go on doing the rest.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Of the various shows of temper of the past few years, only two cases of genuine anger can be discerned: frustration with stagnant wages and with incumbent politicians. Incomes have still not moved much: although average household income rose in 1995 for the first time in six years, earnings for full-time workers, both men and women, declined. As for incumbents, plenty are still ensconced, while the brave new freshmen of 1994 have discovered the charms of special-interest money. But even a small sign of movement in the right direction has made for a generally placid electorate, who seem poised to return a mediocre incumbent by a massive margin. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For America's mainstream politicians, this is good news. It is probably good, too, for American politics, for no democracy can function successfully if the electorate is in a state of permanent disgruntlement. But for America as a whole, there is also a dark side. There is no shortage of issues in America worthy of public outrage--but these are being aired only partially in the political debate.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The inner cities are home to a growing number of people who have no regard for, or connection with, the moral, political or social mores of the country as a whole. Guns and drugs are a growing menace. The public-school system, once internationally admired, looks ramshackle, and too few Americans are leaving school with the skills needed to compete in the global marketplace. Relations between the races are rockier than they have been for some time. And America remains burdened by an unfair and over-complex tax system. Any one of these issues is worth a campaign in itself. But the lesson of 1996 is that none of them will count for anything if the average middle-class voter feels her wallet is well-filled and her prospects satisfactory. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Is this a sign of narcoleptic boredom induced by television? Is it exhaustion produced by over-excitement two years ago? Is it the proof of an attention span no longer than the president's? Yes, all these things; and one more. Most Americans know in their hearts that they are the world's most fortunate nation, the most secure from war, the most economically self-reliant, and the most free. Under such circumstances, of course, it is still possible to be unhappy. But to be politically furious for any length of time takes effort: effort which, in the mid-1990s, most voters simply do not have the time or the inclination to make.<br>

<p align=center>
