<html><head><title>A Democratic Nixon?</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>A Democratic Nixon?</h1>

<font size=1>WASHINGTON DC</font><p>
THE presidential race is winding to a close, and in some ways it seems to have been extravagantly fruitless. More cash--clean, laundered, or otherwise-- was spent on campaign ads than ever before; but for nearly a year Bill Clinton's lead over Bob Dole has remained more or less static. And yet something remarkable has transpired. Mr Clinton's Democratic Party has shifted sharply right; and this change is forcing Republicans to change also. The result may be a long-term shift in the identity and electoral appeal of both big parties. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Democrats used to be the party of the welfare state, of misgovernment-as-usual, of a tendency to believe that the poor and the unconventional and even the criminal deserved more sympathy than average Americans. Starting with his 1992 campaign, and even more convincingly this time, Mr Clinton has abandoned those positions. He has ended guaranteed welfare, and proclaimed the era of big government over. He has trumpeted his tough policies on crime. He has talked little about helping gays or feminists or poor blacks, addressing himself instead to the concerns of the middle class--of people who "work hard and play by the rules", as his campaign rhetoric has it. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In so doing, Mr Clinton has put his party in America's middle ground, a territory once occupied by Republicans. In the late 1960s the Democrats chose to be the exciting party rather than the majority party. They embraced civil rights, feminism and the new campus counter-culture; and these fashionable crusades alienated ordinary voters. Because the Democrats had vacated the middle ground, Richard Nixon could pitch his campaign to the "silent majority" in 1968. He won, and Republicans held the White House for 20 of the next 24 years. The Democrats' single victory, in 1976, was a post-Watergate anomaly. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now America is experiencing the mirror image of this process. Under Newt Gingrich, the radical speaker of the House, the Republicans have become the exciting party. They have latched on to this decade's trendy themes: resentment of government, rising religious fervour, the belief that the era of the Internet will compel radical decentralisation of power. But the exciting party, in the 1960s as now, is not the majority party--at least not when it comes to presidential elections. The Gingrichite drive to curb public spending, to close down several departments of the federal government and to hand their functions to the states, has made Mr Dole seem extreme. As a result, the silent majority that backed Nixon now looks to Mr Clinton. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the moment, not many commentators are willing to see this as a lasting shift. After all, Mr Clinton has not been re-elected yet, and a last-minute catastrophe is always possible. More likely, Mr Clinton could be re-elected and then tack left, as he did after his 1992 victory. The labour unions, which have spent an unprecedented $35m on getting Democrats elected to the House, will demand a pay-off. Indeed, their opposition to spending cuts may be so strong as to undermine Mr Clinton's centrist pledge to balance the budget.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A post-election leftward shift cannot be ruled out, but the odds are against it. Mr Clinton's most obvious leftish policy in 1993 was his attempted revamp of health care; this time round, his campaign is devoid of equivalent promises. Moreover, although the unions will emerge from the election with some clout, other trends will balance this. Democratic candidates for the House and Senate this year have done their best to cast themselves as moderates. They are less likely to push Mr Clinton left than their peers were four years ago. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Besides, there is another reason to believe in the Clinton-Nixon analogy, and it is the most telling. Whatever a re-elected Clinton might do in office for the next four years, the next Democratic presidential nominee is almost bound to be a centrist. The lesson of the past two years is simply too powerful to ignore. At the start of 1995, when Mr Clinton was seen as being on the left, he lagged likely Republican rivals by huge margins in the polls. A year later, when the president was on the right, he was ahead by equally huge margins. For this reason, Dick Gephardt, the likeliest leftish contender for the Democratic nomination four years from now, has lately been tacking right. Al Gore, the probable nominee, is on the right already.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If the Democrats continue to claim the middle ground, can Republicans stave off a string of losses like the one suffered by Democrats before them? This year's campaign shows how difficult this is. For much of this year, Mr Dole has tried to devise policies with mass appeal, but which Mr Clinton had not claimed before him. The Democrats had usurped the Republicans' traditional role as the pro-business party, so for a while Mr Dole echoed Pat Buchanan's attacks on corporate downsizing. The Democrats had become the party of fiscal discipline, so Mr Dole abandoned years of fiscal caution in favour of cutting taxes. Casting around for more ways to look different, Mr Dole put aside his old support for racial quotas and denounced them. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;None of this really worked, with the result that Mr Dole flitted from one theme to the next, sacrificing his claim to be the constant leader who could be trusted by the electorate. It is the crowning irony of this campaign that the garrulous president has promised only small things, leaving people to guess what he would do in his second term. Meanwhile the taciturn challenger has thrown out a promiscuous list of half-explained proposals.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Might things work out differently four years from now? Some of Mr Dole's ploys, such as his attacks on business, are never likely to get a Republican elected. Others, such as his attack on Mr Clinton's character, will not work against a different candidate. But the Republicans are not without hope. On two issues, the Democrats have yet to seize the middle ground, leaving an opening for skilled attack. These issues are school choice and racial quotas.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a speech in California on October 28th, Mr Dole gave a glimpse of the powerful case to be made against racial quotas. Opposition to discrimination of this kind is not a blow against blacks, but a blow in favour of individual rights, he said. He could have gone further. Quotas tend to help the black middle class; by replacing them with a drive to find work for the underclass, government compassion could better find its target. Strangely, neither party has yet made this case. The Democrats urge the need to find jobs for the welfare underclass; the Republicans attack racial quotas. Neither has grabbed the middle ground by putting the two together. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dole tried, but failed, to make a winning argument on school choice. All Americans want better schools; most would like a choice of where to send their children. The Republicans say the answer is to give parents education vouchers. The Democrats are not willing to go so far, partly because of their strong ties to teachers' unions. A more skilled orator than Mr Dole could have feasted on this: his opponents stood in the way of parental freedom and children's opportunity to learn, because of their ties to a special interest. Four years from now, a Republican candidate may well return to this promising subject.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All of which is to say that the Democrats' shift to the centre, though remarkably well advanced, is not complete yet. Mr Clinton has stolen many Republican ideas, just as Nixon governed like a Democrat. But he has not stolen all of them. Over the next four years, this may change: the Democratic Leadership Council, home of the party's intellectual right, is urging a break with racial quotas and progress towards school choice. That would make the centrist Democrats even harder to defeat. Unless, that is, the Nixon-Clinton analogy holds in one final way, and second-term Clinton is disgraced by a Watergate of his own.<br>

<p align=center>
