<html><head><title>The Rules of the game</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>The Rules of the game</h1>

"DON'T accept a Saturday-night date after Wednesday." Thus <i>Rule#7 </i>of "The Rules: Time-tested Secrets for Capturing the Heart of Mr Right" (Warner Books). The slim volume by Ellen Fein and Sherrie Schneider is taking America by storm (or rather, by confetti). It is discussed on talk shows, chuckled over in newspaper features, debated at dinner parties. American girls--not women, in Rules-speak--are either religiously following the 35 Rules in order to find a husband, or else deriding the ideas but buying the book and handing it on to their friends. Either way, America is Rules crazy.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why limit this to winning your man? Might there not be equally potent Rules for winning elections? Indeed there are. They are tested, immutable, obvious. Play by them, you win. You may think the Rules crass, calculating and simplistic, a codification of the sort of manipulation that has given politics a bad name. Maybe. But would-be presidents ignore them at their peril. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The essence of the dating Rules for girls can be reduced to four old-fashioned words: play hard to get. With the political Rules, the guiding principle is just the opposite: play easy to get. Do not be mysterious, reticent, enigmatic, busy with other things. Be understandable, accessible, willing, solicitous, relentless. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Above all, don't break the Rules. "Now we're having Texas state troopers rush to some other state to stop the flow of whatever," Bob Dole said in Houston last week. Impenetrable Dole-speak is against the Rules. You can probably think of many candidates who thought they would do things their own way, follow their instincts, win it on their own terms--only to lose on polling day. They should have stuck to the Rules. Our space is limited, so here are just ten of the most important.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i>Rule#1</i>: Spend, spend, spend. This is the reverse of the dating Rules--a Rules girl never spends a penny. Raise as much money as you can, be it hard or soft, in big lumps or small (though beware of Asians bearing gifts). And never run out of it. Bob Dole was broke between the primaries and the convention--and was duly outclassed by a free-spending Bill Clinton. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i>Rule #2</i>: Always return phone calls. (Again, the opposite of girls' Rules, and the opposite of the often hard-to-get Dole campaign.) Indeed, be the first to phone or fax. The Clinton/Gore people pioneered "prebuttal" and handed their state press secretaries red buttons marking them as a "Rapid Response Team"--a Rules badge if ever there was one.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i>Rule #3</i>: Have a plan, stick to it. Mr Clinton can drive you nuts with his 21st-century bridge-building, and his "<font size=-1>MMEE</font>" mantra of Medicare, Medicaid, education and the environment. But consistency is part of the Rules. The Dole campaign changed course with disconcerting frequency. "There never was a strategy," Don Sipple, a former Dole strategist, told <i>Newsweek</i>.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i>Rule #4</i>: Flattery will get you everywhere. Sweet-talk the voters, especially swing ones such as soccer moms. Talk about things that matter to them--such as <font size=-1>V</font>-chips for televisions, school uniforms, gun-free schools, getting kids through college-- even if you cannot really help that much. Promise to cut their taxes and spend some money on them (see <i>Rule#1</i>). <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i>Rule #5:</i> If you lie, lie well. Don't promise things that you probably don't believe in (such as a 15% tax cut with a balanced budget) or that are inconsistent with your record (ditto). Sound plausible even when you are exaggerating wildly: Mr Clinton's achievements on crime prevention and compassionate leave grow even as he recites them. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i>Rule #6</i>: Demonise your rival, while remaining saintly yourself. So, leave the trashing to surrogates and ads. Better to associate your opponent with discredited figures or ideas (Newt Gingrich, say, or liberalism) than to attack directly. Come across as the person voters would feel safer leaving their children with.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i>Rule #7</i>: Think image, not just words. The Clinton campaign has been the master of the photo-opportunity--whether on the edge of the Grand Canyon, or surrounded by police officers, or on the caboose of the <i>21st Century Express</i>. From the New Hampshire primary onwards, notes Jennifer Laszlo, a political consultant who has written her own manual of campaign do's and don'ts, the Dole campaign has contrived to make their candidate "look like a boring man in a suit".<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i>Rule #8</i>: Make yourself desirable. Look good and energetic. Practise a beatific smile. Dress well and comfortably to suit any occasion. Surround yourself with beautiful people. Have pop stars sing "The Star-Spangled Banner" at your rallies. Do this constantly, so that it seems natural. Otherwise, taking Bo Derek on a bus tour (as Mr Dole did in California this week) looks calculating rather than cool. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i> Rule #9</i>: Don't blink too much. Research shows that the less frequent blinker wins debates. In the San Diego debate, Mr Dole's blink rate was 105 per minute, Mr Clinton's 48.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<i>Rule #10</i>: Know why you're running, and why it's good for the country. You need a convincing answer to the question: Why will voters be better off if they elect you? The answer is your message, which you must repeat <i>ad nauseam </i>(see <i>Rule #3</i>). It is not enough to be running because you think it is "your turn".<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Following the Rules requires a fantastic amount of self-control--discipline would be <i>Rule #11</i>, but the full set of Rules will have to wait for our forthcoming bestseller. From the selection of ten provided here, it should be obvious that one side in the 1996 presidential race has stuck strictly, almost obsessively to the Rules, while the other almost seems to have gone out of its way to break them. You may draw your own conclusions for the likely outcome next Tuesday.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The dating Rules promise happiness-ever-after: no divorces, infidelities or other heartbreaks. Alas, the political Rules offer no such guarantees. They are merely good for getting elected. Governing is another matter entirely.<br>
<br>
</td></tr></table>


