<html><head><title>China's parliament-in-waiting</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" width="67" height="26" alt="Asia" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>China's parliament-in-waiting</h1>

<font size=1>BEIJING</font><p>
WHENEVER a foreign reporter writes of the National People's Congress (<font size=-1>NPC</font>), his fingers instinctively tap out "rubber-stamp" before it. China's parliament was established in 1954. It is, according to the constitution, the highest body in the land, to which all other organs of state power report; the <font size=-1>NPC</font>'s chairman is even supposed to rank alongside the president as dual head of state. But this is all a polite fiction. Power in China is held by the Communist Party, which is not even mentioned in the constitution; the <font size=-1>NPC</font> has a well-deserved reputation as the party's plaything.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The plaything, however, has been a bit more unruly of late. The first real sign of this came in 1992, when the <font size=-1>NPC</font>--which has 3,000 delegates, only 60-70% of them party members--registered a strong note of protest against plans to build the Three Gorges dam on the Yangzi river. Not all the objectors shared western concerns that the dam would carry huge environmental and human costs. Many were instead peeved that it would suck investment away from their own regions. Whatever, 841 delegates abstained or voted against the plan. This year, the <font size=-1>NPC</font>'s chairman, Qiao Shi, led a working group to the Three Gorges to assess the main criticisms. His spokesman acknowledges that forced resettlements have been badly handled. Such meddling was unheard of five years ago.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The congress has issued other mild rebukes to the central leadership. Last year some 550 delegates withheld approval of the routine work reports submitted by China's judiciary. They objected less to the content of the reports, more to the way they were being rammed through the congress, with little time to consider them. One-third of the delegates also objected to a new banking law, after arguing for greater supervisory powers for the <font size=-1>NPC</font>, including (God help citizens of any parliament that gets this) the right to oversee monetary policy. Most famously, last year, 37% of delegates voted against the appointment of a prot&eacute;g&eacute; of Jiang Zemin, China's president, to an important government post.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is worth noting that none of these minor protests actually led to a serious reversal of party policy. And it will be many years, if ever, before the <font size=-1>NPC</font> votes down the annual ritual of the government work report, delivered by the prime minister. This year, Li Peng's report registered only a handful of nays or abstentions. But, arguably, headline votes at the <font size=-1>NPC</font>'s annual gathering are not as important as reforms to the way the congress conducts its day-to-day business. In particular, the 150-strong Standing Committee of the <font size=-1>NPC</font> was given law-drafting powers in 1979. It now works hard at turning into clean laws the nightmarish web of rules, regulations and party <i>diktats</i> by which China is governed. The Standing Committee's permanent staff, insists one western diplomat, are now "really committed".<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some observers see in the <font size=-1>NPC</font> a vehicle for China's future liberalisation. Few would claim, however, that the <font size=-1>NPC</font> is such a vehicle now. Last week, when the European Parliament awarded the Sakharov Freedom of Thought prize to Wei Jingsheng, China's best-known dissident, China's foreign ministry lodged an angry protest with the European Commission at this impertinence. "Parliaments in Europe", said the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s ambassador in a pointed reply, "do not take instructions from executives." <br>
<br>
</td></tr></table>


<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?846896400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
