<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/issue/02-11-96/br7560.html 199.173.162.110 19970113143042 text/html 7724
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 14:26:57 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 31-Oct-96 18:16:31 GMT
Content-length: 7539
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Delinquent behaviour</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>

</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<h1>Delinquent behaviour</h1>

<p><b>There are plenty of reasons behind the moral panic currently engulfing Britain. Real evidence of a decline in children's behaviour is not one of them</b></p> <br>
A HEADMASTER is stabbed to death; a school is shut because its staff say an unruly ten-year-old is making it impossible to teach the rest; staff at another insist that 60 pupils are unteachable. It is as though the devil's own spawn have overrun Britain's classrooms, and are ripping apart the very fabric of society. Except that, while there is plenty of rhetoric about rising numbers of violent and disruptive pupils, there is not much evidence to back it up.  <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Teachers tend to say that they think there are more troublesome pupils than there used to be, but the older generation always thinks that of the younger. The number of pupils excluded from schools has quadrupled in the past five years, but this is probably because schools are under much more pressure to perform (from national tests, league tables and external inspections), and so are less likely to tolerate disruption.  <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The evidence suggests, if anything, that the young are behaving better than their forebears did. The proportion of all 10-17-year-olds cautioned for or convicted of criminal offences actually fell by almost 20% in the ten years to 1994.  <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But of course, once a moral panic gets started, evidence gets flattened by an avalanche of anecdotes. This happened five years ago, when there was a moral panic not about devil children but about devil dogs. In May 1991, newspapers published horrible pictures of a six-year-old Bradford girl who had been mauled by a pit bull terrier. Suddenly, the newspapers were full of other cases of dogs biting children, which happen all the time and normally go unreported. The resulting kerfuffle led to the passing of the Dangerous Dogs Act, hastily drafted and repented at leisure because it proved impossible to implement.  <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The stabbing of Philip Lawrence, a London headmaster, by a teenage gang member in December 1995, has had a similar effect. This one extreme case has triggered other stories of juvenile delinquency in schools, and a panic about the immorality of modern children.  <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But none of these stories can obviously be generalised. Take the crisis over a ten-year-old in a school in Worksop. The disturbed boy whom the teachers refuse to teach has seen his father and uncle die, while his mother has cancer. The chairman of the school governors, a Tory, was unwilling to bow to pressure from the teaching unions. The local authority, which has refused to pay for the boy to be taught separately, is based in Nottingham, which regards Worksop as northern and foreign. Memories of the miners' strike have made local politics unusually vicious. All this is interesting, but not informative about the moral condition of British children.  <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The general themes to be drawn from these stories are political rather than moral. Rivalry between the teaching unions is an important factor. In contrast to other workplaces, almost all teachers belong to a union, so unions can expand only at each other's expense. Nigel de Gruchy, general secretary of the National Union of Schoolmasters/Union of Women Teachers, has been using the issue of unruly pupils to help him achieve his union's ambition of overtaking in size the National Union of Teachers, currently the largest one.  <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr de Gruchy, a skilled publicist who pops up continually in front of cameras at school gates, has encouraged members to express their grievances by calling strikes, and has cleverly identified discipline as one area on which teachers are likely to win public support. His tactics are paying off. His membership grew by 7% last year to 157,000, closing the gap with the <font size=-1>NUT</font>, whose membership was hardly changed at 192,000.  <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Government policy to allow parents to choose between schools is also making things worse in unpopular schools. The Ridings, the school in Halifax where teachers want 60 pupils suspended, is the local dumping-ground in an area where parents have plenty of schools to choose from. The creation of such dumps was an inevitable consequence of the policy, which the government has failed to address.  <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And naturally, too, pre-election posturing is also doing its bit. Politicians have found a convenient scapegoat for modern malaise: children, who, unlike any other slice of society, can be attacked with impunity without the risk of losing votes.  <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since the two main parties have fewer differences than they used to on the substance of policy, mood and image have become ever more important. An issue as vapid and insubstantial as morality is therefore the stuff of current politics. Tony Blair, Labour's leader, has sensed an opportunity to win votes because he regards morality and family values as his strength and the government's weakness. The government, meanwhile, is seeking to show that it is still the true party of law and order. A sort of arms-race of authoritarianism has developed, with both sides reluctant to be the first to say that things have gone far enough.  <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So, hoping to pre-empt new disciplinary measures in the government's education bill, David Blunkett, Labour's education spokesman, told a radio interviewer that parents should be forced to sign contracts with schools covering their children's behaviour, ignoring the fact that unless such contracts are entered into willingly, they are unlikely to be worth the paper they are written on. Moments later, up popped Gillian Shephard, the education secretary, who said she favoured bringing back the cane, though she had no imminent plans to do so. John Major decided the silliness had gone too far, and rebuked Mrs Shephard, saying that the cane would stay banned.  <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On October 30th, the government hurried out a draft version of a moral code to be taught in schools, intended to persuade voters of its determination to strengthen the moral fibre of the nation's youth. This misses the point. Bigger and better sermons on morality will not make children better behaved. Lessons in good behaviour are learned by example, and the example being set this week by politicians and teachers is not a good one.<br>

<p align=center>
