<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>

<p><b>Anti-choice</b> &nbsp; Cardinal Thomas Winning, the head of the Roman Catholic church in Scotland, attacked Tony Blair, the Labour leader, for his refusal to take a stand against abortion.<br>
<p><b>Cheque-book justice</b> &nbsp; Lord Mackay, the Lord Chancellor, proposed a ban on news organisations offering money or payment in kind for interviews with potential witnesses in trials.<br>
<p><b>Lib-Lab pact</b> &nbsp; Labour and the Liberal Democrats set up a committee to discuss possible collaboration on constitutional reform, including Scottish devolution, reforming the House of Lords and changing the voting system.<br>
<p><b>Swift victory</b> &nbsp; "Last Orders" by Graham Swift, a novel about four men on a day out to scatter the ashes of a dead friend, won this year's Booker Prize.<br>
<p><b>Warning</b> &nbsp; In the first-ever anti-terrorist advertising campaign in England, police gave a warning of possible <font size=-1>IRA</font> attacks and promoted a telephone hotline for informers.<br>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Post threat</b> &nbsp; Postal workers voted overwhelmingly to continue their dispute over pay and working conditions, raising the possibility of more strikes in the run-up to Christmas.<br>
<p><b>Rights for princesses</b> &nbsp; Lord Archer, a Conservative peer, said he would introduce a bill in the House of Lords to overturn the 800-year-old rule of royal succession and make the monarch's eldest child first in line to the throne, whether male or female.<br>
<p><b>Gear change</b> &nbsp; Proton, a Malaysian car maker, and Yahaya Ahmad, its chairman, bought an 80% stake in Lotus, a British sports-car maker, for &#163;51m.<br>
<p><b>A sign from God</b> &nbsp; The Church of England said its new logo, a cross inside a letter "e", would give it a "stronger presence in the media marketplace."<br>
<p><b>Supergran</b> &nbsp; Council officials in Bridlington, East Yorkshire, intervened to persuade a 76-year-old grandmother not to do a bungee jump for charity.<br>

</td></tr></table></center>

