<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Dial S for sale</h2>
<p>(See <a href="bw1.gif">table</a>)<br>Demand for shares in Germany's state-owned telecoms giant, <b>Deutsche Telekom</b>, surged ahead of the firm's forthcoming public offering of 20% of its equity. The German government said that the shares would cost DM25 30 ($16-20) each, valuing the firm at up to DM78 billion. In a recently established grey market, Telekom shares were changing hands at up to DM39 each.</p>
<p>Energy firms are also on the auctioneer's block. The Italian government fixed a maximum price for shares in the second stage of its partial privatisation of <b>ENI</b>, a state oil giant. It wants to raise at least 5.2 trillion lire ($3.4 billion) by selling another 8.5% of the firm; last November it sold 15% of its equity. Meanwhile, foreign investors fell over one another in a rush to buy American depositary shares in <b>Gazprom</b>, Russia's gas monolith. The placement of 1% of the company's equity suggests that the firm is worth around $37 billion. </p>
<p>British Telecom is at last faced with a formidable rival. <b>Cable and Wireless</b> is set to become Britain's largest cable <font size=-1>TV</font> and communications group<b> </b>when it merges Mercury, its British telephone unit, with three British cable companies that have North American parents. <font size=-1>C&W</font> will have a 52.6% stake in the new group, which will have assets of roughly &#163;3 billion ($4.8 billion).</p>
<p>Britain's telecoms watchdog banned <b>British Telecom </b>and <b>BSkyB </b>from running a joint promotion. It is worried about the competitive implications of a possible future alliance between the two British giants. <font size=-1>BT</font>, which cannot yet get involved in broadcasting under the terms of its licence, may eventually co-operate with the satellite broadcaster in digital <font size=-1>TV</font>.</p>
<p>Spain's state-owned electricity generator, <b>Endesa</b>, is beautifying itself before privatisation with an agreed bid of Pta200 billion ($1.6 billion) for two electricity distributors in which it already holds large stakes. News of the deal and speculation about other likely takeover bids boosted Spanish share prices.</p>
<h2>Potholes</h2>
<p>A federal judge ruled that <b>Volkswagen</b> and its chairman, Ferdinand Piech, must stand trial in America in an industrial-espionage lawsuit brought by General Motors against the German car maker. But <font size=-1>VW</font> still had something to smile about: its net profit soared 56% in the first nine months of the year, to DM1.5 billion ($977m).</p>
<p><b>General Motors</b> reached an agreement with its Canadian unions, ending a damaging three-week strike involving 18,000 workers in North America.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Eurotunnel</b>, the Anglo French operator of the Channel tunnel, plans to cut 657 jobs from its 3,500-strong workforce in order to make FFr264m ($51m) of savings.</p>
<p>Norfolk Southern, an American railway company, offered to buy <b>Conrail</b> for $9 billion, topping an $8.4 billion offer from its rival, <font size=-1>CSX</font>. The three companies dominate the<b> </b>rail<b>-</b> transport business east of the Mississippi.</p>
<p>(See <a href="bw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Shares in <b>Digital </b>plummeted after bigger-than-expected losses of $66m in the first quarter of its fiscal year raised questions about the success of the American computer maker's turnaround. <b>IBM</b>, on the other hand, is bouncing back. It reported a $1.3 billion net profit in the third quarter of the year, mainly because its <font size=-1>PC</font> unit had returned to health after losing $538m in the same period last year.</p>
<p>America's <b>AT&T</b> picked 49 year-old John Walter, head of R.R. Donnelley, a printing firm, to be its president and chief operating officer. In 1998 the job of chairman and chief executive will be split, and the plan is for Mr Walter to succeed Robert Allen as the firm's chairman.</p>
Tax officials in Israel raided the offices of News Datacom Research, a unit of <b>News Corp</b>. The officials suspect it of concealing income of $150m. Rupert Murdoch, the head of News Corp, denied any wrongdoing.
<h2>Shaky foundations</h2>
<p>In Japan's <b>largest corporate collapse </b>since the second world war, Nichiei Finance, a lender in Yokohama, filed for bankruptcy, with liabilities of &#165;991.4 billion ($8.8 billion). It is the fourth such institution to collapse this year because of financial problems linked to the slump in Japan's property market at the end of the 1980s.</p>
<p>Most of <b>Japan's securities firms </b>reported an improved first half, partly because of buoyant underwriting business. But the biggest company suffered a setback. Nomura reported a net loss of &#165;337.5 billion ($3 billion), after making a &#165;371 billion provision to bail out one of its subsidiaries. In the same period last year it made a &#165;16.4 billion profit.</p>
<p>Yasuo Hamanaka, <b>the world's leading copper trader </b>until Japan's Sumitomo Corporation sacked him earlier this year, was arrested and charged in Tokyo with falsifying company documents.</p>
<p><b>Correction. </b>In the issue of October 12th, we said that China's holdings of American Treasury securities soared to $12 billion in the first half of this year, putting it behind only Britain and Japan as a foreign creditor. The figures quoted were in fact net purchases, which puts China in seventh place, not third.</p>

