<html><head><title>The House in the balance</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>The House in the balance</h1>

<font size=1>FEARRINGTON, NORTH CAROLINA</font><p>
BACK in 1994 Jan Allen threw a party, and the mood of that gathering held the key to the Democrats' defeat in the congressional elections of that year. It was just before polling day, and Ms Allen, a retired <font size=-1>IBM</font> executive and Democratic activist, was dismayed to find her fellow Democrats unmoved by the election. Nearly all of them-- professionals and university professors--assumed a Democratic victory in the local congressional district. Their candidate, David Price, was a clever politics professor with the advantage of incumbency; the Republican challenger, Fred Heineman, was a blunt policeman from New York. And yet, two days later, the unthinkable happened. Mr Heineman was elected, not because the Republican vote had grown much, but because complacent Democrats had not bothered to turn out. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This time the Democrats are determined not to be complacent. On October 21st Ms Allen attended another social gathering, in a genteel housing development called Fearrington Village. The village's barn was decked out with pot plants, and 100 or so well-to-do Democrats stood around eating from plates labelled "Pig Out!". Mr Price, who is trying to win back his seat, greeted everybody assiduously, impressing upon them the need to rally voters. Ms Allen has certainly got the message. She has installed eight new phone lines at her local party office, and rounded up volunteers to call people. Another team of activists stands ready to drive Democrats to voting stations on polling day.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is not just the local activists who have cast off their old complacency. In 1994 the party headquarters in Washington gave Mr Price little advice or money, figuring that, as a four-term incumbent, he could fend for himself. This time, however, party <font size=-1>HQ</font> has been more generous; and the trade unions have spent some $1.3m on local television advertisements to help Mr Price's cause. Two years ago it was hard to attack Mr Heineman; he was a political novice, with no record to pick at. Now that he has spent two years in Congress voting with Newt Gingrich, the Democrats pummel him for voting against the environment, against education, against just about everything that makes life worthwhile.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With more enthusiasm, more money, and a more clearly defined opponent, Mr Price seems virtually sure of taking back his district. The question is whether these same forces, operating in dozens of races around America, will be enough to break the Republicans' control of the House. If it is, a host of Gingrichite committee chairmen will be displaced by Democrats. Whereas a Republican House would keep a second term Clinton in the political centre, a Democratic House would pull him to the left. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To win the House, Democrats need a net gain of 19 seats. This sounds feasible: 12 of the 25 elections since the second world war have produced a swing this size or bigger. Many of the 73 Republicans elected for the first time two years ago share Mr Heineman's vulnerability. They won as fresh outsiders; now that they are incumbents, this appeal is gone.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Two years ago in Chicago, for example, voters elected Michael Flanagan, an unremarkable 30-year-old who campaigned on such profundities as "I want to see good things happen." This time round, however, Mr Flanagan can no longer pose as an outsider. He has accepted cash from fat-cat backers, including the tobacco lobby. Deprived of his main political asset, he appears merely boring. He lags in the polls.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Where they are not dull, Republicans have been made to seem extreme. In part, this is the result of propaganda: the Democrats assail their opponents for "cutting Medicare", even though Republicans suggested only slowing its rate of growth. In other respects, however, the extremist label is warranted. Many Republicans benefited two years ago from the money and votes of groups such as the National Rifle Association; once in office, they have felt obliged to vote for the repeal of the assault-weapons ban. A few candidates go even further. In Texas, for example, Ron Paul denounces tax as theft, and regards government benefits as immoral. His political newsletter is commended by a Canadian neo-Nazi group.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In some cases, Republicans seem in danger of being labelled "extremist" without enjoying the compensating support that extreme politics can bring. The gun lobby and the Christian right are less fired up than they were two years ago, so seem likely to yield fewer votes. They are turned off by Bob Dole's candidacy, not least because he has waffled on their issues. The congressional races do not grab them either. They may adore Newt Gingrich, the radical House speaker; but they are depressed by how far his star has fallen. Other House Republicans have disappointed them in various ways. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This mix of trend and anecdote, raising the possibility of a Democratic House of Representatives, gets some support from pollsters. This week a <i>New York Times</i>/<font size=-1>CBS</font> News poll found that 47% of respondents want the Democrats in charge of Congress, compared with 39% who favour continued Republican control: a month ago, the Democrats' lead was smaller. Several seers reckon that, if Mr Clinton wins by more than a ten-point margin, his coat-tails will carry enough Democrats to victory to tip the House their way. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trouble is that the polls are actually ambiguous, and trends and anecdotes can be advanced by both sides. The coat-tail effect is unreliable. In 1988 the Democrats gained three seats despite George Bush's victory in the presidential race; in 1992 Republicans picked up ten seats, despite Mr Clinton's win that year. Moreover, some who say they want a Democratic House change their minds when asked how Mr Clinton's re-election would influence their preference: the <i>New York Times </i>poll found that 48% would prefer a Republican Congress to balance the president, while only 41% wanted a Democratic Congress as well.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Republicans hope that the fear of a Democratic monopoly will give them the advantage in the last days of the House races. They are also hoping that the barrage of trade-union attack ads will backfire for the Democrats. This week, a new Republican advertisement took to the airwaves, showing union bosses plotting to fix the election in a shadowy backroom; "Big labour bosses, big money, big lies, big liberals," the voice-over intones. In places inundated by union dollars, but without strong union membership, such tactics may work. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One such place is North Carolina; and, despite Mr Price's likely victory there, this state demonstrates the limits of Democratic hopes. Until 1994, the state's House delegation consisted of eight Democrats and four Republicans. Since then, it has been the other way around. This year, even Democrats concede that three out of the state's five Republican freshmen will be re elected. Mr Price's seat, and one other, is the most they hope to win back.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The other vulnerable seat is held by David Funderburk. The Democrats have pounded him with all their usual tactics, accusing him of wanting to gut Medicare, and linking his name to that of Mr Gingrich at every opportunity. But Mr Funderburk remains undaunted. Being linked to Mr Gingrich will hurt him less, he reckons, than being linked to Mr Clinton will hurt his opponent. Locals agree with what Mr Gingrich says, even if they find him arrogant. But they dislike both Mr Clinton and his views.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That, at least, is the basis for Mr Funderburk's campaigning. He comes from a tobacco district, and a bumper sticker outside one of his rallies proclaims, "More Americans smoke than voted for Bill Clinton." Far from running from the Republican record, Mr Funderburk stands on the back of a farm truck and enjoins his audience to "vote the values of the district". He denounces the Clinton administration for being soft on heroin and cocaine ("the preferred drugs of Hollywood") while plotting restrictions on tobacco farmers. He and his fellow Republicans had tried to limit government, Mr Funderburk continued, but Mr Clinton's veto had obstructed them. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Despite the president's likely victory, some Republicans still believe that their agenda is more popular. They also believe that deep shifts--the growth of suburbs, the fear of an underclass left behind by the technological revolution--are pushing America their way. If Mr Clinton wins, it will merely reflect his success in moving rightwards. But the House Democrats have been slower to shift towards the centre. Even if they do well this November, their long-term grip on the House may depend on following Mr Clinton--which would amount to a victory for Republicanism, if not for Republicans themselves.<br>

<p align=center>
