<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
 
<p><b>U-turn &nbsp; </b>John Major surprised MPs by agreeing to government legislation against paedophiles and stalkers after Tony Blair offered him Labour Party support if he would. The government had planned to leave the bills to backbench MPs.<br>
<p><b>Crash</b> &nbsp; Matthew Harding, a millionaire benefactor of both Labour and Chelsea Football Club, was among five people who died in a helicopter crash.<br>
<p><b>Midweek money</b> &nbsp; Oflot, the lottery regulator, approved the launch of a second weekly National Lottery draw, to be held on Wednesdays.<br>
<p><b>Private money</b> &nbsp; The government announced measures to boost the <font size=-1>PFI</font>, an initiative to get more private finance for public infrastructure projects. They include a set of standard terms and conditions, and more freedom to sell stakes in such privately financed deals.<br>
<p><b>Abuse</b> &nbsp; A study by the National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children said that more than 1m British children are sexually, physically or emotionally abused each year.<br>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Tax shock</b> &nbsp; A ruling by the European Court that value-added tax on goods bought using promotional vouchers should be charged at the discounted price, not the full price, threatened to cost the Treasury hundreds of millions of pounds in refunds of overpaid tax.<br>
<p><b>School for scandal</b> &nbsp; Gillian Shephard, the education secretary, ordered an inquiry into The Ridings school in Halifax, West Yorkshire, after teachers threatened to strike unless 60 allegedly disruptive pupils were expelled.<br>
<p><b>Homeless</b> &nbsp; The Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors said there is a "property famine" England and Wales, with the number of homes for sale at its lowest level for eight years.<br>
<p><b>Getting the bird</b> &nbsp; United Biscuits is to sue Asda, a supermarket chain, claiming that Asda's new "Puffin" biscuits are an unlawful copy of its long-established "Penguin" biscuits.<br>

</td></tr></table></center>

