<html><head><title>Launching Deutsche Telekom</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Launching Deutsche Telekom</h1>

<font size=1>BERLIN</font><p>
<p><b>The sale of Germany's telephone giant will reshape Europe's biggest telecoms market. But will it, as many hope, transform German capitalism too?</b></p><br>
DEUTSCHE TELEKOM attracts superlatives. It is the most ridiculed company in Germany, the biggest phone operator in Europe, and (after Tokyo Power) the world's most indebted commercial entity. It has one of the best high-speed telephone networks in the world, yet it is also renowned for treating many of its subscribers badly. Its partial privatisation, which starts on November 18th, is the largest flotation in Germany's history and the second-biggest anywhere (after that of Japan's <font size=-1>NTT</font>, another telecoms giant).<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More than perhaps any other big sale since that of British Telecom in 1984, Deutsche Telekom's privatisation is an attempt to change a country's business culture. At present German capitalism is caught in something of a vicious circle. Germany is unique among big industrial countries in that only about 5% of its population hold shares (in Britain, for instance, the figure is nearer 25%). This is partly a function of history: having lost their savings twice this century in post-war currency reforms, Germans are notably risk-averse. But it also reflects the poor performance of shares in most of Germany's biggest companies, which have offered miserable returns compared with those of government bonds and mortgage-backed securities.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet--and this is where the vicious circle comes in--the poor performance of those companies is also a consequence of the country's lack of an equity culture. Germany's savings are mainly channeled through banks into loans to industry, rather than though mutual funds into shares. As a result, company bosses in Germany are generally under less pressure to produce sparkling results: shareholders, whose own money is at risk if a company does badly, tend to be more demanding.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is changing. The number of foreign investors in German firms is growing quickly and a new breed of German managers such as J<dierisis>urgen Schrempp of Daimler-Benz, a huge conglomerate, have made it clear that shareholder value is now a priority. A recent report by Goldman Sachs, an American investment bank, argues that German firms could easily push up their current low return on equity (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>) by between two and three percentage points. A successful sale of 20% of Telekom would give share ownership a big fillip--not least by paving the way for other large sell-offs, such as that of the government's remaining 36% stake in Lufthansa. Rolf Breuer, a director of Deutsche Bank, describes Telekom's privatisation as "the last big chance" to establish an equity culture in Germany.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With so many things depending on a successful sale, Telekom's board this week announced an indicative price range for the 500m new shares the firm is selling of just DM25-30 ($16-20)--some way below the DM35-40 level forecast a year ago. This price should ensure that the launch is a success. But the shares' likely long-term performance is harder to predict.<br>
</p><p><b><b>The need to be wired</b></b><br>
Telekom's new boss, Ron Sommer (who joined the company from Sony last year), has done his best to reform a company that still thinks and behaves far too much like a civil service department. Customers are now treated better. Repairs now sometimes happen on public holidays and there are many more phone boxes, usually in working order. The company has also launched new services, such as T Online, Germany's most popular Internet service provider. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Telekom's new shareholders will inherit an impressive range of assets. It has Germany's second-biggest mobile telephone network and its biggest cable-television network. Thanks in part to the high prices that it charges in its core business, Telekom is also an impressive generator of cash: it earned DM34 billion last year before interest, tax and depreciation. And Mr Sommer has pushed it into Global One, an impressive-looking international alliance, with France T&eacute;l&eacute;com and Sprint, an American long distance carrier.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet Telekom also has impressive weaknesses. It has a burdensome debt of DM100 billion, partly because modernising former East Germany's telephone system--a political not a business decision--cost it a cool DM50 billion. Moreover, despite Mr Sommer's best efforts, the company is still overstaffed by world standards, with 184 lines per employee, compared to an average of 275 at America's regional Bell telephone companies (though to be fair, the German firm does more things). Getting rid of unwanted posts-- 30,000 of its 200,000 staff are supposed to leave the firm by 2000-- could cost as much as DM100,000 per employee.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Telekom's domestic fixed-link businesses supplied DM51 billion of its DM66 billion in revenues last year (see <a href="wb2.gif">table</a>). That will not last. On January 1st 1998, telecoms in the <font size=-1>EU</font> must be fully liberalised. Telekom will then have to deal with something new and potentially life-threatening: competition in its bread and-butter business of providing telephone services to households and firms. A local call in Germany is still almost as costly as a coast-to-coast call in America. For long-distance and international services in Germany (as in most other monopoly markets), prices are still extortionate.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Already four consortia are marching, in differing degrees of readiness, towards the starting line. One of the most threatening combines <font size=-1>AT&T</font>, America's long-distance champion, with Mannesmann, a German engineering group that has taken only a few years to knock Telekom from the top spot in mobile phones, the only market where it has been exposed to real competition.<br>
</p><p><b><b>The route to profit</b></b><br>
Under Mr Sommer, Telekom should defend its fixed-link business more fiercely. It has already offered price cuts of 40% to business users (provoking protests from its competitors and regulators). It also faces competition from "re-sellers"--companies which buy cheap international capacity and then sell it through call-back services and the like. At least two, Telepassport and <font size=-1>USA</font> Global Link, are planning to launch services for internal German long-distance calls early next year (the latter will invest $100m to install new switches in Germany). Even routed via a neighbouring country, their service will be cheaper than Telekom's peak-time rates. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Thanks to the resellers, to new entrants and to the existing networks owned by various other utilities in Germany, there will soon be a surplus of long-distance capacity. But in the local market, any new competitor will still have to use Telekom's lines to connect with customers. In theory, Telekom will be required to let competitors pick and choose which parts of its network they want to lease (the lines, but not the switches which connect them, for example) at a price set by the regulators.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately, the rules are vague. For instance, it is not clear what constitutes a reasonable ground for Telekom to refuse an interconnection. Worse, the regulator, who is supposed to impose an interconnection agreement if the parties cannot agree on one, has not yet been appointed. (In the meantime, the rules will be enforced by the Federal Ministry for Posts and Telecommunications, which has little experience of regulating a competitive marketplace.) In keeping with their desire to protect Telekom, Germany's politicians seem reluctant to change. "We have people behaving like dinosaurs", complains Stephan Schwarz of <font size=-1>VTM</font>, a lobby group for Telekom's competitors.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, the market is unlikely to stay rigged in Telekom's favour for long. One source of salvation for its rivals is likely to be the European Commission, which has already held up Telekom's planned price cuts to its corporate customers. Expect an even tougher response from regulators elsewhere, particularly America. The Federal Communications Commission is already preventing Global One from launching full operations in the United States until Germany treats outsiders fairly. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In other words, even the friendliest treatment by the German government will only delay, rather than cancel, the day of reckoning for Telekom. Indeed, the point must soon come where the political imperative of having cheap communications (which can be achieved only by opening up the telecoms market and encouraging competitors) will matter more in Bonn than protecting the old monopoly. Where will that leave Telekom's new shareholders--not to mention German capitalism?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;</p><p><b> <b>Got the DTs</b><br></b>A lot of attention (and cash) has been paid to ensure that the current launch is a success. In a DM85m advertising blitz, comedians and other celebrity investment advisers have been singing (literally in some cases) the shares' merits. A disproportionate chunk of the issue will be reserved for German private investors. As Deutsche Telekom will account for nearly 5% of the main Frankfurt share index, almost any fund manager who invests in Germany is going to be needing some shares. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So far, so good. Barring regulatory fireworks from Washington or Brussels, or a stockmarket down-turn, most of the 3m Germans who have registered for the shares should buy at least some. "The banks and the government can't let this fail" is a commonly-voiced sentiment. That powerful interests stand behind Deutsche Telekom's success is certainly true. But this does not make it the risk-free investment portrayed in the advertisements.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Its new shareholders will not automatically make Telekom more efficient. The DM15 billion raised by the share sale will help reduce its debt-mountain, but Telekom will still be vulnerable (one investment bank, <font size=-1>BZW</font>, says that the sale is more reminiscent of a leveraged buy-out than a privatisation). Much will depend on Mr Sommer's ability to cut costs. The success of <font size=-1>BT</font> shows the potential, however.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When shares in Volkswagen, a German car maker, were first floated in 1960, they too were attractively priced and packaged in the hope of creating a nation of shareholders. But soon afterwards their price fell, dipping below their flotation price. Small investors panicked and dumped the stock (had they hung on to it for a long time, they would eventually have done well). The Volkswagen experience helped turn an entire generation of German investors against equities.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The chances are that the Telekom sale will be more of a success and help to open up German capitalism. Even so, an unwieldy monopolist, whose future partly depends on the government restraining its competitors, makes an awkward advertisement for a better way of life.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
