<html><head><title>The front line</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<p><b>Multimedia in Britain</b></p>
<h1>The front line</h1>

MIGHT British Telecom at last face a se rious competitor in its home market? For several years, a number of other firms have been buzzing around <font size=-1>BT</font>. Now they have decided to gang up on it. On October 22nd, Cable and Wireless announced a complicated &#163;5 billion ($8 billion) merger between Mercury Communications, <font size=-1>C&W</font>'s own subsidiary and the company first groomed to challenge <font size=-1>BT</font>, and three cable <font size=-1>TV</font> firms. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The deal is the brainchild of <font size=-1>C&W</font>'s new boss, Dick Brown, who lists its advantages with glee. By connecting Mercury with the three cable firms--Nynex CableComms, Bell Cablemedia and Videotron--<font size=-1>C&W</font> will have the right to lay wires to the door of 6m Britons. Britain's cable companies already offer a telephone service to go with their television; now the three merged companies will be able to carry their calls throughout the country on Mercury's long-distance lines, and deliver them to homes in its regions without paying steep access fees to <font size=-1>BT</font>. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Then there are the usual cost savings of merging operations. Together the companies, which will be called something like <font size=-1>C&W</font> Communications, will have a bit more clout in negotiating a price for television programming. And if <font size=-1>C&W</font> can work out a way to bring in Mercury One<font size=-1>2</font>One, a mobile telephone network it half-owns, it could then offer a tempting all-in-one package of services to its customers: television; local, long-distance and mobile telephony; and whatever whizzy interactive services it can pump down its lines, such as high speed Internet access.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, the new merger is a product of weakness, not strength. After more than a decade of laying lines, the cable companies have failed to repeat their success in America (see <a href="wb3.gif">chart</a>). They now reach more than a third of British homes. But only a fifth of these actually subscribe to the service; worse, this figure has barely moved over the past six years, even declining a bit of late. By contrast in America, more than 60% of the homes that are hooked up subscribe. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Britons, it seems, do not like television as much as couch-bound Americans--or, rather, they do not like the American-style fare that the cable stations offer. They also enjoy better quality broadcast reception than many Americans, which makes cable less necessary. Many of those who do want more <font size=-1>TV</font> are happy to get it from cheap satellite providers, such as <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>. And the marketing tactics of most British cable firms have been lacklustre (a discrete postcard under the door once a year is still considered a hard sell). The one bright spot has been cable's relative success in selling telephone services, which have drawn more customers than television itself. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A telecoms man for most of his career, Mr Brown came to <font size=-1>C&W</font> in July from Ameritech, one of America's seven main regional telephone companies (with a short stint at another firm in between). Ask him about negotiating clout for television programming and he will dismiss it as a detail, but mention local-calling margins and he waxes lyrical about their importance. Alas, he says he cannot reveal just how staggering the merger's savings will be, because a public offering of stock may be in the works. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even if the savings are impressive for calls travelling entirely over the lines of the merged firms, few calls will take this route. Combined, the three cable companies have only 500,000 customers, out of more than 27m telephone homes in the country. Most calls will continue to go from a cable customer to a local non-customer; the merger is of little help there. Even the long-distance ones that travel over Mercury's line may save just 15%. Mr Brown admits that the current merger is just a start; expect more cable firms to join later, he hints. That will increase the buzzing; whether <font size=-1>BT</font> will end up being stung is another matter.<br>

<p align=center>
