<html><head><title>Hang on</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif" width="462" height="26" alt="Special feature">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>Hang on</h1>

BOB METCALFE, one of the inventors of computer networking, predicted this spring that the Internet would grind to a halt this year. And as if to prove the point, a few months later America Online and Netcom, two of America's biggest Internet providers, went down for a day each, cutting off more than 6m subscribers. Pundits saw it as an omen of greater blackouts to come. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The geeks who keep the Internet running disagree. After all, most data show that the Internet is actually getting faster. Local failures are inevitable, but the Internet has so far been surprisingly resilient.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Skeptics worry that this cannot last. Not only is the number of users--already an estimated 40m-50m--doubling every year, but because of the increased use of pictures and sound (which use a lot more capacity than simple text), traffic per user is growing even faster (see <a href="sf2.gif">chart</a>). <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Where this causes congestion is not along the Internet's highways, but at their intersections, where "routers" direct data towards their destination. Here the Internet's health boils down to a conflict between two laws: one coined by Mr Metcalfe himself, and one by a microchip guru, Intel's Gordon Moore.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Metcalfe's law states that the value of a network increases by the square of its users. This means that each new user tends to add more traffic than the one before, because the more people who are on the Internet, the more popular it becomes as a channel of communications. Moore's law is that computer chips double in speed every 18 months--and routers are just specialised computers. Since Internet traffic is growing three times faster, the trends seem set to collide. How can the routers keep up?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Three ways. The first is to share the load: network operators can increase the number of routers and connections, like adding more lanes to a highway instead of simply raising its speed limit. The second is to simplify their job, by tagging each data packet with what amounts to a short postal code rather than an entire street address. Finally, tomorrow's routers will be able to distinguish between data types, sending video down fast lanes and e-mail down slow ones. Anyway, there are only so many people in the world: the rush to surf will eventually slow.<br>
<br>
</td></tr></table>


