</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>The last living liberal</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>The last living liberal</h1>

<font size=1>ST PAUL, MINNESOTA</font><p>
NOBODY campaigns quite like Paul Wellstone. One moment he waves his arms before a crowd of students, urging them to embrace direct action ("Turn the heat up. Nothing will happen unless you keep pushing."). The next moment he drops to the floor to autograph a Wellstone placard affixed to a cleaner's trolley. Then he bounds into a daycare centre, and shares five minutes of empassioned concern with one of the teachers. Standing amidst a gaggle of toddlers would be photo-opportunity enough for any ordinary man. But Mr Wellstone seizes two children by the hands and marches them out into the autumn sunshine to see his rickety campaign bus. The cameras are practically singing.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Wellstone may be about to achieve something quite remarkable. In elections all across America, being "liberal" is supposedly the kiss of death. In Minnesota, however, this firm believer in an activist state is ahead in his race for re-election to the Senate. In elections around the country, attack ads are thought to work. But Republican attacks on Mr Wellstone seem to be backfiring. All across America, too, politics has become a professional domain, ruled over by pollsters, admen and demographers. But Mr Wellstone rebels against this, urging his audiences to "get out there and hold people accountable."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1990, when Mr Wellstone won his first Senate race, many thought him merely lucky. That year, the Minnesota Republicans were divided; a sex scandal had felled their gubernatorial candidate. Rudy Boschwitz, the incumbent senator, was kept from campaigning by a budget row that pinned him down in Washington. When he came home, he made various gaffes. Mr Wellstone's statism did not win, the argument goes; rather, the Republicans imploded.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This year a Wellstone victory would not be so easily dismissed. The Republicans are united; and Mr Boschwitz, who is trying to recapture his old seat, has no distractions from campaigning. On October 14th he lavished a whole day on the sparsely-populated south-west. He hopped between tiny towns in an eight-seater aircraft, spoke from podiums fashioned from hay-bales, and walked down empty shopping streets in search of unsuspecting voters.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Boschwitz is a twinkly-eyed sort, a grandad who runs 100 miles each month, a job-creating entrepreneur who arrived in America 60 years ago with nothing. In short, he is the ideal Republican candidate. His stump speech exudes the optimism that serves his party well. At each stop he celebrates local heroes--a man in a wheelchair who runs a farm, a team of volunteer firemen--and declares that the spirit of ordinary folk can do more to solve America's woes than Mr Wellstone's state activism. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For his televised campaign, Mr Boschwitz has hired Arthur Finkelstein, the ace of Republican air wars. The result is a binge of attack ads, sugared with some humour. In one, a 1960s professor inducts Mr Wellstone into the "liberal hall of fame", to the applause of doped drop-outs holding placards calling for more taxes. In another, a Wellstone cartoon waves a flash-card marked "liberal" up and down with comically inhuman energy. Six years ago, Mr Wellstone had the better television campaign. This time the Boschwitz ads are the more memorable.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Faced with this sort of opposition, Mr Wellstone ought to be in trouble. His views are unfashionable, to say the least. He was the only senator facing re-election who voted against welfare reform; he opposed the Gulf war; he wants the rich to pay higher taxes; his campaign bus is plastered with stickers advertising his ties to the dwindling trade unions. Yet Mr Wellstone is doing fine. The latest poll gives him a nine-point lead over Mr Boschwitz.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What to make of this surprise? It may be that Mr Wellstone's views, though out of keeping with America's as a whole, match Minnesota nicely. The state was too far north, its winters too bitterly cold, to attract normal Yankees as they moved west in the 19th century. Instead, Scandinavians and Germans settled its flat land, and they seem to have brought with them social-democratic tendencies. Minnesota's taxes are high, its schools and social services better than average. The state practises an industrial policy of which Europeans would be proud, pouring $840m into Northwest Airlines in 1991 in order to keep its hub in Minneapolis. Minnesotans cheerfully call their state the Sweden of America.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Out on the stump, Mr Wellstone plays up this idea of Minnesotan exceptionalism. "I feel blessed to be a senator from Minnesota," he roars, explaining that the people of the state are too decent to fall for the Republicans' sink-or-swim individualism. The attack ads have backfired, he suggests, because Minnesotans are sensible and nice. Indeed, "Minnesota Nice" is a phenomenon much discussed in the state: people are honest, uncorrupt, and slow to insult anyone; if you dial the wrong number, the person on the end of the line may volunteer to find the right one for you.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In truth, this Nordic niceness--rooted in solid farm communities, celebrated by Garrison Keillor in his stories about Lake Wobegon--is fading. Minnesotans have left the land for suburban homes, and they have succumbed to the same suspicions of welfare cheats and inner-city crime that have spawned Republicans all across America. Apart from Lake Wobegon, Minnesota's best known contribution to culture may be the country's biggest shopping centre. Every year, 40m visitors flock to the Mall of America outside Minneapolis. For many of them, the last contact with the farm values of old is the autumn apple festival in the mall's rotunda.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The old Democratic dominance of Minnesota has faded too, making it hard to pin Mr Wellstone's strength on the state's supposed peculiarities. There is a Republican governor, and in 1994 the Senate race was won by Rod Grams, an unimpressive and exceedingly right-wing newscaster. Besides, many Minnesota Democrats are not "liberal" in the Wellstone sense. The party is strongest of all in the far-northern Mesabi Iron Range, where miners and farmers tend to oppose gun control, legalised abortion and environmental rules--all of which are proud Wellstone causes.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So, if Mr Wellstone does win, some conventional wisdom will have to be discarded. It will not do to argue that his opponent was weak, or that Minnesota is exceptional. Instead, it will have to be accepted that "liberals" can win, especially if they emphasise Americans' economic insecurities in places where these are strong. Over the past month, Bob Dole has tried to hurt Bill Clinton by branding him with the <font size=-1>L</font>-word. Four years from now, the next Republican presidential candidate may have to try a different strategy.<br>

<p align=center>
