<html><head><title>The last bark</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width="258" height="26" alt="American Survey" border=0><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table><table border=6><tr><td><h3>LEXINGTON</h3><p><h1>The last bark</h1>BOB DOLE simply couldn't wait. He pounced on the very first question in Wednesday's presidential debate in San Diego to engage in his latest campaign tactic: attacking the ethics of the Clinton administration. He talked about "scandals almost on a daily basis", about the improper gathering of <font size=-1>FBI</font> files, about possible presidential pardons. Later, he must have baffled millions of Americans by talking about "contributions coming in from Indonesia", an oblique reference to the <i>scandale du jour. </i>Perhaps he would have attacked more had the questions from the audience given him more openings. But the audience was interested in policy matters. And at the end of the debate the instant polls, for what they are worth, declared Mr Clinton the clear winner.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The new Dole strategy amounts to an admission of failure, the failure of any other approach to make an impact on what has remained an extraordinarily static race. Mr Dole's inability to sell his 15% tax cut is merely the most conspicuous example. So many moments that were supposed to mark decisive turning-points--the decision to quit the Senate, the choice of Jack Kemp as running mate, the Republican convention, the arrival of federal funds to pay for advertising, the first presidential debate in Hartford--have all come and gone with scarcely a blip in the polls. After countless bumpy trips on the Citizen's Ship and umpteen rallies in front of polite crowds, the excitement level surrounding the Dole campaign still fails to register on the political Richter scale. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So Mr Clinton remains what he has been all year: the top dog, sitting pretty. Mr Dole is the hapless underdog, now reduced to growling menacingly and baring his teeth. What has Mr Dole done wrong?<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Just about everything, it would seem. Certainly, he has not helped his cause by his constant ditherings and changes of tactics. The decision, after a week of public wavering, to attack on the "character issue" is the latest <font size=-1>U</font>-turn among many, stretching back to the primaries. Mr Dole allowed himself to be tugged this way and that over Pat Buchanan's challenge and over the issue of abortion. By coming out against affirmative action he belied his own record on racial policy, and by embracing supply-side economics he jeopardised his hard-earned reputation for fiscal conservatism. All this from a man who touts his "leadership" qualities.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He has seemed uncertain how hard to push his tax plan, how vigorously to compete in California, how to express what this election is "all about". If so much indecision was not bad enough, he has too often been painfully inarticulate. Oh yes, and he is also old, falls over and blinks too much. His bid for the White House is widely seen as a close competitor to the 1988 Dukakis effort for the title of the worst presidential campaign of modern times.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton's campaign, by contrast, is one of the best. The president set his course long ago, and has stuck to it. The plan was to avoid a primary challenge, raise lots of money early, use this financial fire-power over the spring and summer to help consolidate a commanding lead over an opponent bumping against his federal spending limits, and then, after the party conventions, run a "holding operation" to stay on top. That is exactly what has happened.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton has also used the office of the presidency to maximum effect, making news and staging made-for-television signing ceremonies. Seemingly prepared for everything, the Clinton campaign's rapid-response effort has even given a new word to the English language: "prebuttal". Remarkably, a White House once notorious for indiscipline has been operating with military efficiency. Reporters have waited in vain for gaffes, flip-flops and snafus. The big exception was the resignation of Dick Morris, the president's strategic guru, over his dalliance with a prostitute. But the bimbo eruption was Mr Morris's, not Mr Clinton's, and by then the Morris strategy had worked its magic. Mr Clinton had neutralised "Republican" issues, from welfare to crime and foreign policy, making him a maddeningly difficult target for Mr Dole to attack. It remained only for Mr Clinton to go out and delight the crowds with his proven brilliance on the campaign trail.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And yet when all is said and done (which, thank goodness, it very nearly is), the contrasting aptitudes of the two campaigns may be less important than they now seem. More fundamental forces are really deciding the contest. Two forces, to be precise, each working in opposite directions.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One, in Mr Dole's favour, is that the country is broadly in a conservative mood. Mr Clinton (with Mr Morris's help) drew the lesson from the 1994 election. He has positioned himself as a conservative on matters of budgets and values--so successfully that Mr Dole is reduced to accusing him of being a stealth liberal. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The other force, this time helping Mr Clinton, is the health of the economy. Incumbent presidents are hard to beat if the economy is growing strongly, as it has been, with low unemployment and little inflation. The national angst over jobs and living standards, much exaggerated by media hype, seems to have abated (even though a recent poll in the <i>Washington Post</i> showed that a large number of Americans believe the unemployment rate to be more than 20%). These are no longer receptive times for a bold new economic plan, such as Mr Dole's 15% tax cut.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dole can still hope that the political winds will in the end work in his favour, just as they did (despite his dreadful campaigning) in the primaries. They should at least tighten the race in the final three weeks; Dole people say they are already seeing such movement in states across the country. But luck, in the shape of the economic cycle, strongly favours Mr Clinton. Beyond the excitements over presidential debates, campaigning prowess and strategic decisions, it is these fundamentals that will determine who has the last bark.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<br></td></tr></table><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845683200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="br7538.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
