http://www.economist.com:80/issue/19-10-96/br7539.html 199.173.162.110 19970113144234 text/html 6703
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 14:38:48 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 17-Oct-96 16:04:10 GMT
Content-length: 6518
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>VAT's the problem</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Taxation</b></p>
<h1>VAT's the problem</h1>

THIS year's budget will be knocked into shape on October 18th, when Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor of the exchequer, and Treasury officials gather at Dorneywood, the chancellor's country pad. This meeting would be a calmer affair were it not for a huge and mysterious hole in the government's tax revenues. This has resulted in a far bigger public-sector borrowing requirement (<font size=-1>PSBR</font>) than is desirable so far into the economic cycle. New data on October 16th put the <font size=-1>PSBR</font> at &#163;3.4 billion in September, and total borrowing for the first half of this financial year at &#163;16.1 billion--making it extremely difficult for Mr Clarke to cut much off the income-tax rate in the budget on November 26th. What has gone wrong?<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Value-added tax (<font size=-1>VAT</font>) is mostly to blame. <font size=-1>VAT</font>, levied on goods and services, contributes almost one-third of total tax revenues, a larger slice than in other big economies (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). Yet in 1995-96, the &#163;43 billion of <font size=-1>VAT</font> collected was a hefty &#163;5 billion less than forecast in the November 1994 budget. That money could have paid for a cut of almost two pence from the basic rate of income tax. Although <font size=-1>VAT</font> revenues are in line with forecasts so far this financial year, that is because these forecasts already assume disappointing <font size=-1>VAT</font> revenues.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Not all of 1995-96's missing &#163;5 billion is inexplicable. The 1994 budget assumed much faster <font size=-1>GDP</font> growth than there turned out to be. Had the Treasury plugged into its forecasting model the amount of growth that actually took place, it would have expected to collect some &#163;2 billion less in <font size=-1>VAT</font>, calculates Chris Giles, an economist at the Institute for Fiscal Studies, an independent research group. But nobody has yet worked out what happened to the remaining &#163;3 billion shortfall, says Mr Giles. A working party set up earlier this year is examining the more plausible theories, and will report to the chancellor soon. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One possibility is that consumers have been spending more heavily on "zero rated" goods than the Treasury expected. Britain has a standard rate of <font size=-1>VAT</font> of 17.5%-- above average for developed countries-- but levies a reduced rate of 8% on domestic fuel, and exempts some goods and services, because they are, ostensibly, necessities. This is no small beer: making zero-rated purchases subject to the standard rate of <font size=-1>VAT</font> would have raised around &#163;15 billion in 1995-96. One reason why spending might have been skewed more towards zero-rated purchases is the launch of the National Lottery--but its impact could only have been tiny, and then only if the money spent on tickets would otherwise have gone on <font size=-1>VAT</font>-able buys.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tax avoidance (legal) and evasion (illegal) are likelier culprits. Britain's "<font size=-1>VAT</font> productivity"--the additional revenue raised by each extra percentage point of the tax rate--has fallen steadily since 1989, suggesting that the increase in the rate to 17.5% has encouraged greater effort to cut tax bills.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Kent Matthews, an economist at Cardiff Business School, reckons that increases in the threshold at which firms start to pay the tax have encouraged innovative ways to cut bills, such as hairdressing salons "renting" chairs to individual cutters, who become self-employed workers earning less than the <font size=-1>VAT</font> threshold. He recently analysed <font size=-1>VAT</font> payment in several industries and compared this with estimated potential <font size=-1>VAT</font> revenues, concluding that revenues in the various sectors were between 30% and 100% lower than they should have been. In restaurants and hairdressing, in particular, the gap between actual and potential <font size=-1>VAT</font> was big and, since 1992, growing.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The small firms that dominate these sectors may not be the only problem, however. The smallest 70% of traders pay only 10% of total <font size=-1>VAT</font> revenues; 75% of the tax-take is culled from fewer than 2,000 big firms. So for &#163;3 billion to go missing, the chances are that those big firms are up to something. That is less likely to be evasion than honest, above-board tax avoidance. According to a senior Treasury official, the number of <font size=-1>VAT</font> experts employed by accounting firms and big <font size=-1>VAT</font> payers has recently risen sharply.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What can be done? Customs and Excise, which collects <font size=-1>VAT</font>, might try harder, perhaps, although it already has a fearsome reputation. Another option is to extend the coverage of <font size=-1>VAT</font> to zero-rated goods and (<font size=-1>EU</font> rules permitting) lower the rate. Dave, a London builder who helps customers avoid <font size=-1>VAT</font> by working for cash, points out that demand for this service has grown as the <font size=-1>VAT</font> rate has risen, whereas "the lower the rate, the less people will try not to pay it." Take note, Mr Clarke.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845683200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
