<html><head><title>Fertile Field</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Welfare</b></p>
<h1>Fertile Field</h1>

PROMISING not to raise taxes may be a prerequisite to getting elected in the 1990s, but it imposes tiresome constraints on politicians once in office: they can borrow, break promises, or, worst of all, have no extra money to spend on pet projects. Or so it seemed. Now a fourth option is at hand, thanks to Frank Field, a Labour <font size=-1>MP</font> who chairs the House of Commons Select Committee on Social Security: impose new taxes, but call them something else.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Field unveiled this idea--which may not be as daft as it seems--in "How to Pay for the Future: Building a Stakeholders' Welfare", published on October 16th. He aims, commendably, to set out a blueprint for reforming the welfare state in ways that reduce incentives to milk the system and care better for the truly needy.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His plans include funding only half of the National Health Service from general taxes. Thus, income tax could be cut--the lower rate from 20% to 5% and the basic rate from 24% to 19%. To pay for the other half of the <font size=-1>NHS</font>, Mr Field would raise the rate of national-insurance contributions by seven percentage points. People would stop paying into the state earnings-related pension scheme (<font size=-1>SERPS</font>), but would be compelled to pay 16% of their income into a non-state pension scheme. Existing <font size=-1>SERPS</font> pensions would still be paid, but the scheme would no longer be able to use fresh contributions to pay them. To raise the cash, Mr Field would issue bonds--ie, borrow it. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It would be easy to dismiss this as fiscal casuistry, designed to obscure the true costs of welfare reform. But Mr Field is a serious thinker, much respected, who makes no bones about better welfare costing. He believes that the main reason people dislike paying tax is that they have no sense of ownership over the money once it disappears into the public purse. But call it national insurance or a compulsory pension contribution, and perhaps even give people individual welfare accounts, and they will see where their money goes and how they benefit from it, and so be willing to pay more. If Labour forms the next government, there is a fair chance that Tony Blair, a big fan of Mr Field's ideas, would see how this one works in practice. New Labour, new compulsory contributions?<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845683200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
