<html><head><title>Swimming in subsidies</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0><p><font size=-1>These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.</font></p></td><td></td><td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table><p><b>Irish Sea ferries</b></p><h1>Swimming in subsidies</h1><font size=1>LIVERPOOL</font><p>COMPANIES running ferries across the Irish Sea, unlike those in the English Channel struggling against the tunnel, are finding that business is growing apace. Perhaps the chance of peace in Northern Ireland boosted passenger and car traffic; but the booming Irish economy is also responsible. Freight and passenger volumes have both doubled over the past ten years (see <a href="br3.gif">map</a>).<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Shipping firms have prospered from this swelling trade, and so too have port companies. But part of the ports' rising income has come from <font size=-1>EU</font> subsidies. Since 1989 it has poured more than &#163;100m into developing Irish Sea ports.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The main effects of these subsidies, which are intended to improve trading links between countries at the edge of the <font size=-1>EU</font>, are to fatten the companies' profits and to distort competition. Some ports do not qualify for subsidies and have complained to the European Commission that they are facing unfair competition. And although subsidies are not supposed to be spent on ships, some of the subsidised ports also own ferry companies, and some ferry firms own ports.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On either side of the short crossing between Ulster and Scotland, about &#163;80m (including a &#163;53m <font size=-1>EU</font> subsidy) will have been spent at Belfast and Larne by 1999, and about &#163;20m (including a &#163;3m <font size=-1>EU</font> subsidy) at Stranraer and Cairnryan. Some of this is to help ferry firms build terminals for a new breed of high-speed freight and passenger-carrying ships.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Stena, a Swedish shipping firm which reckons it carries 64% of Irish Sea passengers, has spent &#163;130m on two huge catamaran ferries each capable of doing 40 knots (74km per hour), twice the speed of conventional ferries. While passengers have poured on to the ships since they began sailings this year, rivals are less happy that Stena owns two of the British ports they sail from--Stranraer and Holyhead--and is getting a subsidy of about 15% towards the &#163;63m cost of terminals for the new ferries at both ports.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The European Commission became aware of these concerns when Stena and two of the other companies sailing from Stranraer and nearby Cairnryan, Sea Containers and <font size=-1>P&O</font>, all sought cash for new terminals. The commission and the Scottish Office gave up trying to work out which bits of the projects were for public benefit and which were for private gain, and simply shared the subsidy out at a lower rate than the companies asked for.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This approach, however, does not deal with the complaint by Sea Containers that Heysham, a Lancashire port it owns, is in an area which does not qualify for <font size=-1>EU</font> regional aid, while rivals like Mersey Docks & Harbour Company (<font size=-1>MDHC</font>) can get <font size=-1>EU</font> money. Since 1988, Sea Containers has spent &#163;10m on Heysham, roughly the same amount that Mersey Docks has received in <font size=-1>EU</font> subsidies.<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fortunately for Sea Containers, however, it looks as though its fears that <font size=-1>MDHC</font> could get an unfair advantage may not materialise because of a battle for control of docks on the Mersey. On the Birkenhead side of the river, Merseyside Development Corporation has put together a scheme for a freight terminal with Forth Ports of Edinburgh. Forth Ports says it cannot go ahead without a subsidy. But its bid for <font size=-1>EU</font> money was blocked this year when <font size=-1>MDHC</font> announced it was going to build a &#163;16.5m freight terminal on the Liverpool side without any aid. <br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Indeed, so much Irish Sea freight is now being handled at Liverpool, that it looks as though neither terminal needs a subsidy to be profitable. The Port of Mostyn in North Wales seems to agree: it says its ambitious plan to build a freight terminal can go ahead without an <font size=-1>EU</font> grant.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845683200,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="br7543.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
