<html><head><title>TECHNOLOGY BRIEF</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width="371" height="26" alt="Science and Technology" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>TECHNOLOGY BRIEF</h1>

<h2>Roboflops</h2>
<p><b>In the final brief of our series asking why some technologies disappoint, we look at the general-purpose robot, which was supposed to be cooking us dinner by now</b></p><br>
THE 1970s have a lot to answer for, but often overlooked amid bell bottoms and disco music is the notion of the do-it-all robot. The decade was a heady time for robotics: a Russian robotic rover wheeled about on the moon, while <font size=-1>R2-D2</font> and <font size=-1>C-3PO</font> nattered charmingly to each other. Robots assembled cars in Detroit and motorcycles in Japan. Industrialists predicted a multi-billion dollar robotics industry within a decade. And the home of 2000, <i>Popular Mechanics</i> confidently predicted, would have a robot butler to go with its personal helicopter.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Alas, most of us still sweep our own floors, serve ourselves drinks and cook our own meals. The only wheeled beasts that roam most of our offices are vacuum cleaners. Even in factories, most of the machines that stamp, bend, package and sort are specially built for the job, which means that they are little closer to the vision of an autonomous, programmable robot than, say, a wind-up clock. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Where is Robby the Robot, not to speak of the rebellious 'droids of "Westworld"? Still far in the future. The past 20 years or so have been frustrating ones for the robotics business, which has been dogged by technical glitches and sluggish demand for what products it has delivered.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;True, the American robotics industry, which almost collapsed in the 1980s, is undergoing something of a renaissance-- some 70,000 robots are now at work in American factories, according to the Robotics Industry Association. But that is still a modest figure. The world leader, Japan, has nearly 400,000 in its factories, though they are still mainly in the automotive and electronics industries, where they started out 30 years ago. Even in Japan, factory workers still outnumber robots by 50 to 1; in America it is 300 to 1.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reason for this is that, contrary to the hype that surrounded their creation, robots are rarely a good replacement for humans. Making a machine that, say, moves a bit like a human arm is relatively easy. Teaching it what to do with its mobility is a lot tougher. The hard part of being human is not bending joints, but seeing, thinking and sensing--all things that machines still do poorly.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Consider a modestly skilled factory worker whose job is to slip rubber rings around a rod. First he must pick up a ring from a tray of them. Easy enough for the worker, but a nightmare for a robot. The problem is identifying the ring, which may be at any angle, amongst a mass of other rings all of the same colour.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Throw enough computing power at this image-recognition problem and a robot can crack it, but more slowly than a person. So the factory may be forced to present the rings in a more ordered way: carefully stacked, for instance, or neatly lined up on a tape. This is expensive.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Once the robot identifies the ring and its orientation, picking it up is easy. But putting it on the rod is not. The worker might place the ring on the end of the rod, then squeeze it and rock it until it slips on. For him, this is simple. But from a robot's perspective, he is engaging in some state-of-the-art "force control" and sensing. Moreover, the worker benefits from a very responsive "feedback loop"--ie, he can feel how hard he is pushing and adjust his squeeze so as not to push too much.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The lack of a sense of touch is a notorious robotic failing. When experts go to a trade fair and see a robot proving its dexterity by washing windows without breaking them, they snicker, knowing that the flexibility of the sponge gives it a big margin of error; the same robot could not put a cream puff in a box without crushing it.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are signs of improvement here. The faster a robot's motors and computer are, the faster it can respond to its artificial sense of touch, and the less likely it is to damage what it is touching. But this is still the stuff of doctoral theses, not of household products. Nappy changing will remain a human chore for a while longer.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even when a factory robot can perform a task more efficiently than a person, the job of programming it and setting up its workplace can be more trouble than it is worth. The advantage of a general-purpose robot arm is that it can be programmed to do many jobs. The disadvantage is that the programming tends to be a job for highly paid <font size=-1>P</font>h<font size=-1>D</font> engineers, not technicians more used to the simple automation found on most factory floors. Commotion Systems, a new Californian firm, is developing easier ways to program robots using pre-designed software modules. For now, however, the chore of "training" robots is still one of the main reasons that they are not used more.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Outside the factory, a robot's failings are even more glaring. Seen through a machine's eyes, the real world is a baffling jumble of obstacles and unrecognisable shapes. HelpMate Robotics, a Connecticut company founded by Joe Engelberger (who is widely considered to be the founder of modern industrial robotics), makes a robot that can carry drugs, <font size=-1>X</font>-ray films and the like from one part of a hospital to another. But to navigate around even this ordered environment, the machine needs infra-red and ultrasonic sensors, a video camera, gyroscopes and an electronic map. Even then it requires a hospital with automatic doors, and sometimes needs to call for help. Stairs are out of the question, although the robot can be taught to operate a modified lift. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Engelberger's firm thinks that a home robot--not a tin domestic for the average family, but an aide for the elderly and disabled--is now within reach. Food might have to be bar-coded with the refrigerator shelf that it belongs on and its microwaving instructions, but a robot-cooked meal, delivered to the bedside, is already possible. A little dusting--don't forget to clear the shelves first--is probably on the cards, too, along with some light vacuuming and other domestic chores, so long as they are confined to a single floor.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But consider other, less routine jobs and HelpMate's hurdles become clearer. "Fetch my glasses from the bedroom" is a simple request, but obeying it summons up three of the trickiest problems in computer science: voice recognition (which allows the robot to translate sounds into words), natural-language processing (which enables it to translate words into commands) and image recognition. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As with many troubled products, the problem with robotics is not so much with the technology itself, but with the expectations that it has raised. Seduced by the humanoid helpers of Hollywood, people tend to think of robots for typical human jobs, which are often the ones for which they are worst suited.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;John Tenney, one of the founders of Commotion Systems, recalls a visit to one spark plug factory, which was considering installing a few robots: "We walked past rows of people doing brain-numbing work, until we got to the part of the factory doing the most complex assembly. They wanted robots there because they had a hard time finding skilled workers. But if it's hard for people, it's even harder for robots. You've got to pick the low-hanging fruit."<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This does not mean that robots will continue to disappoint, only that they are still a long way from becoming general-purpose helpers, much less anyone's plastic pal. Rosie, the Jetson's friendly house-cleaning robot, is likely to remain Rosie the plain old Riveter for a while yet.<br>

