<html><head><title>New adventures in hi-fi</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/mo.gif" width="157" height="26" alt="Moreover" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>New adventures in hi-fi</h1>

OASIS, the world's newest rock mega group, may be paying homage to the Beatles by putting together an album in the fab four's Abbey Road studio, but the practical business of recording music in the 1990s bears little relation to what went on 30 years ago. The pop hits of the 1960s were mostly created using four track tape recorders. Now, 24-track equipment is the norm, tape has given way to the compact disc, and the combination of synthesisers, optical fibre and the Internet has made it possible to make, record and distribute music at a far higher quality and far lower cost than once seemed likely.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;"Good Vibrations"*, a book by Mark Cunningham, who is himself a "song writer, musician and producer", describes the effect of technological change on recorded music since the invention of multi-tracking in 1949. His account is sometimes fascinating, sometimes impenetrably technophile. It is interesting that London's top recording studio can accommodate a symphony orchestra and a heavy-rock band in adjacent rooms with no leakage of sound from one to the other; very much less so that one room contains a "72-channel <font size=-1>SSL</font> 8000 <font size=-1>G</font>-plus console incorporating Ultimation and Total Recall automated fader systems".<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Technology has transformed how established musicians ply their trade. Sting is one of a growing number who work from home, recording tunes in his dining room and mixing them in what was once a cowshed. Frank Sinatra, in America, recorded duets by telephone with, among others, Bono, who was in Ireland--a technological advance that Oasis's warring Gallagher brothers might find handy should they find Abbey Road's quarters too close for comfort. George Michael now samples his own voice for backing vocals, with himself on synthesiser for instrumentals, dispensing (mostly) with session musicians. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But not everyone is so keen. A Luddite tendency has emerged among mainstream musicians, a sort of "campaign for real rock music": The claim is that new technology kills the raw emotion necessary for <i>bona fide</i> rock'n'roll. Paul Weller, Britain's top male vocalist of the moment, boasts of "playing real instruments" and avoiding "all that digital bollocks". Seeking the "kind of space and environment" once enjoyed by the Rolling Stones and Led Zeppelin, an American rocker, Lenny Kravitz, recently recorded in a 17th-century chateau near Paris, while Les N&eacute;gresses Vertes used a deserted casino.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But technology's greatest boon will be for the thousands of aspiring rock-stars who "for a once-only investment of just a few thousand pounds  make better sounding records than could be produced in a top studio 15 years ago." With the Internet promising to become a viable means of distributing and popularising music, the writing may be on the wall for the big companies which dominate the music business by signing up hopefuls on long contracts and controlling the dissemination of their work.<br>


* Castle Communications; 378 pages; &#163;9.99 and $14.95<br>
</td></tr></table>


