<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff"><p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0></p><p align=center><img src="../images/wtw1.gif" alt="Politics this Week" border=0></p><hr size=6 align=center width=65%><center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%><h2>Keeping the peace</h2><p>Talks on Israel's long-delayed deployment from most of<b> Hebron</b> started shakily. The Israeli government wants to renegotiate the accord made by its predecessor. The Palestinians say no. The Americans say keep on talking. Ezer Weizman, Israel's president, put pressure on his own government by inviting Yasser Arafat to lunch and accepting an invitation from Egypt's Hosni Mubarak to visit Cairo.</p><p>Islamist terrorists killed 34 people in southern <b>Algeria</b>, many of them bus passengers who had their throats slit. </p><p>Pro-government candidates did better in <b>Kuwait</b>'s (all male) election than the Islamists who had been the largest single block in the out-going parliament. </p><b>Zaire</b> issued a one-week ultimatum for 200,000 ethnic Tutsis to leave the country. </p><p> <h2>Russia and NATO</h2>Alexander Lebed, Russia's presidential security adviser, who has blown hot and cold on <font size=-1>NATO</font >'s proposed <b>eastward enlargement</b>, said that the organisation should make a pact with Russia before expanding. In any case, Russia should not, he said in Brussels this week, become "hysterical". Back home, Mr Lebed's relations with President Boris Yeltsin, appeared to be worsening.</p><p>After two years of relative peace in <b>Northern Ireland</b>,the Irish Republican Army exploded two big car-bombs in the province's British army headquarters, injuring more than 30 people. John Bruton, the Irish prime minister, accused the < font size=-1>IRA</font> of using the tactics of Nazis. Loyalist politicians made pleas to loyalist terrorists not to retaliate.</p><p><b>Hans Tietmeyer, </b>head of Germany's Bundesbank, criticised would-be members of Europe's proposed currency union for seeking to meet the entry criteria "through a breathless short-term effort with one-off results quickly cobbled together". </p><p><b>Corsican separatists</b>, set off a bomb outside the office of the mayor of Bordeaux, Alain Jupp&eacute;, whose main job is prime minister of France.</p><p><b>Turkey's </b>Islamic prime minister, Necmettin Erbakan, was embarrassed on a visit to Libya when its leader, Muammar Qaddafi, declared that the Kurds deserved a country of their own. Turkish opposition politicians leapt on the affair. </p><p>Belgium's prime minister since 1992, <b>Jean-Luc Dehaene</b>, said he would not try to keep his job when his coalition government's term ends in 1999.</p><p>A drugs-monitoring centre set up by the European Commission two years ago said that between 500,000 and 1m citizens of the <font size=-1>EU</font> take <b>heroin</b>. Up to a fifth of the Union's people aged 18-35 are thought to have taken cannabis.</p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%><p>Nordic governments are trying to quell a long-running <b>motorbike-gang war</b> after an anti-tank missile was fired into a club in the Danish capital, Copenhagen, killing two people. Sporadic gang violence has also occurred in Sweden, Norway and Finland.</p><p><h2>Vote-catching</p></h2>The main candidates for the American <b>presidency </b>had their first debate, in Connecticut, and it was generally declared a draw. It did no harm to Bill Clinton and did not, as Republicans hoped, ignite the candidacy of Bob Dole. Their running mates, Al Gore (the Democrat) and Jack Kemp (the Republican), held a soporific debate in Florida. Mr Gore won.<p><b>Argentina</b>'s two leading Peronist hopefuls for the 1999 presidential candidacy cast doubt on President Carlos Menem's planned reform of labour law. As unions talked of a strike, he stood firm, angering them further with a decree to let workers choose among rival union-run health plans. These bring the unions clout--and siphoned-off cash, say critics. Next step: private sector competition.</p><p><b>Colombia'sarmy </b>and police said they had captured guerrilla documents outlining plans for widespread attacks in the capital, Bogota.</p><p><b>Brazil'sconstitution </b>bars President Fernando Henrique Cardoso from re-election in 1998. Could it be amended? Haggling over the mayoral run-off in Sao Paulo made it likelier. Their own man having come third in the first round, some pro-Cardoso politicians will back Celso Pitta, the front-runner favoured by the outgoing mayor, Paulo Maluf. He and his party, with many members in Congress, have been hostile to re-election, but are now softening.</p><p><h2>Against Bhutto</p></h2><p>Pressure grew on <b>Benazir Bhutto </b>to step down as Pakistan's prime minister when 40,000 people joined an opposition march in Lahore. The marchers accused the government of corruption. Police broke up the march after a government building was stoned.</p><p>Afghanistan's victorious <b>Taliban fighters </b>pressed northwards, aiming to gain complete control of the country, but met stiff resistance from forces loyal to the ousted government.</p><p><b>Japan's birthrate </b>fell to 1.4 babies per woman last year. If sustained, Japan's population will fall to 55m in 2100, from 125m today, according to a government projection.</p><p>Yao Wenyuan, the sole surviving member of China's <b>Gang of Four</b>,<b> </b>was released from jail after 20 years. The gang helped to run Chairman Mao's cultural revolution, in which hundreds of thousands of Chinese were killed.</p><p>An outbreak of <b>dengue fever </b> killed 92 people in Delhi. The fever is carried by mosquitoes which often breed in air conditioners.</p></td></tr></table></center><p align=center><a href="bw0755.html">BUSINESS THIS WEEK</a></p><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845078400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;<a href="bw0755.html">Next article</a></p><p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p></td></tr></table></body></html>
