<html><head><title> Cash to MPs </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Cash to MPs</b></p>
<h1>Cleaning house</h1>

UNDER the 1689 Bill of Rights, <font size=-1>MP</font>s cannot be questioned or prosecuted for any of their actions at Westminster. As long ago as 1975, a Royal Commission headed by Lord Justice Salmon recommended that the Bill of Rights be amended to make the bribery of an <font size=-1>MP</font> a criminal offence. If the commission's recommendation had been enacted instead of being ignored by successive governments, Neil Hamilton, a former junior trade minister, and Mohamed Al Fayed, the owner of Harrods, the two key figures at the centre of the cash-for-questions scandal, could well be facing a criminal prosecution rather than a parliamentary inquiry.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Al Fayed claims that he paid Mr Hamilton, Conservative <font size=-1>MP</font> for Tatton, &#163;28,000 to ask 17 parliamentary questions on his behalf after being advised by Ian Greer, a lobbyist, that <font size=-1>MP</font>s were hired in the same way as taxis. Mr Hamilton acknowledges receiving &#163;10,000 in "commission fees" from Mr Greer. He also admits running up a bill of more than &#163;4,000 at the Ritz hotel in Paris as a guest of Mr Al Fayed. But he denies that these payments, neither of which was declared to Parliament, were linked to his repeated parliamentary representations on behalf of Mr Al Fayed. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is this ugly brew of bitterly contested allegations which Sir Gordon Downey, the parliamentary commissioner for standards, has now been asked to investigate. John Major, who has called for a rapid inquiry, said the charges were "poisoning British politics". That undoubtedly is correct. But a hurried inquiry held in private by a part-time commissioner, who has no powers to require witnesses to attend or documents to be produced, and who can report only to a Tory-dominated parliamentary committee, is unlikely to restore public confidence. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Major has so far rejected demands for a wider inquiry, but he may have to reconsider this stance when Parliament reassembles later this month. Mr Blair, the Labour leader, and Mr Ashdown, the Liberal Democrats' leader, have joined forces in calling for an independent judicial inquiry. If this demand is ignored, both opposition parties are considering tabling a motion of no confidence. Such a motion could put Mr Major, with his majority of only one in the House of Commons, in an awkward spot, for it may be the one motion which could force all the opposition parties, including the Ulster Unionists, to vote against his government.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Quite apart from parliamentary pressures, there is a strong case for a judicial inquiry held under the 1921 Tribunals of Inquiry Act. The disclosure that David Willetts, at the time a government whip and now a junior minister, sought to delay an earlier parliamentary probe into Neil Hamilton's conduct by lobbying Sir Geoffrey Johnson Smith, the committee's Tory chairman, has done nothing to bolster confidence in the Commons' impartiality. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover there is a need to investigate more than just Mr Hamilton. In the thousands of pages of documents connected to the case, there is evidence that Mr Greer paid undeclared commissions not just to Mr Hamilton but to other members of the Commons Trade and Industry Committee. Sir Michael Grylls, the committee's chairman, received such payments from 1985, although he declared this interest to Parliament only in 1990. Tim Smith, the committee's secretary, resigned as a junior minister in 1994 after charges that he had received thousands of pounds in cash directly from Mr Al Fayed in return for asking parliamentary questions.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The need for an independent inquiry is further reinforced by the political nature of many of Mr Al Fayed's charges. He claims that he handed &#163;250,000 to the Conservative Party before the 1987 election and that since then he has given, through Mr Greer, campaign donations to 24 <font size=-1>MP</font>s, including two Labour <font size=-1>MP</font>s and one Liberal Democrat. Mr Greer, for his part, claims to have raised more than &#163;750,000 for Tory candidates. The one thing the two men now appear to have in common is their resentment at receiving so little in return.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Those caught up in this affair will, no doubt, claim they are victims of a changing political culture. If the government had acted on the recommendations of the Salmon Commission to make bribery of an <font size=-1>MP</font> a criminal offence--and to define precisely what bribery is--that excuse would not be available. But it is, at best, a poor defence. As the Royal Commission noted: "Membership of Parliament is a great honour and carries with it a special duty to maintain the highest standards of probity." Few of those involved in this wretched affair seem to have lived up to the "highest standards of probity".<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845078400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
