<html><head><title> Civil Service </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Civil Service</b></p>
<h1>After Butler</h1>

WITHIN months of taking office, the incoming British government will appoint the country's most powerful non elected official. Sir Robin Butler, the cabinet secretary and head of the civil service, retires at the end of 1997, giving him just time to initiate a new government into the mysteries of office--and to allow it to appoint his successor.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since discretion is essential to the job, none of the probable candidates is conducting anything so crude as a campaign. But insiders have noted that <b>Hayden Phillips</b>, the 53-year-old permanent secretary of the Department of National Heritage and a former Brussels <i>chef de cabinet</i> to Roy Jenkins, has been putting himself about a bit. Lord Jenkins's enthusiasm is not echoed widely in Whitehall.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A lively choice would be<b> Richard Mottram</b>, 50, permanent secretary at defence, who previously ran the Office of Public Service and Science under Sir Robin. Mr Mottram has a more speculative mind than most mandarins, with an engaging ability to skirt close to indiscretion without ever crossing the line and actually saying anything indiscreet. He has in the past denied that he wants the job. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Lively too would be <b>Richard Wilson</b>, 54, the permanent secretary at the Home Office. Mr Wilson was highly regarded as a hands-on manager in his previous job as permanent secretary at the Department of the Environment, but some Whitehall insiders question whether he could not have done better in the admittedly difficult task of handling Michael Howard, a populist home secretary. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A less extrovert choice, but perhaps Whitehall's favourite, would be <b>Andrew Turnbull</b>, 51, a former private secretary to Margaret Thatcher. Mr Turnbull, who succeeded Mr Wilson at environment, is reckoned both to have a good brain and to be a good manager. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, there is a further possibility: that Sir Robin will not have a successor at all. Labour is considering splitting his job so that there is one cabinet secretary and a separate head of the civil service. Sir Robin is resisting this, believing that his role as the prime minister's adviser has given him the clout needed to manage the powerful and relatively autonomous permanent secretaries who run individual government departments. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However if Labour wins and Sir Robin fails to persuade it of his view, a new candidate might come into the picture for the cabinet secretaryship. <b>Sir John Kerr</b>, 54, is Britain's ambassador in Washington. Aside from a spell in the Treasury, part of it as private secretary to Geoffrey (now Lord) Howe, his career has mostly been in the Foreign Office, leaving him short of experience in the home civil service. This might spark something of a revolt if he were appointed to run it. But Sir John is a legendary operator with a quicksilver intelligence and the stamina of an ox--just the qualities which a new government might appreciate in a cabinet secretary.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This would open the door for <b>Michael Bichard</b>, 49,<b> </b>the permanent secretary at the Department for Education and Employment, a rare example of a senior civil servant who really is enthusiastic about management, to take on the other half of the job as head of the home civil service.<br>

