<html><head><title> Local by-elections </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Local by-elections</b></p>
<h1>High Tories</h1>

CONSERVATIVE support in local by elections has risen to its highest level for four years. The latest in <i>The Economist</i>'s regular survey of such results shows the Tories won 34% of the vote in wards fought by all three main parties betwen July and September (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>), only four percentage points behind Labour. They have not performed this well since 1992--the year in which they won the last general election. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The main cause of the change is not Labour weakness. Labour's share of the vote, although down by three percentage points from the third quarter of 1995, is actually 2.5 points up on the first half of this year. Rather, the Tory recovery is due to a weaker performance by the Liberal Democrats. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Lib Dem share of the vote, at 24%, is six percentage points lower than in the third quarter of 1995. In the same quarter three years ago, they were polling more votes in local government elections than either of the other big parties. However, they still do much better in local elections than nationally. Their local vote is almost double their national opinion-poll ratings.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;With the general election now no more than seven months away, how does the Tory showing compare with those in the run-up to their last three successful general election campaigns? The good news for the Tories is that they are doing as well or better in local contests than they did before previous general elections. In the third quarter of 1982, they also polled 34% of the vote, but won easily in 1983; in the third quarter of 1986, 31% of the vote, before winning in 1987; and in the third quarter of 1991, 34% of the vote before winning in 1992. However, there is bad news for them too: Labour is running an average of 6% higher in local contests than it was in the corresponding period before its three defeats.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour has claimed some strong local by-election performances in recent weeks, at the expense of the Lib Dems. Moreover, an <font size=-1>NOP</font> poll in the <i>Sunday Times </i>gave it a 23% lead over the Tories, up four percentage points, reflecting its successful conference and new allegations of Tory sleaze.<br>

