<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><p align=center>
<table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</p></center>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" alt="Britain in Brief" border=0></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Admission</b> &nbsp; The Ministry of Defence admitted that some troops serving in the Gulf in 1990 and 1991 had been exposed to high levels of pesticides, and that this could be a factor in "Gulf War Syndrome", the unexplained ailments suffered by more than 1,000 veterans.<br>
<p><b>Cow queue</b> &nbsp; The government also admitted that the backlog of cattle awaiting slaughter under the programme to eliminate mad-cow disease was at least 400,000. A further &#163;45m of state aid was offered to beef farmers.<br>
<p><b>No beef</b> &nbsp; The Vegetarian Society claimed the mad-cow scare made up to a million people in Britain give up eating meat. However, the Meat and Livestock Commission said overall meat consumption was about the same now as it was 30 years ago.<br>
<p><b>Get 'em off</b> &nbsp; The government says that it intends to ban a French satellite television channel from broadcasting pornography to Britain.<br>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Jobs come . . .</b> &nbsp; Hyundai, a South Korean conglomerate, announced plans to spend &#163;2.4 billion building two microchip plants at Dunfermline, Fife, eventually creating up to 2,000 jobs.<br>
<p><b>. . . jobs go</b> &nbsp; British Energy, a privatised nuclear-power generator, said it would cut 1,460 jobs within the next five years.<br>
<p><b>Hoax</b> &nbsp; The <i>Sun</i> newspaper admitted it was the victim of a hoax after it printed stills from a video supposedly showing Princess Diana frolicking with James Hewitt, a former lover.<br>
<p><b>Deserving</b> &nbsp; The High Court ruled that Peter Lilley, the social-security secretary, had exceeded his powers by introducing measures to prevent asylum-seekers from claiming benefit.<br>
<p><b>Tartan tax</b> &nbsp; Workers at Hector Russell, a maker of traditional Scottish dress, were told by the Inland Revenue that they would be taxed on the kilts their employer gives them to wear at work. But the kilts will become tax-free if the company's logo is attached to them.<br>

</td></tr></table></center>

