<html><head><title> Of spandex and software </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>Of spandex and software </h1>

<p><b>WordPerfect was once the proudest name in software. Now it is owned by one of the most shameless. And a good thing too</b></p> 
IT IS hard to believe that Michael Cowpland, Ottawa's most notorious challenger to taste and decorum, could really be a rival to Microsoft's Bill Gates. Mr Cowpland and his wife, Marilyn, drive matching Porsches, his blue, hers pink. Mrs Cowpland recently adorned the cover of a local magazine in a red spandex Santa suit (and sells far more risqu&eacute; stuff in her clothing store). Their massive glass-and-steel mansion, a smaller replica of Mr Cowpland's corporate headquarters, boasts two racquet courts as well as a ten-car garage, and has outraged neighbours in their otherwise staid suburb. Far from living and breathing software, Mr Cowpland prefers martial arts and tennis: he even schedules meetings around tennis championships.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His business methods are unorthodox too. The name of his first company, Mitel, now a large Canadian telecoms-equipment maker, originally stood for "Mike and Terry's Lawnmowers". Mr Cowpland and his partner had intended to make remote-controlled lawnmowers, but switched to electronics in the early 1970s. After he sold his share in Mitel in 1984, he started his current firm, Corel. It now leads the design-and-graphics software business. Corel's trademarks are garish ads (invariably embellished with rainbow-striped balloons), lots of different versions of its software and cheap package deals.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Corel has not yet managed to turn its market share into substantial profits (see <a href="wb2.gif">chart</a>). The average, boring software mogul would spend the next year or so sorting this out, all the time praising the Lord for having discovered at least one part of the industry that is Microsoft-free. Mr Cowpland, however, is neither average nor boring.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In January, Corel bought WordPerfect, the firm that introduced word processing to the world but then let Microsoft Word grab the market. Mr Cowpland paid just $11m in cash and $100m in shares, along with some royalty fees, to Novell, which had paid $800m for WordPerfect in 1994. Considering that WordPerfect, even in its current distressed state, still sells about $300m worth of software a year, its new owner could probably turn a profit by simply letting the franchise tick over. Instead Mr Cowpland is rejigging WordPerfect to challenge Microsoft in its most profitable business, the market for office "suites"--typically, a word-processor, spreadsheet, database and graphics program that work together.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At present this market is dominated by Microsoft's Office package. Ray Noorda, Novell's Microsoft-hating boss, had hoped that WordPerfect would be the torpedo to sink Mr Gates; instead it very nearly sank Novell. Mr Cowpland reckons that he can do better, thanks to two innovations. The first involves launching a new version of WordPerfect using all of Corel's hard-sell marketing tactics. That means bundling more software with the core word-processor and spreadsheet and pricing the product absurdly low. Although the list price is $260, anyone who claims he is swapping to it from a competing program need pay only $99. For corporate customers, the deal is even better: $895 for a version that can serve dozens of individual users. Microsoft, by comparison, charges about $200 per user for its suite.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Mr Cowpland's most daring move is a technical one. Corel is feverishly working on a version of the WordPerfect suite in Java, the Internet's hot new programming language. The advantage of Java is that it can run on any sort of computer, not just those running Microsoft's operating systems. A Java WordPerfect could run on the new wave of cheap "network computers", as well as on personal digital assistants (one of which Corel will be releasing itself next year) and other non-<font size=-1>PC</font> devices.<br>
</p><p><b>Back to the future</b><br>There is a bit of historical neatness to this: WordPerfect first made its name in the early days of personal computing by releasing a version for practically every sort of computer available, no matter how obscure. Rewriting the code for the particulars of each machine made releasing updated versions a logistical nightmare (the firm's headquarters was practically a museum of strange computers and obscure printers, all of which had to be supported). Now Java offers an opportunity to gain the same advantage without rewriting: the same software should run on any machine.<br></b>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Corel releases the first test versions of the Java WordPerfect suite on November 1st. There are plenty of technical hurdles to leap. But it is hard not to admire Mr Cowpland's courage. When Mr Noorda first rode WordPerfect into battle with Microsoft, Novell was one of the richest firms in the industry and dominated the networking sector that would soon emerge as the core of the Internet. Just two years later, it was losing money as a result of its WordPerfect wounds.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The same could happen to Mr Cowpland, whose financial cushion is even thinner. But many in the industry are rooting for him all the same. Microsoft, like all firms, needs competition, but since it took over in office suites it has had far too little. Java could change that. Mr Cowpland, his tennis outfit doubtless adorned with Corel balloons, deserves to take at least a set off Mr Gates.<br>

<p align=center>
