<html><head><title> Still a virtual reality </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" alt="Science and Technology" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>

<h1>TECHNOLOGY BRIEF</h1>

<h2>Still a virtual reality</h2>
<p><b>Our third brief on the pitfalls facing new technologies looks at virtual reality and asks why it has not yet made dreams come true</b></p><br>
LOTS of new technologies promise to transform lives. Virtual reality (<font size=-1>VR</font>) is one--if the hype is to be believed. With the goggles, the gloves and the necessary gigabytes on a computer, it will be possible to create new worlds and fill them with beautiful people (or ugly ones--the choice is yours). It will require no more than slightly faster computers and slightly better gadgets for plugging people into them. The rise of <font size=-1>VR</font> is as inevitable as technological progress itself. Or so it was said.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In recent years, <font size=-1>VR</font>, which first emerged in the 1960s, has become a catch-all term for any computerised, interactive, real time, 3-<font size=-1>D</font> simulacrum, whether viewed on a stereoscopic headset or a single screen. Originally, however, it simply referred to what is now known as "immersive" virtual reality (<font size=-1>IVR</font>), in which users wear special headgear attached to a computer that gives them the impression of being in another environment.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There was no shortage of potential uses for <font size=-1>IVR</font>. It would enable designers to build and test a prototype aircraft without touching a screwdriver. Surgeons would be able to operate from afar. Soldiers would be able to control robotic tanks and aircraft. And, of course, there would be mind-boggling new games.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It would be astonishing if <font size=-1>IVR</font> had lived up to such great expectations. But even by more modest standards, it has been a disappointment. The global market for <font size=-1>VR</font> equipment-- immersive and otherwise--was only about $200m in 1995. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Technologies that replace existing ones must convince customers that they are better. Those that have no precursor must convince people that they are any good at all. <font size=-1>IVR</font> has been unable to do this for two main reasons.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;First, for many of its proposed uses, wearing a headset has no particular advantage over simply looking at a screen. Engineers can now design an entire aeroplane on computer, and then use <font size=-1>IVR</font> to simulate its manufacture and test its performance. But for most of this process, an immersed view is no more informative than a 3-<font size=-1>D</font> picture on a screen. Only when they need a pilot's-eye view--for example, to check that all the instruments are accessible--might they slip on the headgear. Even then, they may often prefer to have the computer draw a stick figure on the screen and calculate what is within its reach.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The same holds true for all computerised design: <font size=-1>IVR</font> and the fancy headset that goes with it are generally unnecessary. In many laboratories the headsets mostly sit idle, reserved for impressing visitors. (Some retailers cash in on this novelty value by using <font size=-1>IVR</font> to show customers the inside of a new house or car.) <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the technology could still be useful for creating environments in which to learn skills-- such as surgery or flying--or to do things--such as playing games--that would be expensive, dangerous, or even impossible in real life. Yet even here <font size=-1>IVR</font> is unable to make good its promises. The reason? The technology is still terrible. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The assumptions were only half right. Computers have got faster, but the peripherals have not kept pace.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The basic piece of <font size=-1>IVR</font> kit, dating back to the 1960s, is a bulky headset with a tiny screen for each eye. Usually, each screen shows a slightly different image, giving the illusion of 3-<font size=-1>D</font>. Attached wires or sensors track the wearer's head movements. From this, a computer providing the images works out what the user is looking at in the virtual scene, and draws it. For a deeper sense of immersion users may bedeck themselves with electronic pointers, earphones, gloves that monitor the shape of their hands, "haptic" devices that give the sensation of touching things, and even smell-emitters.<br>
<p><b><b>A distinct lack of vision</b><br>
</b>The point of being thus festooned is not to fool the wearer into thinking that he is somewhere real. The degree of immersion required depends on the application. Almost all these gizmos are still punishingly expensive and are mainly found in research laboratories. But for many uses--especially games, potentially the biggest single market-- just a headset should do, at least to start with.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But even the headsets turn customers off. Computers are still not powerful enough to eliminate "transport lag", the delay between moving your head and the image catching up. The field of view is narrow, typically just 10-20&#176; wide in games headsets, as against almost 180&#176; in real life. The depth of field feels wrong: whereas in real life looking at an object nearby causes objects in the distance to be out of focus, in <font size=-1>IVR</font> objects at all distances stay sharply defined. Finally, what the eye perceives-- such as motion--is not in synch with what the rest of the body feels. All this can lead to dizziness and disorientation, both during and after the experience.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Better systems do appear when uses are found for them. For example, at the Stanford Research Institute, animal trials of a "telesurgery" system are in progress. Video cameras in the operating theatre send stereoscopic images to the surgeon; robot arms give tactile feedback while replicating his actions. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The trouble is that such systems are developed mostly by those, including universities and the military, who need sophisticated equipment that the mass market neither requires nor can afford. This, says Myron Krueger, a <font size=-1>VR</font> pioneer and the boss of Artificial Reality, a research company in Connecticut, may be why commercial <font size=-1>IVR</font> applications, and games in particular, have disappointed. Companies have yet to produce systems that are good enough and cheap enough for a broad audience, partly because they have yet to be convinced that the demand is there.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Virtuality, a British company that is the leading maker of <font size=-1>IVR</font> games, thinks it is. It has developed a $350 headset for home use that is about to be launched in Japan. This one has a wider field of view than its rivals (although the set will be monoscopic and will not track head movements). Virtuality hopes to do better than either Sega or Nintendo, two Japanese games makers that have launched unsuccessful <font size=-1>IVR</font> games products, or America's Hasbro, which last year wrote off tens of millions of dollars on a similar venture. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, even good headgear may not suffice. Stephen Ellis, a <font size=-1>VR</font> researcher at <font size=-1>NASA</font>, argues that, aside from games, <font size=-1>IVR</font> still lacks a "killer application"-- something to make it invaluable to the masses, not just specialists. It has been tried out for many things, from letting supermarket managers fiddle with new shop layouts to training people to overcome their phobias with huge images of spiders, but there is still no general-purpose use.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some hope the Internet will create one. <font size=-1>VRML</font>, a programming language developed for the Net, allows 3-<font size=-1>D</font> scenes to be put on Web sites easily. This might create the demand for a home <font size=-1>IVR</font> system. Satisfying it will simply require slightly faster computers and slightly better gadgets for plugging people into them . . .<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?845078400,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
