<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Bull run</h2>
<p>(See <a href="bw1.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>American shares </b>powered upwards, taking the Dow Jones through 5,900 for the first time. The dollar squeaked above &#165;112 to a 32 month high, helped by weak Japanese production figures and a boost from housing starts in America. Bullishness invaded European markets too, with record highs in London--the <font size=-1>FTSE100</font> rising above 4,000--and several other markets. America's Treasury secretary, Robert Rubin, speaking at the World Bank meeting in Washington, <font size=-1>DC</font>, said the world economic outlook was the best in a "long, long time".</p>
<p>The European Union--supported by Canada--is to seek a ruling from the World Trade Organisation over whether America's recent <b>anti-Cuba legislation</b> violates international trade law.</p>
<p>Gold shares were pummelled after <b>gold</b> dropped through $380 an ounce, to stand about 9% down on its February high for the year.</p>
<h2>Downhill</h2>
<p>Shares in <b>Olivetti</b> fell after the Italian technology group admitted its net debt nearly doubled in only two months to almost 2.4 trillion lire ($1.6 billion) at the end of August and after a critical internal auditors' report. The loss making group has been spiralling downwards since the departure of Carlo De Benedetti as chairman some weeks ago, followed by more top executives amid accusations of false corporate reporting.</p>
<p>Germany's engineering union, <font size=-1>IG</font> Metall, promised a showdown if companies such as <b>Daimler-Benz</b>, which last week quickly took advantage of new rules to cut sick pay, pressed ahead with plans to renegotiate fringe benefits. Workers have been holding lightning strikes and stoppages in protest.</p>
<p><b>Eurotunnel</b> and its creditor banks at last reached agreement in principle on restructuring the Channel tunnel operator's &#163;8.8 billion ($13.8 billion) debt, repayment of which was suspended a year ago. Eurotunnel shares were themselves suspended as these negotiations were going on. <font size=-1>P&O</font> and Stena Lines are merging their Dover Straits ferry operations to compete with the tunnel.</p>
<p>Sweden's Autoliv, Europe's biggest maker of <b>airbags </b>and seatbelts, is to merge with a rival unit owned by America's Morton International to form a new company, with sales of around $3 billion, in control of 40% of the airbag market across America, Japan and Europe. No price was given. Morton will be left with its specialty-chemicals and salt business.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Koninklijke <font size=-1>PTT</font> Nederland, a Dutch post and telecoms group, launched a $1.6 billion bid for Australian-based <b>TNT</b>, a worldwide courier service that recommended the offer to its shareholders. Combined, the new outfit would have annual revenues of over A$6 billion ($4.7 billion) and operate in 200 countries. </p>
<p>(See <a href="bw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Wayne Huizenga's ambitious plans to merge his fast-growing Republic Industries with <b>ADT</b>, America's biggest electronic-security business, with car-auction operations on the side, finally came unstuck. Investors took a dim view of the $4.4 billion all-share deal when it was announced on July 1st; Republic's shares took a battering then and began recovering only when investors felt the deal could founder.</p>
<p>A planned international offering of depositary receipts in <b>Gazprom</b>, Russia's biggest firm and the world's biggest gas producer, was overshadowed at home by a row over unpaid taxes. Faced with a government claim for an estimated $2.8 billion, Gazprom said that it was being unfairly targeted. The government announced it had drawn up a list of Russia's biggest tax debtors and was pursuing them all. </p>
<p><b>House of Fraser</b>, a British department-store chain, announced a deeper pre-tax loss of &#163;13.6m ($20.8m) in the first half, including a &#163;4.9m charge on the disposal of one of its stores, compared with a &#163;4.3m loss for the same period last year. The group said it will close up to ten of its 50 stores, centralise its distribution system and revive its women's wear sales, a restructuring that could cost as much as &#163;50m.</p>
<h2>Exchange changes</h2>
<p>After nine months of consultation with its members, the <b>London Stock Exchange </b> published a manifesto for change. The document maps out a move towards automated order-driven trading, which will replace a more costly quote-driven system, reliant on privileged market makers.</p>
<p>All change in <b>British insurance</b>. Norwich Union said it would convert from a mutually owned company to a publicly quoted one. And the Prudential Corporation, another life insurer, launched a branchless bank.</p>
<p>(See <a href="bw3.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>Global bond issues</b> have soared so far this year to a record $509 billion, already outstripping a full-year total of $465 billion for 1995, with the top ten bookrunners taking half the business. Two Japanese houses, Nomura and Daiwa, slid out of the top ten.</p>
<p>As much as a third of British bookmakers' &#163;100m ($156m) annual profits may have been wiped out, and one issued a profits warning, after one jockey, Frankie Dettori, swept the board to ride <b>all seven winners </b>at a race meeting at Ascot.</p>

</td></tr></table></center>
