<html><head><title>Too cosy </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Airline alliances</b></p>
<h1>Too cosy </h1>

FEW industrial battles are fought for higher stakes than competition for airline slots. Ian Lang, the secretary of state for trade and industry, is coming under increasing pressure from his cabinet colleagues to nod through the proposed alliance between British Airways (<font size=-1>BA</font>) and American Airlines, two of the world's biggest airlines, without insisting on strict conditions that would reduce their dominance of transatlantic routes.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;According to authoritative sources in Whitehall, Mr Lang was advised this week by John Bridgeman, the director-general of the Office of Fair Trading (<font size=-1>OFT</font>), that the alliance should be approved without a reference to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission. The <font size=-1>OFT</font> originally took a hawkish stance, insisting that the two airlines should hand over to competitors up to a quarter of the landing and take-off slots they control at Heathrow. <font size=-1>BA</font> alone has 38% of the slots out of London. The combined share with American Airlines and other airlines with which both firms are allied would be nearly 50%. Only a significant divestment of slots, the <font size=-1>OFT</font> first concluded, could reduce the competitive advantage that <font size=-1>BA</font> and American Airlines would gain from their alliance.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;However, it appears that the <font size=-1>OFT</font> has considerably diluted these conditions after hearing the two airlines' arguments. The <font size=-1>OFT</font> is now maintaining that <font size=-1>BA</font>'s deal with American is not seriously anti-competitive when it is viewed in the wider European context, where the two airlines control less than a quarter of transatlantic traffic.<b></b><br>
 Mr Lang ought to view the <font size=-1>OFT</font>'s revised recommendations with scepticism. <font size=-1>BA</font> and American Airlines plan to co-ordinate their schedules, combine frequent-flier programmes and share revenues from transatlantic flights. They already control nearly 70% of the flights on the busy London-New York route. No wonder rival airlines such as United and Virgin cry foul. Robert Ayling, <font size=-1>BA</font>'s chief executive, replies that several European and American airlines already have similar code-sharing deals. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Lang's dilemma is complicated by the fact that British-American negotiations on an "open skies" agreement to relax restrictions on foreign airlines operating in the two countries will remain stalled unless the deal goes through. <font size=-1>BA</font> will drop its opposition to greater access for airlines from the United States only if the alliance is approved. American Airlines, for its part, has threatened to walk away from the deal unless it is quickly approved.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Lang should ignore both threat and promise and concentrate on the core of the problem: the need to free up capacity. The excess demand for landing rights at Heathrow is so great that it reinforces the dominance of the airlines that control the peak-hour slots. Unless more landing rights are made available to new entrants, the freer competition of any "open skies" agreement will remain illusory. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Landing charges at Heathrow, one of the most congested airports in the world, are already among the cheapest anywhere. Incredibly, they are about to fall still further while charges at the nearly empty Stansted on the other side of London are about to rise. The chief beneficiaries of this dotty pricing policy are foreign airlines. Low charges are not passed on to passengers as reduced fares because Heathrow's capacity constraints restrict competition.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Landing charges are not, however, the crux of the problem. Industry insiders reckon Heathrow is so popular that the charges could probably be trebled without affecting demand. The ideal solution would be to auction slots to the highest bidder. This would raise the cost of using Heathrow, making Stansted--where demand for slots would initially be far less-- much more attractive. But the rights of airlines to routes acquired over the years cannot just be brushed aside.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A more practical approach was outlined in a report published by the House of Commons' Transport Committee earlier this year. It proposed that landing charges at Heathrow should be increased and the additional revenues allocated to an environmental fund. A better balance between the interests of airlines, of people who live near busy airports and of taxpayers could be achieved if increased landing charges, reflecting Heathrow's environmental costs, were combined with the regular auction of any newly available slots created through expansion of the airport or through the withdrawal from Heathrow of any airline. These are the issues which Mr Lang and the government should be tackling, rather than paving the way for a further concentration of commercial power in the hands of <font size=-1>BA</font> and American Airlines.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?844473600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
