<html><head><title>Electric Jersey </title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Air pollution</b></p>
<h1>Electric Jersey </h1>

THINK of cars and the island of Jersey in the English Channel, and it conjures up an image of the <font size=-1>TV</font> detective Bergerac sleuthing around the bailiwick in his 1940s Triumph <font size=-1>TR1</font> roadster. Now Jersey is turning its back on such romantic but smoky old clunkers. If Jim Bergerac were to come back in a new series, he might be at the wheel of an electric car. From next April visitors to the island will be able to hire electric cars from their hotel for the same price as a petrol-driven Ford Escort. Jersey's experiment, the brainchild of Nigel Philpott, the island's director of tourism, will be the most extensive test of private electric vehicles in the British Isles (not counting golf carts and milk floats). If the trial works, Mr Philpott would like to persuade all hire cars to go electric. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Islanders are worried that more petrol cars crawling over their leafy lanes will destroy Jersey's charm with a combination of noise and air pollution. The island has 724 inhabitants per square kilometre, three times more than Britain and twice continental Europe's most densely-populated country, the Netherlands. Jersey also has a lot of cars: 77,000 (including lorries and buses), or 663 vehicles per square kilometre, almost as many vehicles as people. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Many of these are hired cars used by tourists. So Mr Philpott has roped in the local electricity company, some hotels and a local car-hire company to set up a system whereby selected hotels will have reserved parking spots for electric cars which visitors can book in advance. Since the island is small, a range of around 70 miles is no problem. Jersey Electric, the local utility, has staged trials with electric Peugeots and Citro<e-dierisis>ns. But it looks as if Toyota will win the contract to supply vehicles for Mr Philpott's much bigger experiment.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?844473600,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
