<html><head><title>Deep pockets, short sight</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width="128" height="26" alt="Business" border=0>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></td></tr></table>


<table border=6><tr><td><h1>Deep pockets, short sight</h1>

<font size=1>BERLIN </font><p>
BEHIND a pillar in Berlin's leading electronics store is an expensive black box, for decoding the signal from digital satellite television. The salesman does not recommend it: bad value for money, he says. That is glum news for Leo Kirch, a media magnate. His Kirch group launched a digital pay-<font size=-1>TV</font> venture, <font size=-1>DF1</font>, in late July. It will succeed only if people can be persuaded to stump up DM880 ($576) for the box, plus a further DM20 a month subscription charge.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The signs so far are discouraging. <font size=-1>DF1</font> needs 1m subscribers to break even, and hopes to sign up 200,000 customers by Christmas. Since its launch, barely 10,000 have signed. The programmes (15 channels, plus, for an extra charge, pay-per view films) are not wildly different in either quality or quantity from those already available to German viewers who, on a typical weekend, can choose from 145 feature films and several hours of live football, all for free. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But trying to beat Mr Kirch on content is unwise. He has deals with all the main American studios apart from Rupert Murdoch's Fox, where one is expected soon, and controls the two best sets of sports rights--to the main German soccer league and the World Cup. He also has the financial backing of <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>, Mr Murdoch's successful British pay-<font size=-1>TV</font> business, which has a 49% stake in <font size=-1>DF</font>1.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Kirch's main problem will be to get his content to the viewers. His decoders are expensive and have been poorly marketed--probably because they were brought to market hurriedly. Besides, <font size=-1>DF</font>1 is currently available only on satellite. To sell <font size=-1>DF</font>1 to Germany's 16m cabled households requires the co-operation of Deutsche Telekom, the world's biggest cable operator. Until recently, Deutsche Telekom was competing against Mr Kirch in alliance with Bertelsmann, Germany's largest publishing house. Now it plans its own move into pay-<font size=-1>TV</font>.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As for Bertelsmann, it has pulled out of German digital pay-<font size=-1>TV</font>, complaining-- belatedly--that it is expensive and unprofitable. That may be sour grapes, although similar noises are coming from other parts of the Kirch empire. Pro7, a brash television channel run by Mr Kirch's son, recently said that it was pulling out of a planned pay-<font size=-1>TV</font> venture. "The biggest miscalculation we have seen," said one manager. It will concentrate on business programming instead. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the Berlin electronics shop the salesman sings the praises of the existing pay-<font size=-1>TV</font> channel, Premiere. This uses analogue technology. But after several years it is still not in operating profit. <font size=-1>DF</font>1 may have a similarly sluggish take-off. The clearest prospects for pay-<font size=-1>TV</font> are in servicing distinct markets: football, pornography, minority languages, films and--possibly--financial information. People will not pay much for something while they can watch it elsewhere for nothing.<br>
<br>
</td></tr></table>


