<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: Chris Rijk, 26-Sep-1996 -->
<p align=center><img src="/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width="273" height="24" alt="Business this Week" border=0></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>Steady as you go</h2>

The Federal Reserve held <b>American interest rates</b> steady.<b> </b>With mixed signals from the economy--unemployment at a seven-year low and fattening wages, but signs of slowing growth in the second half of the year--the deciding factor may have been timing. The closing weeks of a presidential campaign are an awkward time for the Fed to act. Consumer confidence ticked up slightly in September, to a six-year high.<br><br>
(See <a href="bw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>The International Monetary Fund said <b>growth in Japan</b> would reach 3.5% this year after a long recession, the fastest among the Group of Seven rich countries and well above the Fund's forecast in May. Growth elsewhere in Asia is expected to slow to 8% this year and 7.5% next.<br>
<h2>Sinking fund</h2>
The European Commission approved FFr3.9 billion ($762m) of emergency aid for <b>Cr<e-acute>dit Lyonnais</b>, adding another chunk of French taxpayers' cash to a rescue plan for the state-owned bank that is already costing up to FFr45 billion. The commission gave warning that another bail-out will amount to a "considerable figure" and insisted that any plan would need to include "real and substantive" divestments. The bank delayed issuing its interim results for a week after the commission's ruling.<br><br>
<b>Bulgaria's central bank </b> nearly trebled its key interest rate to 300% and placed nine state and private banks under supervision in an attempt to shore up a crippled financial system and prevent another default on foreign debt. Lyubomir Filipov, governor of the central bank, said he would resign if the latest measures to stabilise the lev failed to work.<br><br>
A war of words intensified between the central banks of Britain and Germany. A Bundesbank official said <font size=-1>EU</font> members that did not join the <b>single currency</b> should not have unrestricted access to <font size=-1>TARGET</font>, the proposed new payments system. A week earlier, the governor of the Bank of England had said there should be no discrimination.<br><br>
Britain's <font size=-1>BT</font> has taken a 25% stake in <font size=-1>CEGETEL</font>, a <b>new telecoms group</b> set up by France's Compagnie G<e-acute>n<e-acute>rale des Eaux. The aim is to compete with France T<e-acute>l<e-acute>com.<br><br>
The Austrian government rejected a bid for <b>Creditanstalt </b> from a consortium of Austrian, Italian and German banks in yet another setback in its long-drawn-out saga to privatise the bank. First Austrian, a savings bank, then announced that it will form a group to make a bid.<br><br>
Japan's coalition government promised a half-hearted reform of its powerful <b>finance ministry</b>, with inspection and supervision to be hived off to an independent agency.<br>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
Taking the lead of Daimler Benz, German firms scrambled to <b>cut sick pay </b>for workers to 80% of normal salaries after a bill was passed that allows the change from October 1st. Unions protested that the change should apply to future contracts, not present ones.<br>
<h2>Bad line</h2>
<b>AT&T's share price</b> was battered after the American telecoms giant gave a warning that profits in the third quarter could fall short of market expectations by up to 10%, with a further slide to come in 1997 as its core long distance telephone business feels the effects of tougher competition.<br><br>
Coca-Cola is catapulting its <b>Minute Maid </b>orange juice out of its traditional North American base and into Europe and Latin America with the formation of a 50-50 joint venture with Groupe Danone. The French foods group will produce and distribute the chilled juice outside North America. The aim is to be selling the stuff in 50 countries by 2000.<br><br>
(See <a href="bw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>As multinationals multiply, <b>foreign direct investment</b> grows, with mergers and acquisitions accounting for the bulk of activity. Total outflows worldwide rose to $318 billion in 1995, some 40% up on 1994. Inflows to developed countries rose by 53% but to developing countries only by 15%. Five countries, America, Japan, Britain, Germany and France, accounted for two-thirds of outflows; ten countries received two-thirds of total inflows, with America top of both lists.<br><br>
Two regional American oil refiners are to merge as a defence against hostile takeovers. <b>Diamond Shamrock </b> and <b>Ultramar </b>together will form the fourth-largest independent refiner, with a large network of retail outlets and revenue of $8 billion.<br><br>
<b>Lachlan Murdoch</b>, 24-year old son of Rupert, continued his meteoric rise to take on the job of managing director of News Ltd, News Corp's Australian unit. He replaces Ken Cowley, who remains as executive chairman.<br><br>
<b>Hilton Hotels</b> agreed to buy out most of the remaining interests in four more big hotels held by Prudential Insurance Co of America, at a cost of $267m. Prudential has apparently been critical of Hilton's management; Hilton itself has been switching back from franchising its name to buying, as profits in the hotel business perk up.<br><br>
The Dow reflected the market's approval of a deal that would create the world's second-largest <b>satellite network</b> when<b> </b>Hughes Electronics, a General Motors unit, agreed to buy PanAmSat, valuing the four-satellite operator at $3 billion. Share prices rose.<br>

</td></tr></table></center>
