<html><head><title>Thinking the unthinkable</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: Chris Rijk, 26-Sep-1996 -->
<!-- Changed by: Chris Rijk, 26-Sep-1996 -->
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>

</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<h1>Thinking the unthinkable</h1>

<p><b>The huge opinion-poll lead of the Labour Party looks unassailable. But might the message of the polls be misleading?</b></p>
IF YOU read only the opinion-poll headlines, Tony Blair can begin measuring up the curtains for 10 Downing Street. As delegates gather for the opening of Labour's conference in Blackpool on September 30th, the party remains miles ahead; its lead extends to a credibility-defying 33 points, according to the latest Gallup poll in the<i> Daily Telegraph</i>. Although Labour's average poll lead has narrowed somewhat--by a couple of points after John Major was re-elected Tory leader last summer and by the same again earlier this summer--the Tories' recovery is glacial. In 1981, as long before the coming election, the Tories were 11 points ahead; in 1986, two points behind; in 1991, two points ahead-- and now 23 points behind, according to the (more credible) <font size=-1>MORI</font> poll for the <i>Times</i> carried out on September 20th-23rd (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This latest poll will particularly disappoint the Tories. They reckoned to have got the better of the political exchanges in August and September, when Labour had several internal rows. Yet, on this latest poll, the Labour lead has recently grown a bit, by two percentage points. As this week's spat between Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and the Tory Eurosceptics over the European single currency sinks in, the Tories could fall even further behind.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nor, contrary to some Tory claims, is there much sign that people who talk of voting Labour are about to change their minds. According to another <font size=-1>MORI</font> poll in May, 67% of them are "very" or "fairly" strong in their backing. This compares with only 57% of Tories who are "very" or "fairly" strong. "The Tories are in deep, deep trouble," says Bob Worcester of <font size=-1>MORI</font>.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, Labour's lead is based on some firm-looking foundations. Mr Major is as unpopular as ever. According to <font size=-1>MORI</font>, voters dissatisfied with him as prime minister outnumber those satisfied by 34 percentage points, the same as last September. And Labour has leads in all <font size=-1>MORI</font>'s three summary measures of party standing. By a three-to-two majority it is reckoned to have the best team of leaders; by more than two to one to be the most united; and by nearly two to one to have the best policies. Labour leads on eight of the ten issues reckoned by voters the most important facing Britain. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Recent developments in the electoral system also make it very difficult for the Conservatives to win. The system--first past-the-post in single-member constituencies--is kind to parties which concentrate their votes in seats they might take, but hard on those whose vote is evenly spread across the country. Usually, this hurts the Liberal Democrats. But demographic changes and an increase in tactical voting in European and local elections since 1992 mean that it is the Tory vote which now looks the most evenly spread. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At the next election, Labour may need only 1% more of the vote than the Tories to win an overall Commons majority. The Tories may need to poll at least 7% more than Labour to do the same. If the Tories do as well in 1997 as they did in 1992 in terms of the total vote, they are still likely to fall short of an overall Commons majority. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So is a Labour victory a foregone conclusion? Not necessarily. Although most poll analysts do believe that Labour will win, many are more uncertain of this than the polling evidence seems to warrant. Among their reservations:<br>
<font size=-1></font> <br><b>Doubts as to the accuracy of the polls</b>. Before the 1992 election, the polls gave Labour the edge. In the event, the Tories were ahead by 8% of the vote. Some think that the polls are still underestimating Tory strength. Tory supporters are more reluctant to tell interviewers how they vote because, today, many people think it barely respectable to admit to being a Tory. There is a problem of poll methods, too. It seems that the method of sampling used by most pollsters, designed to represent a cross-section of the whole population in a single group of voters polled, is flawed, and includes too few Tory voters in the sample. This is confirmed by a new study by John Curtice, a psephologist with the Centre for Research into Elections and Social Trends, using data from the academic British Election Panel Study. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All the main pollsters now make adjustments to their polls which attempt to allow for the reticence of Tory voters. On these calculations, Labour's vote comes out 4.6% lower on average and the Tories 3.6% higher, according to Professor David Sanders of Essex University. But, if Mr Curtice is right, the polls still overstate Labour's true lead even after this adjustment.<br>
<font size=-1></font> <br><b>The "feel-good" factor</b>. Economic optimism has picked up. According to the September <font size=-1>MORI</font> figures, those expecting the economy to improve in the next 12 months are now only slightly fewer in number than those expecting it to get worse--by a mere one percentage point. Although this is worse than it was in August, when optimists actually outnumbered pessimists by two points, it is still much better than a year ago, when the figure was minus 19 points. A rise in house prices and consumer spending tell the same story. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whether this will spill over into votes for the Tories is a much-posed question. Statistical models linking voting intention to economic optimism broke down when sterling was ignominiously ejected from the European Union's exchange-rate mechanism in September 1992. Since then, voters have been reluctant to give the government credit for an improving economy. But in time better economic performance must surely help the Tories, even though the polls are not yet indicating this.<br>
<font size=-1></font> <br><b>A decline in Tony Blair's ratings.</b> After last year's Labour conference, voters satisfied with his leadership exceeded those dissatisfied by 27 percentage points. In August, that was down to nine points.<br>
<font size=-1></font> <br><b>A "softness" in the Labour vote.</b> Many voters say they will back Labour next time without really identifying themselves with the party. Around 37% of electors now say that they "generally" think of themselves as Labour compared with 51% of electors who say they would vote Labour in a general election. Both parties report that the "focus" groups of voters which they use to test their image report that the commitment of many voters who say they will vote Labour remains uncertain. There is academic evidence to support this. Paul Whiteley of Sheffield University and Howard Clarke of the University of Texas have applied a statistical technique called "error correction" to measure softness. They confirm that the Labour vote is flaky.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But this does not mean that they think Labour will lose. They produce a variety of scenarios for the election. The best gives Labour a landslide-winning 46.5% of the vote. And no amount of "feel-good" alone wins the election for the Tories. But one scenario does: lots of "feel-good" and lots of Labour bickering. "It looks as if Labour is going to win, but they could blow it," says Mr Whiteley. The succinct advice to Labour is: "Shut up now!"<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?843868800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="index.html">Contents</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
<a href="br7501.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&copy; Copyright</a>
1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>

