<html><head><title>Crime</title></head><body bgcolor="#ffffff">
<!-- Changed by: Chris Rijk, 26-Sep-1996 -->
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width="111" height="24" alt="Britain" border=0>
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="/econlogosmall.gif" width="78" height="39" alt="The Economist" border=0>
</td></tr></table>

<p><b>Crime</b></p>
<h1>Suspect figures</h1>

PUT not your trust in statistics is this week's lesson for Michael Howard. For the past two years, the home secretary has been boasting of the falling recorded crime figures and claiming that they prove his dictum that "prison works". Now the number of crimes recorded by the police, published on September 24th, is rising again. Violent crime, Mr Howard's principal target, is rising particularly fast. Presumably this proves that prison does not work.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact the numbers prove nothing except that it is risky to place much reliance on such famously unreliable statistics. The latest batch show that, so far as those recorded by the police go, violent crimes rose by 10% in the year to June; homicides were almost unchanged (at 730, compared with 729); property offences fell by 0.3%; motor vehicle break-ins and thefts fell by 1%.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A more important set of numbers was also published on the same day--the British Crime Survey (<font size=-1>BCS</font>), which is carried out every two years by asking people whether they have been victims of crime. The <font size=-1>BCS</font> shows a 2% rise in crime in 1993-95, the period when Mr Howard was saying the largest fall in crime for 40 years had taken place. Police and academic crime-watchers consider the <font size=-1>BCS</font> to be more accurate than the recorded crime figures.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Robert Reiner, a criminologist at the London School of Economics, argues that "there never was a decline in crime. What has happened is a decrease in the proportion of crime that is getting recorded. The dark figure of unrecorded crime is growing." Mr Reiner thinks this is happening at the moment for three reasons.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;First, one of the main reasons that people report property crime is because their insurance companies require it. During the 1990s, there has been a marginal fall in insurance coverage in the rougher areas of cities, which may lead to less reporting. Second, the police, being overworked, are less inclined to visit people to take details of crimes; and if the victim cannot be bothered to go to the police station, then the crime does not get reported. Third, new management systems have been introduced into the police, requiring them to meet targets related to crime statistics. The police therefore have a greater incentive not to record crimes.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What, then, do the more reliable <font size=-1>BCS</font> figures suggest? There seems to have been a slight decrease in property crime, and an increase in violent crime; but, in all, a smaller increase than at any time since the survey started in 1981. That may well be because of demographics: the proportion of male teenagers, who make up the bulk of criminals, is shrinking.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Otherwise, economics seems to provide the best explanation. <i>Pace</i> the government (which has always insisted, for obvious reasons, that there is no connection between people being out of work and committing crimes), plenty of research points to a positive correlation between unemployment and property crime. That would suggest a fall in property crime at a time when unemployment is falling. The other clear correlation is between rising living standards and violent crime. Most violent crime is alcohol-related; and the richer people are the more they drink, and the more they drink the more they beat each other up.<br>

<p align=center>
<a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; 
<a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?843868800,iss">Search</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp;
