<h1>Fair trade</h1>

BETWEEN now and the general election, Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor of the exchequer, can expect frequent repeats of this week's run-ins with, on the one hand, Tory Eurosceptics and, on the other, Eddie George, the governor of the Bank of England. But the crumb of comfort for Mr Clarke in this week's economic data is that at least he will not face a balance-of-payments crisis. In the second quarter of this year, Britain ran a surplus of &#163;500m on its current account (its overall financial balance with the rest of the world), the biggest, and only the second, quarterly surplus since 1987 (see <a href="br4.gif">chart</a>). A positive balance for the whole of 1996 is now possible, or at worst a deficit of say &#163;1 billion-&#163;2 billion--nothing compared with the record deficit of &#163;22 billion in 1989.<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Economists in the City of London had forecast a deficit of over &#163;1 billion in the second quarter after news that there had been a &#163;3.6 billion deficit in traded goods during that period. But income from overseas investments was a surprisingly strong &#163;3.7 billion. And there was an equally buoyant trade surplus in services of &#163;1.9 billion, including a boost to tourism revenues of perhaps &#163;200m from overseas visitors to June's Euro 96 soccer tournament. <br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although unexpected, this current account rebound is no flash in the pan, reckons Jonathan Loynes, an economist at <font size=-1>HSBC</font>, an investment bank. Although the traded-goods deficit may get bigger as stronger investment and consumer spending sucks in imports, there is no reason why Britain's service exports or its foreign investments should falter, he says. For which good news Mr Clarke should be deeply grateful.<br>

