<html><head><title>Olivetti self-destructs</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>




<h1><center>Olivetti self-destructs</center></h1>
<p><b>The mayhem and the moral</b></p>


IT IS hard to believe, somehow, that Italy is the country that invented double-entry book-keeping, the basis of company accounts. For there is simply no good accounting word to capture the current state of affairs at Olivetti. On the face of it, Italy's biggest information-technology company--a firm as well-known in Europe as Apple is in America--seems simply to be imploding. At the start of this month it turfed out Carlo De Benedetti, its chairman for 18 years and the man who was once seen as the great white hope of Italian business. This week Francesco Caio, Olivetti's chief executive, resigned too. On September 17th alone the firm's share price fell by 10%, though it made a speculative rebound later in the week as Mr De Benedetti regained some influence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On one view, the turmoil at Olivetti represents a triumph for American-style shareholder activism in Europe. This, after all, is a company that has lost money every year since 1990. Unlike many Italian companies, however, it had increasingly turned to foreign investors in order to raise capital. This enabled its shareholders to insist on its Augean stables being cleansed. It was a meeting in London of foreign fund managers controlling a quarter of the company's equity that triggered the resignation of Mr De Benedetti. No such move would have been likely had Olivetti remained more typically Italian--that is, shielded from hostile scrutiny by a tangle of cross-shareholdings, family stakes and loans from friendly banks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Still, some will say that if this is a triumph of shareholder activism, who needs it? Certainly not the defenestrated managers. And arguably not the shareholders themselves. At first glance, the immediate result of their ousting of Mr De Benedetti has been self-impoverishment. Investors in the foreign funds that paid 1,000 lire (64 cents) a share for Olivetti's stock in a rights issue last December are unlikely to proclaim victory until the shares, which closed on September 18th at 511.5 lire, are showing a healthy profit.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Whatever happens next at Olivetti, the moral that is drawn from the affair matters well beyond the Italian border. A growing number of continental European companies from Italy and elsewhere are queuing up to raise capital in both the London and New York stockmarkets. Some, such as Germany's Daimler Benz cars-to-aerospace giant, have already taken the plunge. But those who have yet to jump may well be deterred by the mayhem in Milan, lest they suffer the same fate as Olivetti.
</p><p><b>The two missing ingredients</b></b>
<br>It would be a pity if they were deterred. Many European firms do indeed have much to gain by making greater use of international equity markets. These can provide cheaper sources of capital than bank lending, together with the extra scrutiny that keeps managers on their toes. But for stockmarkets to work their magic, two conditions are essential. First, investors must be confident that firms are providing them with accurate and timely information. Second, a stockmarket needs to be properly regulated. Neither condition seems to have been met in this particular case.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On September 16th Italian magistrates announced that they were questioning Mr Caio about whether Olivetti had issued misleading financial statements about its affairs. Mr De Benedetti has also been questioned. This does not prove that there is anything the least bit wrong with the company's accounts, and Olivetti has vehemently defended them. But it is this uncertainty--not the departure of Mr De Benedetti--that sparked the wild selling of Olivetti's shares this week. In these circumstances, Consob, Italy's stockmarket regulator, should have formally suspended trading in the company's shares until it became clear that the accounts were correct and consistent. It should not have allowed trading in the firm's shares to continue as panic spread. That is no way to run a stock exchange.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
