<html><head><title>The world in his armpit</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>The world in his armpit</h1>


<p>AMERICA adores telegenic leaders, so it is tempting to dismiss a bald guy with glasses. America reveres the treadmill and the weights room, so it is tempting to dismiss someone who looks physically frail. America has made a fetish of the sound-bite, so it is tempting to dismiss a speaker who, in praising a colleague at the recent Christian Coalition conference, could think of nothing better to say than, "What a great future he has, because he is right here and he is right here."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Tempting, but disastrous: Jesse Helms, chairman of the Senate's foreign relations committee, is not a man to be dismissed. For he brings one quality to international affairs that has proved invaluable. "Jesse hates foreigners," says someone who has spent years working with him; then, feeling the need to be fair, he adds, "except for Israelis, maybe." To this one could add that Mr Helms mistrusts most treaties, and the whole apparatus of international relations. He has likened development aid to throwing money "down foreign ratholes". In the latest issue of <i>Foreign Affairs</i>, he says that the United Nations threatens American interests, and that it should be cut by half or dismantled.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Just recently, Mr Helms scored an arresting victory. A 25-year-old Helms staffer who reads <i>Jane's Defence Weekly </i>at bedtime fought a campaign to block America's ratification of the chemical-weapons ban. This was an ambitious venture, for no senator has ever mustered the 34 votes needed to vote down ratification of an arms-control deal before. First Trent Lott, the Republican leader in the Senate, lined up behind the Helms argument. Then Bob Dole put his weight behind it, and the pro-ratification forces had to withdraw the treaty from the Senate lest it be voted down.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It does not take brilliance to win support for an idea that clearly protects American interests. Mr Helms triumphs even without such an advantage: blocking the chemical-weapons treaty may on balance hurt America's interests, rather than the other way round. The treaty probably has enough support in other countries to go ahead anyway; and, if America stays out of it, its chemical companies will remain barred from lucrative export markets. Besides, the treaty will subject some would-be chemical-weapons-makers to inspections, however imperfect. For this reason it deserves America's support.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Helms has won several other anti-victories recently. In the first years of the Clinton administration, there were signs that America's embargo on Cuba might at last be lifted. This was encouraging: exposed to foreign trade and influence, Cuba's nasty dictatorship might well be undermined. Mr Helms, meanwhile, drafted a law entrenching the embargo, and threatening sanctions on third countries that break it. By a fluke, he got Mr Clinton to accept it: in February the Cubans shot down two American civilian aircraft, and the easiest way for the president to respond toughly was to sign the bill. Six months on, Cuba's regime shows no signs of falling. But the third-country clause has scummed up America's relations with its allies, which fail to see why their Cuba policy should be run by Mr Helms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Colombia is another place that Mr Helms has put his stamp on. Last year he backed a law to "decertify" Colombia as punishment for its puny zeal in fighting the drugs war, a move that would deprive it of aid. Up to a point, this was understandable: Colombia's President Samper had been accused of taking drug money for his election campaign. But these accusations were not proven; and, true or not, once in office Mr Samper fought the drug barons mightily. In 1995 his government lost nearly 600 police and security-force men in its drugs war. It also smashed the Cali cocaine mob. America cannot claim to have done as much within its own borders. Never mind: in March Colombia was decertified. Left unaided, the country has since descended even further into mayhem.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What to make of Mr Helms's influence? It reflects poorly on Mr Dole, who as Senate leader could have blocked Mr Helms's ascent to the chair of the foreign relations committee at the start of 1995. Mr Helms's intemperate views were no secret then; indeed, the senator had recently furnished fresh proof of them, by suggesting that the president's life might be endangered if he and his liberal views ventured into North Carolina, Mr Helms's state. Mr Dole might have encouraged Richard Lugar to seek the chairmanship, especially since Mr Lugar had spent as many years on the foreign relations committee as Mr Helms had, and even chaired it in 1985-86. But Mr Dole bowed to the underwhelming fact that Mr Helms had been in the Senate two years longer, explaining: "If you're going to start knocking down seniority, then it's a whole, you know..." . Such is the leadership and courage of the man nominated by Republicans for the highest office in the land.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Mr Helms's successes also say something about America, and about foreign policy in many democracies these days. He has been elected, after all, to four terms in the Senate, and polls suggest that this November he will secure another six years. His criticism of the United Nations, though shot through with half-truths, is no more rabid than the <font size=-1>UN</font>-bashing to be heard last month at the Republican convention. His attack on foreign treaties and entanglements appeals to American voters--just as it would do, for that matter, to German or British voters fearful of European Union. When Mr Helms denounces the transfer of power to international bodies remote from sovereign individuals, he voices a concern heard all over the rich world. He becomes an internationalist, despite himself.
</td></tr></table>
