<html><head><title>Master and slave in Mauritania</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" width=224 height=26  alt="International">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Master and slave in Mauritania</h1>

<font size=1>NOUAKCHOTT</font>
<p>SHE said she was a slave. Mohamed Ould Moissa said Aichana Mint Abeid Boilil was his wife.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Aichana took Mohamed to court to recover her five children. He claimed to be their father and wanted custody. She said she had never had sex with him, let alone been married to him; she called his claim a pretext to keep her children as slaves. The court sided with her, and the family was reunited, except for one daughter, "given" by Mohamed to one of his relations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Slavery was outlawed in Mauritania (see <a href="ir1.gif">map</a>) in 1980, but that did not eradicate the centuries-old practice. In the past, Moorish camel caravans used to sweep down on villages in the south, carrying off everyone the men could lay hands on. The enslaved had to tend their masters' herds, perform domestic chores and work the family's land. Disobedience or any attempt to escape was brutally punished. The women were the sex slaves of their owner, and their offspring generally grew up to be his slaves.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Freed slaves or the descendants of slaves are known as <i>haratin</i>; they make up about 40% of Mauritania's 2m people. Some argue that many are still in bondage. "Nothing has been done to alter the situation that forced the government to ban slavery 16 years ago," says Boubacar Ould Messoud, president of <font size=-1>SOS</font> Esclave, an organisation set up to help slaves. "There are still slaves sweating to feed their masters." Certainly there are many thousands of people who work without being paid in cash.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Slavery is reinforced by race. Traditionally the lighter-skinned Bidan from the north enslaved the "black African" farmers from the south. But skin colour is no exact guide to status. Some Bidan are dark-skinned, and some black groups, especially the Sonink&eacute; and Hal-Pulaar (Fulani), also practise slavery, though less conspicuously.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Eight years after slavery was supposedly abolished, Fatma Mint Souleymane ran away from her master's constant beatings. Only when she reached Nouakchott did she learn that she did not belong to somebody else. "I was always working. I had no way of hearing the radio or time to chat with other slaves. How could I hear about the new law?" she asks. Others have heard about abolition, but know no other life than slavery. They accept their condition as "God's will" or simply do not believe they could be free.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Pointing out that most political and economic power is in the hands of the "masters", the Bidan, Boubacar Ould Messoud accuses the government of not really trying to eliminate slavery, but merely making noises, to appease western aid donors. He calls for a nationwide awareness campaign to inform everyone that they are free and to change attitudes among both "slaves" and "masters". It must be couched in religious terms, he says, breaking the centuries-old indoctrination of slaves, who were told they would go to heaven if they were obedient, and to hell if not.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government prefers to look the other way. "Slavery has been banned, so I can say that, legally, it no longer exists," avows Mohamed Lamine Ould Ahmed, minister for energy and one of few <i>haratin</i> to have got that high. "There are people who've stayed with their former masters. Having been freed, they've chosen to stay in the environment where they grew up, with people of the same tribe--their friends and relations."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This may be partly true. What ex-slaves have gained in freedom, they may have lost in security. Traditionally, they were considered part of the family. Although abuses occurred, owners were responsible for their welfare and provided food, clothes, protection and medical care. Can freedom deliver these? Former slaves are more likely to end up, homeless and jobless, in the slums among the sand dunes around Nouakchott.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the Bidan too are suffering these days. The severe droughts of the 1970s and 1980s ravaged their herds, and many fled with their slaves to Nouakchott. Once in town the slaves, released because their masters could not afford to keep them, and used to manual labour, often did better than their ex-masters, who knew little more than how to ride camels. Often one hears of an impoverished "master" claiming the legacy of his deceased slave--a wooden shack or tent, and maybe a few scrawny animals. Some still accept the argument that if a man owned the slave, he owned the slave's property too.



</td></tr></table>
