<html><head><title>Pay as you earn</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Universities</b></p>
<h1>Pay as you earn</h1>

<p>THE era in which the taxpayer footed most of the bill for sending a large proportion of Britain's 18-year-olds away to university, which began in the mid-1960s following the Robbins Report, may be drawing to a close. On September 19th the vice-chancellors of Britain's 115 universities proposed a scheme in which graduates would have to repay about a third of the cost of degree courses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Opponents of such a scheme say that it would deter students from poorer families--undermining the Robbins principle that university education should be open to anyone who would benefit from it. And none of the main political parties is keen to alarm middle-income voters with the prospect of hefty tuition bills for their children. Nevertheless, the imposition of university fees over the next few years now seems likelier than ever.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The universities have become exasperated with the government's relentless cuts in the funding it provides for each student. They have reached the conclusion that there is no chance of getting more money from whichever party forms the next government, so the students will have to pay. The universities will submit their proposals to Sir Ron Dearing's inquiry into the future of higher education, which will report after the next election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour and the Liberal Democrats accept the need to make students borrow to cover their living expenses, but say they should not pay tuition fees. Gillian Shephard, the education and employment secretary, appeared to adopt a similar line on September 18th, saying she expected the government to continue paying all tuition costs. However, whatever the parties' education spokesmen say now, if the Dearing inquiry calls for students to contribute to tuition costs the proposal is likely to get strong backing from the Treasury. The choice will then probably be between fees and no further expansion--or even a contraction--in university education.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The scheme the vice-chancellors propose is based on one that has been in operation in Australia since 1989. In the British version, for each year of study, students would borrow &#163;2,400 (at today's prices) to pay a fixed fee, plus &#163;4,475 for their living expenses. Once they have graduated, they would pay a surcharge of 3% of gross salary on their national insurance contributions until the debt is cleared. Now, full-time students aged under 21 make no contribution to tuition costs, and typically get a grant of &#163;1,586 a year and a loan of about &#163;1,600.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The prospect of accumulating up to &#163;20,000 in debt (plus interest at around the prevailing bank base rate) during a three-year course may indeed sound daunting to many potential students. But it would be fairer to taxpayers--and not as daunting for students as many critics assume. Once they graduate, students would pay only in proportion to what they earn, and over a term as long as would be required to clear the debt. Those on low incomes would be exempted from repayments. There would be no prospect of bailiffs knocking at the door. And, of course, getting a degree greatly increases the chances of landing a well-paid job, so even after paying the 3% levy most graduates should still be better off.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;While the vice-chancellors' scheme is sensible, many academics fear that the government will use graduates' contributions as an excuse to make further cuts in its grants to universities. They point to Australia's new conservative government, which is both cutting universities' grants and increasing graduates' repayments. That is a possibility here. But surely the alternative--universities bursting at the seams, aspiring students turned away, and the quality of higher education declining because taxpayers simply do not want to pay any more--is worse.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
