<html><head><title>Asia's costly labour problems</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>Asia's costly labour problems</h1>

<font size=1>HONG KONG</font>
<p>"THE situation in the country has changed," Mahathir Mohamad, Malaysia's prime minister, said last month. With the country short of manpower, he argued, firms should stop relying on cheap labour and shift to capital-intensive and high-tech industries. Dr Mahathir's prescription could apply to much of Asia, where labour difficulties are rapidly eroding the region's cost advantage over western countries.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A study published on September 18th by Political &amp; Economic Risk Consultancy (<font size=-1>PERC</font>), a Hong Kong-based firm of consultants, weighs up the various factors that make a country's workforce attractive to foreign investors--including not just the cost of labour, but its quality, availability and stability. <font size=-1>PERC</font> asked 223 expatriate managers based in Asia to rank labour attributes on a scale from zero to ten (with ten representing the worst score). The managers also scored workers in a selection of western countries. When the grades for both skilled and unskilled workers were averaged out, only India and the Philippines got good marks (see <a href="wb1.gif">table</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The problems raised by the managers vary from country to country. Staff in Hong Kong and Singapore, for instance, were highly rated for quality, but were expensive and likely to hop from job to job almost as quickly as the low-cost, but poorly skilled, Vietnamese. Although India may provide the cheapest and most available labour, only the Philippines scored reasonably well in all categories.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet even in the Philippines, which is attracting plenty of interest from foreign investors now that its economy finally seems back on track, problems crop up. For example, small foreign firms encounter particular difficulties, since Filipinos appear to respond best when employed by big multinationals with a strong corporate culture.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>PERC</font> study is another jot of evidence in what seems to be a disturbing trend. Despite Asia's potentially enormous workforce, most companies in the region complain about the difficulties of finding, training and keeping employees. With economic development racing ahead of local skills, workers often have to be imported to fill the gaps--even for unskilled jobs. Hence labourers from Myanmar work on Thai building sites; Filipinos assemble computers in Taiwan, and East European technicians beaver away in Singapore.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Malaysians were shocked earlier this year when 3,600 workers were laid off in Penang, the country's leading enterprise zone and home to 130 electronics firms. Those who cut back included Quantum of Japan, which transferred the manufacture of hard-disk drives to Japan, and America's Hewlett-Packard. Grundig, a subsidiary of Philips, a Dutch consumer-electronics giant, shut its factory completely. Although a slump in electronics was partly to blame for the retrenchment, companies in Penang face a severe shortage of skilled workers, as well as wage increases that have outstripped productivity gains.



</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?843260400,iss">Search</a>
