<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><h2>Banned: the bomb</h2></p>
<p><p>The <font size=-1>UN</font>'s General Assembly voted overwhelmingly to open for signature a <b>Comprehensive Test-Ban Treaty </b>that had earlier been blocked by India and Iran. India can still prevent the treaty coming into force. But other world leaders, including those of the five official nuclear powers, are queuing up to sign.
<p>Iraq's aircraft and air defences defiantly provoked American aircraft in the "no fly" zones. The United States threatened a <b>"disproportionate" response</b>, and flew <font size=-1>B</font>-<font size=-1>52</font> and Stealth bombers to the area. Earlier in the week, Massoud Barzani, leader of the Kurdistan Democratic Party, had advanced to sweep Jalal Talabani's Patriotic Union of Kurdistan from its strongholds in Iraq's Kurdish enclave.
<p>Under Syrian pressure, <b>Lebanon</b>'s two Shia parties, Amal and Hizbullah, changed their minds to fight elections in southern Lebanon (as well as forthcoming ones in the Bekaa valley) on a joint ticket. The candidates they endorsed won overwhelmingly.
<p>Joachim Ruhana, the Roman Catholic Archbishop of <b>Burundi</b>, was murdered by gunmen. In an earlier development, Burundi's neighbours agreed to ease sanctions against the military regime in order to allow in humanitarian aid.
<p>A Commonwealth delegation reached agreement with <b>Nigeria</b> on sending a ministerial team to the country to discuss human rights abuses and a return to democracy.
<p>A relief convoy reached the Liberian town of Tubmanberg and found several thousand <b>starving people</b>. The town had been cut off for weeks by fighting between rival factions.
<p>President Albert Zafy of <b>Madagascar</b> quit after being impeached by the National Assembly. An election is set for November 3rd.</p>
<p><h2>Belgian crisis</h2></p>
<p><p>A Belgian court charged a former interior minister, Alain Van der Biest , and four others with the 1991 <b>murder of Andr&eacute; Cools</b>, a deputy prime minister. Information leading to the arrests may have come from investigations into the murder of four girls and the uncovering of a paedophile and car-theft ring. Outraged by apparent incompetence all round, King Albert called for reform of the judicial system.
<p>Russia's president, <b>Boris Yeltsin</b>, handed over most of his powers to the prime minister, Viktor Chernomyrdin, before he has heart surgery later this month. He did not yield control of nuclear weapons or the right to name ministers and sign decrees.
<p>Europe's monetary committee agreed on a procedure for imposing sanctions against countries that run excessive budget deficits after they join <b>economic and monetary union</b>. Under the deal, still to be ratified, wayward countries could be required to put up non-interest bearing deposits and pay fines.
<p>Russian troops began withdrawing from <b>Chechnya</b> under the terms of the peace agreement.</p></td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<h2>American intrigue</h2></p>
<p><p>Susan McDougal, a business partner of Bill Clinton's in the failed <b>Whitewater </b>scheme, went to prison rather than testify about the president's role in the case. Analysts said this was unlikely to affect the president's chances in the election.
<p><b>Ross Perot</b>, floundering on in America's election campaign, picked as his running mate Pat Choate, an economist known mainly for his attacks on <font size=-1>NAFTA</font> and on pro-Japan lobbyists.
<p>The Senate passed the Defence of Marriage Act, which would deny federal recognition of <b>same-sex marriages</b> and allow states to refuse to recognise any that had been approved by other states.
<p>Mr Clinton asked Congress to find more than $1 billion a year for <b>anti-terrorist measures </b>at airports, federal offices and museums.
<p>At least 28 people in the United States were killed by <b>Hurricane Fran</b>, and 34 North Carolina counties were declared disaster areas.
<p>Further fighting in <b>Colombia</b> left at least 25 soldiers and policemen, and more guerrillas, dead. Vice-president Humberto de la Calle, having told scandal-wrapped President Ernesto Samper to resign because the country was "falling apart", was told in return that he himself should resign. He did.
<p>An opinion poll on <b>Nicaragua</b>'s October 20th presidential election found left-winger (and ex-president) Daniel Ortega now close behind the right-wing front-runner, Arnaldo Aleman. But in a (probable) run-off, he would be likely to be well behind.</p>
<p><h2>Troops out</h2></p>
<p><p>Japanese on the island of <b>Okinawa </b>voted decisively for United States military facilities on the island to be reduced, leading to fears that other regions of Japan may reject American troops.
<p>Malaysia said it was "offended" by statements by Singaporean politicians about possible <b>reunification </b>of the two countries. Singapore was part of Malaysia from 1963 to 1965.
<p>A quarrel between China and Japan over <b>disputed islands </b>in the East China Sea sharpened when the Chinese gave warning of "serious damage" to relations between the two countries unless a lighthouse built by Japanese right-wingers was removed from the islands.
<p>Thirty settlers were killed by tribesmen in <b>Bangladesh</b>'s Chittagong Hill Tracts. It was the worst massacre of settlers for many years. The tribesmen want all settlers to leave and for the region to be granted autonomy.
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
