<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p>

<p><h2>Rolling on</h2>
<p><p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>Unemployment in America</b> dropped sharply in August, to 5.1%, the lowest level in seven years. The Dow Jones climbed strongly, despite the prospect of higher interest rates. Of the big five economies, only America and Britain have succeeded in pushing down unemployment over the year.
<p>In the biggest expansion since it was formed in 1930, the <b>Bank for International Settlements</b>, the central banks' central bank, is adding nine new members from Asia and Latin America to its mainly industrialised member-countries. Among those invited to join, and forestalling moves among Asian countries to form their own (competing) network, were China, India, Singapore and South Korea.
<p>A report from the British government claimed Switzerland held <b>Nazi gold </b>worth $5o0m at the end of the second world war--close to $4 billion in today's terms and much more than was previously thought. The report could increase pressure on Switzerland to examine the role of Swiss banks in shielding Nazi firms. Britain reckons that Swiss banks could still hold 90% of the hoard, which was looted from occupied countries and from Jews, then banked in neutral Switzerland.
<p>Withdrawals from Morgan Grenfell's troubled mutual funds slowed, but the firm's parent, <b>Deutsche Bank</b>, has not ruled out the need to push more cash into the three funds. Deutsche Bank is considering transferring responsibility for the British operations to Frankfurt. The bank dispatched one of its top men to London to help sort out the mess.
<p><b>Kepit</b>, the Kleinwort European Privatisation Investment Trust, is to be broken up, an unusual move reflecting the trend towards protecting shareholders rather than managers. The episode is an embarrassing one for Kleinwort Benson Investment Management, which has seen the &#163;530m ($822m) trust limp since its launch 2.5 years ago.
<p>Sir Alastair Morton reckons <b>Eurotunnel</b> will reach agreement with its leading creditor banks on refinancing its huge debt before he retires next month as co-chairman. The Anglo-French operator of the Channel tunnel cut its losses to &#163;372m ($568m) in the first half from &#163;465m a year earlier, operating near break-even in the second quarter; financial charges shrank from &#163;355m to &#163;330m.</p>
<p><h2>Switched on</h2></p>
<p><p><b>Canal Plus</b> of France, recently thwarted in its plans to expand into Germany's digital-<font size=-1>TV</font> market, is to merge with most of the European assets of <b>NetHold</b> in a deal worth about $2 billion. This will make Canal Plus, with 8.5m subscribers, one of the biggest <font size=-1>TV</font> groups in the world. The owners of NetHold are two South African firms, Richemont, a luxury-goods and tobacco outfit, and Multichoice, a media holding company.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>America's discount</b> <b>drugstores</b> are consolidating. In a $1 billion deal, Phar-Mor will merge with ShopKo Stores, more than doubling the number of pharmacies in its chain. And in a second development Revco, the country's second-largest chain, launched a $330m hostile bid for Big B.
<p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Trading in <b>Olivetti </b>resumed after a turbulent few days. Its shares had been suspended after Carlo De Benedetti stepped down as head of the Italian technology company and another departing executive accused the company of hiding the true extent of its losses.
<p>The <b>semiconductor industry</b> got some good news. One closely tracked indicator, the "book-to-bill ratio" for North American firms, rose slightly to 0.90 (for every $100 in shipments, chip firms received $90-worth of new orders) from 0.86 the month before. World figures, which arrive a month late, looked even better: 0.95 for July. But both are still far below the 1.16 figure of a year ago, suggesting that the industry is coming out of its year-long slump only slowly.
<p>America's Textron, whose 25 divisions worldwide range from Cessna aircraft to automotive parts, awarded a $1.1 billion, ten-year contract to<b> AT&T</b> to install voice, data and video communications.
<p>British women can now get <b>personalised jeans</b> from Levi Strauss, which is trying out its "Personal Pair" scheme in London after the new tailoring service proved popular in America and Canada.</p>
<p><h2>Wrecked</h2></p>
<p><p>Profits at <b>Renault</b> plummeted in the first half, and the French car maker warned of a loss for the full year. Net profits dropped by 91% to FFr158m ($31m), from FFr1.76 billion a year ago. Revenues fell 2.2% as a price war raged and recovery in Europe's commercial-vehicle market failed to materialise.
<p>Two big shipping lines are to merge their container operations, creating the world's biggest container group in a fragmented industry. Britain's <b>P&O</b> and <b>Royal Nedlloyd </b>of the Netherlands will have equal stakes in <font size=-1>P&O</font> Nedlloyd, which will have net assets of $1.5 billion and a $4 billion turnover. The news boosted the shares of both.
<p><b>Prudential Insurance</b>, already embattled in its life business, suffered a new blow. It lost a $4.5 billion-a-year contract to provide health insurance to the American Association of Retired Persons. Three competitors have taken over from it.
<p><p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
