<html><head><title>Funds and games</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>


<h1><center>Funds and games</center></h1>
<p><b>Recent scandals in the fund-management industry are in danger of making regulators over-react
</b></p>

PETER LYNCH, Warren Buffett, George Soros. The fund-management industry has always been known for its stars, courted by investors and canonised by the press for their ability to beat the financial markets. More recently, however, two prominent fund managers have gained notoriety for less stellar deeds. Peter Young, of Morgan Grenfell Asset Management (<font size=-1>MGAM</font>) in London, appears to have put his investors in a pickle; Colin Armstrong, of Jardine Fleming in Hong Kong, is said to have misused investors' funds. The danger now is that the damage will extend beyond these two firms, if regulators respond by issuing a raft of new rules, rather than letting the industry heal itself.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The pressure on them to do so is acute, because in both cases small investors were involved. When an investment banker or derivatives trader goes astray, it is usually his peers that are hurt: Nick Leeson took down the Barings blue-bloods, not the man in the street. But when Aunt Agatha is at risk, cries for the regulators to do something--anything--grow louder.

</p><p><b>Star-crossed investors</b>
<br>In fact, the industry has plenty of incentives to put its own house in order. Until recently, the rise of star managers was caused by the increased competition for new cash among unit trusts (mutual funds). It seemed an excellent marketing formula: find someone with a good track record, build up his public image to match his ego, and then leave him alone to work his magic. "People want to believe in magic, they want to believe in gurus," Mr Young was quoted as saying this week. But the industry is beginning to learn that the star system also entails huge risks. Not only is it a source of mischief, it also makes that mischief more visible when it is discovered. To remain competitive, funds will have to strive to avoid putting performance before propriety.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This requires two big changes. First, funds must reform the way they pay their managers. To lure the brightest stars, most firms allow them to engage in personal trading for their own account. This is a recipe for disaster, as it makes it far easier to engage in practices such as "front running" (buying a stock for yourself, then investing the fund's money in it to boost its price) and "rat trading" (waiting to see how trades turn out, and then booking the best ones to your own account). Although these practices are illegal in most places, they can be hard to detect; forbidding personal accounts would snuff them out overnight. Better to let managers invest in the same funds they manage--so that, to borrow one of Mr Buffett's folksy phrases, "they eat their own cooking" .
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Besides abolishing personal accounts, fund-management firms should also watch their stars more closely. Internal watchdogs are often afraid to trifle with the best performers, lest they leave in a huff. This is perverse. Since beating the market is difficult, a manager who thumps it consistently is either extremely clever, lucky--or a suitable case for monitoring. Indeed, it should not take long for funds that enact such reforms to score points with investors. In the past few years, an entire sub-industry of fund-tracking firms and financial journalists has arisen to monitor funds' behaviour.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But although funds are capable of making many changes themselves, some new regulation is still essential. For a start, regulators must improve their ability to spot malpractice when it occurs. Britain's fund-management watchdog--the Investment Management Regulatory Organisation--learnt of Mr Young's deeds through sheer luck. It is now looking exhaustively into <font size=-1>MGAM</font>'s actions, and trying to discover whether the fund's trustees did their jobs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Regulators can also help to clarify the ways in which unit trusts should disclose their funds' risks. Since all investors are different, these rules must remain flexible. Many investors, for example, prefer to turn their judgment over to a professional, who will hop between stocks and bonds, and between different countries, to chase the best opportunities. If a fund wants to market itself in this way, it should be allowed to. Other investors, however, want to decide for themselves which kinds of assets to invest in; they simply want their unit trust to do so cheaply and effectively. For these investors, it is crucial that a fund does what it says it will: a European equity fund, for example, should not be buying shares in Asia.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If regulators lay down effective disclosure rules, and ensure that they are complied with, it will become far easier for funds to tell investors what they are doing. After that, the need to compete should be enough to make sure that it is trustworthy managers who become the stars of the future.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
