<html><head><title>Too many puffs</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Advertising</b></p>
<h1>Too many puffs</h1>


<p>THE Advertising Standards Authority (<font size=-1>ASA</font>) may be, in the words of its own code, "decent, legal, honest and truthful", but is it effective? For years the self-regulatory body, which is financed entirely by the advertising industry, excited little controversy. More recently, however, it has been running into trouble. Complaints to the authority have risen by nearly a third at a time when its rulings are increasingly under attack from both advertisers and the public.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Politicians appear to have little respect for the authority. The Conservative Party openly defied the <font size=-1>ASA</font> over its judgment that the party's poster featuring Tony Blair with demonic red eyes was a breach of the code. "We are totally unrepentant," said a senior Tory official. Labour seems no happier with the <font size=-1>ASA</font>. Nigel Griffiths, its consumer affairs spokesman, says the <font size=-1>ASA</font> reacts too slowly to complaints. By the time it issues an adjudication the advertising campaigns have already finished, he argues.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Doubts over the authority's competence are not confined to politicians. Pressure groups such as Friends of the Earth, whose advertisements have been the subject of adverse rulings, often claim the authority is unprofessional and poorly informed. Others, such as Action on Smoking and Health, dismiss it as "weak and ineffective".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>ASA</font> also sometimes seems to be out of touch with public opinion. It recently rejected complaints about a Gossard bra poster featuring a semi-naked model reclining invitingly in a haystack accompanied by the slogan: "Who said a woman can't get pleasure from something soft?" The decision has provoked a storm of protest from women's groups. The authority ruled the advertisement's innuendo was acceptable on the grounds that parents could truthfully tell their children that the poster was praising the bra's qualities.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some such controversies, especially on matters concerning public taste, are inevitable. And the very nature of its task means that the authority can never please everyone. But charges of incompetence are more serious. This is the kind of criticism which the authority is now facing from food firms and anti-smoking groups over its handling of an advertisement run earlier this year by Philip Morris, a cigarette company.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The advertisement suggested the health risk from passive smoking was less than eating one biscuit a day. <i>The Economist </i>has learned that the authority provisionally decided that the advertisement was unacceptable because it gave a "misleading impression" of comparative risk but then, only after representations from the company, decided to seek independent advice.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Complaints about the advertisement were first made in June. But it was not until the middle of August that the <font size=-1>ASA</font> decided that it needed independent scientific advice, something which should have been obvious at the outset. By the time the <font size=-1>ASA</font>'s council finally rules on the complaint on September 13th, Philip Morris will have long since ceased running the advert. In France, by contrast, the courts ordered the company to call an immediate halt to a similar campaign and it is now also facing an action for damages.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The French approach risks state censorship and assumes that consumers are too stupid to make up their own minds. Self-regulation, or no regulation at all, makes better sense. But if self-regulation is chosen, there is not much point to it being done incompetently.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>ASA</font> should not have needed three months to judge whether this advertisement was misleading. Had it sought advice earlier, it would have quickly learned there is plenty of evidence available on which to judge the relative risks of eating fat-laden biscuits and passive smoking. Numerous studies have examined the fat issue. And as long ago as 1988 a government-appointed commission reported on the risks of passive smoking. Since then, the Royal College of Physicians has done a similar study.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842655600,iss">Search</a>
