<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><b>Pay clash</b> &nbsp;The Trades Union Congress in Blackpool voted to press for a statutory minimum wage of &#163;4.26 an hour. However, it also voted against setting a precise figure until a Labour government was elected.</p>
<p><b>Still talking</b> &nbsp;The British and Irish governments rejected a demand by Ian Paisley's Democratic Unionists that the Progressive Unionists and the Ulster Democrats, two parties linked to loyalist paramilitaries, be expelled from the Ulster peace talks because loyalists had issued a death threat to a dissident who opposes the loyalist ceasefire.</p>
<p><b>Runcie row</b> &nbsp;According to extracts from a biography of Lord Runcie, a former archbishop of Canterbury, he worried that homosexual clergy might "stab him in the back" and that the Prince of Wales "gave up" on the Church of England a decade ago.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Scots shock</b> &nbsp;Just six days after proposing a second referendum to grant tax-raising powers to a Scottish assembly set up as a result of its first devolution referendum, the Labour leadership abandoned the idea.</p>
<p><b>Whacked</b> &nbsp;The government promised to defend parents' rights to smack their children after the European Commission on Human Rights allowed a 12-year-old boy who had been caned by his stepfather to bring a case challenging British law.</p>
<p><b>Smashed</b> &nbsp;The government said police would be given powers to confiscate alcohol from under-age drinkers.</p>
<p><b>No rally</b> &nbsp;A planned rally of thousands of Muslim fundamentalists in London's Docklands Arena was cancelled because its organisers could not pay for security measures demanded by the venue's managers.</p>
<p><b>Artbreaking</b> &nbsp;A 625 square-feet chalk drawing on a pavement in Carlisle city centre, commissioned to mark the opening of an arts festival, was washed away a few minutes after it was finished by a street-cleaner who thought it was graffiti.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
