<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><h2>Iraq and America</h2></p>
<p><p>
<p><b>Iraq</b> sent its army into the northern autonomous enclave at the invitation of one Kurdish faction to displace a rival faction from Arbil, the Kurdish capital. In response, the Americans launched cruise missile raids against air defences in southern Iraq, and extended the southern no-fly zone almost to the outskirts of Baghdad. Britain backed the strikes, France and Russia disapproved.
<p>After long haggling and under American and Egyptian pressure, Israel's prime minister, Binyamin Netanyahu, met the Palestinians' Yasser Arafat, a thing he once said he would not do. The two agreed to continue the<b> peace process</b>. But Mr Netanyahu refused to set a date for Israel's overdue redeployment of troops in Hebron.
<p>Hutu rebels attacked government garrisons in northern <b>Burundi</b> and shelled the capital, Bujumbura. They hope to bring down the government of Major Pierre Buyoya, who seized power in July.
<p>Good news from <b>South Africa</b>: Nelson Mandela and Gra&ccedil;a Machel, widow of a former president of Mozambique, are a couple; it's official. But no marriage plans yet. Bad news: Bantu Holomisa, a former deputy minister, was expelled from the <font size=-1>ANC</font> for accusing a senior party member of taking bribes.
<p><b>Zimbabwe</b>'s civil servants ended a fortnight-long strike, after the government, already driven to offer a 20% pay rise, agreed to reinstate those it had sacked.</p>
<p><h2>Chechen peace?</h2></p>
<p><p>President Yeltsin's defence adviser, <b>Alexander Lebed</b>, signed a peace deal with the separatist Chechens' guerrilla commander, Aslan Maskhadov, that postpones a final decision on the breakaway republic's constitutional status for five years. But Mr Yeltsin, who is said this week to have agreed to a heart operation, has not yet backed the deal.
<p>In the first of a series of important <b>regional elections</b> in Russia, Dmitri Ayatskov, a technocrat with no formal party affiliation, was elected chief of the region of Saratov with 80% of the vote. This was a blow for the Communists, whose presidential candidate, Gennady Zyuganov, carried the province in July.
<p><b>Bernard Tapie</b>, a colourful and controversial French businessman-cum-politician convicted of fraud, said he would give up his seat in the National Assembly, but for the time being he is hanging on to his membership of the European Parliament.
<p>The European Parliament began to examine charges that the European Commission tried to suppress investigations into links between <font size=-1>BSE</font>, or <b>mad-cow disease</b>, and a similar disease in people. In a letter leaked to a French newspaper, a top farm Eurocrat discouraged a colleague's request for an investigation, saying that "all discussions on <font size=-1>BSE</font> inevitably cause problems in the beef market."
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Ethnic Albanians in <b>Kosovo</b>, a province of Serbia, agreed to end their six-year boycott of Serbian schools. This may pave the way for an accord on the future of the province.
<p><b>Finland's government </b>said it would cut spending by 5% in real terms next year to 191 billion markkas ($42 billion) in order to meet the criteria for joining Europe's economic and monetary union.
<p>More than 2,000 <b>unidentified corpses </b>have been found dumped in Moscow Region this year, <font size=-1>2X2</font> television reported, quoting an official.</p>
<p><h2>Ever onwards</h2></p>
<p><p>The American election campaign kicked off in earnest. <b>Bill Clinton </b>shrugged off the resignation of Dick Morris, his chief campaign strategist, over a sex scandal and, aided by his forceful actions in the Gulf, regained his 20-plus-point lead over Bob Dole.
<p><b>Colombia </b>was shaken by guerrilla attacks in which nearly 80 people died. One army post was overrun, leaving more than 30 soldiers dead and many more than that in rebel hands. The guerrillas, active for decades but not on this scale, combine claims of left-wing politics with real-world kidnapping, sabotage of oil pipelines, and drug-running.
<p>In <b>Mexico</b>, a little-heard-of new "People's Revolutionary Army" launched attacks in several states, killing more than 15 people. The Zapatist rebel movement told the newcomers to stay off its
<p>Chiapas turf, but broke off talks with the government, to prove its own revolutionary credentials.</p>
<p><h2>Identity crisis</h2></p>
<p><p>Japan and China are in dispute over eight <b>uninhabited islands</b>, called the Senkakus (in Japanese) and the Diaoyu (in Chinese). Indonesia conducted a big military exercise around its Natuna islands, where it is engaged in a $36 billion joint venture to develop natural-gas fields.
<p>Hong Kong's chief justice, Sir Ti Liang Yang, became the latest candidate for the job of <b>chief executive </b>after the British colony is returned to China next July. Separately, China agreed that its representative would shake the hand of Chris Patten, Hong Kong's last governor, at the handover ceremony in 1997. The British were relieved.
<p>Lee Kuan Yew, Singapore's former prime minister, said in Beijing that <b>China </b>would suffer "political and economic costs" if it mishandled the reunification of Hong Kong or Taiwan. China should give Hong Kong dissidents "time to adjust" to the transfer of power, he said.
<p>About 13m Japanese took part in an exercise designed to limit casualties in<b> earthquakes</b>. Japan experiences a tremor nearly every day.
<p>A species of <b>pheasant</b>, thought to be extinct and last seen in 1928, has been rediscovered in Vietnam.
<p>
<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
<p align=center><a href="wtw2.html">BUSINESS THIS WEEK</a></p><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
