<html><head><title>The Washington Wobbler v The Baghdad Bruiser</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>




<h1>The Washington Wobbler v The Baghdad Bruiser</h1>

<p>AH, SADDAM. There is nothing quite like that infamous face, and the evocative accompaniment of Peter Arnett once again sending reports from Baghdad on <font size=-1>CNN</font>, to rally Americans and inspire them with a sense of foreign-policy purpose. It is the face of The Enemy. Since the collapse of communism, America has suffered from a shortage of compelling enemies--except in the fantasy world of this summer's blockbuster movie, "Independence Day", which invented a super-enemy from outer space. As a result, the country's foreign policy has tended to appear adrift. Threats to American interests have often seemed distant (as in Bosnia) or faceless (as the possible bombers of <font size=-1>TWA</font> flight 800 remain). Saddam Hussein lends American policy a wondrous clarity and unity.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At least for a few days. Then things get trickier. As you might expect from such a wily operator, the Iraqi dictator has picked the moment for his provocation carefully. For a number of reasons, America faces peculiar difficulties in calibrating its response.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One reason is presidential politics, with the election just two months away. Whether or not this weighs in Bill Clinton's calculations (perish the thought), his task is complicated by the suspicion of others, including America's allies, that it must. The president's plans for missile attacks on Iraq were laid between stops on his campaign bus tour. And his decisions have certainly done his re-election prospects no harm.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Early polls showed Americans to be overwhelmingly in favour of the missile strikes against Iraq ordered by Mr Clinton. Out of the news went the unsavoury story of Dick Morris, Mr Clinton's master-strategist who resigned after tabloid reports of his foolish affair with a prostitute, and in came images of the president acting as commander-in-chief. Criticism of Mr Clinton by his Republican rival, Bob Dole, for allowing the crisis to brew turned to patriotic expressions of solidarity once the military response was launched.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Dole is in any case on shaky ground when it comes to tough-minded advice on the handling of Mr Hussein. Mr Dole, remember, led an appeasing mission of senators who in 1990 met Mr Hussein in the northern Iraqi city of Mosul shortly before the invasion of Kuwait. Kansas was a big grain exporter to Iraq. They delivered a tough letter from George Bush but, according to the Iraqi transcript of the meeting, the then senior senator from Kansas and Senate minority leader told the Iraqi leader that a Voice of America journalist responsible for a broadcast that had caused particular offence to Mr Hussein had been sacked.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But what if the tension in the Gulf refuses to die down and, worse, claims casualties among the American air forces patrolling the now-enlarged no-fly zone over southern Iraq? That would surely aggravate divisions over the appropriate response to Mr Hussein--divisions which pose the second complication for Mr Clinton. Because Mr Hussein's military move came within Iraq's own borders, and in response to a request from one Kurdish faction fighting against another, the case for punitive reprisals looks to some less than black-and-white. Some of America's own allies, notably France, expressed public misgivings about the American riposte. The qualms of others--Turkey, Saudi Arabia--ruled out attacks on Iraq from their territory and so limited Mr Clinton's military options.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is far from obvious that the president could command adequate support for an escalation of his actions against Mr Hussein, if that is what he wanted to do. Opposition would come not only from abroad, but at home. A report published on August 29th by the Cato Institute, a libertarian Washington think-tank, argued that America should withdraw its troops from the Gulf because it has "no interests to justify the risks and costs" of attempting to manage security there.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, America does have big security interests in the Gulf. It has interests in the supply of oil, in the stability of a volatile region, and in the protection of allies from the ruthless aggression of Mr Hussein, the would-be regional hegemon. The trouble is, until this week the Clinton administration has not spent much effort reminding anyone of those interests.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Which points to the third, and deepest, complication exposed by Mr Hussein: the failure of Mr Clinton to develop a clear set of foreign-policy priorities. In the absence of the Soviet threat, Mr Clinton can list a series of lesser post-cold-war threats, such as terrorism and weapons proliferation. But he has given little sense that he has in his mind a hierarchy of American interests or any workable principles by which to judge what he would do to defend them. Instead, Mr Clinton has opted for ad-hocery. This landed him in early trouble (over Bosnia, for example) but later produced some tentative successes (Bosnia again). On balance, there has been enough for Mr Clinton to brag about, but not enough for him to inspire confidence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;You might think that in such circumstances foreign policy would be right in the thick of this year's election campaign, with Mr Dole itching to attack a Clintonian weakness. But no. Foreign policy featured only briefly at both the Republican and Democratic conventions last month. After his laundry list of domestic policies in his acceptance speech in Chicago, Mr Clinton turned to Abroad almost as an afterthought. As for Mr Dole, he told the <i>New York Times </i>this week that his main message was about the economy, drugs, the budget, education; he would add "some foreign policy, some more trade, other things as they come up."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Saddam Hussein has now come up, in a big way. Whatever else Mr Hussein achieves, he has suddenly placed foreign policy where it should have been all along in an American election campaign: at its heart. It was not so long ago that an American president came to power believing, admittedly a tad simplistically, that dealing with the world was the principal job he had been elected to do. "All you need is a competent cabinet to run the country at home," said Richard Nixon. "You need a president for foreign policy." 
</td></tr></table>
