<html><head><title>A vote too far</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Scottish politics</b></p>
<h1>A vote too far</h1>

<font size=1>EDINBURGH</font>
<p>POP into the Edinburgh offices of either the Scottish National Party (<font size=-1>SNP</font>) or the Scottish Conservative Party just now, and you find the same thing--cheery people brimming with optimism. This good humour is at odds with the political standing of both parties. The <font size=-1>SNP</font> has little hope of winning more than the four parliamentary seats it has now, while the Tories' opinion-poll ratings in Scotland remain stuck at little more than half the 26% share of the vote they won at the last election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But the reason for the jolliness is not hard to find. It is the dreadful hash that Labour is making of its plans for a devolved Scottish parliament. What Labour proposes--an elected parliament to run Scottish domestic affairs with limited taxation powers--is clear. It is how this will be established which is causing the merriment.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In June, Tony Blair announced that there would be pre-legislative referendums in Scotland and Wales. These, he argued, would dispel doubts about whether voters wanted devolution and would help speed the necessary bills through Westminster. To counter the Tories' damaging campaign that the Edinburgh parliament would levy a "tartan tax" on Scots, he declared that the Scottish referendum would have a second question solely on the taxation powers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This seemed like a bright idea. But left-wingers and nationalist-minded members of his Scottish party were enraged. They reckoned that Scots would vote for a parliament but against being taxed by it, and that this would severely weaken the scheme. They also resented not being consulted before the announcement.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Blair and his Scottish spokesman, George Robertson, were unable to quell this rebellion despite much arm-twisting. At a meeting of Labour's Scottish Executive Committee on August 31st, after two hours of dead-locked discussion, Mr Robertson accepted an idea that a further referendum authorising a decision by the Scottish parliament to use the taxation powers would make it more likely that yes-votes could be secured to both questions in the first referendum. This two-legged, three-humped camel of a plan then squeaked through the committee by 21 votes to 18.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although Mr Blair thus avoided an embarrassing defeat by Labour's Scottish executive, he now has a worse headache. The <font size=-1>SNP</font> was quick to point out that getting independence only needs two votes (for them in the election and in a subsequent referendum on an independence settlement) whereas getting Labour's full plan for devolution needs five votes (for a Labour government, in the first two-vote referendum, for a Scottish parliament, and then in the second referendum).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>SNP</font> thinks that voters will never understand this; and the party loudly proclaims that Labour is abandoning its Scottish parliament plan. Editorials in the main pro-devolution Scottish newspapers, the <i>Herald</i> and the <i>Scotsman</i>, which have so far loyally backed Labour, also interpret the referendum manoeuvring as evidence that Mr Blair wants to ditch devolution.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This is unlikely. He has already staked too much on it. Nevertheless Labour has given its opponents potent ammunition. On September 3rd, an obviously delighted John Major mocked Labour's latest plans as a "steeplechase of stupidities" in a speech to Scottish businessmen. As it is, Labour's divisive wranglings have cost it Scottish support already. An opinion poll published in the <i>Herald</i> on September 2nd showed that, compared with the previous month, Labour support had fallen by three points to 48%, while the <font size=-1>SNP</font> was up six points to 29% and the Tories were steady at 15%. Mr Blair is due to visit Scotland on September 9th to explain himself. He has a lot of fast talking to do.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
