<html><head><title>Racial bias</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Criminal Justice</b></p>
<h1>Racial bias</h1>


<p>ASK a group of youths on the streets of Brixton in south London what they think of the criminal-justice system, and you will get an earful. The almost universal opinion of young blacks that British justice is biased against them is hardly surprising given the current rates of imprisonment. New research findings to be published later this year show that young black males (Afro-Caribbeans and black Africans) are 12 times more likely to be imprisoned for rape, robbery and drug offences than young white males (see <a href="br2.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Are young blacks singled out for special treatment by the police and the courts or do they offend more often? Perhaps both. The author of the study, David Smith, professor of criminology at Edinburgh University, argues that young blacks do commit a disproportionately large number of crimes. And yet even Mr Smith admits that racial discrimination exists in many parts of the criminal-justice system. 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is that discrimination which was the subject of a report published on September 2nd by the Penal Affairs Consortium, an alliance of 31 penal-reform organisations. The report argues that part of the reason why ethnic-minority groups as a whole, not just blacks, are heavily over-represented in the prison population (18% compared with 5.5% of the general population) is that there is discrimination at every stage of the criminal-justice system.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The study notes that black males are significantly more likely to be stopped and searched by the police than are white males. More than a third of those stopped and searched by police in Greater London in 1994-95 belonged to minority groups. Similarly, a review of seven police forces found that young blacks were less likely to be cautioned and more likely to be prosecuted and remanded in custody than comparable white offenders. It is significant that the sharpest discrepancies in imprisonment rates tend to be for those crimes such as drug possession where the police have most discretion about whether or not to prosecute. In crimes where there is less room for discretion, such as burglary, imprisonment rates vary less.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Once on remand, black offenders were more likely to receive a jail sentence. A 1992 study into race and sentencing by Roger Hood, director of the Oxford Centre for Criminological Research, found that overall, black males were 17% more likely to receive a prison sentence than white males. Even after controlling for 15 key variables, such as the seriousness of the offence, the study found that blacks had a 5-8% greater chance of being sent to prison.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The extent of racial discrimination within the system has become much clearer since the 1991 Criminal Justice Act required racial monitoring by the police, the probation service and the courts. Even less in dispute is the fact that ethnic minorities are seriously under-represented in the staff of criminal-justice agencies. A report published this month by the National Association of Probation Officers found that only five out of the 514 circuit judges were from minority ethnic groups, two of the 339 district judges and 13 out of 897 recorders. And, despite a decade of attempting to recruit more minority policemen and women, their numbers remain tiny. In September 1995, 2,223, or just 1.75%, of the 127,222 police officers in England and Wales came from minority groups.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Little wonder that the view on the streets of Brixton is one of suspicion and distrust. In fact, this breakdown in confidence is itself one reason why young blacks fare so badly in the criminal-justice system. Young blacks are much less likely to admit an offence when questioned by the police, which means they cannot be cautioned and are thus more likely to be prosecuted. Similarly their tendency to plead not guilty in court, even if the evidence is overwhelming, frequently results in harsher sentences.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842050800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br6.html">Next article</a>
</p>
