<html><head><title>Collateral damage</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Sun Microsystems</b></p>
<h1>Collateral damage</h1>

<p>AS THE shells fly in the battle between Microsoft and Netscape for the web browser market, one company flinches more than most each time Netscape takes a direct hit. Since the upstart Netscape first grabbed the lead in the Internet's largest software market less than two years ago, Sun Microsystems has been its most partisan supporter. Together, the pair have whipped up wild enthusiasm for Sun's new programming language, Java, that could challenge Microsoft's overall dominance of the software industry. What happens to Sun if Microsoft wins?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the face of it, the question might seem premature. Microsoft, after all, still has less than 20% of the browser market. But Microsoft's war machine has never run more impressively than it has in browsers. In less than a year, Microsoft has matched Netscape's software technically, signed up all the biggest Internet service firms to distribute its browser, and is giving its program away for free while Netscape charges $50 for its own. If current trends continue, Microsoft may have passed Netscape in the market by the second half of next year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That would be dark news indeed for Netscape, and would not make Sun shine either. Netscape has been Sun's strongest supporter in pushing Java. Although Sun first introduced Java early last year, few Internet surfers could use it until Netscape included it with a new version of its browser earlier this year. Netscape has also promoted the idea that its browser, along with Java, could in effect replace Microsoft's Windows operating system as the main way people and software interact with their <font size=-1>PC</font>. It talks of using Java in the coming wave of low-price "network computers".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Little surprise, then, that Sun wants Netscape to win. But it is not directly threatened by the prospect of a Microsoft victory, for two reasons. The first is that Java is close to establishing itself. With or without Netscape, hundreds of software firms are developing Java programs and have a vested interest in seeing them find a market. Microsoft would prefer developers to switch to ActiveX, its own Java-compatible Internet language, but it knows that its browser must be able to run Java too.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second reason is that, as much as Sun's reputation has been burnished by Java over the past year, direct revenues from the language are minimal. Nearly three-quarters of its $7 billion in sales for the year that ended in July came from workstations and servers--powerful machines running the <font size=-1>UNIX</font> operating system that are used on the desktop by engineers and to run networks and Web sites.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The hitch is that the server market no longer looks the redoubt for Sun that it once was. High-end <font size=-1>PC</font>s running Microsoft's Windows <font size=-1>NT</font> software are almost as powerful and cheaper than <font size=-1>UNIX</font> workstations: they have been gaining ground (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>). True, Sun's machines are powering ahead in the new market for Internet servers (though that is the area where what the company calls the "halo effect" from Java may matter most). All the same, it is clear that in the medium term Sun will need to discover a new market, outside the <font size=-1>PC</font>'s shadow. And this is where Java could matter greatly.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As the competition in high-end computing increases, Sun wants to open another front, at the other end of the market: software for cheap and simple consumer devices, from mobile telephones to television set-top boxes, that connect to the Internet. Java was originally intended to be a language for set-top boxes and "embedded controllers" in electrical appliances and industrial equipment, but was quickly adapted for the Internet when the growth of the network exploded in 1994. Now Sun is returning to its original strategy. Along with Navio Communications, a new Netscape spin-off, it is working on ways to use Java and browsers with gadgets that most people do not think of as computers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sun is even developing its own processor chips expressly designed to run Java quickly on such machines. It reckons that such chips could make up half of the processor and controller market by 2000, bringing Sun $15 billion a year, as much as all its other businesses combined. This claim is questionable--manufacturers may be reluctant to let Sun create a hardware and software monopoly in small devices to match Microsoft's and Intel's lock on the <font size=-1>PC</font>--but it seems inevitable that telephones and other devices will become smarter.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The question is what will fire them: Java or something else? Microsoft, naturally enough, has its own plans for that market. It tried and failed to shoehorn chubby Windows code into telephones and fax machines. Now it is coming back with a slimmer version. It is too early to know how that will fare compared with Java. But it seems inevitable that the victor of the Internet wars will influence the winner in this potentially bigger market below the <font size=-1>PC</font>. Java has the lead at the moment. But if Microsoft captures the browser market, this is where it will surely try to use its clout next.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?842050800,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="fn1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
