<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><h2>Serbmandering</h2></p>
<p><p>The Bosnian president, Alija Izetbegovic, called for a Muslim boycott of the <b>Bosnian municipal elections</b> which Serbs plan to hold on September 14th. The Organisation for Security and Co-operation in Europe, charged with supervising the Bosnian elections, said it was postponing the official municipal poll because of alleged irregularities, though other votes would go ahead that day as scheduled.
<p>Russia's ailing president, <b>Boris Yeltsin</b>, went on holiday to a resort near Moscow. He refused two requests from Alexander Lebed, his special representative for Chechnya, for a meeting to discuss Mr Lebed's Chechen peace plan. Russian troops continued to withdraw from Chechnya's capital, Grozny, leaving it to separatist rebels.
<p><b>Estonia's parliament</b> failed to elect a new state president. Neither the reformist incumbent, Lennart Meri, nor his ex-communist rival, Arnold Ruutel, could muster the two-thirds majority needed, despite three rounds of voting.
<p>A conference opened in Stockholm on the international <b>sexual exploitation of children</b>. The search continued for the bodies of young victims of sex abuse in Belgium.
<p>The <b>Danish Supreme Court</b> agreed to allow 11 citizens to bring a constitutional challenge to Denmark's signature of the Maastricht treaty. The case may take four years. Until it is resolved, Denmark is unlikely to ratify amendments to the treaty being discussed by the <font size=-1>EU</font>'s inter-governmental conference.
<p>After hunger strikes and a two-month protest, 300 <b>illegal immigrants</b>, mostly from Africa, were evicted from a Paris church in an operation involving tear gas, batons and 1,000 police officers.
<p>The <b>hijacking </b>of a Sudanese airliner on a flight from Khartoum to Amman ended at London's Stansted Airport with the release of all passengers and crew. The Iraqi hijackers and their families were taken into custody.</p>
<p><h2>Heads will roll</h2></p>
<p><p>Two former presidents of <b>South Korea </b>were sentenced for their roles in a military coup and a massacre in Kwangju in 1980. Chun Doo Hwan was sentenced to death and Roh Tae Woo to 22.5 years in jail. Government critics said the two men had been put on trial to boost political support for President Kim Young Sam.
<p>Yakio Hatoyama, a member of <b>New Party Sakigake</b>, part of Japan's ruling coalition, said he was resigning to form a new party that would stand for "real democracy".
<p>Prosecutors arrested Takeshi Abe, the ex-head of Japan's <font size=-1>AIDS</font>-study team, for allegedly administering <b>untreated blood products </b>to haemophiliacs even though he knew that these might lead to <font size=-1>AIDS</font>. About 1,800 haemophiliacs have been infected with <font size=-1>HIV</font>, the virus that leads to <font size=-1>AIDS</font>, of which more than 400 have died.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Four members of an opposition party in <b>Singapore </b>faced jail after being accused by the government of "contempt of Parliament". They had allegedly lied about the cost of the state's health care.
<p>More than <b>200 pilgrims </b>to a shrine at Amarnath in the Himalayas died in bad weather. The shrine has a naturally formed ice phallus of Shiva, a Hindu god.</p>
<p><h2>Inroads</h2></p>
<p><p><b>Israel's government</b> approved further Jewish settlement-building ("unfreezing a plan accepted by the Rabin government", it said), and allowed the demolition of a Palestinian community centre under construction ("without a permit") in East Jerusalem. "Declaring war" on the Palestinians, cried Yasser Arafat, calling a half-day shutdown in the West Bank and Gaza.
<p><b>Turkey and Israel</b>, already linked by an agreement on air-force training, signed one for co-operation between their defence industries.
<p>The <b>Zimbabwean government </b>offered a 20% pay rise to thousands of civil servants whose strike since August 20th had disrupted the country's essential services.
<p>A former senior South African security policeman, Eugene de Kock, was convicted on 89 charges, including six of<b> murder</b>, by a court in
<p>Pretoria after a trial lasting two years.</p>
<p><h2>Making tracks</h2></p>
<p><p>At their convention in Chicago, <b>the Democrats </b>re-nominated Bill Clinton for four more years in the White House and offered "the end of the era of big government." To get <font size=-1>TV</font> coverage, Mr Clinton travelled there by train, and the paralysed "Superman" star, Christopher Reeve, made a prime-time speech.
<p>The Defence Department denied that it had intentionally quashed a 1991 classified report, revealed in the <i>New York Times</i>, suggesting that American troops were exposed to <b>Iraqi chemical weapons </b>during the Gulf war. But it said the full relevance of the report had not been recognised at the time.
<p>Foreign<b> oil companies in Colombia</b> were rattled by a proposal in the country's Congress for changes which--said the foreigners--would make them little more than contractors for the state oil company. Then the interior minister said it was ready to talk about anything, oil nationalisation included, that might bring peace with "left-wing" guerrillas who demand just that and sabotage pipelines to prove it.
<p><b>Japan</b> embarked on a love-in with Latin America. After Mexico, Chile and Brazil, its prime minister, Ryutaro Hashimoto, visited Peru to sign a $615m loan deal, before flying to Costa Rica.
<p>
<p>
<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
