<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><h2>Connecting</h2>
<p><p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>Two fast-growing American telecoms companies will merge to create a <b>business-communications giant </b>that could threaten rivals in both America and Europe. In the third big telecoms merger this year, WorldCom agreed to purchase <font size=-1>MFS</font> for $14.4 billion to form a company that will be able to offer local, long-distance and Internet access rolled into one.
<p><font size=-1>SKW</font> Trostberg, the specialty chemicals unit of Germany's Viag, will pay SFr1.3 billion ($1.1 billion) for Master Building Technologies, a unit of Swiss-based Sandoz, a union that would create by far the biggest <b>building-chemicals business </b>in the world.
<p>South Africa's Gencor admitted that the hoped-for merger of its platinum operations with those of Britain's Lonrho to create the world's second-largest <b>platinum producer </b>would not happen, following opposition, on antitrust grounds, from the European Union.
<p>In a fast-growing--and consolidating--business, <b>AccuStaff </b>is set to become America's fourth-biggest recruitment company with the purchase of Career Horizons for close to $900m.
<p>In what would be a huge foreign investment for <b>Turkey</b>, Royal Dutch/Shell, Mitsubishi of Japan and America's M.W. Kellogg have sought permission from the government to build a $2.4 billion liquefied-gas terminal and power-station complex.
<p>Anglo American, under pressure to slacken its corporate grip on South Africa, agreed to sell most of its 47.4% stake in Johnnic Industrial Corp to <b>black investors</b>. The National Empowerment Consortium will take 41% of the industrial holding group in a deal worth more than 3 billion rand ($665m).
<p>Barry Diller, a hyperactive media mogul, began the slow reorganisation of Silver King Communications by taking full control of <b>Home Shopping Network</b> in a share swap valued at $1.27 billion.
<p>America's Kimberley-Clark doubled to 30% its share of the French <b>disposable-nappy market</b> when it took over Peaudouce, a brand owned by <font size=-1>SCA</font>, a Swedish pulp and paper company that swapped Peaudouce for a British tissue mill. The deal is a threat to Procter &amp; Gamble, another American nappy (diaper) maker, which has 40% of the French market.</p>
<p><h2>Blocked</h2></p>
<p><p>America called off scheduled talks with Britain on an <b>open-skies pact</b>, saying the two sides were too far apart. A controversial proposed alliance between British Airways and American Airlines depends on the two governments making a deal.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Target, a big chain of discount stores in America, will stop selling <b>tobacco products</b> from September, citing falling profits and the costs of complying with legal restrictions.
<p><b>Virgin Express</b>, a Brussels-based airline which has taken advantage of deregulation within the European Union to run cheap flights, found its path blocked by (non-<font size=-1>EU</font>) Switzerland. The airline, owned by Britain's Virgin Group, dropped plans to start a new service between Brussels and Geneva next week after the Swiss government objected to the airline halving the fares normally charged by Swissair and Sabena of Belgium.
<p><b>Daimler-Benz</b> unveiled an impressive boost in first-half earnings, having made an operating profit of DM827m ($553m). In the first half of 1995 Germany's biggest industrial firm reported losses of DM613m.
<p><b>Boeing </b>will increase production of its new 777 airliner in 1997 and add another 5,000 workers this year, taking to 13,200 the number of new jobs for 1996, a 13% increase.</p>
<p><h2>Burgeoning</h2></p>
<p><p>After a tense few days in which a Virginia court backed American names (investors) disgruntled with the &#163;3.2 billion ($5 billion) recovery plan formulated by <b>Lloyd's of London</b>, an appeals court in Baltimore dismissed the injunction, leaving the way clear at last for the insurance market to press ahead with its reconstruction. More than 90% of the 34,000 names worldwide have accepted the deal.
<p>More consolidation in reinsurance: <b>Swiss Re</b> became the world's largest life and health reinsurer with the &#163;1.7 billion ($2.7 billion) purchase of Mercantile &amp; General, the insurance arm of Britain's Prudential. Munich Re fell to second place despite its $3.3 billion purchase earlier this month of American Re.
<p><b>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)</b><br>Corporate confidence in Japan dipped in the latest quarter, just when analysts thought optimists might at last outnumber pessimists. Bond yields and the Nikkei both dropped. Consumer confidence in America, reached a six-year high.
<p>An acquisitive American life insurance and financial-services group, <b>Conseco</b>, bought two more insurance companies, American Travellers and Capitol American Financial, plus the remaining shares in two others, American Life and Bankers Life, in a move costing more than $1.7 billion.
<p><b>Russia's stockmarket watchdog</b>, the Federal Securities Commission, was demoted by presidential decree from a ministerial-level body to a state committee at the beck and call of the finance ministry.
<p><p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
