<html><head><title>The quality of Korean mercy</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>



<h1><center>The quality of Korean mercy</center></h1>
<p><b>The trial and sentencing of South Korea's former leaders raise some hard questions--not least for authoritarians in the rest of Asia</b></p>


HOLDING hands as they stood together in the dock, Chun Doo Hwan and Roh Tae Woo, two former generals and leaders of South Korea, were sentenced respectively to death and to 22.75 years in prison this week. That both men may yet be pardoned will not erase the discomfort many people felt at the sight of two once powerful men humbled in this way.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The sharpest discomfort will have been felt by other authoritarian rulers in Asia, who must wonder whether one day they too may face a reckoning in court. But even those pressing for democracy and the rule of law have reason to ponder events in South Korea. Several questions hang over the trial. Was this really justice in action? Even if the two men were guilty as charged, is it really wise or fair for an emerging democracy to treat former rulers with such harshness? And what impact will the sentences have on the transition to more liberal government elsewhere in Asia?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On the first two questions--about the justness and wisdom of the trial--the answers must be equivocal (see <a href="as1.html">page</a>). There was a strong element of political expediency in the decision to prosecute the two men. Kim Young Sam, South Korea's current president, had originally said he would let history judge his predecessors. Many suspect that he changed his mind not out of a sudden desire to see history's wrongs righted but because he feared that Messrs Chun and Roh were considering a political comeback.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sympathy for the two old generals does not rest on that alone. The two men presided over a period of extraordinary economic growth, which made their countrymen significantly better off. Mr Roh even smoothed the transition to democracy, won a free election in 1987 and then, in 1992, stepped gracefully aside to allow a civilian to take his place as president--the very civilian who authorised his prosecution. In other words, the two men were not all bad. Some people argue that, whatever their misdemeanours, it would have been better to forgive and forget.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet Messrs Chun and Roh were not innocent men and their conviction has established an important principle: that South Korea's leaders are accountable before the law. Both men were convicted of offences--such as treason and accepting huge bribes--that would be crimes under any conceivable government. And though they did their countries much good, as well as some harm, it is hard to argue that the two men do not deserve any bringing to book. The Kwangju massacre in 1980, which solidified Mr Chun's hold on power, claimed at least 200 victims. There is clearly a demand, both from the families of the victims of Kwangju, and within South Korea as a whole, for some kind of accounting for the events of 1979-80. Such an accounting may help to draw a line under the years of military rule and the traditions of political corruption those events sustained. The good deeds of the generals can only be mitigating factors--and in fact it looks as though such considerations will lead to pardons for both of them.
</p><p><b>The lessons for dictators</b>
<br>The question of the impact of events in South Korea on the rest of Asia is more troubling. The current South Korean government can reasonably say that such intangible calculations are not really its concern. Its main preoccupation is to help its people to come to terms with the country's troubled recent history and, at the same time, to establish civilian government and the rule of law.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But it is probably true that neither the generals who run Myanmar, nor President Suharto in Indonesia, nor the Communist Party in China, will be encouraged to move towards democracy by the fate of Messrs Chun and Roh. After all, Mr Roh ceded power as gracefully as any military man can. Now he has fallen victim to the process of democratisation that he helped to foster. The moral drawn by Asia's nervous dictators may well be that, when democrats are at the door, lock them up rather than usher them in.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the sake of the rest of Asia, it might have been better if the South Koreans had followed the South African model: establish a commission to examine the past, and try to strike a balance between justice and reconciliation. Still, it is unlikely that, even if the South Koreans had behaved with more restraint, assorted rulers in Jakarta or Beijing would then have cheerfully ceded power. And the broader lesson of South Korea is that ordinary Asians, despite their alleged preference for strong leadership, will also increasingly demand--and get--accountable government and the rule of law. That, after all, is what was being demanded at Kwangju.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
