<html><head><title>The mighty fall in South Korea</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/as.gif" width=67 height=26  alt="Asia">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>The mighty fall in South Korea</h1>

<p>AS IF resigned to their fate, Chun Doo Hwan and Roh Tae Woo--two former presidents of South Korea and army colleagues since their days at military academy--trudged into court on August 26th, holding hands and wearing prison uniform, to hear their sentences. There were no gasps of surprise, just an eerie silence as the judge wrapped up his two-hour statement and sentenced Mr Chun to death on charges of mutiny and treason for his role in the military coup of 1980 and the subsequent massacre of demonstrators in Kwangju. For his part in these events, Mr Roh was given a sentence of 22.5 years in prison. Outside in the drizzling rain, 600 riot police edged nervously around as a couple of dozen protesters yelled abuse and demanded a still harsher sentence for Mr Roh.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Apart from their crimes against the state, the two former presidents were also found guilty of receiving huge amounts in bribes from industry while in office, and were fined more than 500 billion won ($610m) between them. Both have until September 2nd to appeal against their sentences. Thirteen of their former military cronies were also given jail terms of four to ten years for crimes perpetrated during the coup and subsequent crackdown. A dozen of the ex-presidents' former aides were given prison sentences for their roles in collecting the bribes, along with nine businessmen who were found guilty of bribery.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The eight-month court case was supposed to heal the wounds that have festered since the tragic events of 16 years ago. After the assassination in 1979 of President Park Chung Hee (himself a former general) by his security chief, Mr Chun used his position in the army to snuff out the chance of political liberalisation. Instead, supported by Mr Roh, he seized power and proceeded to expand martial law throughout South Korea, claiming that the communist regime in North Korea was planning to take advantage of the chaos and massing its troops for an attack.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The invasion from the North never came. But the coup set off student protests in the south-western city of Kwangju in May 1980. The army's bloody crackdown there officially left some 200 protesters dead. Unofficial estimates run much higher. But, faced with further widespread protests in 1987, Mr Chun resisted the temptation to resort to force again. Instead, he eventually stepped aside in favour of his prot&eacute;g&eacute;, Mr Roh. Benefiting from a split in the opposition, Mr Roh won South Korea's first free presidential election in 1987.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;During his five-year term in office, Mr Roh won credit from his countrymen (as well as the court last week) for bolstering democracy and for improving South Korea's standing abroad. The country played host to the Olympic Games and joined the United Nations during his time in power. His friend and mentor, Mr Chun, was exiled to a distant temple in disgrace as part of a deal the two men struck in a bid to end the continuing criticism of their mutiny and suppression of civil rights. In 1992 Mr Roh stepped down, and Kim Young Sam was elected as South Korea's first civilian president in 32 years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Roh, and even Mr Chun, might eventually have been forgiven their military sins by a country grown rich and successful during their stewardship, had it not been for a scandal that broke last year. The hidden millions that Mr Roh had raised from various captains of industry came to light in October and quickly implicated Mr Chun. With both men behind bars, President Kim moved swiftly to get a special law passed that prevented the country's statute of limitations on the 1980 coup and the Kwangju incident from taking effect. The new investigation into the two incidents launched by President Kim led to the trial that started last December and culminated in this week's sentencing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The guilty verdicts were a foregone conclusion, although some were taken aback by the severity of the sentences on the ex-generals. Even more surprising were the tough prison terms received by the leading businessmen for bribery. Kim Woo Choong, the founder and chairman of Daewoo, and the heads of three other <i>chaebol</i> (industrial conglomerates), were given jail sentences of two years or more. The chairman of the Samsung group, Lee Kun Hee, had his two-year sentence suspended. All of them remain free for the time being. Daewoo's Mr Kim has just gone to China to open a new hotel and to Eastern Europe to visit his new car factories.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Big business has been rattled by the turn of events. The South Korean courts have traditionally been lenient towards businessmen charged with corruption. Their contribution to the country's prosperity has tended to excuse most misdeeds. Some believe the government is spoiling for a fight, blaming business (hypocritically) for the corruption that has long permeated politics. There is even talk that, if he avoids jail, Mr Kim may have to resign his position as chairman of Daewoo and go into exile abroad. He has run into trouble with the government on several occasions since he threatened to run against Kim Young Sam in the 1992 election.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The whole trial has been shot through with accusations of political opportunism. Government critics claim the case against the two former presidents was only brought to strengthen President Kim's influence before the general election last March. Cynics have also pointed to the hurried way the case against the two ex-presidents was mounted just as serious questions were beginning to be asked about illicit payoffs that President Kim is said to have received from Mr Roh to finance his own presidential campaign. Such questions remain to be answered.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Certainly, the prosecutions of Mr Chun and Mr Roh have helped President Kim crush the factions within the ruling party that remained loyal to the two ex-presidents. That should help him when picking a successor to run for the presidency in 1997. To ensure that he does not suffer a similar fate as his two predecessors, President Kim needs to have a friendly face in the presidential palace when he steps down. But he also needs at least to give the appearance of having handled the recent trial with dignity and fairness.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No one expects Mr Chun to be hanged. His lawyers are preparing his appeal, a procedure that could take the courts until next May to decide. But what if Mr Chun decides not to appeal? In his final statement in court, Mr Chun said he expected no mercy and wanted only to be the "last victim of political revenge" . Against their lawyers' advice, both Mr Chun and Mr Roh have privately hinted that they are ready to let their sentences stand. If that is what they decide to do, President Kim might then have a serious problem on his hands.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?841446000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="eu1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
