<html><head><title>An easy-going lot</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>The National Lottery</b></p>
<h1>An easy-going lot</h1>

<p>WHEREAS the regulators of the privatised utilities are getting a reputation for being tough on the companies they supervise, Oflot--the National Lottery regulator--is looking like a bit of a soft touch. Last month, the House of Commons Public Accounts Committee said Peter Davis, director-general of Oflot, had made "serious errors of judgment" in accepting free flights from one of the firms in the Camelot consortium, which runs the lottery. And on August 30th a report from the National Audit Office (<font size=-1>NAO</font>) criticised Oflot for being slow to carry out checks on some of Camelot's operations, and for failing to ensure that Camelot's computers are secure.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>NAO</font> says that, apart from a few initial checks, it took Oflot more than a year from the lottery's launch in November 1994 to start work on a system for monitoring whether cheques drawn on Camelot's prize-payment account were all being paid to genuine winners. Progress has been slow in other areas too. Oflot is supposed to carry out an assessment of Camelot's marketing every six months, but no such assessment had been carried out almost a year after the lottery was launched.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If the prizes won on the lottery fall short of an annual target laid down in Camelot's licence, the firm eventually has to hand over the difference to the funds that distribute a proportion of all lottery takings to a variety of good causes. Until then, it earns interest on the money. The <font size=-1>NAO</font> points out that this added &#163;6m to Camelot's profits of &#163;77.5m in the year to March. Last year, the House of Commons National Heritage Committee said Camelot should be made to hand over the interest as well. Camelot argues that this would require a complete renegotiation of its licence, and Oflot seems happy to accept this.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The <font size=-1>NAO</font> also points out that the lottery's computers have crashed three times since it was launched. Punters' money was apparently not put at risk, but the report complains that no tests have been carried out to see what would happen if someone deliberately overloaded the computers or fed them false instructions to try to breach their security. Camelot says it has already done tests that exceed British Standard 7799 (which covers computer security) and that the software it uses has been widely employed in other countries' lotteries, and has so far proved resilient. Oflot accepts Camelot's assurances, and says it cannot see how the tests the <font size=-1>NAO</font> is calling for would make much difference.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The lottery has been a huge success, has raised larger sums than expected for a wide range of good causes, and has had no breaches of security. But Mr Davis would be wrong to dismiss the <font size=-1>NAO</font> report as nit-picking. If the public became worried that lottery money was at risk from computer hackers, or that Camelot was making an unreasonably big profit, there could be a big drop in the number of people taking part. Perhaps it is time for Oflot to follow in the footsteps of the electricity and gas regulators, and start taking a tougher line.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
