<html><head><title>Trimming the fat</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Local councils</b></p>
<h1>Trimming the fat</h1>

<p>IN THE run-up to the budget in November, local councils will once more be pressing the government to let them increase their spending by more than the rate of inflation. Councils in England, which currently spend about &#163;50 billion a year, have already asked for permission to increase this by 5% next year. The government, desperate to keep public-sector borrowing under control, is unlikely to agree. Instead it may suggest to councils that they take a closer look at a series of recent reports by the Audit Commission, which monitors councils' finances. These suggest that there is plenty of scope for savings.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The commission's most recent report, published earlier this month, is a study of the lessons garnered from audits of councils carried out in the fiscal year 1994-95. It concludes that far too many council staff are calling in sick, "an indicator of poor morale and an opportunity for significant savings". The commission found that one council in London (it does not say which) cut &#163;500,000 from its pay bill simply by monitoring absences due to "sickness" more closely. The potential savings across the country from such a measure could add up to tens of millions of pounds.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The commission also says that fraud against local councils is on the increase, and urges that councils try harder to prevent it, rather than merely detecting it after the event. Auditors identified specific cases of fraud involving &#163;46m in 1994-95, although the commission believes the actual amount is far higher. A study published in January by the Department of Social Security reckoned that fraudulent claims for housing benefit (which is administered by local councils) may come to as much as &#163;1 billion a year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Last year another highly critical report from the Audit Commission said that councils were spending &#163;500m too much on pay, especially senior officials' pay. The report argued that, when councils' budgets are trimmed, "senior <font size=-1>HQ</font> staff often escape unscathed while the council freezes vacancies or cuts the number of front-line staff." In some councils, a junior librarian has eight levels of management above him. In the leaner ones, there are just four.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As a result of such poor management, councils' bills for white-collar staff rose almost twice as fast as average earnings in Britain between 1987 and 1993. Last year's report caused a rumpus, but its estimates were probably cautious. They were based on the assumption that councils could cut their pay bills by 5%; a few councils that had made a determined effort saved 10%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reluctance of many councils to get rid of their staff and to hand work over to private firms means that they are unlikely to be getting the best value for money. A study published on August 30th by the Institute for Fiscal Studies, an independent think-tank, looked at how the cost of collecting household rubbish changed after the government forced councils to invite tenders from private firms to do the job. It found that, four years after compulsory tendering was introduced, those councils whose own workforce won the contract had cut their costs by 10%. Those who had given the contract to private firms were saving 20%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In spite of councils' protests, the government is pressing ahead with the expansion of compulsory tendering: one of the prime targets for this is councils' finance departments, which cost about &#163;2 billion a year to run. It is likely that a large proportion of this could be saved. For instance, the Audit Commission has found that it takes just two people to handle 100,000 invoices a year at some council offices; in others the same job is being done by 14 people.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One source of possible savings has so far received little attention: councils' spending on property. Birmingham council announced this month that it wanted to cut the office space it occupies by 20% this year, by encouraging more staff to work from home or to share desks. Housing-repair staff and hygiene inspectors are likely to be among the first to start working from home. The council aims to save &#163;2.5m in total over the next three years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why are so many councils hesitating to make the most of the scope they have for cutting costs? Almost all of the efficiency gains would mean job losses, and councillors have traditionally seen themselves as important providers of employment in their local area. Council staff are highly unionised, and would not accept big job cuts without a fight.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Moreover, councils suspect, with some justification, that the more they save now, the smaller the grant the government will give them in future. Since government grants provide more than 80% of councils' income, this is a considerable disincentive to making the hard decisions needed to achieve big savings.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Britain badly needs a better way to pay for local services. The Labour Party has said it wants to restore local-government powers, but has not said much about the increased financial accountability, and autonomy, this would entail. One of its few specific proposals on the matter is to abolish compulsory competitive tendering while requiring that councils "obtain best value for local residents" --an intriguing combination. After the poll-tax fiasco, there seems to be little enthusiasm in any political party for another set of drastic reforms.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
