<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><b>Absolutely finished</b> &nbsp;The 15-year marriage of the Prince and Princess of Wales was formally ended. A clerk from the prince's solicitors took his application to the back office of a London court where it was rubber-stamped with the words "decree absolute".</p>
<p><b>Evil eye</b> &nbsp;The Advertising Standards Authority told the Conservative Party to make no further use of a poster which depicted Tony Blair, the Labour leader, with demonic eyes. The advertising watchdog said the Tories were wrong to portray Mr Blair in an adverse or sinister way without his permission.</p>
<p><b>Discipline</b> &nbsp;Loyalist terrorist leaders in Ulster publicly threatened to kill two of their own men for opposing the loyalist ceasefire.</p>
<p><b>Help</b> &nbsp;The government said a leaked Benefits Agency document, which seemed to show that it misled Parliament over the possible closure of a telephone help-line for people in urgent need of welfare payments, was wrong; and that <font size=-1>MP</font>s were correctly told that no decision has yet been made.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>VHS on the NHS</b> &nbsp;The Department of Health won an injunction halting sales of a video showing 27 operations. Its distributors say the money they paid to the surgeons went to medical charities and the National Health Service.</p>
<p><b>Broadcast news</b> &nbsp;John Birt, director-general of the <font size=-1>BBC</font>, called for the television licence fee to be increased by more than inflation, and Michael Grade, chief executive of Channel 4, said he would fight rumoured plans by the government to privatise the station.</p>
<p><b>First loss</b> &nbsp;WH Smith, a bookseller, reported the first loss in its 204-year history--a deficit of &#163;195m.</p>
<p><b>Beer deal</b> &nbsp;Bass bought the brewing interests of Allied Domecq for &#163;200m, thus regaining its position as Britain's largest brewer.</p>
<p><b>Baring all</b> &nbsp;Aberdeen College advertised for nude models for its art classes, and was overwhelmed with applicants.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
