<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p>

<p><h2>Buba relents</h2>
<p><p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>The <b>German Bundesbank </b>trimmed its key short-term repo rate by 0.3% to 3%. The news helped to relieve pressure on the French franc, encouraging the Bank of France also to cut its intervention rate by 0.2% to 3.35%. The Federal Reserve had earlier decided to leave American short-term rates unchanged.
<p>Shares in <b>tobacco companies</b> fell yet again, on news that President Clinton was about to approve the Food and Drug Administration's proposals to regulate tobacco as a drug.</p>
<p><h2>Latin foray</h2></p>
<p><p><b>Chrysler</b>, the smallest of America's big three car makers, is venturing further into Latin America. It has announced a new $315m factory in Brazil to assemble pick-up trucks and build diesel engines, and another $65m investment to expand its $100m car plant in Argentina.
<p>Germany's smallest car maker, <b>Porsche</b>, which is looking for a partner to help finance a move away from luxury sports cars and into upmarket sports utilities, is talking to Mercedes-Benz. For Mercedes, which is about to produce a sports utility of its own in Alabama for America's buoyant market for such vehicles, the benefits are unclear--other than to take up slack capacity in some of its factories.
<p>First-half profits at <b>Volvo</b>, Sweden's biggest car maker, fell by 28% to SKr3.9 billion ($590m). The firm's car unit seems to be turning round; but its overall results were hit by losses at its American lorry-making arm.
<p>The Dutch government confirmed that Samsung Aerospace of South Korea is again visiting The Hague to discuss buying <b>Fokker</b>. The aircraft maker collapsed in March after its main shareholder, Deutsche Aerospace, pulled out.</p>
<p><h2>Heir today</h2></p>
<p><p><b>AT&T</b>'s heir-apparent quit suddenly, leaving America's long-distance telephone giant searching for another president and <font size=-1>CEO</font>. Alex Mandl, who was number two in the group for less than a year, was tempted away by the challenge of running a new wireless-communications venture.
<p><b>Coca-Cola's coup</b> in persuading Cisneros Bottling in Venezuela to switch allegiance from <b>PepsiCo</b> has boosted Coca-Cola's 10-15% share of the country's (admittedly small) soft-drinks market to 60%. A stunned PepsiCo said the move by Cisneros was illegal; Cisneros complained that PepsiCo had rejected its expansion plans.
<p>The battle for the <b>Internet </b>heated up further. Ten of America's biggest technology and communications companies agreed to set up a $100m venture-capital fund to finance start-ups developing products that use Java, an Internet programming language. Noticeably absent was Microsoft, which is promoting a competing standard.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Meanwhile, <b>Netscape</b>, which is battling with Microsoft for control of the market for Web browsers, accused the software giant of antitrust violations. It claims that Microsoft is charging some <font size=-1>PC</font> makers more for the Windows 95 operating system if they include Netscape's browser with their machines.
<p>(See <a href="wtw3.gif">chart</a>)<br><b>America's trade deficit</b> (in goods and services) with China overtook its deficit with Japan for the first time. The June figures showed that the deficit with China rose by nearly 9% in the month to $3.33 billion. The deficit with Japan grew only 3.6%, to $3.24 billion, down from the $5.34 billion it stood at a year ago. Overall, America's trade gap in June was some 24% narrower than a year earlier, at $8.11 billion.
<p>Pre-tax profits at <b>BSkyB</b> jumped by 66% to &#163;257m ($398m) in the year to end-June, with new subscribers rising by 900,000 to 5.5m in Britain and Ireland. The satellite broadcaster's revenues rose 30%, squeaking above &#163;1 billion for the first time.
<p>Germany's <b>Hoechst</b>, through its AgrEvo agrichemical unit, is taking over <b>Plant Genetic Systems </b>in a two-stage deal that values the Dutch-Belgian research group at around DM1 billion ($672m). The deal, said Hoechst, gives it "critical mass" in plant biotechnology, and puts paid to speculation that Hoechst was losing interest in agriculture.
<p><b>Alan Bond</b>, a one-time tycoon who won the America's Cup yacht race for Australia in 1983, was jailed for three years for fraud. The ownership of Manet's painting, "La Promenade" , had been shifted to benefit a private family company to the detriment of Bond Corp. Another former Australian tycoon, John Elliott, was acquitted on charges of defrauding the Elders group.
<p>The break-up of Britain's Thorn <font size=-1>EMI</font> into two separately listed companies brought two different reactions from investors.<b> EMI Group</b> quickly saw its share price leap as investors reckoned the now unencumbered music company was not only a good investment but could also be ripe for a bid. Shares in <b>Thorn</b>, the consumer-rentals side of the business, went the other way.
<p>Two of America's biggest companies in the fast-growing <b>manufactured-homes market </b>are coming together. Champion Enterprises of Michigan is paying about $328m for Dallas-based Redman Industries.
<p>One of the biggest property developers in the world, Texas-based <b>Hines</b>, paid <font size=-1>MACIF</font>, a French insurer, about FFr1.5 billion ($295m) for a 50% stake in seven shopping centres, one of which will be the largest covered mall in Europe.
<p><p>
</p>
