<html><head><title>Wobbly tigers</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>



<h1><center>Wobbly tigers</center></h1>
<p><b>East Asia's economies are experiencing growing pains</b></p>

TO EXCITED onlookers, the East Asian tigers seem to be tiring. Their export growth has slowed. Several are running alarming current-account deficits; some currencies have come under speculative assault. Attacks of political jitters, ranging from Seoul to Jakarta, make matters worse. Some foreign investors are nervously asking whether more Mexican meltdowns could be in the making (see <a href="fn1.html">page</a>). Others have concluded that the miracle years, at least, are over.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Recent figures lend the pessimists some plausibility. Thailand's exports rose only 7% in value in the first half of this year, compared with a 27% rise last year. China's exports have actually fallen. Malaysia and Thailand look like running current-account deficits of 10% and 8% of <font size=-1>GDP</font> respectively this year--similar to the deficit that undid Mexico. Across the region growth forecasts are being whittled down. This is grist to the mill not just of current gloomsters, but also of those who argue that the East Asian "miracle" was always a myth, based not on genuine leaps in efficiency but on huge and unsustainable increases in capital and labour inputs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet the pessimism is premature. In the long run, East Asian growth will almost certainly slow, as economies mature; but that run is still some way off. The tigers' current ills should be temporary, caused in part by weaker demand in the rich world, and in part by easily rectified policy mistakes at home. Sluggish demand in Europe and a stock overhang in America have cut demand for electronic goods--a big chunk of East Asian exports--just as over-capacity has depressed semiconductor prices. The recent rise in the dollar, to which many Asian currencies are in effect pegged, has eroded the tigers' competitiveness. Yet even after these have been reflected in downward growth revisions, East Asia will remain by far the world's fastest-growing region.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More disturbing than any of these ills has been the intemperate response of some governments. The Malaysian prime minister has hinted at import controls on non-essential goods. South Korea and Thailand have begun official campaigns to discourage luxury imports. Such prescriptions treat the symptoms, not the disease, and they could have dangerous side-effects in economies that are highly dependent on free trade. Ministers would do better to tighten their monetary and fiscal belts than to toss out their Italian ties.
</p><p><b>Chasing their tails</b>
<br>Two key distinctions between East Asia and Mexico are that Asians save more than Mexicans, and that their current-account deficits reflect an investment boom, not a spending spree. Yet investment is not always good (any more than consumption is always bad). Foreign-financed investment will pay only if it boosts countries' long-term export potential and so generates enough income to repay the debt. Several current projects--Malaysia's new administrative capital or the world's tallest building in Kuala Lumpur among them--look unlikely to do that.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even more seriously, exchange-rate policy has often undermined monetary control by making it hard to raise interest rates. Most East Asian governments have held their exchange rates low to keep exports competitive. But heavy inflows of capital in recent years have caused rapid monetary expansion, which has in turn triggered inflation or higher imports. Easier money has also facilitated unwise investment.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The correct cure is for governments to run even tighter fiscal policies to dampen domestic demand, and to unshackle their currencies. Thanks to current market nervousness, some currencies, such as the Thai baht, would probably fall at first. But in the medium term they would be likely to rise; unlike the Mexican peso in 1994, most East Asian currencies are undervalued. That may sound counterintuitive when their economies are running massive current-account deficits, but these reflect an excess of investment over domestic savings, not an overvalued exchange rate.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What about East Asian governments' fears that exchange-rate appreciation could further hammer their exports? Japan shows that this need not happen. Its exchange rate has risen strongly over the past two decades, with, until recently, few ill-effects on exports. Indeed, it is normal for emerging economies that are seeing rapid productivity growth to experience a rise in their real exchange rates. This can come about via higher inflation or, better, through an appreciation in the nominal exchange rate. Hobbled tigers may easily trip over; free tigers are less likely to.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?840841200,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
