</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Modesty ablaze</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="sf.gif"  alt="Special">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Modesty ablaze</h1>

<p><b>In a new book this week, and at the Democratic convention next, Bill Clinton is putting his grand vision for leading America into the next millennium. Translated into practical policy, his agenda looks unambitious</b></p>


<p>NOT for Bill Clinton a quiet family gathering to mark his 50th birthday. No, on the eve of his birthday last Sunday the president celebrated with cocktails for 200 at the Sheraton in New York, a glitzy gala at Radio City (linked by satellite to parties at 89 other places), and finished up with a modest $10,000-a-plate dinner for 700 at the Waldorf-Astoria. There was a jumbo cake and a jumble of celebrities--Whoopi Goldberg, Tony Bennett, Aretha Franklin, Kenny Rogers, Shania Twain and many more. There was also the obligatory Clintonian tear, shed as his elementary-school teacher from Hot Springs, Arkansas recalled how she gave a busybody Clinton, aged seven, a <font size=-1>C</font> for conduct.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Here, you might think, was a fitting reflection of what America has learnt to associate with Clintonism: entertaining and irrepressible, yet prone to excess and full of baby-boomer self-indulgence. And inseparable from politics. The festivities raised an estimated $10m for the Democratic Party. But Mr Clinton is hard to pigeon-hole. Lest his partying seem a tad too ostentatious, he humbly spent his actual birthday with his vice-president rebuilding a burnt-down black church in Tennessee.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The president's half-century is emblematic in a subtler way. At 50, he looks different from the boyish Mr Fizz who came to the White House effervescent with energy and ideas; the face bears more lines, the hair is greyer, the eyes seem more sunken. He jokes about being eligible for membership of the American Association for Retired Persons. He reflects wistfully that being 50 means "more yesterdays than tomorrows". Ironically, the president (as well as his much older challenger) is having to contemplate the limits of age.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And his presidency has had to adjust to the age of limits. The office has given Mr Clinton a painful lesson in the politics of scarcity. He came to the White House bearing too many promises that he could not deliver. He was the self-advertised agent of change who became a veto-wielding change-resister, bent on restraining Republican revolutionaries. He championed a 1,400-page health-care reform, one of the greatest expansions of federal power since the New Deal, only to declare the era of big government over and to end the federal guarantee of welfare for the poor that had existed since before he was born.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Three powerful constraints have been at work. First, Mr Clinton won in 1992 with only 43% of the popular vote, a relatively weak mandate. It should have led him to reach across the party divide to build support for his proposals. Instead, Democrats in Congress persuaded him even before he reached the White House that they could work without Republican help. Mr Clinton's reward for overreaching was the rejection of his health-care plan and a fist in the face from voters, who in 1994 gave Republicans control of both houses of Congress for the first time in 40 years.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hence the second constraint: a Republican-run Congress that has largely set the agenda since early 1995. Mr Clinton turned out to be rather adept in his new role of counter-puncher to the Republicans. Still, to paraphrase the president, the era of big Clinton proposals was over.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Big proposals anyway tend not to come cheap, and in deficit-cutting times money is hard to find. The federal budget is the third big constraint on Mr Clinton. Once the federal government has paid for defence, debt interest and its commitments to health care for the elderly and other "entitlements", less than one-fifth of the budget remains for discretionary spending. Not much there for a would-be government activist like Mr Clinton to play with.
</p><p><b>Clinton being Clinton</b>
<br>All this should help to concentrate the minds of people puzzling over the sort of president Mr Clinton would be if he were to win another term in November (as polls still predict, see <a href="sf1.gif">chart</a>). In Washington, it is fashionable to begin such speculation by wondering how Mr Clinton would behave when, for once, he no longer had to think about his next election. He has been running for some office or other ever since, as a 16-year-old, he worked the dormitories at Camp Robinson in Arkansas to be elected one of his state's "senators" to the Boys Nation in Washington, <font size=-1>DC</font>. This year Mr Clinton never actually bothered to make a formal announcement of his re-election bid; it hardly seemed necessary for a president often caricatured as running a "permanent campaign" anyway.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If he wins, runs the speculation, could Clinton finally be Clinton? And what would that mean? Over the past four years he has variously seemed a New Democrat, an Old Democrat, and even an imitation Republican. He has been ill-disciplined and tightly controlled, a reformer and protector of the status quo. Republicans fantasise that an unfettered Clinton would be a liberal (to non-Americans, a social democrat) like his wife, Hillary, or his deputy chief of staff, Harold Ickes. Others fondly believe that he would be an unabashed centrist like Dick Morris, a consultant who has masterminded his return to favour.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such speculation is fun but largely fruitless (given the difficulty of tying down a man who is fraternising with stars one day and banging nails into church beams the next). It also misses the point, which is that even a Clinton free of campaign calculus would in all probability face much the same constraints that have shaped his first four years in the White House. In a three-way race, polls now show him gravitating back towards 43% of the vote. The chances that the Democrats will recapture both houses of Congress are slim (see <a href="am1.html">page</a>). And the budget arithmetic remains as stubborn as ever.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So detective work on a second-term Clinton starts with these constraints and then looks for other clues. Clues come from the pattern of other second-term presidencies, from Mr Clinton's record in his first term, from his agenda for another and from his new book "Between Hope and History" (Times Books). Taken together, they point to a curious hybrid, a mixture of Millennium Bill, orator-in-chief for a dawning "age of possibility", and Modesty Bill, born-again incrementalist in an age of constraint.
</p><p><b>If at first you succeed, try again</b></b>
<br>From George Washington to Ronald Reagan, the experience of presidential second terms has often been poor. The pattern is of disappointment or downright failure: re-elected Eisenhower achieved little; Nixon resigned in disgrace; the Reagan revolution happened in his first year. It is all too easy to see how a second-term Clinton could conform to the pattern.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Scandals such as Watergate and Iran-Contra are all too common in second terms. And with Whitewater and several similar matters unresolved, it does not take much to imagine a re-elected Clinton engulfed by scandal. The Clintonites hope they might have got some of these second-term blues out of the way in their first term. But since an independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, is still sifting through the evidence of Whitewater and the rest, that hope may be vain. The problem that scandal reveals is often hubris, a sense among people in a re-elected administration that they can now do anything they want--like pack the Supreme Court, to take the example of Franklin Roosevelt. Who would think the Clinton White House to be hubris-free?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are other pitfalls. Staff turnover tends to be high, and sometimes highly disruptive. The Reagan White House lost much of its effectiveness with the appointment of Donald Regan as chief of staff. The day after Nixon's re-election in 1972, his chief of staff, H. R. Haldeman, demanded letters of resignation from all cabinet officers and sub-cabinet appointees. It would be no surprise to see a big exodus of exhausted veterans of the first Clinton term.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Second-term presidents are wont to think increasingly about their place in history, and accordingly gravitate more and more towards foreign policy. That has already begun to happen with Mr Clinton, prompted by the loss of initiative in domestic policy to the Republican Congress. Conventional wisdom says second-termers have about two years to get any serious domestic legislation done, after which they become lame ducks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That is awkward, for second-termers may lack the agenda and the verve for swift action. Most are returned to office not for what they promise to do but for what they have already done. As Chuck Jones of the University of Wisconsin observes, the past three re-elections (Eisenhower, Nixon and Reagan) have been strikingly similar: they were "approval elections", in which the president wins overwhelmingly while an opposing Congress is also voted back. Now, voters seem to like the job done by President Clinton and the Republican Congress, after initial stand-offs and government shutdowns. In a recent poll by <font size=-1>USA </font>Today/<font size=-1>CNN</font>/Gallup, 64% said they counted Mr Clinton's first term a success.
</p><p><b>The record so far</b>
<br>History, then, suggests that, even if he is re-elected, Mr Clinton's finest achievements may already be behind him. No matter. In "Clinton: The President They Deserve" (Fourth Estate, forthcoming), Martin Walker of Britain's <i>Guardian</i> newspaper argues that Mr Clinton has already achieved nothing less than a post-cold-war reordering of America's policy consensus. During his presidency, Mr Walker claims, Democrats and Republicans have come round to broadly similar views about leaner and meaner government at home, and free trade abroad. Mr Clinton read and (not surprisingly) admired Mr Walker's book.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The depth of this consensus is open to argument. So is whether Democrats or Republicans deserve most credit for it. But what is certain is that over the past four years Mr Clinton has come to adopt (or co-opt) some core Republican policies.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;True, the process has often been chaotic. Mr Clinton campaigned as a social conservative but soon got bogged down in issues such as gays in the military and political correctness in cabinet appointments. For too long, the Clinton White House was a place of rambling meetings, run by a president who talked too much, tried to please too many people and micro-managed too many decisions.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;His policy reversals were numerous and ignominious. Having promised a middle-class tax cut, he raised taxes (only to let slip long afterwards that he thought he had raised them too much). He promoted a $30-billion stimulus package, which he later privately derided as "pure pork". (Thankfully, the pig was killed by Republicans in Congress.) His welfare reform arrived too late and, he subsequently confessed, was too weak. After projecting budget deficits as far as the eye could see, he suddenly converted to the Republican cause of a balanced budget by 2002. Above all, he saw health-care reform--the country's most urgent priority, he said, and his central piece of legislation--go down in flames.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet Mr Clinton has also shown himself to be resilient and capable of learning on the job. In foreign affairs, he has grown into the job through his stumble into Haiti (a tentative success) and his better-late-than-never intervention in Bosnia (ditto). He bravely defied public opinion to come to Mexico's aid in 1995. His peacemaking efforts in the Middle East and Northern Ireland have run into trouble, but he has gained kudos for trying. Few would have thought it when he came to power--and fewer still after America's public humiliation in Somalia--but it is no longer absurd to talk of Mr Clinton as a foreign-policy president.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At home, he has discovered a gift for sounding presidential at times of national tragedy, such as the bombing in Oklahoma City and the crash of <font size=-1>TWA </font>flight 800. He has learnt to use the presidential bully pulpit to talk eloquently about social issues, especially race. And over time, with both Democratic and Republican Congresses, he has signed a swathe of legislation, ranging from gun controls to health-care portability, and rises in the earned-income tax credit and the minimum wage.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The result is that Mr Clinton's record of achievement so far looks better than that of his Democratic presidential predecessor, Jimmy Carter. Three big pieces of legislation stand out. True, two of them--the passage of the North American Free-Trade Agreement (<font size=-1>NAFTA</font>) in 1993 and the recent welfare reform ("ending welfare as we know it")--were Republican-inspired and involved the president in an agonising confrontation with his own political supporters. But it took Mr Clinton to deliver enough Democratic votes for these measures, much as it took Nixon to go to China. The third, the budget battle of 1993, Mr Clinton won by the thinnest possible margin against unified Republican opposition. It was the basis of a fiscally prudent macroeconomic strategy that has paid off.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Under the Clinton administration, the budget deficit has shrunk by more than half and (with a little help from American enterprise and Alan Greenspan's Fed) the economy has grown steadily, while inflation has remained in check. Americans have created more than 10m new jobs and unemployment, 7.1% of the workforce when Mr Clinton came to power, is down to 5.4%. The stockmarket has soared and the "misery index"--the unemployment, inflation and interest rates combined--is the lowest for nearly three decades.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is a decent record, but one that leaves Mr Clinton curiously short of ideas for the next four years. He has become the don't-rock-the-boat candidate, a bulwark against Republican excess. He has been criss-crossing the country with a collection of small but popular initiatives, promoting school uniforms or youth curfews, or brokering deals that give free cellular telephones to neighbourhood-watch schemes or give parents more control over what their children see on television. Little presidential initiatives seem to go down big: Mr Clinton's espousal of family leave (rules requiring firms to give parents time off for say, taking their children to the doctor) have been immensely popular.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So the Democratic Party he leads calls for smaller government and for a "moderate, achievable, commonsense agenda". In the age of limits, Mr Clinton has scaled himself back to the point where he no longer has any Big Idea. He is Modesty Bill.
</p><p><b>The agenda</b>
<br>That is not the way the president presents himself, of course. At the Democratic convention, he will bundle up his little ideas into something grander, complete with the vision thing. Happily for him, a second term would take him into 2001. Enter Millennium Bill, ready to define the quality of life Americans want in the 21st century.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And what might that be? Peace and prosperity, apparently. The two are related in the Clintonian vision: peace abroad requires a robust American economy. So a second term would see Mr Clinton galloping after various peace-making initiatives and adding new ones where opportunity arose, say, in Cyprus (presumably, he will have a more vigorous foreign-policy team to help him do this).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As for prosperity, in his new book, Mr Clinton reiterates his familiar mantra: "opportunity, responsibility, community". In so far as this meant anything in the first term, it boiled down to putting America's macro-economy into some sort of order. The second term, says the president's spokesman, Michael McCurry, would be about the micro-economy--about pay cheques and the details that affect "real" living standards.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The budget-balancing effort would continue, but education--which White House officials dub the key to higher living standards--would be at the heart of Clinton-2. Here the president has a blizzard of proposals: a $1,500 tax credit to help give all Americans the chance of at least two years in college; more money for public-school infrastructure and for pre-school programmes; encouragement for schemes that put computers in classrooms and keep schools safe.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Sensible as this sounds, there is only so much that a president can do for education, which is mainly the responsibility of state and local governments. The federal government controls only 6% of America's education budget. Mr Clinton's own Treasury Department reckons that the best way to improve living standards for the middle classes is to have policies--such as further trade liberalisation--which make sense for the economy as a whole.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Clinton might go for a bit more incremental health-care reform. He would like to promote portable pensions and campaign-finance reform (especially if Ross Perot, a third-party candidate, runs strongly on the issue). But overall it is the modesty of the once-expansive Mr Clinton's agenda that is so striking.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Will he be content for things to stay that way? The activist in him (and in Hillary) will surely seek outlets. If the era of big government is over, for example, might he not explore the possibilities of "smart" government? He has talked of "a different kind of government activism", of "rule-making", of a president's scope for doing "an awful lot of things by executive action" . The danger in this is that the president would revert to the sort of busybody behaviour that earned him a <font size=-1>C</font> for conduct back in second grade. He might become a meddler burdening his country with rules that cost money and, perhaps, intrude on civil liberties.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;An alternative possibility could lie in another characteristic that affects second-term presidents: the tendency to focus on their place in history. Such long-term thinking has not been much in evidence in Clinton-1. But it might conceivably lead Clinton-2 to begin the necessary debate on reforming Social Security and other entitlements which threaten to cripple American taxpayers in the next century. Launching a reform of such magnitude would be unpopular and politically perilous. That is why it is conspicuously absent from his book. But it is the towering task for a true 21st-century president.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
