<html><head><title>The speaker vanishes</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>The speaker vanishes</h1>


<font size=1>SKIPPACK, PENNSYLVANIA</font>

ONE of the more substantial stories of the recent Republican convention in San Diego was that Newt Gingrich, the radical Speaker of the House, had done a disappearing act. Early this year, after Mr Gingrich's drive to balance the budget had resulted in a government shutdown, polls suggested that his unpopularity surpassed that of Richard Nixon during Watergate. So Mr Gingrich spoke only briefly in San Diego, and not during prime time. The stage was occupied instead by moderate Republicans more likely to charm undecided voters.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Gingrich's vanishing has nothing on Jon Fox, a Republican Congressman from Pennsylvania. On August 15th Mr Fox's campaign manager, Linda Gerhard, told your correspondent that she was not sure where her candidate was. On August 16th she said the same. The next day--a Saturday, and so a prime campaigning day--she professed unchanging ignorance. A couple of hours later, your correspondent attended an agricultural fair in Mr Fox's district. Funnily enough, the missing congressman was there as well, tugging at a poor goat's udders in a speed-milking competition.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Besides dodging the press, Mr Fox has grown wary of meetings with constituents. He generally gets on well with local folk, and was once pronounced (by the <i>Philadelphia Inquirer</i>) "the zen master of constituency service". But Mr Fox is no longer loved by all, thanks to his links to the disappearing Mr Gingrich. Last year Mr Fox supported the speaker's plan to rein in the cost of Medicare, the health programme for the old. Enraged pensioners have heckled Mr Fox, and picketed his meetings. They have driven a steamroller up to his door, a gentle appeal not to steam-roll senior citizens. Now Mr Fox's staff refuses to tell callers where he plans to speak, lest seniors heckle him again. His tea ceremonies have become almost private affairs, with carefully selected audiences.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such Republican disappearances encourage Democrats to talk of winning back the House of Representatives this November. Two years ago, with Mr Gingrich very much in view, the Republicans took control of the House for the first time since 1952. They managed this by turning a host of disparate local campaigns into a national referendum on the unpopular President Clinton. Now, however, Mr Clinton's standing has improved, and his place as public demon has been taken by Mr Gingrich. This is what gives the Democrats their hope of winning back the House--though the Senate, which always kept its distance from Mr Gingrich's schemes, seems likely to remain Republican.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Democrats draw courage from House elections past. The Republicans currently hold 236 seats to the Democrats' 198, so if 20 seats changed hands they would lose their majority. This seems within reach: 12 of the 25 elections since the second world war have produced a swing this size or bigger (see <a href="am1.gif">chart</a>). Moreover, House landslides have a way of reversing themselves. Democrats gained 38 seats in 1964, only to lose 47 seats in 1966; Republicans gained 33 seats in 1980, but lost 26 seats two years later. This time round, 77 Republican congressmen are defending seats in districts that Mr Clinton carried for the Democrats in 1992. A Democratic victory, reversing the Republican landslide of two years ago, seems altogether possible.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Democrats' main targets are the 73 Republicans elected for the first time in 1994. The freshman class voted faithfully for Mr Gingrich's efforts to rein in federal spending and so balance the budget. For this generally honourable effort, they got little thanks: one poll found that 45% of Americans saw them as "extremists". Twenty-nine of the freshmen were elected last time with 55% or less of the vote: their seats would be more than enough to return the House to the Democrats. To press their advantage, the Democrats have linked House freshmen to Mr Gingrich in thousands of television ads. Some of the targets are losing their nerve: Mr Fox's disappearing act does not bespeak much confidence.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;And yet, in an equally telling way, Mr Fox's opponent is also concealing something. His name is Joe Hoeffel, and he too was milking goats at the Saturday fair, a bit more speedily than his rival. Afterwards he munched a hamburger, shook some hands, and headed off to a supermarket that had the two qualities campaigners seek: a lot of people, and only one exit. As shoppers emerged, Hoeffel leaflets were shoved into already overladen hands. You had to read the leaflet very carefully indeed to see that Mr Hoeffel is a Democrat.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This hiding of party label has an important purpose. Registered Republican voters outnumber Democrats in the district by two to one. So, although Mr Fox squeaked home in 1994 with just 49% of the vote--making him one of the freshmen-to-beat if the Democrats' hope of a reverse landslide is to be realised--he still has a huge advantage. Again, Mr Clinton carried the district in 1992, making it one of the 77 that Democrats count as winnable. But the truth is that Mr Clinton's narrow victory that year was largely thanks to the independent candidacy of Ross Perot, who drained the Republican vote. In 1988, in a two-man race, George Bush carried the district comfortably.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In short, Mr Fox's disappearing act illustrates the Democrats' ground for hope, but Mr Hoeffel's subterfuge shows why these hopes may well be disappointed. The Gingrich brigades are unpopular for now, but the dominant current of the past 15 years favours the Republican Party. More and more Americans live in the suburbs, fear crime, resent tax, hate government. This explains why, since 1988, Republicans have signed up 4.2m new members in the 28 states that register voters by party, whereas the Democratic Party has added only 1.4m. It also helps to explain why Republicans held the presidency from 1981 until 1993, and why even the victorious Mr Clinton was backed by only 43% of the voters.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For a time, the Democrats retained control of the House despite this Republican advance. This was because the South, though willing to support Republican presidential candidates, retained strong ties to sitting Democratic congressmen. Gradually, however, these old timers are stepping down or switching parties. Younger Democrats can no longer count on tradition and civil-war memories to carry them to power. Their constituents are letting their social conservatism, not their historical consciousness, guide their choice of party.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This year alone, some 30 Democrats are retiring from the House, six of them from Texas. Republicans reckon this Texodus, together with other upsets in the old Confederate states, gives them a chance to expand their House majority. Democrats may pick up a seat or two in the liberal north-east; the west and mid-west look balanced. John Morgan, a Republican demographer whose predictions in 1994 proved uncannily correct, reckons his party will pick up a total of ten seats or so this November.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;To frustrate this prediction, the unpopularity of Mr Gingrich and his party will have to be extreme. The signs are that it is fading. Bob Dole is doing better in the presidential race, which should encourage more Republican voters to turn out, so helping congressional candidates. In January an <font size=-1>ABC</font>/<i>Washington Post </i>poll, which asked voters which party's candidates they would be more inclined to send to the House, put Republicans nine points behind the Democrats; this month the gap was just three points. Until recently, Democrats were planning to attack House Republicans for not passing any laws. But Republicans have just scored a number of successes, notably welfare reform. They can no longer be accused of running a do-nothing Congress.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For the time being, therefore, the House Republicans are feeling smug. But the past half-century has shown how volatile House elections have been, how mysterious the motives of voters. Outside the single-exit supermarket, Mr Hoeffel handed a leaflet to a muscular, dyed-blond man, who responded with a series of obscenities. For a full minute the car park echoed with his shouts, while his wife looked on nervously. Then the man got into his car, drove back up to the supermarket door and yelled: "I'm voting for you."



