<html><head><title>Trends of the week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<h1>Trends of the week</h1>


<p><b>Bounce:</b> Most polls showed Bob Dole sharply narrowing the gap with Bill Clinton, thanks to a smoothly choreographed Republican convention and his well-received acceptance speech. But Mr Clinton can expect his own bounce at the Democrats' convention in Chicago.
<p><b>Turn-off</b>: Only 17.9m viewers tuned in to the networks' coverage of Bob Dole's speech at the Republican convention, 34% fewer than watched the closing session at the 1992 Houston convention.
<p><b>Air wars</b>: The Dole-Kemp campaign, out of money and outgunned in the airwaves in recent months, at last got its hands on $61.8m of federal funds and started firing back with its first new television advertisement since the spring.
<p><b>Tax wars: </b>Claim and counter-claim over which was the biggest tax increase in history: Clinton's in 1993, says the Dole campaign; Dole's in 1982 (when he chaired the Senate Finance Committee), counter the Clintonites.
<p><b>Nominations: </b>The Green Party picked Ralph Nader, a consumer advocate, as presidential candidate. Mr Nader wants grass-roots activists to challenge America's "corrupted" political duopoly. The new Reform Party, also challenging the duopoly, nominated Ross Perot.
<p><b>Issues of the week:</b> Ecofeminism and earth spirituality, both to be found on the Green agenda, to Mr Nader's intense discomfort.
<p><b>Dubious counting: </b>Ross Perot's votes, Bill Clinton's golf round, Bob Dole's spending cuts.
<p><b>Publishing sensation: </b>"Between Hope and History: Meeting America's Challenges for the 21st Century", by Bill Clinton (co-author of the 1992 blockbuster, "Putting People First" ). A must for wavering voters at $16.95.
<p><b>Song</b>: "Happy Birthday, Mr President".

