<html><head><title>The warder of the nation</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/ir.gif" width=224 height=26  alt="International">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>The warder of the nation</h1>

<font size=1>HAVANA</font>
<p>THE knock on the door came in the middle of the night. Two plain-clothes men entered the home of the startled Cuban family, and dragged away the American who had just rented a room from them. Dozens of other visitors were caught in the dragnet that eerie night and hauled off to be questioned at a crumbling mansion known as "the centre for the control of foreigners".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The official in charge, with the patience of a man relishing his power, explained that foreigners simply must not move out of hotels into private homes. Nor may they rent private cars from locals. Never mind that the law does not forbid Cubans to make money this way, and that plenty have been doing it openly for months. After a few tense hours, the American was dumped back at his hotel, with the comment: "How else can we maintain control?"
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Fidel Castro clearly has no intention of easing his grip. The end of the Soviet Union and of its subsidies forced him to allow a bit of capitalism, and a smaller dose of political freedom. But neither is welcome. The Cubans this week kicked out an American diplomat whose support of political dissidents had long irritated them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some of Mr Castro's enemies believe outside pressure can finish him. President Clinton has just appointed a senior envoy to drum up international support for the Helms-Burton law, which seeks to punish companies that invest in Cuba. But the United States' bully-boy tactics have outraged its friends. And the impact of American sanctions seems likely to be diminished by a slow economic recovery now under way in Cuba. As Mr Castro well knows, the real threat is from within.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He has never faced serious political opposition in Cuba. One reason is that an extensive network of informants ensures that none gets organised. Another is that the natural leaders of any opposition have mostly fled the country. The groups that did emerge could muster few followers: an old joke calls them "bicycle clubs", because all the members can fit on one.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When these groups at last organised themselves last year into a united front, called Concilio Cubano, the government watched warily. Infighting, prodded along by infiltrators, might have done for the group anyway. But as it gained momentum and support abroad early this year, the regime cracked down. Some 150 members were detained before it could hold its first official meeting in February; key organisers remain in prison. Dissidents vow to fight on, but the break-up of Concilio has turned them once again into isolated voices.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One human-rights advocate, pointing out a spy in the park across from his house, explains that activism in the interior is much harder than in Havana, with its bustle of people and friendly embassies. A movement for academic freedom was recently crushed. An activist says students and university staff in Havana are ripe for organising--but what can she do from the remote province to which she has been banished? The frightened mother of a persecuted journalist clings to the telephone number of a Concilio contact, written on her palm in case she is suddenly abducted.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A bigger threat to the system than political dissidence, argues Vladimir Roca, himself a brave voice of dissent, may be the arrival of a bit of free enterprise. The regime has legalised the dollar and self-employment--but then has clamped down on the result. When hundreds of tiny caf&eacute;s appeared, offering tastier fare than the state-run restaurants, they were hit with hefty taxes, seating limits and frequent inspections, to keep the market spirit within bounds. Farming has been partially freed. There is more food around, and more farmers and middlemen with money. So now this too is under threat. The same fear explains the clampdown on private car and room rentals, and on prostitution, widespread and tolerated two years ago.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;While the more open-minded officials and academics have been receiving conference invitations, scholarships and other support from abroad, hardliners are worried. Raul Castro, Fidel's brother, calls those who want faster economic reform the "fifth column" of the Mafia and the <font size=-1>CIA</font>, and since March has been shoving them aside.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The regime is not alone in its concern about the impact of capitalism. The voice of Jose Conrado, the priest of Palma Soriano in eastern Cuba, was nearly drowned out by the pounding drums and raucous revelry of the carnival around his church last week. But the excesses of the annual bacchanalia bother him less than the "grave moral decay born of the economic situation" . The dual economy has forced Cubans to do anything--from engaging in prostitution to stealing from their employers--to make a dollar, he argues, for without that a family simply cannot eat.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A red banner in El Cobre, near the eastern city of Santiago, proclaims <i>Ayer, hoy y siempre</i>--yesterday, today and forever. It is not promoting communism, though, but another revolution slowly taking shape. The banner hangs at Cuba's holiest Catholic shrine. The growing moral emptiness of Castroism has led to a sharp rise in church attendance, both Catholic and Protestant, notably among the young. Initiations into <i>santeria</i>, a variety of cults derived from Africa, are on the rise. But here the regime is tolerant; it sees capitalism as a far more immediate threat.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even there it may be wrong: such capitalism as exists may in the end serve as a lifeline. But one threat is inescapable. A billboard in Granma province, depicting the heroes of the revolution, declares: <i>Ayer, hoy y ma&ntilde;ana--</i>yesterday, today and tomorrow<i>.</i> But it stops short of <i>siempre</i>. Even Fidel is not immortal. The revolution began in Granma, and support for it and the great leader remains strong there. Till when? Few believe the regime can long outlast the death of the one man who supplies its mystique. This month he turned 70.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
