<html><head><title>Making merry</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Utility regulation</b></p>
<h1>Making merry</h1>

<p>TOGETHER, the privatised telecoms, gas, electricity and water industries serve 25m customers and have annual sales of &#163;51 billion, representing 8% of Britain's <font size=-1>GDP</font>. So it is hardly surprising that the regulators who determine what prices these industries can charge have become controversial public figures.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On August 21st Clare Spottiswoode, director-general of Ofgas, the gas regulator, stepped into the limelight yet again, imposing new limits on the price British Gas can charge other firms for using its pipelines. This will save households an average of &#163;28 a year. British Gas, predictably, protested that the cut represented "the seizure of shareholders' income on an unprecedented scale" and said it may appeal to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Ms Spottiswoode is not the only regulator to clash with the regulated. Recently battles have raged between Oftel's Don Cruickshank and British Telecom, Ian Byatt of Ofwat and the water companies, and Stephen Littlechild of Offer and assorted electricity firms. This may reflect good regulation at work: a well-regulated monopolist is not a happy one. However, the belief is growing in the City of London and Parliament that these rows owe as much to the personal idiosyncracies and agendas of individual regulators as to good regulation. Is British regulation, invented in the 1980s during the privatisation process, not working?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Since privatisation, all the regulators have become steadily tougher, imposing more stringent price limits and promoting more competition. They limit prices using a formula restricting increases to inflation minus an amount, <font size=-1>X</font>%, determined by the regulator and fixed for five years. At the end of the first five years after privatisation, each regulator increased "<font size=-1>X</font>"--but by much more since early 1995 than before. This is reflected in the price of utility shares which, in the past 18 months, have underperformed the <font size=-1>FT</font>-<font size=-1>SE</font> 100 index by a third. (See <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>)
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some regulated firms and City analysts attribute this recent display of regulatory muscle to politics. Formally, the regulators are independent of government. But, with an election pending, might they be acting on orders from the Tories to lower prices and make privatisation popular with voters? Or, because Labour complains endlessly about the fat profits of the utilities and intends to reform regulation, are they becoming enthusiastic consumer champions in order to win reappointment should the government change? Or, less cynically, has constant criticism made the regulators wary of doing anything that seems to favour privatised firms over the consumer?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Naturally, none of this can be proved. Every regulatory act is justified by pages of tedious documentation, full of complex calculations of the cost of capital and so forth, disputable but never disprovable. But if the regulators have been favouring customers at the expense of shareholders--who are due a decent return on their capital--the regulators will have helped consumers only in the short run at the cost of doing them harm in the long run.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Why? The privatised utilities are hugely unpopular because they earn juicy profits. But high profits in the short term are the <i>quid pro quo</i> for lower prices in the long term. That is because the regulator sets the price cap at a level that should allow the utility a reasonable profit if it performs reasonably efficiently, and far bigger profits if it performs more efficiently than the regulator expects. When the regulator next reviews the price cap, the greater efficiency achieved by the firm is then taken into account, resulting in lower prices.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The prospect of bigger profits is the carrot encouraging a utility to increase efficiency. Without that, the firm has little incentive to become more efficient, and so consumers may not get lower prices. In fact, despite all the speculation, there is a great deal of evidence that the regulatory system has been working as it should. Many privatised firms initially made (perhaps too) healthy profits, but they did this by increasing efficiency. In real terms prices have been reduced by 44% in telecoms, by 24% in gas and by 10% in electricity since privatisation. They have risen only for water, where the resulting income has been used to begin rebuilding decrepit infrastructure. And now that the regulators have seen how much utilities can earn, they are lowering prices still further and demanding even greater improvements.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Unfortunately Labour remains unimpressed by this. It not only promises to levy a "windfall profits" tax, but proposes to replace the current system of price regulation with what it calls a "profit sharing" rule, splitting any "extra" profits between shareholders and customers, perhaps fifty-fifty. This idea is analysed in "Incentive Regulation", a recent report by the Centre for the Study of Regulated Industries, a research group. It points out that, to deliver the same incentives to boost efficiency (ie, total benefit to shareholders and customers) as the current regulatory system, the price cap would have to be fixed for a longer period than under the current system, which rewards shareholders before customers. It would also encourage firms to use creative accounting and, to be fair, firms would have to be able to recoup cash from customers should their profits fail to meet expectations.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In any case, Labour is ignoring the fact that the regulatory system already shares extra profits between customers and shareholders--erring on the side of consumers. Ivan Viehoff, an economist at Nera, a consultancy, calculates that in the electricity industry, over 70% of the benefit from an efficiency saving introduced in the year after a price review typically goes to customers, and 90% of the saving from a change made in the year before a review. That is why utilities often delay such changes until after a review, says Mr Viehoff.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Instead of whingeing about utility profits, or regulators, both Labour and the Tories ought to explain more clearly to the public how the incentives in the current system operate, so that utility profits are seen in context, rather than undermining a system that is working well.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
