<html><head><title>Preparing for prime time</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Flat-screen technology</b></p>
<h1>Preparing for prime time</h1>

<font size=1>TOKYO</font>
<p>AFTER numerous false starts, the flat television set is at last poised to reach the stores this autumn. Japanese electronic companies are preparing to roll out a range of flat-screen <font size=-1>TV</font>s that are only a few inches thick but offer picture sizes of up to 40 inches (102cm) diagonally. But do not expect customers to stampede to buy the early models. A typical set will cost around $8,000--almost three times the price of today's big-screen <font size=-1>TV</font>s. So why the sudden interest of the Japanese firms in getting slimmed-down screens into the retail market? The answer has as much to do with computers as with televisions. (See <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>)
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some specialist flat screens are already in operation; the New York Stock Exchange, for instance, uses nearly 3,000 of them. However, the most common use for the technology so far has been the smaller flat-panel displays used in lap-top computers. Sales of such liquid-crystal displays (<font size=-1>LCD</font>s) reached $6 billion in 1995--and the business has been dominated by Japanese firms, such as Sharp, <font size=-1>NEC</font>, Toshiba and Hosiden. However, the latest 12-inch colour <font size=-1>LCD</font>s that the Japanese firms were hoping to sell for $650 a panel are now being offered by South Korean suppliers for $420 apiece. By contrast, the market for bigger flat-<font size=-1>TV</font> screens looks blissfully free of competitors.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Another prompt for action has come from the desk-top computer market. The conventional cathode-ray tube (<font size=-1>CRT</font>) monitor used by desk-top computers is getting too big for the desk. New computer programs, particularly Microsoft's Windows 95, cram lots of graphical detail on to the screen. Already, 17-inch computer monitors have replaced the old 14-inch versions as standard; an increasing number of users are buying 21-inch models, which cost more than $900, are the size of small packing crates and weigh a ton. At these dimensions and prices, space-saving flat-screen alternatives begin to look highly attractive.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Given that 70m desk-top computers are now sold every year this looks like a promising business. Sharp, which has 44% of the <font size=-1>LCD</font> business, has spent $500m boosting its capacity for making large <font size=-1>LCD</font> panels for the desk-top monitor business. It hopes to grab 5% of this market next year--even though the flat-screen devices will still cost three times more than comparable <font size=-1>CRT</font> displays. When the price difference is down to just twice as much, Sharp reckons its flat-panels will win 15% of the monitor market--an annual 9m units that might be worth more than $10 billion a year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Flat-screen monitors could also play a crucial role in the equally long-awaited (and by no means certain) convergence of the <font size=-1>TV</font> and the <font size=-1>PC</font>. The chief problem with <font size=-1>PC</font> monitors as <font size=-1>TV</font> sets is that they are too small for the picture to be seen from across the room. That is changing: Gateway <font size=-1>2000</font>, one of America's largest mail-order suppliers of <font size=-1>PC</font>s, already sells a $3,800 computer equipped with television functions and a 31-inch monitor. But such monitors could strain even the sturdiest desk. Flat-panel displays would solve that problem; they would also give the <font size=-1>PC</font>-<font size=-1>TV</font> a standard.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Revealingly, many of the big <font size=-1>CRT</font> makers are rushing into the flat-screen business, even though it will cannibalise their existing market. <font size=-1>NEC</font> is spending &#165;25 billion ($230m) on a new factory in Kagoshima to produce 40-inch plasma display panels (<font size=-1>PDP</font>s)--a rugged form of flat-panel display that provides a wider viewing angle and is easier to make in large formats than the traditional <font size=-1>LCD</font>. Early versions are expected to cost around &#165;450,000 apiece. By 2000 <font size=-1>NEC</font> expects to have spent &#165;85 billion building up its <font size=-1>PDP</font> capacity to 150,000 units a month. The company hopes that by the end of the decade the worldwide market for <font size=-1>PDP</font>s will be worth &#165;260 billion a year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<font size=-1>NEC</font> will face plenty of competition--not least from Fujitsu, which launched a 21-inch <font size=-1>PDP</font> screen several years ago. The company is spending &#165;60 billion on a factory in Miyazaki to produce 20,000 42-inch panels a month by December. Hitachi claims to be spending much the same on <font size=-1>PDP</font> facilities. After halting its flat-panel work in 1993 because of rising costs and uncertain demand, Hitachi is reckoned to be two years behind its rivals.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Meanwhile Sony is quietly pressing on with its big-screen Plasmatron, a cross between a <font size=-1>PDP</font> and an <font size=-1>LCD</font> that it has developed jointly with Tektronix in the United States. Sony is preparing to launch a 25-inch flat-screen <font size=-1>TV</font> this autumn; and to follow it up with a 40-inch model next year. Sony claims that Plasmatron displays can be stretched to 50 inches or so.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When the Japanese electronic industry throws its money behind a product as heavily as this, things happen. Ironically the immediate future of flat-screen <font size=-1>TV</font>s may be bound up with the single exception to this rule: high-definition television. Although Japanese firms have been pushing the product for years, the aesthetic advantages of <font size=-1>HDTV</font> are obvious only on screens at least 40 inches across. Flat screens that size would be nearly a yard shallower than traditional <font size=-1>CRT</font> tubes. At that size, making glass tubes becomes even more expensive than crafting silicon panels, so huge flat-screen <font size=-1>TV</font>s may yet end up cheaper.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
