<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><h2>They're off</h2></p>
<p><p>Bob Dole picked his old Reaganite adversary, Jack Kemp, as his running-mate for the presidential election; Nancy Reagan moistened eyes over her husband's "long goodbye"; Colin Powell got a conservative audience to cheer his tolerant speech; and the <b>Republican convention </b>began the party's desperate attempt to catch up with Bill Clinton in the opinion polls.
<p>A New York policeman, strolling unchallenged through off-bounds parts of Kennedy airport, confirmed the slackness of American <b>airline security</b>. Four weeks after <font size=-1>TWA</font> flight 800 crashed, evidence began to point to an explosion.
<p><b>Colombia's </b>government made a deal with angry peasant farmers in its southern region of Putumayo. The government will not use aerial spraying to destroy their coca plantations provided they do the job themselves. They will get subsidies to switch to food crops. Peace in Putumayo? We'll see. Less coca-growing? We probably won't see.</p>
<p><h2>Hope in Cambodia</h2></p>
<p><p>Thousands of <b>Khmers Rouges guerrillas </b>were reported to be ready to stop fighting the Cambodian government, creating speculation that the civil war may be ending. Ieng Sary, once Pol Pot's deputy, was said to be among those seeking peace.
<p>Singapore is to install a system that will ban the island's 100,000 <b>Internet users </b>from having access to "objectionable" material. Critics of the plan say it could be a means of political censorship.
<p>The chairman of <b>Myanmar</b>'s ruling military junta, Than Shwe, paid an official visit to Malaysia. Opposition groups condemned the welcome given to the representative of a regime "notorious for its atrocities" .
<p>South Korean <b>riot police</b>, backed by helicopters, raided a university campus to end a demonstration by students sympathetic to North Korea.</p>
<p><h2>All the tsar's men</h2></p>
<p><p>Russia's Communist-dominated lower house of parliament, the Duma, reconfirmed <b>Viktor Chernomyrdin</b> as prime minister. If the recently re-elected but frail president, Boris Yeltsin, were to die or become incapacitated, Mr Chernomyrdin would take over for three months.
<p>Russia's new presidential defence adviser, Alexander Lebed, went to <b>Chechnya </b>to talk peace with a separatist guerrilla leader, Aslan Maskhadov, after Chechen fighters had intensified the war by capturing parts of Grozny, the republic's capital. By August 15th, a partial ceasefire seemed to be holding.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><font size=-1>NATO</font> put its troops in <b>Bosnia</b> on alert when the Bosnian Serbs stopped them inspecting a military base; the inspection went ahead. Franjo Tudjman, Croatia's president, promised Warren Christopher, America's secretary of state, that the Bosnian Croats would dissolve their mini-state, as promised in the Dayton agreement.
<p>Two <b>Greek-Cypriots</b> were killed and many injured by Turkish-Cypriot soldiers and civilians. They were demonstrating, on the border between the two communities, against the island's continued division.
<p>Romania and Hungary agreed on the text of a treaty which, among other things, is supposed to protect <b>ethnic</b> <b>Hungarians </b>in Romania.</p>
<p><h2>Treaty banned</h2></p>
<p><p>Negotiations on a global <b>nuclear test ban treaty</b> failed, as India stuck by its objection that the text did not include a timetable for nuclear disarmament.
<p>Foreigners left <b>Burundi</b> as international sanctions imposed after a military coup began to bite.
<p>Two years after an estimated 1m people were massacred in<b> Rwanda</b>, its parliament passed a law under which more than 80,000 people imprisoned on suspicion of genocide can be tried.
<p>South Africa's rand slithered, as a <b>bribes scandal </b>lapped near President Nelson Mandela. Bantu Holomisa, until recently a minister, says the <font size=-1>ANC</font> accepted money from a businessman who wanted charges against him dropped.
<p>Eight leading supporters of ex-President Kenneth Kaunda went on trial in <b>Zambia </b>charged with treason and hiring saboteurs to plant bombs.
<p><b>Nigeria's</b> ruler General Sani Abacha sacked the military administrators of all the country's 30 states.
<p>Jordan's <b>King Hussein</b> visited Saudi Arabia's King Fahd, ending a six-year rift that started when Hussein showed support for Iraq in the Gulf war.
<p>In a deal that has annoyed America, <b>Iran and Turkey</b> signed an agreement for some $20 billion-worth of Iranian natural gas to be sold to Turkey over two decades.
<p>Libya's<b> Colonel Qaddafi</b> sent fighter jets to flush out rebel Islamists holed up in mountain strongholds in eastern Libya.
<p>A gift from Saudi Arabia to Gazans of 10,500<b> lamb carcases</b> had to be incinerated because Israel had held them up for a month.
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
<p align=center><a href="wtw2.html">BUSINESS THIS WEEK</a></p><br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
