<html><head><title>In the name of St Ronald</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>In the name of St Ronald</h1>

<font size=1>SAN DIEGO</font><br><p>
THERE were streamers and balloons, party hats and upbeat tunes, and lots of wonderful sideshows. Bob Dole, the Republicans' presidential nominee, cruised into San Diego by ship. Newt Gingrich, their leader in the House, won a salute from friends in the city's spectacular aquarium. Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, appeared on a Harley-Davidson motorbike, part of a cavalcade of 7,000. "Bikers believe in conservative values," he said.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Republicans are hoping that this week's convention, ending on August 15th, will launch them on the road to victory in November. In previous weeks they had bickered over the platform that the convention would adopt, and had ended up with a harsh document liable to alienate mainstream voters. Moreover, most of the convention delegates held hardline views that risked costing more votes if aired freely before the television cameras. The extremism of the Republicans' 1992 convention is thought to have contributed to George Bush's humiliation that year. And so, to avoid another fall, the convention managers' first task was to bury both platform and delegates. They succeeded brilliantly.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The convention opened on August 12th, and the platform was voted through almost unnoticed: the vote was left off the schedule the organisers handed out, and many people in the convention hall were too busy shaking hands and slapping backs to pay any attention. Party bigwigs paid least attention of all. Asked about the significance of the platform, Mr Dole replied that he had not even read it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Awkward delegates were hushed up just as efficiently. Pat Buchanan, whose fiery conservatism scared off mainstream voters four years ago, was denied a chance to speak, despite the fact that he had won more than 3m votes in the primaries. Two moderate Republican governors, Pete Wilson of California and William Weld of Massachusetts, were silenced too, because they had threatened to attack the party's right wing and thereby draw attention to it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Those who did speak had their words vetted in advance, with one big exception. Colin Powell, the ex-general who might have won the nomination had he wanted it, refused to be cowed. The result was memorable. The son of black immigrants, he breathed passion into the Republican faith that diligence and ability can propel anyone to the top of American life. Himself the product of a modest, hard-working family, he made the party's rhetoric on family values sound more powerful than usual. A career soldier who led America to victory in the Gulf war, he could talk the Republicans' tough foreign-policy line without being accused of empty machismo.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Mr Powell did more than play on stock Republican themes. He took a risk, and it paid off superbly. "You all know," he told the conservative crowd, "that I believe in a woman's right to choose and I strongly support affirmative action." A few delegates booed, and then a few more. But, before a hostile momentum could build up, Mr Powell danced back to safer themes. America, he quickly said, is "a country where the best is always yet to come, a country that exists by divine providence." And he ended in a way inconceivable anywhere else in the rich world. He punched his fist into the air and shouted out, "America!"
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The delegates were on their feet and cheering. And so, by the end of the convention's first day, the conservative platform was forgotten; and the conservative delegates had lost their heart to the party's chief moderate. The ensuing days reinforced Mr Powell's achievement. Speaker after speaker emphasised Republicans' compassion: their desire to help the weak, their sympathy for the poor. The party platform was harsh on immigrants: no matter, Republicans were now celebrating their own immigrant ancestors. The party had until recently attacked those who depended on the welfare state; now, misty-eyed Republicans were painting President Clinton as the chief enemy of caring government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But, having apparently buried their harsh image of the recent past, what did Republicans have to offer? Back in the spring, when Mr Dole wrapped the nomination up, it was assumed that he would campaign on the quality of his character. He has overcome war wounds that might have killed a less determined man; Mr Clinton is a draft-dodger, an adulterer, a friend of crooked property dealers. But, six months on, the character issue seems to leave voters unmoved. So now Mr Dole has performed a startling reversal. He has compromised his integrity by abandoning old beliefs, and hopes to win voters by bribing them.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This self-abasement has come in two parts. First, Mr Dole promised to cut taxes without cutting spending by as much, so abandoning years of fiscal responsibility. Second, Mr Dole chose Jack Kemp as his running-mate. In the past, Mr Kemp has insulted Mr Dole. He has disagreed with Mr Dole. And, before the campaign is out, he may humiliate him.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Kemp fancies himself as a man of ideas, and thinks Mr Dole a dull pragmatist. He once said that Mr Dole's library had burned down and "both books were lost--including the one that had not been coloured yet." Mr Kemp was one of the first popularisers of the idea that tax cuts pay for themselves, and he derided doubters (who included Mr Dole) as gutless pessimists. From his first years in Congress, Mr Kemp had little respect for seniority or the art of compromise, Mr Dole's chief attributes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It is true that George Bush was no friend of Ronald Reagan when they joined forces in 1980, and that the two went on to victory. Mr Kemp, too, is doing his best to fall in behind his new boss. He has backed away from his old support for racial preferences, and now declares (never mind what he said before) that the children of illegal immigrants should be denied schooling. And yet, despite these shifts, Mr Kemp is at heart a prima donna. Ed Rollins, who chaired his disastrous presidential bid in 1988, described his friend and boss this way: "He was impossible to discipline and simply wouldn't listen."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Kemp has a redeeming feature, and it is a big one. He shares Mr Reagan's appealing optimism, his faith that rich and poor alike will prosper from America's freedom and openness. Thus he would keep America's markets open to foreigners and free of heavy intervention by the state, believing that this promotes the spirit of enterprise which will uplift the inner cities. This view flies in the face of the Republicans' pessimistic wing, which triumphed in the writing of the platform. But it appeals to Mr Dole. Having bet his campaign on Reaganite tax cuts, Mr Dole would love to wrap himself in Mr Reagan's aura.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Will this neo-Reaganism work? It is a sure bet among the party's loyalists: there were tears on the convention floor when Nancy Reagan came to represent her husband, too frail to be there. Yet Reaganism may not be enough to win uncommitted voters over to Mr Dole. For one thing, he lacks Mr Reagan's charm, and his infectious confidence in the moral value of his policies. For another, Mr Reagan's tax policies are widely reckoned to have been disastrous. Already the Democrats are running television advertisements accusing Mr Dole of taking risks with the economy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Some Republicans argue that the Dole tax cuts will work where Mr Reagan's backfired, because times are different. Then, Mr Reagan's tax cuts were not balanced by spending cuts, because pro-spending Democrats controlled Congress. Now, Mr Dole could be pretty sure of imposing spending cuts, because anti-government Republicans control Congress. Besides, Mr Dole is armed with a line-item veto that did not exist in Mr Reagan's time, so he can cut egregious pork out of spending bills.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such arguments are unlikely to survive the rigour of the campaign. If Mr Dole proposes budgets that cut spending by only three-quarters as much as they cut taxes, as he says he will, the deficit will grow unless a truly miraculous burst of economic growth boosts tax revenues fabulously. Besides, Mr Dole may find it harder than Mr Reagan did to unseat an incumbent president by attacking his economic record. In August 1980 America was plagued by unemployment of 7.7% and inflation of 12.9%. In 1996 Mr Clinton can boast of an economy that has created 10m jobs, of an unemployment rate of only 5.4%, of dormant inflation. In choosing to fight Mr Clinton on the economy, Mr Dole reveals his desperation.



