<html><head><title>Trends of the week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>


&#4;
<ul><h1>Trends of the week</h1>


<p><b>Word:</b> Dream, as in "The American Dream". In various forms the dreamy word popped up no fewer than 23 times in Susan Molinari's speech to the Republican convention.
<p><b>Four-letter words:</b> Dole, Kemp.
<p><b>Future:</b> Bill Clinton will next week publish his secretly-written book on America and the 21st century.
<p><b>Modesty: </b>Newt Gingrich describing Martin Luther King as the greatest Georgian of this century.
<p><b>Non-sequitur:</b> The Republicans' promise to boost growth by cutting taxes and thus stimulating harder work. But they also pledge to help people spend more time at home with their families.
<p><b>Unread</b> <b>document:</b> The 107-page Republican platform. Among the self-confessed non-readers: Newt Gingrich and Bob Dole.
<p><b>Pro-abortion slogan:</b> "Every ejaculation doesn't deserve a name."
<p><b>San Diego button:</b> "Eleanor Roosevelt's ghost told me to vote for Dole".
<p><b>Anti-abortion slogan: </b>"Intolerance is a beautiful thing" (spotted at a Prayer Breakfast for Pat Buchanan).
<p><b>Climate: </b>Sun. A convention guide boasts that San Diego had a near-perfect record of 364 days of sunshine last year (it snowed on Christmas Day).
<p><b>Missing ingredient:</b> Spontaneity--there was no room for it in a show firmly designed for watching on television.
<p><b>Abuse:</b> Of children, used to endorse almost every Republican idea.</ul>
</td></tr></table>
