</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Lessons in self-improvement</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Inner-city schools</b></p>
<h1>Lessons in self-improvement</h1>

<font size=1>BIRMINGHAM</font>
<p>CALLERS to Ed Doolan's phone-in show on <font size=-1>BBC</font> Radio <font size=-1>WM</font> in Birmingham now have, it seems, one thing less to complain about. When Mr Doolan gave evidence to the Birmingham Education Commission, an inquiry set up by the city's Labour council in 1993, he said his show got a constant stream of angry calls about the state of local schools. The commission's damning findings prompted the council to set up an ambitious school-improvement scheme. Now, says Mr Doolan, "it is very rare to get a complaint about the schools."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A more conventional indicator of Birmingham's progress is the one used in the government's school league tables: the proportion of pupils who get at least five <font size=-1>GCSE</font> passes at grade "<font size=-1>C</font>" or better. By this measure, Birmingham's council-run schools are improving, but still have some way to go. The proportion of pupils with five passes rose from 26.8% in 1993 to 31.2% in 1995, when the national average was 43.5%. The council is hoping that this year's <font size=-1>GCSE</font> results, published on August 22nd, will be better still, and raise it from last year's 85th position in the league table of England's 108 local-education authorities.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Clearly it will take some years for the effects of any improvement in the city's nursery and primary schools to show up in better exam grades for those leaving secondary school. But there is little doubt that the schools are being transformed. The Birmingham Education Commission issued a follow-up report in October 1995, and according to Professor Ted Wragg of Exeter University, its chairman, the commission found that "remarkable progress" had been made in dealing with its earlier criticisms. David Blunkett, the Labour Party's education spokesman, has made a series of visits to Birmingham and has picked up some lessons for the party's education policy.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The strategy to improve Birmingham's schools was the brain-child of Tim Brighouse, who became the city's chief education officer just as the commission published its first report in 1993. The most important in his long list of initiatives is getting each school to set itself an ambitious but achievable set of targets, and to keep raising those targets each year. Schools also have to make a series of guarantees to their pupils. For instance, primary-school pupils are promised a part in some sort of public performance (such as a play or concert), and secondary-school pupils are guaranteed work experience in a local business.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The council has also responded to criticism that it does not spend a sufficient share of its income on schools: in this financial year the schools budget is &#163;316m compared with &#163;283m two years ago.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Grove Junior &amp; Infants' School in Handsworth is one of the star performers in Birmingham's improvement scheme. The school won national attention last year when four 11-year-old pupils took and passed their <font size=-1>GCSE</font> in maths--five years early. In a speech in January, Tony Blair, Labour's leader, cited this as an example of the sort of academic "fast-tracking" for able pupils that a Labour government would encourage.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Anybody visiting Grove school after hearing horror stories about violence and chaos in urban schools is in for a pleasant surprise. David Winkley, the head teacher, has created an oasis of relative calm in one of Britain's poorest inner-city districts. The school has a waiting list of parents wanting to get their children in--Mr Winkley boasts that he even gets applications from Sutton Coldfield, one of Birmingham's more affluent suburbs. The school's walls are covered in examples of good work, ranging from algebra to art. The school tests its 720 pupils three times a year and plots their results on a computer database, comparing how well each one performed with predictions based on results from earlier tests.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Apart from fast-tracking for able pupils, Grove school is already carrying out several measures recently adopted as policy by Labour: children who fall behind get intensive coaching; plenty of homework is set, and there is a "homework club" after school for those who fail to hand in their work; all parents sign home-school contracts and are summoned to the school if their children misbehave. Pupils are tested as they start their compulsory schooling at the age of five, a Labour proposal which has now been taken up by the government.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When Wendy Davies took over as head teacher of Selly Park girls' secondary school in the mid-1980s, it was facing closure because of falling numbers. Now it is oversubscribed. In 1989 only 5% of pupils left with five or more <font size=-1>GCSE</font>s at grade '<font size=-1>C</font>' or better; last year 30% did so, and the target for this year is 35%. Since 83% of the girls do not have English as their first language, and most of them come from a Muslim culture where academic achievement has not traditionally been seen as important for girls, this is a considerable achievement.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour says it will make all local-education authorities draw up school-improvement targets, as Birmingham has done. The contrast between Birmingham's progress and the lack of action in other inner-city boroughs shows that it is also necessary to send inspectors to examine the quality of management at councils' education departments, as both Labour and the government are proposing to do. As one senior inspector puts it: "Tim Brighouse offers leadership where other chief education officers only offer management." Schools are under pressure to do better, but by getting them to set their own targets and letting them decide how to reach them, Mr Brighouse has avoided giving teachers the impression that an endless stream of impossible demands is being imposed from on high.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Blunkett could also learn a lot from this management style, which Mr Brighouse shares with successful head teachers like Mr Winkley and Mrs Davies: they somehow manage to combine iron resolve with an outward air of warm collegiality. None of them likes to talk about the messy business of removing people who are not up to the job. But each has the patience and determination to find ways of doing so without provoking bitterness. The heads of 80 of Birmingham council's 450 schools left their jobs or took early retirement in Mr Brighouse's first two years, and yet inspectors have noted a big improvement in morale among teachers.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One lesson from Birmingham that Gordon Brown, Labour's shadow chancellor, will find especially encouraging is that a great deal can be achieved in Britain's inner-city schools at little extra cost. It is true that Birmingham is spending more on its schools, but many of its successes have cost next to nothing: setting targets; involving parents; even Grove school's computer system for monitoring pupils' progress is fairly cheap.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Labour wants to put most of any extra spending on education into primary schools, where classes are larger and inspectors' reports have uncovered alarming shortcomings. Birmingham's experience suggests that it may be possible to convince secondary schools to accept this. Mrs Davies says she understands Birmingham council's decision to put most of its extra spending into primary schools because if these schools send her 11-year-olds who can read, write and do maths properly, then her job will be much easier.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It will be a few more years before the extent of Birmingham's success becomes clear. But the improvements so far should make it clear to Labour's leadership that it now needs to put pressure on other, Labour-run councils in Britain's cities to spend less time bleating about government funding, to banish the notion that little academic progress can be expected from the children of poor families or from ethnic minorities, and to take action.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?840236400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="br3.html">Next article</a>
</p>
