<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><b>Long to reign?</b> &nbsp;The Fabian Society, a Labour Party affiliate, urged the party to stop ducking the issue of reforming the monarchy. It said the queen should lose her constitutional powers and that "God Save the Queen" should be replaced with a new national anthem.</p>
<p><b>Power cuts</b> &nbsp;National Grid, which transmits electricity in England and Wales, protested against new price controls proposed by Offer, the electricity regulator, which would cut up to &#163;5 a year from average household bills.</p>
<p><b>Marching on</b> &nbsp;Ulster's marching season drew to a fairly peaceful close. Big marches by loyalists in Londonderry and republicans in Belfast went ahead without violence, but police fired plastic bullets at nationalists who attacked a war memorial in Londonderry.</p>
<p><b>Fall-out</b> &nbsp;The government asked the American defence department to check its records after the Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament produced evidence that accidents involving nuclear weapons at American bases in Britain in the 1950s had been covered up.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Crashes</b> &nbsp;London suffered two big smashes: a woman died and 69 people were hurt when two trains collided near Watford Junction; and four people escaped with slight injuries when a Learjet crash-landed on the <font size=-1>A40</font>.</p>
<p><b>Unpalatable</b> &nbsp;The National Audit Office said that more than half of the government's targets for improving the nation's health by changing its diet would be missed. Women are drinking more and more children are smoking, in spite of campaigns to discourage them.</p>
<p><b>Top marks</b> &nbsp;The proportion of pupils passing their <font size=-1>A</font>-level examinations rose to 85.8%, compared with 84% last year. The government brushed aside suggestions that this was because they were getting easier to pass.</p>
<p><b>McJobs</b> &nbsp;Michael Portillo, the defence secretary, refused to take sides in a row over plans to turn the Conservative Party office in his constituency into a McDonald's fast-food restaurant.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
