<html><head><title>Freer than free</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Microsoft v Netscape</b></p>
<h1>Freer than free</h1>
<p><b>The battle for control of the Internet is now about marketing pizazz, rather than technological prowess</b></p>

<p>IN THE Internet's distant youth--say, three months ago--bits and bytes were what counted. The software engineers at Netscape made Navigator, the fastest, whizziest "Web browser", and around 85% of all Internet surfers used the program. Confident that Navigator had a clear advantage over Internet Explorer, Microsoft's rival product, the stockmarket valued Netscape at more than $6 billion. Now Netscape's valuation is closer to $3 billion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The reason for this adjustment made its debut on August 12th: Microsoft's Internet Explorer (version 3.0). To cut a long technological argument short, this new version is on a par with Navigator. However, parity does not guarantee Microsoft anything. After all, Microsoft currently has a market share of less than 5%. Internet folk will desert an accepted standard only if they are bullied, bribed or seduced into doing so. These enticements are, in their legal form, known as marketing, a business in which Microsoft's boss, Bill Gates, is fearsome.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Observers may wonder what all the fuss is about. Certainly not direct revenues: both Microsoft and Netscape give their browsers away free (Microsoft to all users; Netscape to about half). Instead, browsers are a loss-leader in what could prove a rich Internet software market.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Netscape already makes a third of its money by selling "server" software and services to people who run Web sites. These people stump up because of the ubiquity and reputation of Netscape's browser. Microsoft's strategy works in a similar way, but Mr Gates's mind is really on something bigger. Browsers implicitly challenge the traditional <font size=-1>PC</font> world that Microsoft dominates; like other Internet software, they can run on all sorts of computers, not just <font size=-1>PC</font>s using Microsoft Windows software. To protect its franchise, Microsoft needs to turn its browser, which uses Windows technology, into the standard.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Over the past few months Mr Gates has struck a series of deals with leading Internet-access companies to give their subscribers Internet Explorer as the default browser. This arrangement now extends to the three main commercial on-line services, America Online, CompuServe and Microsoft's own Microsoft Network, as well as to the two biggest Internet-only providers, <font size=-1>AT&T</font>'s WorldNet and Netcom. On August 14th, the two biggest British Internet service providers also said they were defecting from Navigator to Internet Explorer. Most of these deals have been waiting for Microsoft to release version 3.0 of Internet Explorer; now that it has done, the firms will start shipping the browser to subscribers. Between them they reach more than 13m subscribers--the vast majority of home users.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Such ruthless marketing tactics may explain both Mr Gates's wealth and his lack of friends in the software industry. In fact, many current users may still stick with Netscape's browser out of habit. Anticipating that, Microsoft has found another way to turn their heads. It has signed a further raft of deals that will give users of its new browser free access to some popular services that otherwise charge a fee. These include the <i>Wall Street Journal</i> Web site (which now charges an annual on-line subscription of $49), <font size=-1>ESPN</font>'s sports site, and InvestorsEdge.com, a financial site.
</p><p><b>Charge of the byte brigade</b></b>
<br>Worst of all for Netscape, Microsoft controls the best marketing channel of all: the <font size=-1>PC</font>'s operating system. Most new <font size=-1>PC</font>s are shipped with Microsoft's Windows <font size=-1>95</font>, which now includes Internet Explorer. That will account for 46m copies in 1996 alone (although they will be useful only for the computers that are connected to the Internet), reckons Dataquest, a consultancy. The next version of Windows, which is not due until next year, will have the browser built in, eliminating the entire concept of a browser as a stand-alone program.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Microsoft makes more money from the interest on its $7 billion of cash than Netscape's total annual revenues. "Microsoft can afford to buy market share," says Martin Haeberli, Netscape's director of technology. "We can argue about the fairness of that approach, but we can't compete in the same way."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet even if the contest is purely about marketing prowess, Netscape has some things going for it--such as its own marketing innovativeness and brand loyalty. Thanks to its 85% market share, the firm has at least one version of its browser in the hands of virtually every user who might want one. Netscape reached its current position by letting the Internet do its marketing and distribution for it: word of its software brought millions of users to its Web site to download a copy. Now about 30,000 Web sites around the Internet sport a logo encouraging users to download the latest version of Navigator from Netscape's site.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But in its race to stay ahead of Microsoft, Netscape has loaded Navigator with so many features that downloading has turned into an hour-long ordeal. So Netscape is having to adopt more conventional (and expensive) methods to get the latest version of its browser into the hands of users: it is hard to buy a modem or e-mail software these days without a copy of Navigator being thrown in free. Netscape even bundles its software with Hewlett-Packard's popular consumer printers (which must have impressed Microsoft; the software giant plans to do the same).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Haeberli admits that Netscape's market share will shrink under Mr Gates's bombardment. Interse, a Web tracking firm, reports that the number of visitors using Internet Explorer at its site has doubled to 16% in the past month. Mr Haeberli claims that browsers are just one battle in a much bigger Internet war. He compares the marketplace to a sea of fog with a few hills visible nearby. Netscape dominates the browser hill; Microsoft may soon replace it. "People assume that this is the highest hill, but we're not making that mistake." 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What might be a higher one? If Netscape knows, it is not telling. This sounds a little like putting a flag in front of a retreat and calling it a parade, but there are grounds for trusting Netscape. In the race for the next big thing, it is often wise to favour the firm that found the last one.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?840236400,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
