<html><head><title>Business This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw2.gif" width=273 height=24  alt="Business"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><h2>Of no import</h2></p>
<p><p><b>Malaysia </b>said that it might introduce quotas and higher import duties if the country's current-account deficit does not shrink soon. Like other South-East Asian countries, Malaysia is adjusting to a slowdown in galloping export growth.
<p>(See <a href="wtw1.gif">chart</a>)<br>The rise in the <b>Swiss franc</b>, which seems to be the result largely of a flight by investors out of the <font size=-1>D</font>-mark ahead of European economic and monetary union, is causing problems. The Swiss central bank is under pressure to cut interest rates--but the inflow of capital is helping to push up monetary growth, risking a revival of Swiss inflation.
<p>America and Japan settled their differences, more or less, over their <b>semiconductor-trade row</b>, with Japan generally getting its own way. No new import targets were set, and the two agreed to set up a chip makers' committee to watch over the industry.</p>
<p><h2>Up and away</h2></p>
<p><p>Among several American get-togethers were <b>two big takeovers</b>. <font size=-1>GE</font> Capital, General Electric's burgeoning financial-services unit, paid $1.8 billion for First Colony, a Virginia-based life-insurance company with $11 billion in assets. Consolidation in health care continued with the agreed $2.1 billion takeover by PacifiCare Health Systems of <font size=-1>FHP</font> International, which has floundered since failing to buy WellPoint 18 months ago. PacifiCare will become America's fifth-largest managed health-care outfit.
<p>Two more <b>British life insurers</b> are to merge. Refuge Group and United Friendly Group, which between them have &#163;6.5 billion ($10.1 billion) under management, will form a company called United Assurance. They plan to shed 1,800 jobs.
<p><b>Rank Organisation</b>, a big British entertainment firm, plans to restructure itself. A new holding company, Rank Group, will focus on core activities--films, recreation and the Hard Rock brand. Rank will sell non-core interests, including its minority stake in Rank Xerox. Its pre-tax profits were &#163;128m ($196m) in the first half of 1996, down from &#163;444m last year.
<p>The full privatisation of <b>Stet</b>, Italy's telecoms giant, is to go ahead. The present centre-left government overcame the opposition of communists and unions to get one of the country's biggest asset sales off the ground by next March. Stet's shares fell sharply.
<p>The French government moved Yves Michot up from managing director to become chairman of state-owned <b>A&eacute;rospatiale</b>. He will oversee the proposed merger with Dassault Aviation and the restructuring of Airbus Industrie, in which A&eacute;rospatiale has a 37% stake.</p>

</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><p><h2>Bust-ups</h2></p><p><b>Europe Online</b>, which tried to establish a multilingual Internet service to rival CompuServe, was declared bankrupt by a Luxembourg court after talks with possible purchasers failed. Meanwhile, the world's biggest on-line service, America Online, suffered an embarrassing nine-hour blackout while it was loading new software.
<p>(See <a href="wtw2.gif">chart</a>)<br>Passengers on <b>British Airways</b> moved up-class in the first quarter, boosting pre-tax profits by 11% to &#163;150m ($330m). But its share price continued to weaken as relations with its American partner worsened. <font size=-1>US</font>Air, which last week launched an antitrust suit against <font size=-1>BA</font> over its proposed alliance with American Airlines, now wants the courts to sever its three-year link with <font size=-1>BA</font>.
<p>Japan's Sony and Philips of the Netherlands are to begin licensing patents for the next generation of <b>digital video discs</b>, saying they are fed up with endless talks in the consumer-electronics industry on the pooling of patents which has delayed the launch of a new range of <font size=-1>DVD</font>s.</p>
<p><h2>Embarrassing</h2></p>
<p><p>The <b>Bank of Japan</b> is to order several "major banks" to tighten up management of their operations abroad after an investigation in New York found, among other laxities, that many banks had not separated their dealing and settlement functions--a flaw that caused both the Barings collapse and the Daiwa debacle, when a lone trader in each case was found to be handling both functions.
<p>America's <b>National Association of Securities Dealers</b> is to spend $100m combatting abuses in the Nasdaq stockmarket, as part of a settlement with regulators. Under the deal with the Securities and Exchange Commission, which follows a two-year investigation, the <font size=-1>NASD</font> will make it easier for regulators to police dealers' trading practices.
<p>Despite a 76% increase in provisions for bad debt, <b>Union Bank of Switzerland</b>, the country's biggest, recorded first-half net profits of SFr1.11 billion ($932m), a rise of 33%. <b>Dresdner</b>, Germany's second-biggest bank, reported an even bigger profit rise of 44%, to DM1.4 billion ($950m).
<p><p>Strong growth in their Asian banking operations boosted half-year results for two London-based banking groups. Pre-tax profits at <b>HSBC</b> <b>Holdings</b> soared by 34% to &#163;2.3 billion ($5.6 billion), and at <b>Standard Chartered</b>, where business in the Middle East and Africa was also good, they rose by 27% to &#163;406m, excluding &#163;42m-worth of exceptionals.<b> Barclays Bank</b> also reported a profits increase of 15% to &#163;1.3 billion, triggering a &#163;470m share buyback.
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
