<html><head><title>Going west</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Dole in California</b></p>
<h1>Going west</h1>

<font size=-1>SAN JOSE, CALIFORNIA</font>
<p>WELCOME to California, Bob Dole: up to a point. On August 11th Mr Dole comes to San Diego in formal triumph to receive the Republican Party's nomination for president. He will thus be stuck for the better part of a week in a state where he is a daunting 27 points behind Bill Clinton. Even some of the state's top Republicans are muttering that, were it not for the convention, Mr Dole would be wiser to spend his time somewhere else.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Back in May, Mr Dole announced that he would fight Bill Clinton tooth and nail for California. That was sensible. If Mr Dole can deprive Mr Clinton of California's 54 electoral-college votes, Mr Clinton is probably finished. So Ken Khachigian, Mr Dole's planner for California, promised Mr Clinton "80 days of hell" after the San Diego convention. So far, it is mostly Mr Dole who has been getting Californian hell.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In late March, he was 21 opinion-poll points behind Mr Clinton among registered voters, but everyone expected that gap to narrow in the summer. Republicans insisted that California has a notoriously volatile electorate. John Herrington, chairman of the state's Republican Party, said at the beginning of June that he would target the south of California, Los Angeles and the area east of it known as the "inland empire". "We go back and get our base," explained Mr Khachigian in the local language in June. "Then we incrementally start rebuilding. Then, once that's done, we start going for swing voters--this I anticipate post-convention."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No luck, yet. Since then, despite a series of trips by Mr Dole to California, the gap has widened to 27 points, according to a poll on July 18th by the <i>Los Angeles Times</i>. Mr Khachigian has not yet nailed down his base. A quarter of California's Republicans prefer Mr Clinton; of Republican women, fully a third do. From Shasta County in the remote north to the Republican heartland of Orange County, Mr Dole has tried to punch every usual Californian button: talking angrily about cuts in the defence industry, blasting illegal immigration, making a tepidly conciliatory speech about Hollywood, saying that Mr Clinton's environmentalism has hurt loggers in the north of the state. Nothing has helped. Mr Clinton had already hit all those buttons.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Democrats are gleeful. "Bob Dole's eight years older than Yeltsin, and unlike Yeltsin he can't do the twist," says Bob Mulholland, the campaign adviser of California's Democratic Party. Bill Carrick, Mr Clinton's planner for California, gloats about the effect of Mr Dole's five campaign visits: "I'm really disappointed Dole hasn't given us more time out here."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Dole people reply that they have not yet begun to fight. There is some plausibility to this. Mr Dole's campaign has been penniless so far this summer, and Mr Clinton continues to lavish attention on California; on August 7th he came to San Jose to kick off his 26th visit to the state as president. Mr Dole's coffers open up again after the convention, according to federal campaign spending rules. And the convention itself will give Mr Dole lots of free time on television. If the unruly Republicans can keep their convention conventional, the show in San Diego should bring Mr Dole a bounce in the polls.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It had better be huge. As the San Diego convention ends, the Dole people will be deciding whether it is worth buying lots of advertisements in California. With so many mid-western states in dispute, and with signs of weakness even in Republican strongholds in the South, Mr Dole can ill afford to throw his dollars at a massive gap in this state. "If the convention were in any of the other 49 states," says Dan Schnur, a former spokesman for Pete Wilson, California's Republican governor, "California could and should be a write-off." 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But if Mr Dole bombs in California, he could drag the whole state-wide party down. Lots of California's Republicans are grateful to Mr Dole for not giving up on the state altogether, as George Bush did in 1992, but that gratitude is wearing thin. That same <i>Los Angeles Times </i>poll on July 18th showed the Republicans lagging in the race for Congress, with 40% to the Democrats' 51%. There are half a dozen vulnerable Republican members of Congress, including the fire-breathing Bob Dornan in Orange County, still weak after his failed run for the presidential nomination. In the state's legislature, the Democrats are expected to keep control of the Senate, and hope to wrest the Assembly from the Republicans.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Already, the Dole campaign's weakness is showing. Mr Wilson and Mr Dole are sniping at each other. Mr Wilson came back from the brink of oblivion in 1994 by linking his gubernatorial campaign to Proposition 187, a ballot initiative stripping illegal immigrants of social services; now he wants Mr Dole to try the same trick with Proposition 209, which would bar affirmative-action for minorities and women. Mr Dole is having none of that. Ward Connerly, a black Wilson man who is pushing Proposition 209, has been denied the chance to make a speech at the convention. For his part, Mr Wilson, who is pro-choice, is threatening a floor fight over abortion. If California continues to treat Mr Dole so well, he may come to wish he had had his convention in Massachusetts.




