<html><head><title>Deflating the bounce</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Deflating the bounce</h1>

IF AMERICANS hate politics, as has been claimed, they must loathe conventions. Television ratings suggest this is how things are going. The number of viewers watching these demonstrations of artificial exhilaration has gone down steadily in recent years. And the famous "bounce"--the rise in the opinion polls that candidates hope to get from the cheering at the convention--is no real pointer to election-day success (see <a href="am1.gif">chart</a>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In 1960, households watching the conventions of John Kennedy and Richard Nixon (nearly 84% of the total) tuned in for an average of 8.58 hours each; the more photogenic Mr Kennedy drew more viewers, and went on to win the election. By 1984, only 72% of the country was watching, for an average of only 3.05 hours; the less photogenic Walter Mondale drew more viewers than Ronald Reagan but--beware, Mr Dole--did not get elected. In 1992, only about 21% of households were tuning into convention coverage at any given moment, down from 28% in 1968.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What of the bounce? Does it help a candidate to victory? Not necessarily. Bill Clinton's 16-point bounce in 1992, the largest since such polls were begun, was followed by his election. But two of the three candidates who achieved the next biggest bounces of the past quarter-century--Jimmy Carter in 1980 and Walter Mondale in 1984--went on to lose the election. And, though Ronald Reagan's 1984 bounce was tiny, his presidential victory was vast.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although the networks' planned coverage of the conventions is fairly skimpy, at least there will be no competition from a baseball all-star game, as there was in 1992. Given the presence of <font size=-1>CNN</font>, <font size=-1>MSNBC</font> and <font size=-1>C</font>-Span, which will offer convention coverage, much of it live, for 24 hours a day, interested Americans can watch all the speeches, balloons and placards they can stomach.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Republican faithful have still another option. Unhappy with the filter of plain independent journalism, Haley Barbour, the party's chairman, got private financing to air <font size=-1>GOP-TV</font> on the Family Channel, which is controlled by the televangelist founder of the Christian Coalition, Pat Robertson. If Peter Jennings and Tom Brokaw cannot ensure a bounce, Mr Dole is hoping the political equivalent of infomercials will.
</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839631600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="as1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
