HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 15:38:06 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 18:10:21 GMT
Content-length: 3055
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Hard line on porn</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>

</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<p><b>Policing the Internet</b></p>
<h1>Hard line on porn</h1>

<p>INTERNET providers have had a rough time dealing with zealous European authorities worried about the dissemination of pornography. In December, Bavarian prosecutors stormed into the German headquarters of CompuServe, an American on-line service, with a warrant to ban 200 allegedly pornographic newsgroups (public discussion forums). CompuServe complied, shutting off these areas to all its subscribers for several weeks. And in May, French police arrested two prominent Internet managers in France for allegedly distributing paedophilic images. The men were released a few days later, but only after, in true Gallic style, other providers had staged a cyberspace strike, switching off parts of their networks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;How much more civilised, then, was the meeting on August 2nd between British Internet providers and members of Scotland Yard's Clubs and Vice Unit. Like the Bavarian cops, the police were worried about pornography carried on Internet newsgroups. A sizeable proportion of the perhaps 20,000 newsgroups on the Internet deal with sexual topics, ranging from support for victims of abuse to particular sexual fetishes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The guardians of the law explained that the alternatives were police action against the providers or self-regulation. Faced with this choice, the Internet Service Providers Association (<font size=-1>ISPA</font>), which represents most of Britain's providers, has agreed to take the latter course, and block 1,000 newsgroups which Scotland Yard has deemed to be carrying illegal pornography.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;While there is much to be said for the softly-softly attitude of the police, the approach has a number of deficiencies. First, the vast majority of illicit material on newsgroups is not pornography but pirated commercial software. Second, hard-line pornographers might use innocent-sounding groups to distribute material. Third, Britain's obscenity legislation is incoherent. Until it makes sense, neither the police nor the providers will really know when the law is being broken.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
