<html><head><title>Monopoly game</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>The Post Office</b></p>
<h1>Monopoly game</h1>
<p>

THE Post Office's exclusive right to deliver letters charged at less than &#163;1 was suspended on August 5th, a day before the latest in a string of 24-hour strikes by postal workers over pay and working practices. The suspension is a clear signal to the unions that the government is prepared to undermine the Post Office's profitability if they persist in their action. Already, in several cities, private companies are beginning to nibble away at the corners of the monopoly. This suspension will encourage them, and the nibbles may become bites.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Until the suspension, the Post Office had the power to investigate and prosecute firms that broke its monopoly. In 1994 it won a High Court injunction to stop Deltec, a courier firm, from running a cut-price postal service in Edinburgh.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But it has been slower to act against First Class Mail, which is charging 17p for next-day delivery in Portsmouth (the Post Office charges 26p) and says it is delivering "several thousand" letters a week. Ray Judic, the firm's general manager, says he got a warning letter from the Post Office when he started the service three years ago, but has heard nothing since.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Dave Fowler, a director of <font size=-1>CCP</font>, which is offering cut-price postal services in Nottingham, says he was recently grilled for four hours by Post Office investigators. Since then, he has changed his pricing structure. He now charges each customer &#163;3.99 for the first letter, and then gives the next 20 deliveries free, which works out at the same 19p a letter he used to charge. Mr Fowler hopes this will get around the &#163;1 minimum charge imposed by law, though this seems unlikely. <font size=-1>CCP</font> handles 7,000 letters a day, mainly from businesses such as solicitors, estate agents and doctors, who send most of their mail to local addresses.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Winning Post, of Chesterfield, delivers about 5,000 letters a day, charging 20p for first-class deliveries. Rather than claiming to have found a way around the monopoly, Paul Revill, the firm's manager, argues that all monopolies are illegal under European Union law. No doubt the Post Office and the other national postal monopolies across the <font size=-1>EU</font> would dispute this, but the matter has not been tested in the courts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Cut-price postal services have also been set up in Mansfield and Derby, and, since the suspension of the Post Office monopoly, cheap deliveries have arrived in London: City Post, a courier firm, is offering its customers (mostly law firms, banks and other big businesses) same-day deliveries in the City and West End from as little as 25p.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Post Office argues that if it is to continue making daily deliveries to every address in Britain for the same price, then it must keep its monopoly. Competitors would undercut the Post Office for the most lucrative deliveries in towns and cities, leaving it the unprofitable business of delivering to remote rural areas.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But its fledgling rivals cast doubt on its arguments. Mr Revill of Winning Post says the Post Office "wastes billions and is very inefficient" and reckons he could easily provide a cheaper service in rural areas, if allowed to. Whether or not he could, why should the vast majority of post users, who are based in towns and cities, pay a disguised tax in the form of higher postal charges, to subsidise daily deliveries to remote parts of the Outer Hebrides? It would probably be cheaper to give them all a fax machine.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government would like to privatise the Post Office, but in 1994 it was forced to drop its plans by backbenchers worried about cuts in services in rural areas. However, the same fears were expressed when telephone services were being privatised, and turned out to be groundless.

<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
