<html><head><title>Wrong numbers</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>


<h1>Wrong numbers</h1>

<p>ON AUGUST 5th, Oftel, the telecoms industry regulator, published a consultative paper which broke the news that many of Britain's biggest cities would need new telephone numbers before the end of the century. This latest upheaval--the fourth since 1990, when London was split in two, inner and outer--springs from the success of Britain's deregulated telephone industry. Demand is booming and competition is spreading. Some parts of the country have six operators touting for business. This, however, is no comfort to Britain's furious phone-users.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Because of rising demand for lines, London, Cardiff, Belfast, Portsmouth and Southampton will run out of numbers within four years, as will some 30 more areas within 20 years. Oftel proposes scrapping these five cities' existing four- or five-digit telephone codes (that begin with 01), replacing them with a new set of three-digit codes (beginning with 02) and extending numbers to seven or eight digits. To make things easier for customers, old and new codes will run in parallel for several months before the old ones are phased out.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The British public is inclined to blame Oftel. Oftel is inclined to blame <font size=-1>BT</font>, the former state-owned monopoly. Oftel argues that it did not take control of telephone numbers from <font size=-1>BT</font> until 1994 and found itself holding a can of worms without enough time to sort them out before "ph<font size=-1>ONE</font>day" in April 1995, when a 1 was inserted after the 0 in most codes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Oftel is now trying to stay ahead of the game. It has proposed some sensible uses for other phone codes, which will mean annoying mini-disruptions: 05 numbers for big companies, 07 for mobile phones, pagers and personal numbers, 08 for free and cheap calls and 09 for premium-rate services. These changes would make it easier for customers to tell how much a telephone call will cost before they make it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Britons can comfort themselves that things are worse elsewhere. Telephone numbers in Germany and Austria have become an anarchic mess of between ten and 15 digits. Some numbers are now so long that some international calls to them fail. New Yorkers have had to put up with repeated telephone code splits: there will soon be 13 codes for the metropolitan area. The French telecoms authorities take no prisoners: on October 18th, when local dialling will be abolished entirely, new numbers will come in, and old numbers will be abolished, overnight.



</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
