<html><head><title>Accelerating</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>



<p><b>Traffic</b></p>

<h1>Accelerating</h1>



<p>AS LONDONERS fume in the capital's traffic jams, aggravated by this summer's tube strikes, they can ponder upon the fact that the future will probably be worse. A study to be published by the Automobile Association (<font size=-1>AA</font>) next month will reveal an unstoppable growth in traffic.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are now more than 25m cars in Britain, an increase of 20% over the past decade. In the last 40 years, travel by car has risen tenfold while travel by bus has fallen by half. Cars now account for 87% of all passenger miles compared to just over a quarter in 1950 (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>). The government has done little to discourage this growth, other than to increase fuel taxes by a real 5% a year. Local authorities are shortly to be given powers to deal with the pollution that results, including closing roads and controlling the speed, volume and type of traffic.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;According to the author of the <font size=-1>AA</font>'s study, Stephen Glaister, an economist at the London School of Economics, some 47% of households now have more than one car, compared with 39% in 1988. Expenditure on motoring rises almost exactly in line with increases in income, so the numbers will depend on economic growth. The Department of Transport predicts that traffic will double over the next 30 years: ministers have been trying to massage this forecast downwards, without success.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The potential for growth in the nation's car fleet is huge. Britain's car ownership per head is in the middle rank of developed countries; much lower, for instance, than in the United States, Germany and Italy. This is likely to change. Only 37% of British women in their 60s have driving licences compared with 70% of those in their 40s. As these motoring daughters replace their non-driving mothers, car ownership and use is bound to increase.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Britain already has some of the most congested roads in Western Europe, with twice as many cars per road mile as France or Belgium. The average British driver now spends five days stuck in traffic jams every year. Motoring organisations claim this could treble within a decade.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are no obvious solutions in sight. The unpopularity of building new roads or charging for road space has terrified ministers into paralysis. Increased fuel prices have done little to ease congestion. Motorists are so attached to their cars that, according to a survey carried out by Lex, a big car dealership, even if the price of fuel were to double, fewer than a third of those who drive to work would stop doing so. Nor, apparently, will the prospect of ever-increasing congestion do much to help. Eight out of ten drivers who commute to work would still use their cars even if traffic delays doubled, according to the Lex survey.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Improving public transport would make much less difference than is often assumed. A 50% increase in rail use would reduce road traffic by 5%. A study of five British cities by the Transport Research Laboratory, an independent research agency, found that halving bus fares would reduce car use by less than 1%.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So is there no hope of living peacefully with the car? There are some obvious ways forward if only the political will could be found. Most car journeys are short--more than half are under under five miles, a quarter under two miles. Many of these journeys could be done by bus, cycle or on foot if the right incentives were in place. A study on car dependence published by the Royal Automobile Club last year found that the use of a car was essential for only about a fifth of journeys. Persuading more drivers to leave their cars behind will require a shrewd mix of incentives such as free out-of-town parking and regulatory stick such as inner-city pedestrian-only zones. Charging for scarce road space might be even more effective. The idea terrifies politicians.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
