<html><head><title>Is there life on Mars?</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/st.gif" width=371 height=26  alt="Science And Technology">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Is there life on Mars?</h1>
<p><b>Maybe</b></p>

<p>IT MIGHT, as David Bowie once sang, be a God-awful small affair, or it might be the scientific discovery of the century. A group of American researchers, led by David McKay of the Johnson Space Centre in Houston, Texas, (a part of <font size=-1>NASA</font>, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration) has cut open a 2kg lump of rock and found evidence that it was once inhabited by alien life forms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The rock is a meteorite, known as <font size=-1>ALH84001</font>, which was found in the Allan Hills in Antarctica some 12 years ago. The evidence comes in four parts. First, this particular meteorite started life as part of the Martian surface. Second, it contains organic compounds (by which chemists mean complex molecules based on carbon, not necessarily the products of biological activity), which seem also to have originated on Mars. Third, there are tiny crystals of iron oxide and iron sulphide that look as though they may be the products of biological activity. And fourth, there are small spheres of carbonate material that look suggestively biological in origin and may contain actual fossils.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This evidence will now be extensively probed. The first bit seems secure. Most chemical elements consist of several different sorts of atom, known as isotopes, that weigh slightly different amounts depending on the number of neutrons in their nuclei. In different parts of the solar system, any given element consists of slightly different mixtures of these isotopes. The oxygen in the Allan Hills meteorite has an isotopic composition characteristic of Mars.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The rock, one of about a dozen reckoned to have travelled from Mars to earth, has clearly had an adventurous history. It was formed volcanically, some 4.5 billion years ago--close to the birth of the solar system. The bit of Martian surface that it inhabited was then smashed up every so often by asteroid strikes until about 3.6 billion years ago, creating a pattern of small fractures<b>. </b>At some point after that it seems to have been immersed in running water. It was then blasted away from the planet's surface by another asteroid impact about 15m years ago, which probably accounts for a second set of fractures. After that it orbited the sun until 13,000 years ago, when it ran into the earth, landing in Antarctica.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second piece of evidence relies on the presence of organic chemicals known as polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (<font size=-1>PAH</font>s). These are widespread on earth (they are found in coal and petroleum; naphthalene, the material used in mothballs, is an example). They are also found in other parts of the solar system, including certain meteorites. Not, it might be thought, strong evidence for Martian life. But the <font size=-1>PAH</font>s in the Allan Hills meteorite are unusual. They resemble neither common terrestrial ones, nor meteoritic ones. Instead, they look surprisingly like the sort into which bacteria dissolve when subjected to rock-forming processes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The particles of iron oxide and iron sulphide also look like the products of bacteria. The iron oxide is in the form of magnetite--a substance that is, as its name suggests, magnetic. Many earthly bacteria secrete particles of magnetite within themselves. These are known as magnetosomes, and are believed to help the bacteria containing them to navigate, by allowing such bacteria to orient themselves with the earth's magnetic field. Iron sulphide is also a common bacterial product, associated with those bacteria that do not need oxygen to respire.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The most interesting evidence of all comes from the carbonate spheres. These, the researchers claim, must have been created before the meteorite arrived on earth because some of them are cracked by whatever last shocked the rock. Even if this did not happen when it left Mars, it could not possibly have happened after its impact in Antarctica.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That the particles of magnetite and iron sulphide are embedded within the spheres is therefore good evidence that these, too, were not formed on earth. But the spheres themselves are very suggestive. They seem to have grown by accretion, and the chemical details of the different layers, as well as the order in which they were laid down, are, the researchers say, what would be expected if they had been produced by living creatures rather than non-biological processes. And, perhaps most significantly of all, the researchers' eye of faith can see fossils of those creatures on the surface of the spheres. These "fossils" are a mere 100 millionths of a millimetre long; they are similar in size and shape to terrestrial nanobacteria, about the smallest known of all life-forms.
</p><p><b>It's the freakiest show</b></b>
<br>None of this amounts to proof, of course. But it is all very suggestive. Some words of caution are necessary, though.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;First, science has been here once before. In the 1960s many students of the origin of life became excited about a meteorite known as the Orgueil impact (it fell in France in 1864). Bartholomew Nagy, at the University of Arizona, in Tucson, found that it contained, besides abundant quantities of organic molecules, a variety of structures that he named "organised elements", but which were widely believed at the time to be microscopic fossils. They were not. One turned out to be a grain of ragweed pollen. Another was a particle of furnace ash. To be fair to Dr Nagy (who died a few months ago), he never himself claimed he had found traces of life. And most of his organised elements were, indeed, indigenous to the meteorite. But, since then, researchers have been extremely cautious in the claims they have made.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Rightly so. The possibilities for terrestrial contamination of a meteorite are enormous. Antarctica is not Gascony, but industrial pollution is ubiquitous. Artificial organic chemicals can be detected even in the south pole's pristine climate. And the past few years have also shown that life is far more tenacious and tolerant than had been imagined. Bacteria have been found living in hot springs at the bottom of the ocean, in lakes under the Antarctic ice, even in the middle of rocks, apparently subsisting on the minerals they find there.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;For those who favour the idea of life on Mars, this is all to the good. Although its history includes running water (and therefore an atmosphere thick enough to stop such water vaporising into space), by human standards Mars has never been exactly hospitable. The existence of earthly bacteria that could have thrived in Mars's past is, from this point of view, encouraging. But it also makes the possibility of contamination more plausible. Dr McKay's group's results were trailed at the Lunar and Planetary Science conference in Houston two years ago. No one was particularly impressed at the time, mainly because it was felt that the <font size=-1>PAH</font>s were probably the result of terrestrial contamination.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There are still sceptics. Yet Dr McKay and his team feel they have now laid the idea that the <font size=-1>PAH</font>s are the result of contamination to rest. Apart from the low levels of <font size=-1>PAH</font> pollution in Antarctica, the concentration of the chemicals in the Allan Hills meteorite is higher in the middle than at the edges and not, therefore, likely to be the result of inward leakage.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The other evidence has come under scrutiny, as well. Ian Franchi, of the Open University in Britain, which has one of Europe's foremost meteorite research centres, points out that carbonate spheres tend to grow on rocks left lying around after they have been brought out of the Antarctic cold, though this would not explain why some of those spheres are cracked. Other researchers, such as Beda Hoffman at the Natural History Museum in Berne, Switzerland, fear that the evidence for nanobacteria may have been "over-interpreted". The origins of such tiny particles are hard enough to pin down in terrestrial rocks, let alone in meteorites. Almost all researchers, though, are united in a wish that Dr McKay and his team actually prove correct.
</p><p><b>The best selling show, too</b></b>
<br>Whether they do or not, their claim comes at an opportune moment. The past ten months have seen the emergence of a new discipline--the study of other solar systems. Though long predicted, the first of these (bar one freaky one around a pulsar) was not discovered until October last year. Now more than half a dozen are known or suspected. They are centred on nearby, otherwise unexceptional stars. Planets, it seems, are normal fare in the cosmos.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This puts a different complexion on the search for extra-terrestrial life. Though a few science-fiction writers, such as Fred Hoyle, have dreamed up creatures that live in interplanetary space, most anchor their imaginary charges firmly on the surfaces of planets. The more planets there are out there, the more "platforms" there are upon which life could evolve.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;It will not, of course, be possible to visit these planets with the sort of spacecraft that current technology and budgets can build, but they may provide inspiration--something that space programmes the world over have been sorely lacking since the glory days of the 1960s and 70s. And visiting Mars, after all, is certainly possible.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If the red planet has harboured life in the past (and even if there is none there at present), fossils are likely to be widespread. It should not be necessary to send all that many robot landers to pick up rocks and bring them back to earth before the jackpot, if it exists, is hit. At present, the first <font size=-1>NASA</font> mission that will do this is not scheduled to take off until well after 2000. The agency plans to send the first of a series of non-returning missions there in November. But a report by America's National Research Council says that unless <font size=-1>NASA</font> gets more money to back up these plans, their scientific objectives could be "seriously undermined". <font size=-1>NASA</font> will be delighted that the new result prompted President Clinton to put America's "full prowess behind the search for further evidence of life on Mars." Looking at meteorites is one thing. But to be certain, the only answer is to go to Mars and bring back some rocks.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839631600,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>

</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
