<html><head><title>Reacting to terrorism</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>

<h1><center>Reacting to terrorism</center></h1>

TRUTH, it is said, is one of war's casualties. In the case of terrorism, truth may more or less survive but to the list of tragically real victims must nevertheless be added some of the more abstract sort: consistency, on the part of politicians; and self-restraint, on their part and the part of commentators. Admittedly, each new outrage challenges the ability to respond with the right blend of credibility and determination. But, alas, there has been no shortage of practice--the pipe-bomb in Atlanta that killed two people on July 27th and the probable bombing of a <font size=-1>TWA</font> aircraft off New York on July 17th, killing 230 people, were but the latest in a long, bloody line. And in these cases, as so often in the past, consistency has been sacrificed to posturing, self-restraint to hyperbole.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The second of these victims is the more understandable, if still regrettable. The whole point of the terrorist act is to provoke a reaction disproportionate to the act itself. The truest terror is the random sort, which carries the implication that anyone, anywhere, might find themselves the next target. America is a violent country, but most people think they can avoid the violence because they know roughly where, and in what circumstances, most violence takes place. Assassinations, too, pose a different threat: only a narrow category of people believe themselves to be vulnerable to them. Terrorist bombs, placed in parks, on aircraft or (as in Oklahoma last year) outside office buildings, spread their fear more widely. Whether they are placed by an individual or by a group, and whether or not the perpetrator discloses the motive for the bombing, the intention is the same: to cause panic.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Which is why the greater the outcry, the greater the alarm, the more the terrorist will consider his risks to have been worth the reward. It is not possible, or desirable, to ignore a bomb. But to carry on as planned, treating the bombing as a marginal, criminal occurrence to be dealt with in the manner of other crimes, is the best way to limit that reward. That was the choice correctly made by the Olympic authorities. It was not the choice made by those who yelled that "something must be done", nor by the politicians, President Clinton among them, who reached in their drawers and dusted off their "tough on terrorism" files, proposing new legislation and demanding international action at a summit in Paris.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The implication of new legislation is perverse: if laws could control terrorism, why aren't they already there? This phenomenon is not new, even in America. Moreover, Mr Clinton's proposals could threaten civil liberties (see <a href="am1.html">page</a>), infringing the very freedoms (of speech, communication, movement) that terrorists thrive on attacking. And the implication of demands for international action, through trade sanctions, against "rogue nations" believed to sponsor terrorism (Iran, Iraq, Sudan and Libya) is more sinister: it reveals an instinct to find foreigners to blame, be they the rogue nations themselves, or the duplicitous Europeans or Asians who refuse to go along with sanctions.
<br>
<br>
<b>The trade-offs begin at home
</b><br>That is where the posturing comes in. America is not the only country guilty of self-serving inconsistency in its reaction to terrorism, but it is the latest, and perhaps clearest, example.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Terrorism can be countered even if, by its very nature, it can never be eliminated altogether. But there are awkward trade-offs to be made. If the terrorist is to be deprived of his opportunities to cause devastation then money needs to be spent on increased security measures at vulnerable locations. And not just money: the price of luggage screening, metal detectors and security interviews with air passengers, for example, is also measured in time, bad tempers and congestion. America's airports, and its Federal Aviation Authority, have in the past chosen not to ask their customers to pay that price. Perhaps rightly, for the price is high, relative to the risk. Yet instead of making that choice explicit, and defending it, they have sought to pass the price on, blaming foreign airports for terrorism and insisting on tighter security there. The result is absurd: although the risks are similar, a passenger flying on American Airlines from London faces tight security; one travelling on the same airline from New York is barely hindered.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This same habit, of seeking to sound tough but without paying the price for it, can be found in America's demand that "rogue nations" be punished through trade sanctions. Where there is hard evidence that a government is responsible, directly or indirectly, for terrorism, there could be grounds for retaliation, by military or other means. But where the evidence is vague or even non-existent, such a tactic is both counter-productive and dangerous. Counter-productive, because it fuels such countries' resentments and allows their leaders to forge unity out of adversity. Dangerous, because once sanctions are imposed they are hard to remove as pressure groups and protectionists come to find them convenient. Like laws that infringe civil liberties, they also damage something essential to a democratic society: the idea that justice requires hard evidence and due process of law.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;At some point, evidence may be found, notably in the case of the <font size=-1>TWA</font> airliner. Then, and only then, punishments can be considered. For the time being, the response must be a mixture of caution and calculation: caution, so as not to over-react; calculation, about the gritty trade-offs that vigilance, security and detection entail.<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839026800,iss">Search</a>
 
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="am1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
