<html><head><title>Politics This Week</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center>
<img src="../images/wtw1.gif" width=271 height=24  alt="Politics"></p>

<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><h2>Thunderous</h2></p>
<p><p>Responsibility for the Atlanta bomb, which killed two people and injured hundreds, increasingly seemed to lie at home. Painstaking recovery of the wreckage of <font size=-1>TWA</font> flight 800 revealed no hard evidence but a firmer belief that a bomb destroyed the aircraft. Bill Clinton and congressional leaders agreed that more must be done to prevent <b>terrorism</b>; and the Group of Seven countries plus Russia promised to draft by November a treaty to make terrorist bombing an international crime.
<p>Changing 60 years of political history, Mr Clinton at last signed the Republicans' bill that abolishes automatic
<b>welfare</b> entitlements for Americans. Welfare will now be a "second chance", not a "way of life".
<p>After 5.5 years as <b>Argentina's</b> globally respected economics minister, Domingo Cavallo was replaced, as pressure grew for less austerity and more growth. The job went to the--equally orthodox--central-bank president, Roque Fernandez. Policy would not change, he said, to financial markets' relief. But trade unions said a general strike already called for August 8th would go ahead.</p>
<p><h2>Fly-past</h2></p>
<p><p>Turkish <font size=-1>MP</font>s voted to let American warplanes continue to fly from bases in Turkey to protect Kurds in northern Iraq after Necmettin Erbakan, the new Islamist prime minister, reversed his earlier opposition to <b>Operation Provide Comfort</b>.
<p>A 69-day <b>hunger strike</b> by political prisoners in Turkey, in which 12 people died, ended after the government met some of the prisoners' demands.
<p>An American envoy, John Kornblum, went to <b>Bosnia</b> and won an agreement to strengthen the Muslim-Croat Federation. He also wanted to ensure that Radovan Karadzic has kept his pledge to step down as leader of Bosnia's Serbs. The European Union threatened to pull its mission out of the town of Mostar unless Croats there accept the results of municipal elections, won by Muslims.
<p><b>Pravda </b>("Truth"), founded by Lenin and as hardline as ever, was closed by its Greek owners. They accused the paper's journalists of drinking too much and of partisan reporting.
<p>Members of the European Union have failed to use 20 billion ecus ($25 billion) of <b>aid</b> available for poor regions, according to a commission report, with Italy the worst performer. Many governments are trying to meet targets for economic and monetary union and have difficulty matching <font size=-1>EU</font> contributions. Budget ministers, meanwhile, agreed to cut 2.5 billion ecus ($3.2 billion) from the <b>European Union's budget</b> next year.
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p>Spain announced increases in <b>taxes on tobacco and alcohol</b> to cover an unexpected shortfall of 721 billion pesetas ($5.7 billion) in last year's public accounts.
<p>The European Commission proposed the slaughter of up to <b>2m calves</b> to support beef prices, which collapsed after mad-cow disease was linked to people. Part of the 2 billion ecu ($2.5 billion) cost would come from cutting subsidies to cereal farmers. A British study indicated that <font size=-1>BSE</font> could be passed from cows to their calves.</p>
<p><h2>African action</h2></p>
<p><p>East African leaders, meeting in Tanzania, agreed to impose full economic sanctions on <b>Burundi</b>. They called on Pierre Buyoya, Burundi's new military leader, to restore the constitution, parliament and political parties--but stopped short of demanding the reinstatement of President Ntibantunganya, ousted last week. Mr Buyoya, a Tutsi, made a bid to end the ethnic fighting by appointing a Hutu prime minister.
<p>In northern <b>Uganda</b>, armed members of the Lord's Resistance Army cult were reported to have killed 60 villagers and 40 soldiers.
<p>Fifteen commuters were killed in a<b> stampede at a railway station</b> near Johannesburg during a crackdown on people travelling without tickets.
<p>Lebanon's president put an end to speculation that a <b>Lebanese-Israeli peace</b> might precede a Syrian-Israeli one. An Israeli news report said a Syrian envoy had visited Jerusalem.
<p>The Palestinian Authority, having helped the Israelis find the<b> body of an Israeli soldier</b> murdered by Hamas seven years ago, appealed to Israel's prime minister to free Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, the wheelchair-bound cleric imprisoned for life for ordering the killing. A Palestinian died after apparent torture in a West Bank prison.</p>
<p><h2>Testing</h2></p>
<p><p>China conducted a <b>nuclear test</b> and then said it would call an indefinite halt to all further tests. The announcement coincided with the re-opening in Geneva of talks aimed at completing a worldwide ban on future tests. Both India and China continue to express reservations about the proposed draft text.
<p>Troops killed at least three people in <b>Jakarta</b>, the Indonesian capital, after riots broke out. The cause of the disturbance was a government decision to evict supporters of Megawati Sukarnoputri, an opposition leader, from the headquarters of the political party she had led until recently.
<p><b>Benazir Bhutto</b>, the prime minister of Pakistan, said she would appoint her husband to the cabinet, as part of a government reshuffle.
<p>China protested after Ryutaro Hashimoto, Japan's prime minister, made a visit to a shrine commemorating <b>Japan's war dead</b>.
<p>
<p>
<p>
</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
