<html><head><title>Do it with care</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Fighting terrorism</b></p>
<h1>Do it with care</h1>

<font size=1>ATLANTA AND WASHINGTON, DC</font>
<p>LEGISLATE in haste, repent at leisure: it should be obvious that rushed legislation, like a rushed marriage, is liable to end in tears. But politicians can be just as foolish as young lovers. Bill Clinton is already living with the consequences, including an angry dispute with America's closest allies, of his recent decision to tighten the embargo against Cuba--against his own better judgment, but in response to many Americans' irritation about the exploitation by outsiders of nationalised property in Cuba, and their outrage over the behaviour of Cuba's government. Now, in a climate of fear and fury over both the bomb at the Atlanta Olympics and the crash of <font size=-1>TWA</font> flight 800, the president is in a hurry to pass a new law to combat terrorism.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In an election year, when the last thing Mr Clinton wants is to be accused of being soft on crime, this is good politics. But is it going to prove good sense?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The same temptation to act fast followed the bombing of the federal building in Oklahoma City last year. Early professions of bipartisan resolve dissolved into disputes over the details as congressmen examined the proposals and a strange coalition of interests--from civil libertarians to gun owners--expressed their opposition. It took a year for the so-called Terrorism Prevention Act to pass, and when it did it excluded some of the main measures that the White House had originally proposed.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Now Mr Clinton sees an opportunity to resurrect those measures (or at least to remind voters of how tough he would like to be). He is asking Congress to provide money for a study of the effectiveness of adding chemical markers, or "taggants", to explosives, to make them easier to trace. He would like approval for various changes that would help law-enforcement agencies to keep tabs on suspected terrorists: readier access to hotel and airline records, and an easing of rules on "multi-point" wiretaps that allow the monitoring of telephone calls by a suspect wherever he roams, not just from a particular telephone line. Ideally, the White House would like Congress to do these things before its summer break begins on August 3rd.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this is happening before it is certain who or what caused the <font size=-1>TWA</font> and Atlanta deaths, and therefore what might have prevented them. Immediately after the pipe bomb exploded in the early hours of July 27th in the crowded Centennial Olympic Park in Atlanta--killing one woman on the spot, indirectly causing the fatal heart attack of a Turkish cameraman, and injuring scores of others--suspicions fell on America's home-grown militia groups, which everybody has been peering at suspiciously ever since the Oklahoma City bombing.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;By July 30th, investigators were focusing on a burly security guard, Richard Jewell, who had spotted the suspicious backpack and been hailed as a hero for his life-saving efforts. But Mr Jewell, a former deputy sheriff in north-eastern Georgia and now an employee of a security firm hired by <font size=-1>AT&T</font> to patrol the company's pavilion in the Olympic Park, sturdily denies having planted the bomb.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even before the Atlanta Games opened, Olympic security officials were mindful of an incident at the 1984 Los Angeles Games, when a policeman "found" a bomb in a bus for Turkish athletes, only to admit later that he had put it there himself to attract publicity. On that occasion, fortunately, the bomb did not explode, but the episode was an example of what officials considered before the Olympics to be one of the main security threats in Atlanta: individual crackpots, not organised groups.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What caused the <font size=-1>TWA</font> explosion is not yet known, although the hypothesis that the aircraft and the 230 people on board were brought down by a bomb grows stronger as, bit by excruciating bit, bodies and debris are hauled out of the sea off Long Island. The pattern of the wreckage seems to fit the theory that a blast near the front of the aircraft blew away the cockpit and the first-class cabin. If so, it seems likely that the bomb was either in the cabin or in the cargo hold just below it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The extent of remaining uncertainty makes hurried counter-measures seem inappropriate. Each time an act of what is assumed to be terrorism is committed on American soil, Americans express shock that they are no longer immune from such horrors. But in truth they never were immune, and it is not obvious that terrorism against Americans, whether home-grown or foreign, is actually on the increase. Unmistakably increasing, however, are the often pernicious actions taken in the name of making a fight against terror.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The anti-terrorism bill enacted this year, for example, contained nothing that might have stopped the blast in Oklahoma City, but it did contain provisions--some introduced by Congress, but Mr Clinton signed it anyway--that could be held to restrict the rights of many ordinary people. Mr Clinton acquiesced in big constraints on the right of appeal against death sentences. He approved extra powers to deport suspect foreigners. He expanded the scope of the death penalty. These and other actions on his part, such as his support for Internet censorship and for the compulsory registration of sex offenders, have brought accusations that the president is trampling roughshod over some cherished American freedoms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even without any legislation, sensible things can be done to reduce the threat of terrorism. Security checks at American airports (which often appear cursory) can be made more precise. Greater care can be taken in the hiring of security guards (who are often badly paid and not notably efficient). Public vigilance can be encouraged. But, in passing new laws, there is a delicate balance between people's desire for security and their right to freedom. In choosing between the two, Mr Clinton, unsurprisingly, seems mindful above all of a third consideration: his desire for re-election.



