<html><head><title>Here today...</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>


<p><b>New York's fiscal future</b></p>
<h1>Here today...</h1>

NEW YORK
<p>LIKE many other American cities, New York spends much of each year struggling to close gaps that open up in its municipal budget. In January, for instance, the city predicted a shortfall of $800m in its $32 billion budget for the 1995-96 fiscal year. By year's end in June, however, the budget was balanced and New York even boasted a surplus of some $350m. How? In part, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani relied on round after round of cost-cutting. But he also leaned heavily on $1.1 billion of "one-shot" savings, mostly sales of city assets, and intends to make use of a further $1.5 billion-worth of new one-shots in 1996-97. Therein lies what may be a fiscal time-bomb.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One-shots cause several problems. First, because they cannot be repeated, such savings leave a similar-sized hole to be plugged in coming years: selling <font size=-1>WNYC-TV</font>, a city-owned television station, may provide $204m for the 1996-97 budget, but it cannot be sold again next year. Second, many one-shots merely defer costs. In both 1993-94 and 1994-95 New York refinanced bonds to cut its current debt-service costs. But as a result, notes Alan Hevesi, the city's comptroller, New York's cumulative debt-service costs in the five subsequent fiscal years will be $126m higher. One-shots can steal future revenues, too. To help balance its 1995-96 budget, New York sold $265m of municipal mortgages. This deprived it of $30m a year in future revenues. And the city still has to repay $193m of debt that financed the housing it no longer owns.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The long-term effects of one-shots and other short-sighted budgetary measures are dissected by Mr Hevesi in a new report, and in two critical studies by the state comptroller and the state's Financial Control Board. Mr Hevesi calculates that New York's heady budget mix of one-shots, bond refinancings and two-year pay freezes for city employees saved it a total of $1.5 billion during 1995-96, and will save it a further $591m during the current fiscal year and another $211m in 1997-98. The following year, in contrast, those same measures will raise the city's costs (partly as a result of cutting its revenues) by $516m. And in 1999-2000 New York will be $1.6 billion worse off as a result of today's short-term schemes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;All this shows up clearly in the city's own forecasts of probable future budget shortfalls. Early in each calendar year city authorities predict the likely budget gaps for the next four fiscal years. Mr Hevesi notes that, in the late 1980s and early 1990s, the shortfall forecast for the fourth "out-year"--the year that is furthest from budget-makers' minds, in every sense--usually amounted to only a few percent of New York's total funds (ie, total operating revenues less state and federal aid). This reflected the city's then-cautious approach to one-shots and other measures that deferred costs. But in recent years the size of the gap projected for four years hence has soared (see <a href="am1.gif">chart</a>). Indeed, the forecast made early this year suggests that the shortfall in 1999-2000 could be as high as $5.2 billion--23% of the city's projected funds.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the past, long-term forecasts of New York's budget deficits have often proved unreliable: the early-1992 prediction of a $2.9 billion budget gap for 1995-96, for instance, proved too pessimistic. And the city has, eventually, always been able to close its gaps. Today's forecasts, however, are likely to be more accurate, for a simple reason: New York's growing use of one-shots and cost-deferring measures means that tomorrow's revenue shortfalls are increasingly set in stone. With fewer options for closing bigger and more certain gaps, New York may face a millennium meltdown.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839026800,iss">Search</a>
 
