<html><head><title>Privacy and paedophilia</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/eu.gif" width=105 height=26  alt="Europe">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>Privacy and paedophilia</h1>

<font size=1>STOCKHOLM</font>
<p>QUEEN SILVIA of Sweden does not court controversy. The German-born former Olympic Games hostess usually maintains a royal circumspection and lets her folksier husband, King Carl Gustaf, do the talking. But, in a rare television interview on July 23rd, she sparked a public row by lambasting Sweden's liberal child pornography laws. Parliament had failed for years to outlaw possession of child pornography, she complained, and she suggested it might work faster if the 349 deputies saw its horrors with their own eyes. For good measure, she proposed that newspapers publish the names of convicted paedophiles rather than, as now, protecting their identities.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Most Swedes agree with her. Close to 1m, more than a tenth of the population, have signed petitions calling for a ban on the possession of child pornography. Publishing and distributing the stuff has been illegal since 1980, but, according to the Save the Children Fund, a charity, Sweden is the only country in Europe, bar Albania, where owning it is not. That makes it a haven for paedophiles, police claim.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet Queen Silvia's sortie has attracted more outrage than assent; and it has shifted attention from pornography to the political influence of the monarchy. <i>Ex</i><i>press</i><i>en</i>, the biggest-selling daily, set up a telephone line for readers to render judgment on whether she should have spoken out. This seems odd. Sweden's monarchy has almost no power; the king's rare pronouncements--against Norwegian seal hunts and wage rises, for example--have been met with shrugs. In 1993 Queen Silvia called for censorship of childrens' videos, also a more controversial stand, without causing a stir.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So why the fuss this time? Personal liberty is almost as sacred to Swedes as are their coddled children. The constitution guarantees broad rights to freedom of expression, including the publication and possession of adult pornography. Debauchery behind closed doors, Swedes tend to believe, is a victimless peccadillo. Banning child smut without infringing other liberties is a balance Sweden is finding hard to strike.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hence its hesitant approach to reform. A parliamentary commission set up two years ago has become mired in dispute and controversy. One member did the cause no good by suggesting that possession of child pornography was no great crime since most new material involved foreign children. Another predicted the result would be an unenforceable fudge, banning only "unpublished" material. Even after law-makers agree to criminalise possession, two sessions of parliament need to ratify the measure, which means it cannot become law before 1998. Sweden's ambivalence is about to become embarrassing: this month it plays host to a world congress on the sexual exploitation of children.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet Queen Silvia's sortie has attracted more outrage than assent; and it has shifted attention from pornography to the political influence of the monarchy. <i>Ex</i><i>press</i><i>en</i>, the biggest-selling daily, set up a telephone line for readers to render judgment on whether she should have spoken out. This seems odd. Sweden's monarchy has almost no power; the king's rare pronouncements--against Norwegian seal hunts and wage rises, for example--have been met with shrugs. In 1993 Queen Silvia called for censorship of childrens' videos, also a more controversial stand, without causing a stir.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;So why the fuss this time? Personal liberty is almost as sacred to Swedes as are their coddled children. The constitution guarantees broad rights to freedom of expression, including the publication and possession of adult pornography. Debauchery behind closed doors, Swedes tend to believe, is a victimless peccadillo. Banning child smut without infringing other liberties is a balance Sweden is finding hard to strike.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hence its hesitant approach to reform. A parliamentary commission set up two years ago has become mired in dispute and controversy. One member did the cause no good by suggesting that possession of child pornography was no great crime since most new material involved foreign children. Another predicted the result would be an unenforceable fudge, banning only "unpublished" material. Even after law-makers agree to criminalise possession, two sessions of parliament need to ratify the measure, which means it cannot become law before 1998. Sweden's ambivalence is about to become embarrassing: this month it plays host to a world congress on the sexual exploitation of children.
</td></tr></table>
