<html><head><title>Pain in the NEC</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Politics</b></p>
<h1>Pain in the NEC</h1>

<p>CLARE SHORT may have been "hurt" by her demotion to overseas-development spokesman by Tony Blair. Ken Livingstone may moan that the parliamentary Labour party is like "the old Soviet Union". Lynne Jones may complain of Mr Blair's "Thatcherite agenda". But despite the grumbles of left-wing <font size=-1>MP</font>s, Mr Blair got away with his ruthless follow-up to his supporters' victory in July 24th's shadow cabinet elections--though his public approval rating fell to its lowest ever in a <font size=-1>MORI</font> poll.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;He has rewarded some of his strongest supporters. One is Alistair Darling, a young Scottish lawyer who did not stand in the election but has nevertheless joined Mr Blair's team in the pivotal post of shadow chief secretary, charged with stopping his colleagues making spending pledges. Yet Mr Blair has also had the sense to balance such promotions with an olive branch to the left. He promoted Peter Hain and Ian McCartney, two leftish but loyal Labour <font size=-1>MP</font>s. This widened his base in the Parliamentary Labour Party without weakening his authority.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On July 31st Mr Blair began a trickier but even more important job: sorting out relations between a Labour government and the party's National Executive Committee (<font size=-1>NEC</font>), which includes representatives of the trade unions and of Labour constituencies. Typically, the <font size=-1>NEC</font> has moved to the left when a Labour government has been in power, acting as a focus for internal opposition. James Callaghan, prime minister from 1976-79, even complained in his memoirs that "some of the Members of Parliament on the <font size=-1>NEC</font> appeared to want to set themselves up as an alternative government."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Blair does not want to risk repeating that experience. As he currently commands a comfortable majority on the <font size=-1>NEC</font>, he has decided that now is the time to fix it. Tom Sawyer, the party's general secretary, has been at work on the nuts and bolts.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One suggestion in Mr Sawyer's report to the <font size=-1>NEC</font> is that it should focus on organisational work, including communications with the membership, not on policy. Another is that its own membership be revised so that it includes more Labour councillors and fewer <font size=-1>MP</font>s. A third is that the party's annual conference should consider policy statements prepared in consultation with ministers, rather than often hostile individual resolutions from constituency parties.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Blair has already said that he is "not going to have a situation where the chancellor of the exchequer has to start going to committees to justify himself when he's got the country's interests to resolve." Some Blairites talk of banning ministers from sitting on the <font size=-1>NEC</font> altogether.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the eyes of some experienced party hands, that would go too far. Lord Callaghan refers to the "advantage" of "cross-fertilisation" between people who were both members of his government and the <font size=-1>NEC</font> and of the need for ministers and <font size=-1>NEC</font> to "run in tandem". Mr Blair's ministers would spend long enough in their Whitehall offices, surrounded by obsequious civil servants and seductive red boxes. A little time in the presence of supportive but critical party colleagues would do them and a Labour government no harm.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839026800,iss">Search</a>
 
