<html><head><title>Hawks and doves</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>



<h1>Hawks and doves</h1>

<p>IT WAS a very Liverpudlian verdict. On July 30th, a crown court jury in Britain's most anarchic city acquitted four women of charges relating to &#163;1.5m-worth of damage to a Hawk trainer jet that was owned by British Aerospace and due to be exported to Indonesia. The women did not deny the damage: they argued that they "had lawful excuse to disarm Hawk <font size=-1>ZH</font>955 because they were using reasonable force to prevent a crime"--the oppression of the citizens of East Timor. The defence of justification exists, but it is normally used only in cases of assault to prevent burglary.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Yet this acquittal is also part of a long British tradition. Juries have often returned perverse verdicts when they perceive that justice and the law are on opposite sides. This was most in evidence in the 18th century, when juries often acquitted people charged under the Black Act, a law that made it an offence punishable by death not just to poach but also to appear in any form of disguise on land where poaching might take place. Such verdicts required some courage: thwarting landowners in those days was more dangerous than is offending British Aerospace today.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More recently, a jury acquitted Clive Ponting, a civil servant, on charges of breaching the Official Secrets Act by leaking information on the sinking of the General Belgrano, an Argentine warship, during the Falklands War. Mr Ponting argued that his duty to the truth was greater than his duty to the government. The judge's summing-up pointed strongly to a conviction; the jury ignored it.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;British Aerospace said, understandably, that it was surprised by the verdict, since it had licences to export the aircraft to Indonesia and no reason to doubt Indonesia's assurances that the aircraft would not be used in East Timor. The company may be wondering whether this verdict creates a general licence to nip into their factories and smash up their jets. Presumably not--so long as the vandals are not Christian women in sandals who leave a political video in the cockpit and ring a news agency to say they did it.



</td></tr></table>
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839026800,iss">Search</a>
 
