<html><head><title>Tune in, turn on</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Channel 5</b></p>
<h1>Tune in, turn on</h1>

<p>IF A total stranger knocked on your door and asked to retune your video-cassette recorder (<font size=-1>VCR</font>), would you let him (or her) in? No wonder the most difficult part of launching Britain's fifth analogue-television channel is organising the vast retuning exercise. The winners of the Channel 5 franchise, a consortium backed by Pearson (part-owners of <i>The Economist</i>) and United News &amp; Media, originally expected that the job would cost &#163;55m. Some well-placed observers think the cost could be almost double the original estimate.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;What has gone wrong? The need for the retuning exercise, which starts this week, arises because the frequency on which the channel will be broadcast in some parts of the country is close to the one that many <font size=-1>VCR</font>s use when they play videos (see <a href="br1.gif">map</a>). To check for interference, almost 10m homes will have to be visited.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;When the four rival bids for the franchise were drawn up last year, the retuning plans of Channel 5 Broadcasting, the eventual winner, were criticised by some of its rivals as "fragile" and "ambitious". Its estimate of costs was less than half that of New Century Television, a consortium backed by <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font>, Britain's satellite broadcaster, which calculated a figure of &#163;120m.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The differences appeared to result mainly from variations in assumptions about the number of homes a retuner could visit in a day, about the level of supervision retuners would need, and about the complexity of the problems that retuners would find in the homes they visited. At the time, the Channel 5 team insisted, to the apparent satisfaction of the Independent Television Commission which awarded them the franchise, that they were no more optimistic than the <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> consortium, and that the two numbers were not at all comparable.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Channel 5 now seems to have abandoned some aspects of its original plans in ways that will increase the cost. According to Chris Goodall, a consultant who drew up the original Channel 5 retuning plans, the company took too long to turn its attention to retuning. Its current plans involve making appointments with home-owners who are not at home when the retuner first calls: given the notorious reluctance of people to stay in for a workman, that may be slower than the original plan simply to knock repeatedly on doors. They are also, says Ian Ritchie, chief executive of Channel 5, wondering whether to use the occasion as a marketing opportunity: understandable, but more time-consuming than merely twiddling a screw-driver.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The key change, though, may be the decision that big video-rental chains should retune their own machines. Originally, the idea was that one retuner should take full responsibility for an area of 2,000 homes, a scheme intended to ensure that every home was covered, to improve security and thus reduce the need for supervision.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Already, the share prices of the two main backers of the new company have fallen with a wallop. Worse may be in store if, in spite of the stringent security precautions Channel 5 is taking, retuning proves to be a "burglars' charter". Who coined that vivid phrase? Greg Dyke, now boss of Pearson Television, when he led an unsuccessful bid for the Channel 5 franchise in 1991.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But Channel 5 may yet have the last laugh. As Mr Dyke also likes to point out, nobody has ever lost money on a television franchise (although some have come close). The franchise will run for ten years, and perhaps a further decade beyond that, through an era when digital television will be heavily promoted, and when <font size=-1>B</font>Sky<font size=-1>B</font> will become an aggressive contender for advertising, as well as for eyeballs. Yet it offers something unique: nearly nationwide coverage by a conventional commercial broadcaster. Neither the fragmented Channel 3 companies, nor Channel 4 with its obligation to cater for minority tastes, have that mix. If Channel 5 can predict audience tastes more accurately than retuning costs, it will prove Mr Dyke's point.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839026800,iss">Search</a>
 
