<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>



<p><b>Unappealing</b> &nbsp;Michael Howard, the home secretary, suffered his 12th defeat by the judiciary when the Court of Appeal ruled that he had acted unfairly when he set a minimum 15-year sentence on the two boys who killed two-year-old James Bulger.</p>
<p><b>Appealing</b> &nbsp;Mr Howard referred to the Court of Appeal the case of four men jailed in 1979 for the killing of 13-year-old Carl Bridgewater--averting a likely legal challenge to his earlier refusal to do so.</p>
<p><b>Gunned down</b> &nbsp;The Conservative <font size=-1>MP</font>s who form a majority on the House of Commons Home Affairs Committee faced widespread attacks, including from other Tories, for rejecting a ban on the private ownership of handguns following the Dunblane massacre.</p>
<p><b>Licensed to thrill</b> &nbsp;The chief constables of West Yorkshire and Lancashire called for the legalisation of brothels, to make prostitutes safer and to reduce the risk of spreading disease.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>The &#163;15m man</b> &nbsp;Alan Shearer became the world's most expensive soccer player when Newcastle United bought him from Blackburn Rovers for &#163;15m.</p>
<p><b>Not cricket</b> &nbsp;Former England cricketers Ian Botham and Allan Lamb lost a libel action against Imran Khan, a former Pakistan captain, in which they claimed he had branded them as uneducated racists.</p>
<p><b>Cell death</b> &nbsp;The destruction of some 3,000 frozen human embryos, created by <i>in vitro</i> fertilisation for couples unable to conceive naturally, but not used, began on August 1st. Some called it a "prenatal massacre of the innocent".</p>
<p><b>Gay dad</b> &nbsp;In the first known British case of a male homosexual being allowed to adopt a child, a gay male nurse was allowed to adopt a five-year-old disabled boy.</p>
<p><b>Free as a bird</b> &nbsp;A racing pigeon that went missing during a race from West Sussex to Dorset four years ago has turned up in China.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
