<html><head><title>Oh what a lovely millennium bug</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/wb.gif" width=128 height=26  alt="Business">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<h1>Oh what a lovely millennium bug</h1>
<p><b>Many computers think all years start with "19". This will cause havoc in 2000. The cure will be expensive, but will not cost as much as the "millennium bug" industry claims</b></p>

<p>AS THE previous millennium approached in Europe, hucksters persuaded gullible peasants to give up their homes and farms in anticipation of the coming apocalypse. A millennium on, the apocalypse business has become more lucrative still. A whole industry is flourishing on fears of a computerised catastrophe, caused by a nasty bug that makes many computers choke on any year that does not begin with "19".
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Computer-systems managers have known about the problem for decades--indeed, some of them created it in the 1960s and 1970s when they decided to use only two digits to store years in database records, to save storage space. Most had assumed that their computer programs would have been superseded by now.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;If you have a credit card with an expiry date of 2000 or later, you will know they were wrong. Many sales terminals will accept neither four-digit dates nor "00". Older accounting programs, payroll, banking, telephone, inventory and pension systems--indeed, almost any mainframe computer programs written more than a decade ago, when storage capacity was scarce--are all likely to read 2000 as 1900 or, more commonly, simply to gag on the date, potentially stopping businesses in their tracks.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Last year, companies got a hint of what it might cost to put this right when the Gartner Group, a Connecticut-based computer consultancy, calculated that removing "millennium bugs" from the world's computers and software would cost anything up to $600 billion over the next four years, more than $10m per average medium-sized firm. Worse, the longer companies delay, the more the solution will cost. J.P. Morgan, an investment bank, reckons that the cost of rewriting a line of code will rise from $1 today to nearly $7 by 2000, as panicky companies fight over an insufficient number of competent mainframe programmers. For many organisations, such a bill would gobble up more than half their computing budgets for the rest of the century.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Faced with such numbers, companies alternate between shock and denial. The issue has already become a political football. In Britain the Labour Party is demanding that the Conservative government deal with the problem now instead of leaving a multi-billion pound problem for its successor. The state of Nebraska is footing the bill for fixing its own software from a two-cent tax on cigarettes.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Waiting cheerfully in the wings is a phalanx of mainframe companies, computer consultants and services firms, and laid-off mainframe programmers, whose skill at reading old software code has gone from liability to asset overnight as companies grasp the problem. They are part of a burgeoning "Year 2000 industry". J.P. Morgan has assembled an index of the share prices of 20 firms in the millennium-bug business, ranging from software firms to consultants and contract programmers. Since the start of 1996, the index has risen 50%, twice as much as the rest of the software industry (see <a href="wb1.gif">chart</a>). The share prices of some of the purest Year 2000 plays, such as Viasoft, Computer Horizons and Data Dimensions, have risen as much as 20-fold over the past year.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;They are benefiting greatly from hype. After an <font size=-1>NBC</font> news report in April, which quoted the Gartner Group projections, J.P. Morgan's index rose by 20%. Other attention-provoking events--congressional meetings, articles in the financial press--have moved it too. Although computer buffs may have known about the problem for years, many companies are only just waking up to it. More than half of all European companies have not made plans to deal with the Year 2000 problem, according to a survey by <font size=-1>EDS</font>, a computer-services firm. Many have not even taken an inventory of the software programs they use, to know which might be affected. Yet the strange thing is that the massive costs that investors are anticipating may be wildly overstated.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The Gartner cost estimates, taken at face value, defy common sense. The projected size of the world's entire systems-integration business between now and 2000 is perhaps no more than $300 billion. Gartner's upper cost figure, of $600 billion, is about half the world's total computer spending--hardware, software and services--over the same period. If each of the world's 5m programmers cost an average of $30,000 apiece in salaries and overheads, this figure would employ every one of them full-time from now until midnight on December 31st 1999.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In fact, much of the Year 2000 spending will not represent new money. Most companies already devote a big chunk of their computing budgets to software "maintenance" and support, including removing bugs. The rest goes on upgrades, new projects and the replacement of old systems. Over the next four years, these investments may have to wait while the money is spent on millennium debugging. But overall spending may not go up much.
</p><p><b>Party like it's 1999</b>
<br>Indeed, much of the alleged cost will not consist of spending at all. It is opportunity cost: money that would have been saved or earned by the new projects that will be deferred or cancelled to make way for Year 2000 repairs.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Even the direct costs are unlikely to be as large as predicted. The Gartner Group reached its estimate partly by assuming that it will cost, on average, $1.10 per line of code to fix most common mainframe computer programs. It reckons that the world's companies have about 225 billion lines of such code between them. Assuming that virtually all of these programs will need attention accounts for more than $200 billion of costs (Gartner's $600 billion estimate includes, among other things, the cost of fixing the data files the programs use and other sorts of programs and computers).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The problem with this estimate is that it assumes that all existing programs will be repaired. In fact, many will simply be scrapped: either replaced by off-the-shelf software, or not replaced at all. Some companies will take the opportunity to upgrade their systems from mainframes and minicomputers to <font size=-1>PC</font>-based "client-server" systems, on the basis that, if they are having to spend a fortune on software, they might as well buy some improvements in productivity as well. Others may simply hand the jobs done by the problem programs--and the Year 2000 risks that go with them--to outside firms.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A reasonable guess would be that perhaps half of all affected programs will be deemed not worth fixing, will have only cosmetic errors (printing the date wrongly on reports, for example), can be replaced easily with off-the-shelf software, or will disappear as part of the move away from mainframe and minicomputer systems. That could halve the cost of fixing the bug. Ignoring opportunity costs and other such notional expenses (which do not involve direct outlays) could "save" another $100 billion.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;That still leaves a problem that will cost the world's companies some $200 billion, most of which will ultimately find its way to the computer industry. The biggest winners are likely to be software firms offering programs that find Year 2000 bugs, and consultants and systems integrators such as <font size=-1>EDS</font> and Computer Sciences Corp. They can make a problem go away--albeit at high cost--with tools that can analyse and partially cure problem programs, plus programmers who can do the rest.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;No company has yet devised a magic "Year 2000 solution". Most of the work is likely to involve mind-numbing manual labour, much of it done by the growing contract-programming industries in such countries as India, Ireland and Russia, where costs are half those in America and rich European countries. The computer industry as a whole may not make much extra money, but some of the stodgiest firms in the industry will benefit hugely. Mainframe programmers have not been on the cutting edge of computing for a long time, but they are quickly becoming one of the hottest commodities around. Perhaps their decision to save a couple of bytes with each date a few decades ago was not so short-sighted after all.



<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?839026800,iss">Search</a>
 
