<DOCHDR>
http://www.economist.com:80/issue/27-07-96/ld1.html 199.173.162.110 19970113155224 text/html 8293
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 13-Jan-97 15:48:09 GMT
Last-modified: Thursday, 08-Aug-96 14:14:54 GMT
Content-length: 8108
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>The hidden cost of red tape</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>

<h1><center>The hidden cost of red tape</center></h1>

BEING a politician would not be nearly as exciting if one did not have so much of other people's money to throw around. Many rich-country voters could be forgiven, therefore, for thinking that they had made their leaders' lot a dull one of late. In America, pressure from Republicans in Congress has forced the Clinton administration to scale back its spending plans. In Western Europe, where governments are keen to reduce budget deficits to qualify for monetary union, some semblance of spending restraint is at last beginning to appear. Bond markets everywhere are imposing discipline when voters fail. So will politicians lose heart, having lost their ability to spend to their hearts' content?
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Far from it. They have two ways to spend your money. They can take it from you and spend it directly; or they can regulate. In other words, they can order you to spend it yourself, on something they have decided is good for you.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Suppose that a government wants to reduce pollution. It could do so by buying, say, $1 billion-worth of anti-pollution devices and giving one to every power plant, raising the money through taxes or borrowing. Or it could simply decree that all power plants must be equipped with anti-pollution devices, forcing power companies to fork out the $1 billion themselves. Either way, society would be consuming $1 billion of its resources in order to cut pollution.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Nothing wrong with that, you might think: pollution is, after all, a bad thing. But there are differences between these two forms of spending. A government that spends directly must go through the reasonably transparent exercise of taxing or borrowing. A government that merely regulates passes these costs on to customers, employees and owners of power plants, making the costs hard to track and measure. Is there an even better use for that $1 billion? Since this spending is invisible to it, a government need not care; you can call any sort of tune if someone else is paying the piper.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This habit, already bad, will grow worse. In America, politicians find it especially hard to resist calls for training schemes, environmental laws, parental leave and much else (see <a href="sf1.html">page</a>). Since they can no longer pay for these by taxing and spending, regulation is ballooning out of control.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On one estimate, the cost of complying with America's federal regulations has risen to 47% of its federal budget, up from only 40% in 1988. Other countries are faring no better. Japan may be a model of fiscal conservatism, but its regulators impose vast indirect costs on the country. European governments are just as bad. They not only spend more of their countries' <font size=-1>GDP</font>s but also regulate promiscuously, especially in the labour market. And on top of all of the costs of complying with the rules, there is the cost--unknowable but possibly large--that regulation imposes in the form of lost productivity. Many economists believe that over-zealous environmental regulation contributed to the great productivity slowdown that took hold in the industrial countries after 1973.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In theory, the simple solution is for governments to avoid all forms of indirect spending, and pay for everything directly. They would reimburse companies and individuals for the full costs of implementing their policies, paying for all of these activities with debt and taxes. But this sort of radicalism is impossible, for two reasons.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;First, many government policies are much simpler, and cheaper, to implement through regulation: it is easier to require firms to use good safety standards, for example, than to have government agencies implement them in every office and factory. And trying to reimburse each firm for its share of the burden would create a bureaucratic nightmare. Second, even if the government could compensate everyone for complying with regulations, this would create a huge incentive problem. Just think what would happen to wages if the government agreed to pay every employer the difference between the minimum wage and the wage that it would have offered to its workers in a free market.

Transparent tape would be better
Regulation, therefore, is here to stay. The question is how to deter governments from resorting to it as if it cost nothing. One solution often proposed is cost-benefit analysis: government agencies would be required to estimate the economic costs of implementing their policies, weigh them against the benefits they will offer, and implement only those policies that offer net benefits. But the benefits are often perilously difficult to measure. What is the value of a clean beach, or racial equality? Indeed, it is precisely in cases where the benefits are ephemeral that voters tend to look to governments for action. Even if statisticians were able to put a figure on the economic benefits of such things, would anybody take their estimates seriously? Of course not. It is not the job of economists and statisticians to tell people what they want.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;They can, however, tell people how much the things they want will cost. And that is the beauty of a proposal that has been floated by the Republicans in Congress. It is to create a regulatory "budget" , parallel to the traditional spending budget, that would force a government to make the same sort of trade-offs when it is requiring people and firms to spend their own money that it makes when it is spending the money it has raised through taxation.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This way, voters and their representatives would still have to decide for themselves what good things they want for society. But the budget would impose some discipline. Imagine what would happen if every year or two the party in power was forced to say how much it was going to spend on regulation, and how this spending would be allocated. The opposition would no doubt question the government's priorities, perhaps recommending more spending, perhaps less. Voters would benefit from hearing the sort of debate that they hear now when their tax dollars are being spent.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Naturally, this approach has some technical problems of its own. Though easier to measure than the benefits, the costs of regulation are often hard to quantify. Sometimes, doing so requires guessing the difference between what firms are spending under existing regulation and what they would have been spending if left to their own devices. Once a regulatory budget had been set, this process of reckoning and guesswork would quickly become politicised.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;But so what? If the regulatory budget was in danger of being breached, those who felt strongly about the need for particular regulations would push for the budget to be raised. If the alleged costs of some regulation were exaggerated, the relevant interest groups would challenge the calculations. Attempts to codify them would spark furious debate about the true cost of regulation<b>--</b>precisely the debate, in other words, that democracies desperately need and presently lack.
<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838422000,iss">Search</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="index.html">Contents</a>
 &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="sf1.html">Next article</a>
</p>
<p align=center><font size=-1><a href="http://www.economist.com/copyright.html">&#169; Copyright</a> 1996 <i>The Economist</i> Newspaper Limited. All Rights Reserved</font></p>
</td></tr></table></body></html>
