<html><head><title>Po-li-tics on Route 66</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/am.gif" width=258 height=26  alt="American Survey">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<table border=6><tr><td>

<h1>Po-li-tics on Route 66</h1>

<font size=1>KINGMAN</font>
<p>THE swimming-pool floor at the Quality Inn in Kingman, Arizona, is emblazoned with a giant sign saying "Route 66". In the lobby, Route 66 memorabilia, from <font size=-1>T</font>-shirts and caps to key-rings and maps, are on sale. Outside in the forecourt, in front of some old petrol pumps, a 1964 Corvette is being raffled for $5 a ticket. The proceeds are for Kingman's Route 66 museum, one of several springing up along the "Main Street of America", as early boosters called the road that twisted its way for 2,400 miles across eight states from Chicago to Los Angeles.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Growing numbers of people are heading back along it. Some 80% of the road has survived into the age of the Interstates. Now it is not so much a means of getting (slowly) from <font size=-1>A</font> to <font size=-1>B</font>, but a place to watch nostalgic baby-boomers, clutching their copies of Jack Kerouac and John Steinbeck and humming the lyrics of "Route 66". Since Bobby Troup wrote that song in 1946, it has been recorded by at least 66 other singers, among them Nat King Cole, Bing Crosby, the Rolling Stones, Bob Dylan, Chuck Berry and, woe betide, Asleep at the Wheel.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;This October in Vega, Texas, enthusiasts will gather to celebrate the 70th birthday of the fabled highway. In his splendid book, "Route 66: The Mother Road" (St Martin's Press), Michael Wallis notes that back in 1926 George Gershwin was all the rage, motion pictures were still a year away from finding their voice and Fred Astaire had yet to find Ginger Rogers. And, he might have added, in Russell, Kansas, a boy named Bob Dole was three years old.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Perhaps Mr Dole, who was back in Kansas on July 22nd to celebrate his 73rd birthday, could learn a thing or two from the renewed fashionableness of Route 66. The road signs that came down in the 1970s have become valuable collectors' items. In recent years the states along the road have been putting up new signs to mark "Historic Route 66" and to point the way to it from the Interstates. Shops are doing a brisk trade in Route 66 accessories (one advertisement urges drivers to "Get your 'ticks' with the Official Route 66 Watch Company"). <i>Route 66 Magazine</i>, a three-year-old quarterly, is growing beyond the wildest dreams of its publisher, Paul Taylor.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Mr Taylor points to the road's association with a world that seemed slower, easier, more innocent. People like to remember "a time of leaving the doors unlocked, of mom-and-pop diners, of taking your time." Route 66 is an American metaphor for mobility, freedom, progress, a sense of possibility.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Is it not also an ideal metaphor for Mr Dole: Route 66, the thread that runs through his life? For a dozen miles, the road also happens to run through a corner of his native Kansas, carefully by-passing Bill Clinton's Arkansas in the process (though there is now a Route 66 museum in Clinton, Oklahoma). The Republican presidential candidate may of course fear that any reminder that he is older than this piece of American heritage might make voters think he himself belongs in a museum. But Route 66 shows that nostalgia is positively hip.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In one of his forlorn efforts to define the essence of this election, Mr Dole earlier this year ventured that "It's about the future, because that's where we're headed." Perhaps he should now head to Vega, Texas, and declare that "It's about the past, because that's where we're coming from." 
</td></tr></table>
