<html><head><title>Doesn't add up</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td valign=top><img src="../images/br.gif" width=111 height=24  alt="Britain">
<p><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td><td></td>
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist">
</td></tr></table>


<p><b>Educational performance</b></p>
<h1>Doesn't add up</h1>

<p>NOT only are English children among the rich world's worst at mathematics, but they have slid down the scale since the 1960s. This is the conclusion of a report published on July 25th by Ofsted, the schools inspectorate for England, which reviews the evidence from international comparisons of children's abilities. The fact that English pupils do rather better in science, while good news in itself, shows that the poor performance in maths is not all down to "cultural differences", such as the greater importance that East Asians are said to attach to education. If it were, East Asians would be as far ahead in science as they are in maths. So, Ofsted concludes, we cannot be teaching maths properly.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As well as measuring how much English pupils lag behind those in other countries, the studies reviewed by Ofsted suggest some reasons for their weaknesses. A big study in 1990 (see <a href="br1.gif">chart</a>) noted that in England, pupils spend less time doing maths than in most other countries, and get less homework than anywhere except Scotland.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In a comparison of two similar sets of tests on 13-year-olds, one in 1964 and the other in 1983, England slipped from fourth to ninth place out of ten countries taking part. Its ranking would have been even worse but for the fact that star performers such as China, South Korea and Taiwan did not participate in these particular tests. Since the 1983 tests, England has seen a steady improvement in the proportion of pupils passing their <font size=-1>GCSE</font> (and its predecessor, <font size=-1>O</font>-level) in maths. So has the gap with other countries closed? Probably not, says David Reynolds, professor of education at Newcastle University and one of the Ofsted report's authors, because other countries have improved even more.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Average test scores in England are brought down by its greater proportion of low achievers, compared with such countries as Taiwan. Schools in these countries test their pupils more regularly, and often insist that all pupils repeat the tests until they get adequate scores, giving them extra lessons and homework if need be. Schools in countries in which children do well at maths also spend more of their time on "interactive whole-class teaching", where the teacher lectures the entire class, constantly firing questions at pupils to ensure they understand what is being taught. In English schools, pupils are more often left to work through textbooks or worksheets on their own or in small groups.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;International comparisons of any sort always have to be treated with caution. For instance, one reason that Taiwanese children do so well in tests designed to measure international differences is that they are more used to taking tests than English children. But England's performance may be boosted by the high proportion of English schools that refuse to take part in such international tests: presumably the ones that do join in are the better ones.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As well as getting schools to spend more time teaching maths, to set more homework and to test their pupils more often, Mr Reynolds says more attention should be paid to teaching the teachers. He has recently been to study the education system in Taiwan, and says it seems to have successfully incorporated the best of teaching methods from countries as diverse as China, Japan and America. Trainee teachers in Taiwan get more intensive coaching in which methods work best; in England, argues Mr Reynolds, we have "failed to assemble a body of knowledge about what works in the classroom." 
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The government has recently announced a string of measures to redress some of these failings: some teacher-training colleges are to be reinspected, because Ofsted suspects that its inspectors have been too lenient; tests of mental arithmetic are being introduced for 11- and 14-year-olds; more in-service training for teachers is being directed towards brushing up their maths. However, this drive will not be helped by the fact that, as a recent survey of teacher-training institutions by Oxford Brookes University found, there are now only 66 applicants for every 100 places on courses for training maths teachers. Falling unemployment has meant numerate graduates can find better-paid jobs which involve less hassle than teaching.


