<html><head><title>Britain In Brief</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<center><p align=center><table width=65% align=center><tr><td valign=top align=center>
<img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></p>
<p align=center><img src="../images/brbrief.gif" width=231 height=24  alt="Britain"></p>
<p align=center><font size=-1>
These articles in the Britain section are published in the UK printed edition only, and are published here for the benefit of readers of non-UK editions.
</font></p></td></tr></table></center>
<hr size=6 align=center width=65%>
<center><table width=65%><tr valign=top><td valign=top width=30%>


<p><b>Charged</b> &nbsp;Eight men including a former American marine were charged with conspiring to cause explosions, after investigations by anti-terrorist police in London and Birmingham.</p>
<p><b>Questioned</b> &nbsp;Hours after John Major met loyalist politicians at Downing Street, a group of loyalists was arrested for questioning over the murder of a Catholic taxi-driver in County Armagh.</p>
<p><b>After-dinner chat</b> &nbsp;It emerged that John Beckwith, a businessman who belongs to the Premier Club, which charges people up to &#163;100,000 to dine with the prime minister to raise funds for the Tories, was negotiating to buy Britain's 58,000 armed-forces homes.</p>
<p><b>Unmasked</b> &nbsp;The author of a leaked Treasury memo, which Labour denounced as a secret plan to demolish the welfare state, turned out to have applied for nomination as Labour's parliamentary candidate for Barnsley East.</p>
</td><td width=5%></td><td valign=top width=30%>
<p><b>Blamed</b> &nbsp;The High Court ruled that people who caught Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease as a result of being treated with a growth hormone could claim compensation from the government.</p>
<p><b>Busman</b> &nbsp;Dawson Williams, boss of British Bus, Britain's third-largest bus firm, was charged with corruption over an alleged &#163;600,000 gift to a banker.</p>
<p><b>Buying British</b> &nbsp;The government awarded defence contracts worth a reported &#163;4 billion, despite last-minute opposition from the Treasury. Britain's <font size=-1>GEC</font> and British Aerospace were the main beneficiaries, although the latter will share the task of building a cruise missile with Matra of France. This may lead to a merger of the French and British businesses.</p>
<p><b>Sporting</b> &nbsp;John Major said a national sports academy would be set up, using &#163;100m of lottery proceeds.
</p>
<p><b>Worcester sauce</b> &nbsp;In a desperate attempt to make money, Worcester museum is gathering up the dust from its exhibits--including the teeth of King John--and selling it for &#163;1 a bag.</p>
</td></tr></table></center>
