<html><head><title>Old Lady, new problems</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<table width=100%><tr><td align=left valign=top><img src="../images/fn.gif" width=360 height=26  alt="Finance And Economics">
<td align=right valign=top><img src="http://www.economist.com/econlogosmall.gif" width=78 height=39  alt="The Economist"></td></tr></table>
<p><b>Financial regulation</b></p>
<h1>Old Lady, new problems</h1>


<p>SINCE Barings, a British merchant bank, collapsed in February 1995 after amassing &#163;860m ($1.4 billion) of trading losses, there have been many outside assertions that poor regulation by the Bank of England was partly to blame for the fiasco. Stung by the criticism, the Old Lady of Threadneedle Street has been indulging in a little navel-gazing of her own.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;On July 24th she revealed the results. The report, written by Arthur Andersen, a consultancy, considers how the Bank might become a better regulator. The Bank has agreed to the report's recommendations, trumpeting them as a "major programme of change". Sadly, they are not.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The demise of Barings exposed several weaknesses in the way the Bank and other financial regulators keep watch over their charges. First, big banks have increasingly far-flung networks; national regulators simply do not have the resources to follow them. The trading risks that sank Barings occurred in Singapore, not in London. Second, the Barings group, like many other modern financial conglomerates, owned both a bank, which took deposits, and a securities firm, which took trading risks. Yet most regulators are still divided along traditional industry lines.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The third weakness follows from the second: regulators are struggling to understand the complex trading risks that banks run. According to an official report into Barings' collapse published last July, regulators admitted to Barings executives in February 1993 that they did not "really understand" Baring Securities, its trading arm.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The fourth problem is more troublesome still. Until recently, regulators have relied mainly on totting up numbers (measuring a bank's capital, its biggest loan exposures, and so on) to do their job. But spotting weak management and poor controls is arguably a more important task. Barings suffered from both. On July 23rd Ian Hopkins, its former head of risk management, told a parliamentary committee that meetings of Barings' risk-management committee sometimes degenerated into "lots of table banging and lots of shouting."
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The changes that the Bank announced this week should go some way towards tackling the last two of these problems. In future, it will recruit more supervisors, as well as experts in complicated financial instruments such as derivatives. It is also developing new ways to monitor banks' risks. And to help it judge the quality of a bank's internal controls and management, it will require its supervisors to visit their charges more often. (Astonishingly, the Bank's regulators never made a formal visit to Barings' offices before its collapse.) As a result of these reforms, the Bank reckons that the &#163;35m it spends on supervision each year could rise by &#163;7m-8m.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;There is little mention, however, of how the Bank might better supervise banks' international operations. Nor is anything said about how it could work more closely with securities regulators, such as Britain's Securities and Futures Authority (<font size=-1>SFA</font>).
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;As Michael Foot, the Bank's director of banking supervision, points out, it has been working hard to forge closer links with the <font size=-1>SFA</font>. But the dilemma is an acute one. There are few investment banks left in London without a commercial-bank parent; whether they own securities firms or not, most commercial banks now run big trading risks. Wholesale securities and banking regulation ought, many argue, to come under a single regulator.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Should that be the Bank of England? Possibly not. On balance, the <font size=-1>SFA</font> has a better claim for the job. After all, it has more experience in scrutinising trading businesses, where the biggest risks are often taken. A better solution still might be to create a new, independent regulator in which both the Bank's commercial-banking experts and the <font size=-1>SFA</font>'s investment-banking ones could be housed. The Andersen report does not address such issues.
<br>&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;More money and more staff should help at the margin. But if Britain's financial regulators seriously want to reduce the chances of another Barings, they may have to start thinking more radical thoughts.


<br><p align=center><a href="http://www.economist.com/index.html"><i>The Economist</i> Home Page</a> &nbsp; - &nbsp; <a href="http://www.economist.com/cgi-bin/search_form.cgi?838422000,iss">Search</a>
